</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWNBACK-VIOLENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNBACK A LEADER IN NATIONAL EFFORT TO DEFEAT CULTURE OF
VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the very moment the press conference he had
called Monday to discuss youth violence was set to begin, Sen. Sam
Brownback, the senior Republican from Kansas, was in a taxicab
shuttling between the White House and Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The room, meanwhile, was full. Sen. Byron Dorgan, a North Dakota
Democrat waiting to share the cameras with him, was in the hallway
cooling his heels.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback finally arrived about 15 minutes late. Just before
taking the microphone, he acknowledged a face in the front row, and
in an audible whisper said, ``Good morning.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about 2:15 in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive Brownback if his sense of time is a little skewed these
days. His clock is dictated by the demands of the issue du jour _
culture and violence. As the nation probes its collective psyche
looking for explanations of the high school murders in Littleton,
Colo., last month, Brownback has emerged as one of the leading
Washington headshrinkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time frame where the country is willing to listen
and discuss culture,'' he said. ``I think it's been building for a
long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a moment of maximum political exposure, especially for
someone such as Brownback who has been pushing cultural renewal for
years.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the floor Wednesday, calling for a measure that would
allow entertainment companies to work together toward a voluntary
code of conduct about violence in programming.
</P>
<P>
   For all the polls that politicians use to divine public opinion,
and all the advice they get from experts, success often comes from
just being in the right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   A 42-year-old conservative Republican, Brownback has been riding
a fast train ever since he arrived in Washington less than five
years ago. After one high-profile term in the House as one of Newt
Gingrich's often-quoted revolutionaries, he ran for the Senate in
1996, for the seat Bob Dole held for 27 years. He won and
immediately made the cover of Time magazine in the company of the
Senate Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   He is soft-spoken and disarming. But he is also somewhat of a
political swashbuckler, crossing swords with the entertainment
industry, or taking on issues like campaign finance reform that are
sure bets for attention. Yet he also is a lonely voice against
slavery in Africa, an issue that gets scant mention.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Hill aides call him prudent and careful, never one to do
anything purely by accident. It was in the Colorado massacre that
he saw the confluence of issues and concerns that have been part of
his recent focus _ and why viewers suddenly see him constantly
before the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Long before high schoolers Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold
massacred 13 classmates and a teacher, Brownback had been outspoken
about the depiction of violence in music, movies and video games.
Picking up the baton from Tipper Gore, who championed the issue in
the 1980s, he held a well-publicized hearing two years ago on
violence in rock and rap music.
</P>
<P>
   When he said in 1997 that the lyrics were ``a long way from
Elvis shaking his hips on the Ed Sullivan Show,'' Brownback
symbolized the kind of amazement of an over-40 generation suddenly
surprised that its own children had gone far beyond anything it had
ever considered risque.
</P>
<P>
   The next year he held two forums on the subject of violence and
kids killing kids.
</P>
<P>
   His was also a very public _ and political _ lament that
something was wrong with the culture. But the nerve he had hit
didn't really buzz until after Littleton, when he led a Senate
hearing _ one that had been scheduled two months before the
shootings _ into how violence is marketed to children by the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, his life has been a steady diet of press conferences
and television interviews. He was late for his Monday press
conference because of the White House summit on youth violence. But
he held another the next day with a second cultural renewal ally
from across the aisle, Democrat Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a frequent guest on the major news shows. He even
chartered a private plane to get him from Kansas early one Sunday
morning to Washington for his maiden appearance on NBC's ``Meet the
Press,'' and then whisk him back home to be with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting out early on this thing makes him somebody in
demand,'' said Nancy Nathan, the show's executive producer. ``There
is sort of a snowball effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback acknowledges the risk in possibly being seen as
exploiting the Littleton tragedy for political purposes. But both
he and others say that the shootings exposed what they think
represents an open wound in American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``To change the culture, you can use politics as the vehicle,
but culture is dominated by fields other than politics,'' Brownback
said. ``So you've got to go to the airwaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his opponents in the current campaign to ``shame'' the
entertainment industry into cleaning up its act give him praise for
his style, if not his point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe people like Sen. Brownback are extremely sincere
and feel strongly about what they say,'' said Jack Valenti,
president and chief executive officer of the Motion Picture
Association of America, the film industry lobby in Washington. ``I
can't be getting upset toward someone who speaks his mind honestly,
with integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said that as much as politicians like him want to do
something, the solutions would not come from legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that even his own home is not immune. He recently found
his 11-year-old son playing a video game that showed ``two guys
fighting and killing each other with axes.'' He removed it from the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you change your culture,'' Brownback said, ``by
millions of individual acts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
