<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ, YANKS SET OFF ALARMS AS THEY FALL TO WHITE SOX, 8-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The magic has vanished for Orlando Hernandez and the
dominance has vanished for the Yankees. At least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had another sluggish start Friday night in which he
could not collect outs and the Yankees had another exasperating
game in which they could not produce much offense. The result of
this distressing combination was an 8-2 loss to the Chicago White
Sox at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has lost his last three starts, has one victory in his
last six starts and has been blitzed for 30 earned runs in his last
321/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have lost four straight games in the Bronx and have
managed a measly two runs in the last 28 innings. They had three
hits after the third inning Friday night. Just call Hernandez and
the Yankees ugly and uglier.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Yankees are 20-14 and are in first place in the
American League East. But they are dysfunctional right now. They
rumbled to the top with reliable pitching and by overwhelming teams
at home. Last night, the Yankees sputtered in both areas and now
they should have major concerns about the pitcher known as El
Duque.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was the essence of precision and consistency after
joining the Yankees last June, baffling teams with his array of
pitches and arm angles. He won 12 games in four months, and
probably won the most critical game of 1998 when he stopped
Cleveland in Game 4 of the American League Championship Series. And
he was being touted as a Cy Young Award candidate this year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hernandez (3-4) has an earned run average that has
inflated to 6.55 and has already lost more games at the Stadium
(2-2) in a month and a half than he did in four months last season
(8-1).
</P>
<P>
   With a patient and opportunistic attack, the White Sox nicked El
Duque for four runs in the fourth inning. Hernandez walked four of
the first five batters in the inning and allowed the White Sox to
tie the score, 1-1, when he missed on a 3-2 pitch to McKay
Christensen the No. 9 batter, after being ahead of him 1-2. All
four White Sox batters wlked on 3-2 pitches. Hernandez was not
unbelievably wild. He was around the plate, but the White Sox were
resilient in fouling off pitches and extending at bats until
Hernandez tired and succumbed.
</P>
<P>
   When Ray Durham hit a sharp grounder to second and the Yankees
could not turn an inning-ending double play, Greg Norton scored the
second run. Mike Caruso followed by lining a shot off Hernandez's
left shin that caromed across the infield and into shallow right
field. Mark Johnson trotted home from third and Durham scampered
home from first as if it were a track meet.
</P>
<P>
   When second baseman Chuck Knoblauch picked up the ball about 180
feet from the plate and hesitated before throwing, Durham hustled
home and easily beat the wide throw. The White Sox were up by 4-1,
and Hernandez, who had thrown a stunning 47 pitches in the inning
ambled off the mound like a lost soul once again.
</P>
<P>
   It was another forgettable outing for the right-hander, who was
cuffed for seven runs in a 14-5 loss to Seattle last Saturday and
bolted the Stadium before the game ended. Hernandez tossed a pitch
behind Frank Thomas and then plunked him on the left elbow in the
third inning last night, and while it was obvious Hernandez wanted
to hit Thomas, his motives were unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Parque (5-2) the Chicago starter, did not retaliate, but he
whiffed seven in five and one-third innings to win for the fourth
time in his last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 innings, the Yankees finally ended their scoreless
streak in the second when Shane Spencer singled in Bernie Williams.
It was the Yankees' first hit with runners in scoring position in
18 at-bats. But Spencer helped end the inning and throttle a
possible rally when he was doubled off first base after he did not
follow the flight of a fly ball to right field on a hit-and-run
play.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer grimaced, knowing that the lost chance could be
critical. On another shabby night for Hernandez and the Yankees, it
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some guys now their wives better not have razor
blades around'' Zimmer said. ``They're liable to cut their throats.
They're probably trying so hard it's not getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The pitching coach MEL STOTTLEMYRE said that ROGER CLEMENS would
probably not pitch in the three-game series with Boston next week
because the Yankees want to be cautious about his strained left
hamstring. The Yankees do not feel that Clemens is 100 percent and
think it would be risky for him to return against the Red Sox, his
former team, because he could overdo it. Clemens could return
Friday in Chicago, at the earliest. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
