u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-NYT &LR;      05-15 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CHINA AGREE ON U.N. STATEMENT ON EMBASSY BOMBING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (budgeted earlier as KOSOVO-NATIONS)  (bl)  
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A week after NATO missiles hit the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, China and the United States hammered out a
formal statement late Friday night expressing the Security
Council's ``deep distress and concern'' about the attack.
</P>
<P>
   A deal was struck close to midnight when China agreed to drop an
explicit statement of ``shock'' about the missile strike in
exchange for the milder language.
</P>
<P>
   China had insisted on a harsh statement that first ``condemned''
and then ``deplored'' the attack, an insistence that effectively
delayed Council action on other pending issues. Among them was a
three-week-old resolution on the plight of Kosovo refugees that
endorsed principles of a peace settlement adopted by the Western
powers and Russia earlier this month in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Furious about the strike on its embassy, China maintained that a
formal presidential statement on the embassy bombing need top
priority on the Council's agenda. ``The Council should react first
to the bombing because it is such a serious matter,'' said Chen
Ranfeng, the spokesman for the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the Council's 15 members sympathized with China's
indignation over the attack that killed three and injured 20 more,
several were irritated by Beijing's decision, in effect, to hold
the Council's business hostage to the apology it wanted. One
African nation complained vociferously that China was holding up
important business relating to Africa, specifically an extension of
the legal authorization of a peacekeeping mission in the Western
Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   Five nations, including China, are permanent Council members,
and can veto any formal action. But on presidential statements, the
Council operates on consensus, making it easy for unhappy members
to disrupt or delay proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Though milder than the original version of the statement China
circulated earlier this week, China's fourth draft statement
proposed that the Council ``deplore'' the bombing rather than
``strongly condemn'' it as earlier drafts proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Even this weakened disapproval was unacceptable to the United
States and its NATO allies, however. ``We will not agree to
deplore,'' Peter Burleigh, the acting representative here, told
reporters after he had sought instructions from Washington on the
latest Chinese draft.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials objected to the formulation because they said it
suggested that NATO had intentionally attacked the embassy, a
diplomatic installation that under international law cannot be
targeted. ``Would you deplore a tornado?'' said one Western
official, explaining Washington's stance.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock was broken late Friday night after Burleigh huddled
with his counterpart, Chinese Ambassador Qin Huasun, and proposed
that the Council ``strongly lament'' the incident rather than
``deplore'' it. The consultations then adjourned temporarily while
Qin tried to check the language with his foreign ministry in
Beijing. After failing to receive instructions, he told Council
members that he would assume personal responsibility for accepting
the language.
</P>
<P>
   After an initial period of confusion, U.S. and NATO officials
have repeatedly apologized for what they have called a tragic
mistake. President Clinton succeeded in getting President Jiang
Zemin of China to accept his telephone call today expressing
condolences and apologies.
</P>
<P>
   After agreeing on the compromise wording, the Council members
met in a formal, televised session where they stood for a moment of
silence in memory of the three Chinese victims of the missile
strike. Then they approved the statement, the Council's first
official reaction to the embassy bombing, and adopted a series of
resolutions that had backed up during the week. A second minute of
silence was observed for the victims of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Few diplomats said that they thought China would delay
considering a peace plan for Kosovo once NATO and Russia agreed on
a proposal to restore peace in the Balkans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
