<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8235 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSOURI-LEGISLATURE-     05-15 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-LEGISLATURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GENERAL ASSEMBLY CUTS TAXES BY $202 MILLION ON FINAL DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL and KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY _ Prodded by Gov. Mel Carnahan, Missouri
lawmakers cut taxes by $202 million and passed a revamped pension
increase for themselves before adjourning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut cleared the Senate 34-0 after less than half an hour
of discussion. The House had backed it 126-0 earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also set up a graduated driver's license system for
young motorists and passed an economic development bill that
sponsors said would benefit Centertainment and Trans World Airlines
in Kansas City and other industries.
</P>
<P>
   But the two biggest issues of the final, frenzied day were the
tax cut and legislative pension increase. Both topics had triggered
unusually angry comments by Carnahan earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the governor called lawmakers ``self-serving'' and
said he would veto a pension increase they had just passed because
it was extravagant. He also had threatened to call a special
session if lawmakers failed to give him a tax cut of around $200
million, as he had proposed in January. Carnahan had opposed some
lawmakers' calls to slash taxes even deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Friday's adjournment, Carnahan said he was pleased
with the revised tax measure and gratified by the session's
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax cuts are exceedingly difficult to pass, but this one is
good public policy,'' Carnahan told reporters. ``It's broad-based,
and we can afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who favors abortion rights, said the session's low
point was the lengthy debate over abortion that ``poisoned the
atmosphere over the last several weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders cited the tax measure as a key
accomplishment in a 4 1/2-month session that veteran lawmakers
described as lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Pro Tem Ed Quick, a Liberty Democrat, said
lawmakers accomplished a lot even if much of it happened in the
final week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you viewed this as a war, it was successful, and everyone
worked hard in the end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GOP legislative leaders were less effusive.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leader Delbert Scott of Lowry City said GOP
pressure on the tax issue contributed to agreement on $202 million
package and other reductions. Scott and other Republican leaders
blamed the session's listless quality on Carnahan's early entry
into next year's U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made him candidate Carnahan rather than Governor Carnahan
right from the start,'' Scott said. ``All his statements were
colored by that...and he was missing in action.''
</P>
<P>
   As the session ended Friday, all sides were congratulating
themselves on passing a tax-cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri has to return about $160 million to taxpayers to comply
with the state's revenue and spending lid, known as the Hancock
amendment. If lawmakers had failed to agree on a tax cut, the money
would have been returned through refunds.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut will:
</P>
<P>
   - Boost the personal exemption for single filers and married
couples filing separate state returns to $2,100 from $1,200. The
exemption for married couples filing a combined return will rise to
$4,200 from $2,400.
</P>
<P>
   - Increase the exemption for a head of household or a surviving
spouse to $3,500 from $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   - Allow a state deduction for the self-employed on their health
insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   - Trim the state's corporate franchise tax rate by 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   - Liberalize the state deduction on pension income. Current law
allows single filers to deduct up to $6,000 if their incomes do not
exceed $25,000 and married couples to deduct up to $32,000. The new
law will gradually phase out that deduction for each dollar over
$25,000 or $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Steve Gaw, a Moberly Democrat, praised negotiators
who hammered out the plan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough road,'' said Gaw, who made the issue one of
his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Gibbons, a St. Louis County Republican, said the
tax cut represented broad-based relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good settlement,'' Gibbons told the House. ``It's a
good way to reduce taxes in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons and other Republicans noted that total tax reductions
this year would be about $250 million, including tax credits in
other bills besides the $202 million cut. The governor said he
would have to review those other reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also approved a hotly debated state retirement plan
that will increase legislative pensions 35 percent, despite
objections from colleagues who said it would contribute to public
distrust of government.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan threatened to veto a nearly identical plan earlier in
the week. The only change from the earlier version is the
elimination of a 17 percent increase for longtime lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The new system would increase pensions for all but a dozen
lawmakers. But it would cap pensions at 100 percent of a sitting
lawmaker's salary. However, about a dozen veteran lawmakers could
receive more under the current system, including several who are
already eligible for more than their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   With the increase for those lawmakers left out, Carnahan said he
intended to sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative pension increase was tied to a bill that would
give state workers, teachers, firefighters and other government
employees about a 6 increase in retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sarah Steelman, a Rolla Republican, tried to send the bill
back to a conference committee to strip lawmakers' pensions out of
the legislation. The motion was defeated 21-13.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan was adopted in the Senate 21-12. In the House,
where a vote usually takes a couple of minutes, nearly 15 minutes
passed as members delayed voting until it was apparent that the
measure would pass. The new plan was adopted 83-67, one more vote
than the minimum needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate sponsor, Democrat John Scott of St. Louis, called it
a good bill that would boost retirement benefits for thousands of
workers across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mary Groves Bland, a Kansas City Democrat, said the public
was not upset by the legislature's pension increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think badly about the legislature, because the media
tell only bad things about us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Kenney, a Lee's Summit Republican, criticized Carnahan
for opposing a pension increase that affected only a dozen
lawmakers while accepting a huge increase for all the rest. He said
the veto threat was little more than a public relations stunt.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Republican Rep. Matt Bartle of Lee's Summit
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are passing is no less excessive, unreasonable and
self-serving,'' Bartle said. ``What is the difference, Mr.
Governor? If you couldn't sign (the previous bill), you shouldn't
sign this one.''
</P>
<P>
   On another key issue, efforts to make it illegal for anyone to
drive with a blood-alcohol level of 0.08 percent or higher, instead
of the current 0.10 percent, died late Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the reduction earlier this year. But the bill
that the lower limit was attached to died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House backers tried to add the reduction to another measure, but
it failed.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas Friday, lawmakers approved a new, graduated
driver's license system, which backers said would give young people
more time to improve their driving skills before they drive without
any restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Current law allows people 16 and older to apply for unrestricted
driver's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in January 2001, applicants age 16 to 18 can apply for
intermediate driver's licenses. They must have had temporary
permits for at least six months and proof from a parent or guardian
that they have had 20 hours of supervised driving.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers with an intermediate license would be banned from
driving alone between 1 and 5 a.m. unless traveling to and from
school or a job. Anyone with an intermediate license who gets six
or more points for driving violations in a 12-month period would
have to complete a driver improvement program. Those who meet the
conditions could apply for a full license at the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   The same bill provides for auto inspections and vehicle
registration renewal every other year instead of annually. It also
provides for driver's license renewals every six years instead of
every three.
</P>
<P>
   Other bills that won approval on the final day will:
</P>
<P>
   - Provide new tax credits to TWA and Centertainment, the
multimillion-dollar project that includes hotels, shops and
theaters in southern downtown Kansas City. The bill, by Rep. Henry
Rizzo of Kansas City, also expands the list of communities that can
qualify to be enterprise zones, which can be a key financial tool
in attracting industries.
</P>
<P>
   - Revamp a variety of criminal sentences, in part to trim the
state's prison population; create a new ``aggravated offender''
crime for people with more than three convictions for driving while
intoxicated within a certain timeframe; and ban the use of tobacco
products in state prisons starting July 1, 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
