<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC STILL GETTING NO RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ It has been five years since a Kentucky Derby winner
was made the betting favorite in the Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   And today, Charismatic is getting less respect than most.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-1 long-shot winner of the Derby two weeks ago is 9-1 in
early wagering for the 1 3/16-mile second leg of horse racing's
Triple Crown at Pimlico Race Course. Many believe Charismatic
simply got lucky in the Derby, where his outside running path
around the turns kept him away from traffic trouble that hindered
many in the 19-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely going to be a lot of doubt, period,''
admits his jockey, Chris Antley. ``It was a troubled race. The best
horse doesn't always win. You have to be lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you've got to be careful. ... Don't discredit this
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Menifee finished a fast-closing second to Charismatic at
Churchill Downs, and he is the early 2-1 Preakness choice.
</P>
<P>
   The starting field is expected to include a dozen 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic is trained by D. Wayne Lukas, winner of a
record-equaling four Preaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   But Menifee has a strong Maryland angle on his side, too. His
jockey, Pat Day, has ridden five Preakness winners, one shy of the
record held by the late Eddie Arcaro.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers Lukas, Bob Baffert and Nick Zito have combined to win
12 of the past 14 Triple Crown races. Lukas also has Cat Thief
running today. Baffert, who scratched Silverbulletday, will be
represented by another filly, Excellent Meeting. Zito has Stephen
Got Even and Adonis.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble caused by a crowded Kentucky Derby field has caused
many owners and trainers of also-rans to give their horses another
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 12 Preakness horses also started in the Derby, tying
a record established in 1983. Other than Charismatic and Menifee,
trying again today are Cat Thief (third in the Derby), Excellent
Meeting (fifth), Kimberlite Pipe (sixth), Worldly Manner (seventh),
Stephen Got Even (14th), Valhol (15th) and Adonis (17th).
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers to the Triple Crown are Patience Game, Badge and
Torrid Sand, who was excluded from the Derby due to a lack of
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The tightly packed Kentucky Derby field forced Menifee to drop
far back in the pack early in the race from his No. 18 post
position. Despite slow early fractions that worked against them,
Day weaved the Blue Grass Stakes winner through heavy traffic
around the second turn and through the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Menifee made up six lengths on Charismatic in the final
quarter-mile and lost by only a neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did lose position in the Derby,'' trainer Elliott Walden
said. ``We fell farther back than we had to based on the speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Menifee starts from post 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be closer this time,'' Walden said. ``If he runs that
race back, he'll be tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Lukas, a seasoned Triple Crown veteran, Walden, 36, is a
relative newcomer to the upper echelon of the sport. But he already
has endured a career's worth of frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Walden's first Triple Crown horse was last year's Victory
Gallop, who like Menifee finished a strong second in the Kentucky
Derby and was made the Preakness favorite. However, Victory Gallop
finished second to Real Quiet again in the Preakness, before
pulling a photo-finish upset in the Belmont Stakes that denied Real
Quiet the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   So counting Menifee's near miss in this year's Derby, Walden has
a win and three seconds with four Triple Crown starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get to you a little if you allow yourself to dwell on
it,'' Walden said. ``But then you've got to realize how fortunate
you are to be in the position in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Menifee, Preakness horses with legitimate Derby excuses
are Excellent Meeting (crowded back at the start and in traffic on
the second turn), Kimberlite Pipe (held up in traffic on both
turns), Stephen Got Even (pinballed between horses on the first
turn) and Adonis (bumped repeatedly after the start and extremely
wide into the stretch).
</P>
<P>
   Also, Worldly Manner _ owned by powerful Godolphin Racing Inc.
of Sheik Mohammed al Maktoum _ was running in the Derby after an
eight-month layoff.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic, who twice raced for a claiming price earlier in his
career, has had plenty of racing and wasn't bothered as much by the
large field. But Lukas points out that Charismatic is improving and
did race three- to four-wide around both turns in the Derby, so his
victory wasn't a complete fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storyline all week has been that \RCharismatic\S got
lucky,'' Antley said. ``We'll be in the run of it, and so will many
others. I don't believe he'll be 30-to-1 again, but then again, I
don't think he'll be the favorite, either.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 0011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
