r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ALLEN-IVERSON-TEX     05-15 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ALLEN-IVERSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIXERS' IVERSON REMAINS AN ENIGMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Spend some time chasing Allen Iverson and come
away confused whether you're famished or nauseated.
</P>
<P>
   Starving for his celestial creativity, the cobra-quick moves
that make him the NBA's most dangerous offensive player? Or fed up
with his corn-row cockiness, the ``so what?'' attitude that makes
him the league's poster boy for the me-first, hip-hop generation?
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, you're not the only one struggling to find an
appetizing balance with Allen Me-Myself-and-Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   In a league long propelled by refined stars like Bird, Magic and
Michael, the NBA's next big thing brings to the hardwood table a
real, raw persona that features his trademark hairdo, untucked
jersey, a prison record, crystal doorknob earrings, endless energy
and a necklace pendant the size of Rhode Island. He also sports a
traveling posse led by a mother who wears enough gold to be Mrs. T,
sprinkles holy water on his forehead at halftime and often wears
her Philadelphia 76ers No. 3 jersey backward so ``Iverson'' is in
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a billion people who love me, but also a billion
more that hate me,'' Allen Iverson said before his team's Eastern
Conference quarterfinals series Game 2 against the Orlando Magic on
Tuesday. ``Not everybody's going to like me, and that's cool by me.
Look at Jesus Christ. People hated him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Like him or hate him, be sure to watch him. In the 76ers' two
playoff wins over favored Orlando, he has attracted and distracted
the Magic's defense for 30 and 33 points, forcing guard Penny
Hardaway to constantly double-team him and coach Chuck Daly to
label him a ``genius with the basketball'' while dusting off the
physical, focused ``Jordan Rules'' defense once reserved for His
Airness.
</P>
<P>
   He added an NBA-playoff record 10 steals to the 33-point scoring
soliloquy he put up Thursday that has the 76ers in position to
advance to the Eastern Conference semifinals with a victory today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to put him in this category, but he's like Michael in
that he gets his shots no matter how you play him,'' said Magic
guard Nick Anderson, one of five defenders assigned to stop him
this series. ``The best thing is to be physical with him, bump him
and knock him off balance into picks. But to do that, you've got to
catch him first.'' \Nsubheds:Crossover appeal Despite having the
league's signature crossover dribble, Iverson's signature may be an
enigmatic personality that his him visiting owner Pat Croce's ill
god-daughter at the hospital in the morning, then showing up late
for practice that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants `Misunderstood' on his tombstone,'' said Iverson's
mother, Ann. ``Because of the way he dresses and the crowd he hangs
with, people have put him in this little category of how bad he is.
He's a good guy, but you've got to get to know him to know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess `Misunderstood' will give him his little comment at
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   At only 6 feet, 165 pounds, Iverson is the NBA's biggest little
man. And with a green light to shoot and almost as many moves as
tattoos, he is the hardest player to defend since Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather go to the dentist than guard him,'' said Cleveland
Cavaliers guard Bob Sura. ``At least there aren't 20,000 people
watching you go through pain.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ability to swish 3-pointers, beat defenders off the
dribble and basically create his shot from anywhere on the court,
Iverson is the league's most unguardable guard. Despite giving away
12 inches and 150 pounds, he made enough rainbow jumpers and
electric layups to nip the robotic dunks of the Los Angeles Lakers'
Shaquille O'Neal for the 1999 scoring title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a little guy as good. You can't guard him,''
said Pacers president Donnie Walsh. ``He's too quick, with such an
assortment of shots. When he goes in with the giants he looks like
a pinball.''
</P>
<P>
   A No. 1 overall pick who led the league in turnovers as a rookie
in '96-97, Iverson this season took advantage of 76ers coach Larry
Brown moving him from point guard to shooting guard. Instead of
bringing the ball up court, Iverson now wears defenders down by
constantly moving through a maze of screens. The shortest scoring
champ in history and the first 76ers player to lead the league
since Wilt Chamberlain in '65-66, he likely will receive several
MVP votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without him, the Sixers would be the Clippers,'' said
Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson put up almost 27 points per game, though he averaged a
league-leading 42 minutes and 22 shot attempts, finished with the
lowest winning average in 42 years and the worst shooting
percentage (41.2) for a scoring leader since '57-58.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't, however, among the league leaders in modesty. Listen
to Iverson, and you'd think he averaged 72 instead of 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can guard me one-on-one,'' said Iverson, whose 30-point
playoff debut bettered the postseason beginnings of every
modern-day star except Julius Erving (33). ``God decided that, not
me. I think I'm the best player in the league right now.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, he led the 76ers to their first playoff
appearance since '91, overcoming his shoot-first mentality to give
Philly fans something to cheer about. Realizing his team was 1-7
when he scored 40 or more points, Iverson began to grasp the golden
rule: Shoot when you're open and pass if you're not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands now if he scores 50 and we lose, it doesn't
matter,'' said teammate Eric Snow. ``I'm not sure he always thought
that way.'' \Nsubheds:The `Answer' is While the league is promoting
squeaky clean players like Tim Duncan and Grant Hill as its marquee
attractions, its new scoring sensation is only six years removed
from being a 17-year-old sitting in a Virginia jail for his part in
a bowling-alley brawl. After an investigation and resulting
gubernatorial pardon, Iverson missed his senior year at Hampton
High School before going on to play at Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Few players _ as Iverson did last year _ have produced a
crossover move so nasty it knocked Jordan to his knees. Even fewer,
however, wear tape over their gaping earring holes, boast an
assortment of skull caps or consult former shoot-a-holic World B.
Free.
</P>
<P>
   While carrying the 76ers to the postseason and thawing a
previously chilly relationship with fans, Iverson also endured a
turbulent season. Not only did he trade dirty looks and dirtier
words with Brown, he was sued by Mercedes-Benz for $30,000 in back
payments on three cars, and he fired super-agent David Falk despite
a six-year, $71 million contract extension and the debut of his
wildly popular ``Answer'' shoe by Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   His critics point to his questionable circle of friends (which
includes Reebok executive Que Gaskins and childhood mentor Gary
Moore), his omnipresent mother who travels with the team and
brandishes her ``No. 3 is My No. 1'' sign in every arena, and his
selfish style of play. Jordan once ripped Iverson for his lack of
reverence for the game's older players and this season, Houston's
Charles Barkley said flatly, ``I can't stand him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you write the positive Iverson stuff you're not going to
sell a lot of papers,'' Iverson said. ``Write the negatives, and
those babies will be gone as soon as they're printed.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson, who turns 24 next month, also has irritated Brown and
his teammates by showing up late for practices, shootarounds and
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks he can stay out all night and still be dominant once
he gets to the arena,'' said Brown. ``He'll learn that's not the
case. If he was a pro, and I mean that in a lot of ways, he'd be so
much better.'' \Nsubheds:Growing pains While the detractors focus
on Iverson's professional and personal immaturity, his fans squint
through the hair-triggered haze to see potentially the game's best
player. Pacers coach Larry Bird _ seemingly the
substance-over-style anti-Iverson _ is staunchly in his corner.
Pointing out that mainstream America also wasn't ready for Walt
Frazier's sideburns, Erving's Afro or Pete Maravich's saggy socks,
Bird said Iverson's play speaks louder than his peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a chance to be one of the greatest guards of all
time,'' said Bird. ``All the other stuff doesn't matter. Five years
from now we might all be wearing corn rows, who cares? The kid can
play on my team any day.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he's had to referee several Brown-Iverson skirmishes and
on two occasions had to relocate Iverson's friends from complaining
season-ticket holders nearby, Croce said Iverson's maturation is in
motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen's really not someone you can talk to,'' said Croce, who
calls Iverson by his childhood nickname ``Bubba Chick.'' ``He has
to learn through his own experience and sometimes it's painful. But
he's growing. The first time I met him after the draft he was all
slouched over and wouldn't stand up to shake my hand. Now I get a
big hug after every game. With a guy this good, and this good at
heart, we've just got to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   If Iverson does admit to a shortcoming, and it's grudgingly at
best, it's his age. It's youth, he says, that gives him the vibrant
legs to make him the league's fastest player from
baseline-to-baseline. And also youth that prompts him to naturally
rebel against authority and conformity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess over time the critics will back off, but for now I
wish they'd just let me grow,'' he said. ``Everybody wants me to be
35, but I'm not. I'm going to make more mistakes, every day. I've
matured from five years ago, even a year ago. I can deal with it. I
wish everyone else would.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
