<HEADLINE>
`EL NINO' GARCIA STILL GOING STRONG AT NELSON TOURNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Just below the club manufacturer logo on Sergio
Garcia's golf bag are the words ``El Nino.''
</P>
<P>
   That's only fitting considering the way the 19-year-old Spaniard
has stormed through the two courses at the Four Seasons Resort and
Club the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who has neither graduated from high school nor earned
his driver's license in his home country, dazzled the galleries at
the GTE Byron Nelson Classic again yesterday with another stellar
round. After Thursday's impressive 8-under-par 62 at the Cottonwood
Valley course had him tied for second, he dealt with much tougher
conditions yesterday on the Tournament Players Course, yet still
managed a 3-under-par 67.
</P>
<P>
   The two rounds have Garcia, the British Amateur champion, at
11-under-par 129, just a stroke back of co-leaders Steve Pate and
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very good round for today's game,'' Garcia
said. ``Today's condition was really tough, and there was a lot of
wind and was changing all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather played a much bigger role in everyone's game as the
wind _ virtually nonexistent on Thursday _ gusted to more than 20
mph. Garcia also had the task of playing the TPC, considered the
more difficult of the two courses.
</P>
<P>
   However, Garcia played more like an experienced veteran than a
19-year-old, posting birdies early (on holes No. 1, 3 and 6)
combined with an eagle on the par-5 No. 7 before conditions
worsened. He then played the back nine at just 1 over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to play good golf and make some birdies,'' Garcia
said. ``I always try to be calm and just enjoy myself. If I make a
bogey, bogey. If I make a birdie, birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Garcia is controlling his emotions and enjoying the
moment, he also understands what a PGA Tour victory would mean. He
has already offered to dedicate the victory _ should he win _ to
the family of Gene Sarazen, who died Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was the only serious moment in a postround news
conference during which he repeatedly answered questions about
school, driving and his homeland. He also pointed out just what
kind of education he's getting here when asked what teen-age
experiences he's missing from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably I'm missing that,'' he said. ``But the guys who are
in Spain now, they are missing this. So I wouldn't change things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
