<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS: TIME TO STOP TALK, `JUST PLAY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Sergei Zubov doesn't want to talk anymore. Not
about his game-ending mistake in Game 4, not about how well he's
been playing in the NHL playoffs, not about Russian politics.
</P>
<P>
   The time for talking, the Stars defenseman has decided, is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to you before and bad things happen,'' Zubov said of
softening his ``no interview'' policy this week. ``Now, I don't
talk, I just play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars hope to follow Zubov's lead tonight in Game 5 of the
best-of-seven Western Conference semifinal series with the St.
Louis Blues. They hope to stop analyzing and stop dissecting a
series that is basically even in most statistical categories. When
the Blues and Stars meet at 6:30 tonight at Reunion Arena, talk of
power-play success, of who's winning faceoffs and whether Brett
Hull is scoring or not will become moot for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the talking can continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been analyzing everything so much and worrying about
what we're not doing well,'' Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig said of
a 3-2 overtime loss in Game 4 on Wednesday in St. Louis. ``All the
bad breaks in the last game, all the mistakes _ we have to throw
that all out. ... we need to start concentrating on all the things
that we're doing positive.'' Zubov might be the best example of
that, and he might be the key to any success the Stars have against
the Blues in the coming games. With much of the Stars' playoff
success on the line tonight _ the series is tied 2-2, and the Stars
have two of the final three games at home _ Zubov's philosophy
provides a peek into the collective mind of the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play bad, if I make mistake, I know it before anyone else
does,'' Zubov said in a prophetic moment before Game 4. ``I don't
need anyone to tell me what I did wrong, I don't need anyone to
show me. I know why I'm playing bad or good. I know how to fix
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock agrees. He coaches the Stars so that
plays will be automatic in the playoffs. Although Zubov made a huge
mistake in sending a high-risk pass through the neutral zone in
Game 4 _ a pass Blues center Pierre Turgeon turned into an
overtime, game-winning goal _ it was one of the few playoff
mistakes Zubov has made.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a great year, he's had a great playoffs, and he made
a mistake. So move on,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov is fifth in the NHL in ice time, averaging 31 minutes and
30 seconds per playoff game. He's fifth in the NHL in plus-minus at
a plus-6. So if he doesn't want to talk about it, that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk to him,'' Hitchcock said. ``But you know what we've
talked about _ we've talked about how important he is for our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubov is the point guard, the puck-controlling pulse of a team
that thrives on puck control. His calm hand is crucial in moving
the puck against the Blues' forecheck, which thrives on knocking
down passes in the neutral zone and heading toward the net on
odd-man rushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Zubie is he makes passes like the one he made
in overtime all year, and he makes them work,'' Ludwig said.
``Obviously, that was a bad time and a bad place, but he can't
change his game because of one bad pass. If anyone can handle the
pressure of that and the challenge of that, it's that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars need more positives from Zubov, coaches and players
agree. They need the positives more from Hull and Mike Modano and
Joe Nieuwendyk as well. They need that tonight more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge game, and that's what the playoffs are all
about,'' winger Mike Keane said. ``We've played this team four
times, and we're both pretty aware of what we need to do and what
we don't need to do. We have a lot of players who have been in this
situation before. Talking isn't going to change much now. We need
to go out and do it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
