<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-15 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BIG AS GAME 5 IS FOR STARS, IT'S BIGGER FOR HULL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the day before Game 5 of a fitful second-round playoff
series, and Brett Hull is lathered in perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other high-priced thoroughbred of pedigree, this is
supposed to be his time. His Kodak moment. His chance to bury, once
and for all, his playoff ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the day after a draining, second overtime loss to
St. Louis, coach Ken Hitchcock's optional workout had attracted 12
Stars players. Hull had been one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Hull again had voluntarily logged overtime after the
regular practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a solid player for us all year,'' Hitchcock says,
sitting on a locker room bench circled by writers from Texas and
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the way he's played. He has the second-most
minutes played on the team. And he's going to play a lot more as we
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, tonight's Game 5 of this Stars-Blues series
marks the most consequential game that the Dallas version of this
franchise has ever played.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hull, it is even more important than that.
</P>
<P>
   Lose to his old team tonight, and Hull will certainly face a
jeering chorus when he returns to St. Louis on Monday for Game 6.
Lose the series, and Hull will hear Blues management say, ``See _
it was Hull's fault in the playoffs all along.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not fair, but who would Hull be to argue?
</P>
<P>
   When St. Louis wouldn't tender him a no-trade contract, Hull
signed with the Stars for three years at $17 million, with a
reported option for a fourth year at $7 million. There were no
hidden motives here. For his $24 million, hired-gun Hull was
supposed to provide scoring depth and breathe new life into the
power play.
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, he did all that, scoring 32 goals, 15
on the power play. But now it's May, hockey's unkindest month, and
Hull must finally strut where he has always stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff time. No matter what Hitchcock said yesterday, Hull has
not been a $24 million player in this second-round series. Instead
of teaming with Mike Modano, he has logged time on the third line
with Benoit Hogue and Mike Keane. His contributions on the power
play have been inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   The ghosts howl.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull _ not lighting the lamp? Not putting the biscuit in
the playoff basket?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it doesn't matter,'' Hull answered. ``On this team,
all that matters is whether you won or lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole system is a team system. It doesn't matter if I
score or if Mike scores. It's the total package.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, grinder. Spokesman for hockey's new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   This is not your father's NHL, Brett Hull. But he knows that.
Gone are the 5-4 and 6-5 games, replaced by role players and
checking forwards. Ugh.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, great as he was, hung around and tried to adapt.
Mario Lemieux tried one more time and simply went home.
</P>
<P>
   Hull remains, a dinosaur of sorts. He has one frontier left to
conquer and, one would think, a cast to help him conquer it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here he is, backed to the playoff wall by, of all people,
his former team.
</P>
<P>
   He is supposed to be out there on the ice each night, firing
away or drawing attention, creating more ice space for Modano or
Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hull said yesterday, laughing, ``I played the whole
game behind their goal line the other night _ forechecking.''
</P>
<P>
   He says it doesn't matter. It doesn't matter, as long as the
Stars win.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock wouldn't say whether Hull's line mates tonight would
again be Hogue and Keane. ``I don't know who he's coming out \Ron
the ice\S with,'' the coach said. ``All I know is he's coming out a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The writers from St. Louis scratch their heads. They don't
recognize this guy, they say. This grinder. This new Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a real good player for us,'' Hitchcock tells them.
``To me, playoff hockey is all about how involved you are. Are you
in the middle of the battle, creating space? Because if you're on
the outside, watching, waiting for the battle to come to you, it
never comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock leaves the rhetorical riddle hanging in the air. He
doesn't name names.
</P>
<P>
   But he's talking about you, Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Time to silence the playoff ghosts. Time to show St. Louis how
much they should miss you.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stars, it is a game rife with significance. For Hull,
bigger. As big as it's ever been.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
