<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-15 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LIKE TWO BROTHERS BATTLING IN THE BEDROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It must be the rule of their series, or the nature of
the species. These familiar teams, these feuding Knicks and
frothing Heat, play until they no longer can, like battling
brothers squaring off in their bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The longer it goes, the more bitter it gets, which brings us to
the waning moments of a death-defying performance Friday night by
Miami, to Terry Porter flying downcourt on the break.
</P>
<P>
   Porter, 36 years old, the chief instrument of the Heat's 87-72
victory in Game 4, went in for the layup, with the Heat, up by 11,
pulling away. Latrell Sprewell, angling in from the lane, hammered
Porter to the floor. For the Knicks, it was a vicious punctuation
to an ugly quarter. For the Heat, it was one more reason to rush
back home in a confident rage.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Van Gundy, Pat Riley's assistant, stood up and walked down
the Heat's aroused bench. ``Remember all that,'' Van Gundy
screamed. ``Remember what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   They, of course, being the players coached by Van Gundy's
younger brother, Jeff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What the Knicks and the Heat do, three years running now, is
drain from each other every last playoff drop of blood, sweat and
tears. They return to Miami tomorrow for another endgame, Game 5,
after the Knicks failed Friday night to serve out the match and
series at home.
</P>
<P>
   They took an 11-point lead early in the third quarter Friday
night at Madison Square Garden, then splattered like the apple that
was heaved onto the court by some unhappy and unstable fan just
before Sprewell's thuggish foul on Porter. The Knicks made two
field goals in the fourth quarter against a team they beat two
nights before by 24. They shot 36 percent for the game and their
leading scorers were Allan Houston and Charlie Ward with 12.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Riley for doing what he does best, lathering his team
into a defensive fury, and for finally remembering Voshon Lenard's
name. Riley was so thrilled to be going home for another game he
actually made an admission practically startling for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have been wrong,'' he said of his refusal to use Lenard
in anything but garbage time in the blowouts in Games 1 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Lenard came off the Miami bench to score 10 points,
but it was Porter who was Riley's answer to the question of how he
expected to win a series, much less a title, with the offense he
dragged into these playoffs. Direct and adept off the dribble with
either hand, Porter dribbled Sprewell and Houston into a
near-drunken stupor, his penetrations scrambling the Knicks' team
defense and freeing up Tim Hardaway for the open jumpers he needed
to compensate for his wounded right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `Guys, we've got to put out heads down, take it
to the rim,''' Porter said. ``Now we go home, though I don't know
if we have an advantage. They've embarrassed us at home already in
this series. They came back and beat us during the regular season
after we were up 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens from here on out in this Kentucky Derby-like
playoff season, that game three weeks ago was the Knicks' most
significant in terms of their late-season development. They would
not have even come this far without it, so let it no longer be said
that the National Basketball Association's regular season is
virtual reality, except for the price of a courtside seat.
</P>
<P>
   Where would the winding river have taken the Knicks had they not
staged that inspiring turnaround against the Heat, the
fourth-quarter odds and the momentum of their own free fall from
playoff position? That Sunday, when the Knicks rallied from 18 down
with six minutes to play in Miami Arena, they finally appeared in a
defining moment as they had been conceived: quicker, quirkier, less
predictable than before.
</P>
<P>
   Before more rotten apples are tossed at the Knicks, remember
that they won Game 5 last season in Miami. They have that memory
and the game three weeks ago, which is the one that got Riley and
his players into this struggle in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said before the playoffs started, I didn't see any team
that I feared,'' Patrick Ewing reiterated Friday night. ``And I
feel that if we can continue to play the way we've been playing,
share the basketball, we can beat anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant Games 1 and 3, not Friday night, when the Knicks melted
again under Miami's defensive pressure, when the passive Houston
resurfaced and the wild Sprewell drained the offense of fluidity
and Larry Johnson fell in love with the 3-point line. It all came
apart in that 10-point fourth quarter, and Sprewell took out his
frustration on Porter, who said, diplomatically, ``I haven't seen
the films but I don't think he was going for the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he smiled, devilishly, and added: ``A good, hard playoff
foul. I'm sure it will be even more physical Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ewing would say, ``See you Sunday.'' Game 5. Knicks-Heat.
Battling brothers. The way it has to be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
