<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Eager for money to pay for the war
in Yugoslavia, the White House said it expected President Clinton
to sign a nearly $15 billion emergency spending measure that
doubles what the president had requested for the Balkan conflict,
for Central American hurricane victims and for hard-pressed
American farmers. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ By a squeaker of a vote, Senate
Republicans passed a measure to promote background checks at gun
shows. Democrats, preferring a more stringent proposal of their
own, almost solidly opposed the measure. By Frank Bruni. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-POLLUTE (Washington) _ A federal appeals court set aside new
air quality standards issued by the Environmental Protection Agency
in 1997, handing the Clinton administration a major environmental
defeat. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-DOCTRINE (Washington) _ In voiding a clean air standard, the
appeals court focused on the `nondelegation doctrine.' The notion
that Congress can violate the constitutional separation of powers
by delegating too much legislative-like authority to another branch
of government has essentially been a dead letter since the New
Deal. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-COELHO (Washington) _ What it means that Tony Coelho, the
archetypal Washington insider and fund-raising master, is going to
run the Gore campaign. By David E. Rosenbaum. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   ASSASSIN-GAME (Westport, Conn.) _ Beginning next week, 35 elite
college-bound students here will arm themselves with plastic guns
and stalk classmates through town. They have elaborate plans for
staying alive, and expect the annual contest to last three weeks.
The final two survivors will shoot it out in a park, then collect
cash prizes. But some students are bowing out this year, deciding
that four weeks after the killings in a Colorado high school might
not be the best time for the spring ritual. By Mike Allen. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HAWAII-TRUST (Honolulu) _ The Bishop Estate, a powerful
institution that has long been a source of intense native pride, in
recent years has come to be seen as the embodiment of Hawaii's
brand of inbred, closed-door politics. Most of the trustees were
connected to the state's ruling political establishment, so their
dramatic ouster has led to predictions of a shakeup in institutions
from the Legislature to the state Supreme Court, whose members used
to select the Bishop trustees. By Todd S. Purdum. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-MILWAUKEE (Milwaukee) _ A decade ago, an eccentric band
of reformers here set out to guarantee every poor person a path
from poverty _ an assured job at a sufficient wage with child care
and health care. But as the program closes its offices this week,
an exhaustive volume of new research offers some disquieting
conclusions. Among the adults, only 27 percent managed to stick
with their subsidized jobs long enough to escape poverty. Their
average annual earnings were just $6,600. By Jason DeParle. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   SEARS-CHILD-LABOR (Undated) _ The Labor Dept. announced a
$325,000 fine against Sears, Roebuck after investigators uncovered
child labor violations at more than 60 percent of the Sears stores
they visited. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   MALCOLM-X-DIARY (New York) _ City officials are investigating
how the bloodied, bullet-riddled diary of Malcolm X, which was in
his coat pocket when he was assassinated 34 years ago, got into the
hands of a private collector who is now auctioning it off in
California. By Kevin Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   NEV-GUN-LOVERS (Clark County, Nev.) _ 50 students gathered in
the desert for Ignatius Piazza's free submachine gun training
class. They came from all over the U.S., lured to this vast sand
pit for one day so that Piazza could pitch them his plans for the
first resort community in the world for gun enthusiasts. By Evelyn
Nieves. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ It has been exactly 50 years since
the death of Peter Maurin, one of the unlikeliest figures ever to
ignite a religious revolution. He helped create the Catholic Worker
movement, a mix of pacifism, anarchism and identification with the
poor that has had a great impact on American Catholicism and social
and religious radicalism of all sorts. By Peter Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DUKE-RESEARCH (Undated) _ A four-day-old ban on federally
financed human experiments at Duke University Medical Center was
lifted Friday after Duke officials agreed to overhaul their
protections for human subjects. By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-FALSE-REPORT (Undated) _ The 33-year-old reporter in
Kentucky who was fired Monday after revealing that she had lied in
her newspaper columns about having cancer to cover up the real
diagnosis, AIDS, now says that she has never been treated for AIDS,
either. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Belgrade) _ More than 60 ethnic Albanians were
killed and another 60 badly wounded late Thursday night when bombs
blew apart a village in southwest Kosovo, near Prizren, Yugoslav
officials and journalists at the scene said. By Steven Erlanger.
WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ After Belgrade charged that a
NATO warplane had fired on refugees in the southwestern Kosovo
village of Korisa, Pentagon officials said NATO warplanes were
attacking in the general area around Korisa, but that they had no
evidence so far that any of the planes had been near the village.
By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ A week after NATO missiles hit
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, China and the U.S. hammered out a
formal statement expressing the Security Council's `deep distress
and concern' about the attack. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott and Russian envoy Victor Chernomyrdin agreed this week on
some ways to approach Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. They
plan to confer with Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari to persuade
him to accompany Chernomyrdin when the time is right to talk to
Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTERNET (Belgrade) _ Internet enthusiasts were rushing
to send off last minute emails at one downtown internet cafe after
word went around that the U.S. was going to cut off Yugoslavia off
from the World Wide Web. The loss of Internet access is still only
a threat, but Internet providers here are worried that a partial
shutdown is imminent. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ A week after the NATO bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, President Clinton was finally able to
express his condolences directly to Chinese leaders in a phone call
that also touched on Chinese efforts to gain entry to the World
Trade Organization. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MRSCLINTON (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Hillary Clinton swept
through Macedonia on a visit that illustrated the Clinton
administration's continuing struggle to balance the diverse strands
of its Kosovo policy. By David Rohde. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ After a day of angry and vivid
speeches accusing Russian President Boris Yeltsin of crimes ranging
from treason to genocide, the Communist speaker of the Russian
Parliament predicted that the lower house would vote Saturday to
impeach the president on one of five charges. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-WELSH (Gaiman, Argentina) _ In this windswept corner
of Patagonia is a town of low mud-brick houses trimmed with ivy and
Protestant churches marked by signs in an ancient language that
only 600,000 people in the world speak today. The place has become
a beacon for Welsh people from Britain and the U.S. And the
lyricism and practical lessons of Celtic folklore, fables and
poetry have attracted the interest of some Argentines who have no
Welsh ancestors at all. By Clifford Krauss. WITH MAP.
</P>
