<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices jumped in April by an
unexpectedly sharp 0.7 percent, the largest monthly gain in nearly
nine years. A 6.1 percent gain in energy prices led the increase.
Still, prices for many other products and services, from food and
clothing to housing and medical care, also rose. A separate report
showed a stronger-than-expected pickup in industrial production. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-MOTORBIKES (Bologna, Italy) _ Ducati and the builders of
other Italian motorcycle classics are looking to expand, notably in
the U.S. They hope to imitate Italian luxury icons like Gucci and
Bulgari as well Harley Davidson in developing a new global
marketing savvy. But stock-market analysts remain wary. By John
Tagliabue. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   USWEST-GLOBAL (Undated) _ U S West, the regional telephone
company, and Global Crossing, an upstart company that operates a
worldwide fiber network, are in talks over a $30 billion merger. By
Seth Schiesel. WITH PHOTO and GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING-REBOUND (Undated) _ Manufacturing has survived
slowdowns in Asia and elsewhere. That would not be surprising
except for the fact that export growth has fallen sharply. While
services often get credit for the robust U.S. economy,
manufacturing is clearly holding its own, government statistics
show. By Michael M. Weinstein. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ By accusing American Airlines of
lowering its prices in a deliberate attempt to drive smaller
competitors out of its hub at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, as it did on Thursday, the Justice Department has adopted
a risky legal strategy. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   DERIVATIVES (Undated) _ The nation's accounting rule makers may
delay the date when companies must begin following a new rule that
requires them to record the value of derivatives in their financial
statements. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Against the backdrop of Russia's
political turmoil, the economy showed signs of growth for the
second month in a row, with some industries returning to their
pre-crisis production levels, according to a report issued by a
Moscow economic research group. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-APPOINT (Geneva) _ Anger and betrayal have colored the World
Trade Organization's deadlocked talks to choose a new leader, but
behind the emotions are three substantive issues _ the interests of
workers, farmers and the environment _ that have generally
polarized the 134-nation group, producing odd alliances of rich and
poor, big and small. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHEON-WEBMD (Undated) _ Healtheon Corp., the medical
record-keeping Web site based in Santa Clara, Calif., that was
started by Netscape founder Jim Clark, is expected to announce
Monday that it is merging with WebMD, a privately held Internet
provider of medical information. By Laura M. Holson.
