<P>
   NEW-THINKTANK (Washington) _ In Thinktankland, both conservative
and liberal groups have competed for years to convert their policy
ideas into policy in the real world. But a new entry, the New
America Foundation, has been trying to change the think tank
landscape. It seeks to introduce younger voices, break out of the
traditional liberal-conservative categories and produce
unconventional ideas. Yet no matter how many innovations New
America offers, none may be as brilliant as the one associated with
its founding: getting money from the cyberbarons of Silicon Valley.
By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ELLISON-JUNETEENTH (Undated) _ Ralph Ellison, author of
`Invisible Man,' has been accused of being an `Uncle Tom' and a
careerist producing `obsequious bleatings of white appeasement.'
Such accusations have faded, but there are still rumblings of
discontent about Ellison's persistent defense of American ideals
and his `elitist' esthetic demands. Matters are bound to become
still more complicated when Random House publishes `Juneteenth' _ a
novel posthumously constructed out of 40 years' accumulation of
notes and excerpts. By Edward Rothstein. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WILLS-PROFILE (Undated) _ A profile of of writer Garry Wills. He
has written `St. Augustine,' which tries to revise the popular view
of the saint, and the work may disappoint some sinners. Wills says
Augustine wasn't sex-obsessed at all but concerned with how sexual
dysfunction reflects man's fall from grace; and that the
`Confessions' was not a straight autobiography but `mainly a
theological meditation on his own life.' `Revelation is not simply
a text outside life,' he says. `Rather it enters your life in the
form of your own experience.' By Dinitia Smith. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
