<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO LEADS RANGERS PAST ORIOLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Will Clark wanted to re-sign with the Rangers
when he became a free agent in the off-season. Instead, the club
opted to bring Rafael Palmeiro back to town.
</P>
<P>
   Clark gave the Rangers his blood and sweat for five seasons,
playing every game hard, and contributing to the first two division
winners in club history.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmeiro showed last night why the Rangers made the right
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's two-out, two-run double off former teammate Arthur
Rhodes in the seventh inning was the big blow in the Rangers' 7-6
victory against the Baltimore Orioles at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good that I helped win a game,'' Palmeiro said. ``I
played with Arthur for such a long time, but I don't know any
particular pitching pattern. I just know he throws hard. I was just
looking for a pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The hit, which scored Tom Goodwin and Ivan Rodriguez, made a
winner of reliever Tim Crabtree (2-0). John Wetteland worked the
ninth for his 11th save, despite giving up a two-run homer to Cal
Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's hit was just inside the right-field line, and just
past the glove of diving Orioles first baseman Jeff Conine.
</P>
<P>
   Conine was playing first base because Clark, who signed with
Baltimore after the Rangers got Palmeiro, is on the disabled list
with a fractured left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Clark remains a productive player when healthy, but was on the
DL five times. Palmeiro, on the other hand, has played more games
than anyone else in the majors in the '90s. He has played in 34 of
the Rangers' 35 games this season despite having two knee surgeries
during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me to play every day,'' Palmeiro said. ``It
is important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the major reasons Palmeiro was in a Rangers
uniform and able to deliver the game-winning hit last night.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who was disappointed that the Rangers didn't want him, is
unable to show them they made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who played for the Orioles for five years before
departing for a free agent, has no hard feelings toward his old
team, but has hurt them badly the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   He had two doubles and the two RBI last night after going
2-for-2 with four runs and an RBI in the Rangers' 15-7 victory
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no extra incentive,'' Palmeiro said. ``I try to do the
best I can whether it's Baltimore or Oakland. I'm not trying to do
anything special.''
</P>
<P>
   As big as Palmeiro's hit was, an infield single by Goodwin
proved to be equally important after Ripken homered off Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Kelly was on second when Goodwin grounded the ball up
the middle. Orioles second baseman Delino DeShields fielded it
behind the base, and Kelly kept running. He scored to give the
Rangers a three-run lead, which proved vital.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won despite another less-than-stellar performance by
a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clark was in and out of trouble _ mostly in _ for 6 1/3
innings. He allowed four runs on nine hits and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   He left with one out in the seventh with a 4-2 lead, thanks
mainly to a two-run homer by Rusty Greer and a solo shot by
Rodriguez off Orioles starter Scott Erickson in the fifth, but the
Orioles tied the score on a triple by B.J. Surhoff off reliever
Mike Munoz that scored two runners Clark left on.
</P>
<P>
   The tie was broken when Palmeiro did his thing in the bottom of
the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
