<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOTHING NEW FOR ROCKETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The faces along the bench have all changed, but the
Houston Rockets are showing a familiar resiliency, a common trait
among coach Rudy Tomjanovich's teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' Game 3 victory over the Lakers on Thursday saved
Houston from an early playoff exit, but that's nothing new to
Tomjanovich. In his eight seasons, Tomjanovich's teams have faced
16 elimination games _ and won 12 of them.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the Rockets' remarkable string of eight
consecutive elimination-game victories through the 1994 and 1995
playoffs. Both seasons ended with NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   If he's got some kind of ancient Jedi wisdom that guides him
through adverse situations, Tomjanovich isn't saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speech (before Game 3) was, `I have no speech. I have no
Knute Rockne speech,''' Rockets guard Brent Price said. ``He's been
there before. He uses his past teams as examples all the time. He
said if we stick together, stay together through thick and thin,
through all the hype and the arrows being shot at you, we can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt all along we had the talent to win this series.... He
knew we have a great team and we knew what we needed to do. He
didn't have to say a whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tomjanovich's experience benefits him in more subtle ways.
Under fire, he simply exudes a calmness that his veteran team in
turns reflects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we had 10 (elimination games) in two years, and I bet
that's more than some coaches who have been around more than 20
years in the league,'' Tomjanovich said. ``So I'm used to having
this crazy feeling. I just don't get into panicky situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sort of learn. That's a hell of a situation to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets responded with a desperate determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in, we were in the corner,'' Tomjanovich said. ``As the
game was going on, we were laying in the corner. You know what I'm
saying _ when you're getting punched out and you're back there with
your arms on the (ropes) and we have to come out swinging haymakers
or it's over. So that triggered something in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Trends: History remains on the Lakers' side. The franchise has
taken a 2-0 lead in a best-of-five series on 12 previous occasions
and won the series 11 times. The lone collapse was in 1993, when
the Phoenix Suns came back from 0-2 and beat the Lakers in overtime
of Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   And the Game 3 defeat wasn't unusual. Before this series, the
Lakers were 7-5 in Game 3s after leading 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   In NBA history, 12 teams have come back from 0-2 deficits to win
a series, but only five times in best-of-five series. The last team
to do so _ the Rockets, beating the Suns in the 1995 conference
semifinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
