<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINSSABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES BEAT BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ It started off so promising, this series.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins won the opener over the Sabres at home and there was
optimism in the air. There was speculation that they could be
perhaps what the Washington Capitals were last season _ the
Cinderella club that rode a hot goalie all the way to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three games, the slipper has shrunk to the point
where there's no possibility of it fitting the Bruins. After Friday
night's truly awful 3-0 loss to the much-superior Buffalo Sabres,
the Bruins trail the Eastern Conference semifinal series three
games to one and are one defeat from elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is 0-18 in series in which it has trailed 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were outplayed, outhustled, and out-hit, and their
lack of experience showed. For far too many minutes, the team
looked completely lost. They looked like a group of tourists
dropped out of a bus halfway down the Mass. Pike and told to find
their way home. They didn't know where to start.
</P>
<P>
   As bad as it was, it would have been exceedingly worse if not
for goalie Byron Dafoe, as the Sabres came out with passion,
intensity, and a killer instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an old-fashioned ass-booting tonight,'' said coach Pat
Burns. ``That's what it is. There's no excuse for it. We got our
asses booted and that's exactly what it is. Now we have to react.
It's disappointing. It's not how you get put down on your ass, it's
how you get back up. We didn't get up today.''
</P>
<P>
   It was such a disaster it was hard to know where to begin to
break it down. One crucial spot was at the 3:35 mark of the opening
period when center Joe Thornton, clearly Boston's finest forward in
Game 3, was walloped in the head by the knee of right wing Vaclav
Varada and had his bell rung. Thornton went to the dressing room
for repairs and returned to the ice at 13:54 only to leave again,
this time for good.
</P>
<P>
   He played only four shifts for 2:51 before calling it a night.
That put a crimp in Burns's game plan. Burns had intended to bump
right wing Dmitri Khristich, a flat-out disappointment so far in
the playoffs, down to fourth-line duty. Once Thornton was lost,
however, Burns had no choice but to reinstall Khristich on the top
two lines.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, the Sabres, who were as dominant in this period as
they had been in the third period of Game 3, held the Bruins to
four shots while peppering Dafoe with 16. Dafoe, who faced a total
of 39 shots, managed to hold the fort through the first 20 minutes
but it was clear that if he didn't get some help, and soon, that
wasn't going to be able to last.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo put some real heat on Boston during a two-man advantage
for 1:37 midway through the middle period when Landon Wilson and
Kyle McLaren were called for penalties. The Bruins and Dafoe staved
off the five-on-three but at the tail end of the five-on-four, they
could keep the lid on no longer. Two seconds after the penalty to
Wilson expired, the Sabres scored. Defenseman Alexei Zhitnik, who
was public enemy No. 1 in Boston for the hit on Ray Bourque in Game
2, put Buffalo on the board at 8:20. Defenseman Jason Woolley fired
the puck down from the right point and Zhitnik, parked along the
edge of the crease, redirected it in for the 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, already without defenseman Don Sweeney (back
injury), lost defenseman Darren Van Impe for a time in the second
at 12:20 when he was felled by a Geoff Sanderson shot. He went to
the locker room and returned a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were so strapped for offense, it was almost pathetic.
At the 13:30 mark, the Bruins had a total of 10 shots, while the
Sabres had 10 shots in the first 6:30 of the second alone.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing happening for Boston, and it was especially
evident on a 41-second two-man advantage during which it failed to
even fluster goalie Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Sabres' dominance, the Bruins trailed only by a
goal. But that changed in the waning seconds of the period. With
16.9 ticks left on the clock, Varada, who had already done his
share of damage by knocking Thornton out of the game, teed up a
slapper from the right circle that caromed off the goal post and
past Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2-0, but it might as well have been 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   As if things weren't bad enough for Boston, center Michael Peca
only made it worse when he tallied a shorthanded goal at 11:39,
putting the finishing touch on a game that was already long over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were brutal,'' said Dafoe. ``They played great, they
deserved to win. They were the better team tonight, they've been
the better team all series, and that's why they're up, 3-1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
