<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8263 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUPONTCOLUMN-BOS     05-15 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPONTCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON CRASHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ The end to the Bruins' season came when Joe Thornton
crashed awkwardly into Vaclav Varada early in the first period
Friday night. Mathematically, officially, the end will come when
they lose their fourth game to the Sabres, perhaps as early as
Sunday afternoon at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   But realistically, it's over, and it ended in a thud, when
Thornton's head banged into Varada's leg with only 3:35 ticked off
the clock in the first period. Thornton returned later in the
period, but only briefly, and what already had been a struggling
Boston offense disappeared in total when Thornton didn't come out
for the start of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, we played bad the whole game,'' said the Bruins'
first-line center, Jason Allison, who again was hogtied by
Buffalo's sensational team-wide defense. ``We played bad from the
drop of the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we played, it wouldn't have mattered if we had Mario
Lemieux and Jaromir Jagr in our lineup. One or two guys just aren't
going to do it for us. We didn't play as a five-man team out there,
and when we don't do that, we're not going to win. They're just too
good of a team, too good of a five-man unit to beat if you're not
playing the same kind of game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, through head coach Pat Burns, only would say that
Thornton ``got his bell rung.'' In medical terms, that would mean
he was concussed. If so, the chances of his returning to action
less than 48 hours later, for Game 5 on Causeway Street, would be
virtually nil. The increase of concussions has been a league-wide
concern the last 3-4 years and extra precautions are taken before
returning a player to action. With the series at 3-1 in Buffalo's
favor, it especially would make little sense to expose a ``bell
rung'' Thornton to more action.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton was not available for comment. A team official said the
second-year center was told by Burns to make himself unavailable to
the media.
</P>
<P>
   Varada, meanwhile, stood in the triumphant Buffalo dressing room
and talked willingly of the collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a two-on-one (break),'' said the rock-hard winger,
who plays on the Sabres' No. 1 checking line with Michael Peca and
Dixon Ward. ``I came across to try to hit him _ and he dropped a
pass for (Sergei) Samsonov. I (went) to hit him and he fell into my
legs. He hit my knee. He fell right before the hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaclav's description made it sound as if Thornton was ducking,
and in so doing made his head vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Stymied for the previous two games, both losses, the Bruins
entered the night with some lines altered, including taking
Thornton's wingers, Steve Heinze and Anson Carter, and pairing them
with Allison. Thornton's wingmen were Samsonov and Landon Wilson, a
trio that rolled over the boards as the club's third shift of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton made it to the Boston bench under his own power after
his collision with Varada, but soon made his way down the runway
and into the dressing room. At about 13:45 he reported back to the
bench, and was back out on the ice at 13:54, this time with Dmitri
Khristich and Wilson as the siderunners. The period ended 0-0, and
it was the last ice Thornton would touch, other than perhaps a bag
of frozen cubes held to his distressed head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think what happened was, they lost Thornton early and it
hurt 'em,'' said Sabres coach Lindy Ruff. ``They tried to double
shift Allison a lot after that, but Thornton was out of the mix. I
don't they could execute after that.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know if they could have executed even with a healthy
Thornton. The Boston offense began to shrivel up in Game 2 at the
Vault, under a tremendous forechecking job by the Sabres. It
continued in Game 3. Allison couldn't find room to shoot.
Khristich, his right wing, continued his tiptoe through the Lost
Forest. He led the team in goals (29) in the regular season and has
the best shot of any Boston forward. All of that dropped out of his
game April 18, the Bruins' final game of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   When Thornton exited, it left the Bruins with only one true
scoring center. Khristich slipped in there as a makeshift pivot at
times. Otherwise they had Tim Taylor anchoring the checking line,
as always, and Shawn Bates as the fourth-line pivot. Bates, little
used in the postseason, showed some spark and hit Dominik Hasek
with one of Boston's few true scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to come in and play the way we've played the
last two games, we don't deserve to win,'' said Taylor, who again
took three pain-killing shots to assuage the hurt in his shoulder
and ribs just to suit up for the game. ``We have to play the way
they are _ that's with 20 guys playing, with 20 guys finishing
their checks hard and finishing on defense. Obviously, Joe's a big
part of our team, yes. It doesn't help us any when he leaves. But,
hey, it was 0-0 when he left, and we were still fightin'.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we played from there . . . we don't need guys going
one-on-one, trying to stickhandle through three guys. We have to go
for the rebounds, go for the jams, put the puck on net. That's the
only way we are going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The one true thing the Bruins had going for them, once more, was
Bryon Dafoe in net. Again, by virtue of the assault he faced, he
turned in a better game that Hasek. The shots were 39-24 in
Buffalo's favor, and quality chances were about 12-3 on Buffalo's
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you get more deflated than that first period?'' said
Dafoe, asked if he saw an emotional letdown upon Thornton's exit.
``He's a huge part of our offense, obviously you miss him. We all
hope he's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, added the goalie, ``It was a piss-poor effort _ not
something we expected in a Game 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Thornton remained in the mix, maybe Allison would have found
more room. Maybe Thornton himself would have popped in a goal or
two. Maybe that Boston attack that looked so sharp against the
'Canes would have revived. But without Thornton, there wasn't a
trace of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got off late tonight, that's the bottom line,'' said
defenseman Hal Gill. ``We weren't doing the things that we do well.
That's no secret. We got outplayed. We got outworked. We got
outhustled. That's not the way we play. That's not our team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Friday night, and now the end is near.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
