<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SHAUGHNESSYCOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS HAS WORK CUT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Bruins president Harry Sinden didn't mince words as he
walked to the team bus after Friday night's embarrassing, 3-0,
playoff defeat at the hands of the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the (expletive) kicked out of us,'' said Sinden.
``Tonight we were good players, no team. We didn't play as a team
and we got the (expletive) kicked out of us. I don't know what
their thinking was. This is a team game and if you play as
individuals, you're dead in the water. And that's all we do. That's
what it was tonight. No team. Buffalo _ they're a team.''
</P>
<P>
   So now the series returns to Boston Sunday and we find out if
Pat Burns is really Tuna-on-Skates. Can he coach and motivate young
players like Bill Parcells? Can he rally his troops against
impossible odds? Can he make these individuals play as a team?
</P>
<P>
   Burns expected his guys to show some fire-on-ice at Marine
Midland Arena, but there was no Bruins spark in Game 4. Don Sweeney
was out with a bad back, and Joe Thornton spent most of the night
in the dressing room after almost getting knocked out by a knee to
the head. Meanwhile, erstwhile snipers/playmakers Dmitri Khristich
and Jason Allison were harder to find than Tom Finneran at a
Save-the-Pats rally.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Patriots, this Bruins season is starting to feel
like the Fall of Foxborough we witnessed early last January when
all the Patriots were hurt and armed with excuses as they went to
Jacksonville for their playoff execution.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare for a Bruins team to play without heart, but at least
the coach and his players had no alibis for the
mistake-by-the-lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an old-fashioned ass-booting,'' admitted Burns.
``There's no excuse for it . . . We have to feel defeated. But it's
not how you get put down on your ass, it's how you get back up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuse,'' said bewildered captain Ray Bourque. ``You think
you're ready to play and come out hard, but they had the jump on us
all night. We got beat pretty good. We've got to play a lot better
and we know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Byron Dafoe kept the B's in it. It was 0-0 after one even
though the Bruins were outshot, 16-4, in the first period. He had
no chance on Buffalo's first goal, then finally cracked when Vaclav
Varada beat him with a slapper at the end of the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were brutal,'' admitted Dafoe. ``I don't know why we came
out the way we did. We just didn't respond all night. We didn't
have any pressure. I just try to stop the puck and I did it for as
long as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The B's were clearly battling their postgame depression from
Wednesday. New England's Hockey Krishnas know that Game 3 was
The-One-That-Got-Away and it now has a chance to go down in the
annals as the 1999 version of the ``Toe-In-The-Crease'' game that
effectively eliminated the B's against Washington last spring.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to believe the black and gold could be so lifeless
in the wake of Wednesday's heartbreaker. But they were.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 1-0, the Bruins had their best chance with a
five-on-three for 41 seconds late in the second. Boston got
nothing. Dominik Hasek saved a couple of weak efforts by Steve
Heinze and Anson Carter as Buffalo fans chanted ``Ray Bourque
Sucks.'' Meanwhile, Thornton was in the locker room after taking a
knee to the face from Varada.
</P>
<P>
   With 16.9 seconds left in the second period, Varada (as if he
hadn't done enough damage already) made it 2-0 with a wide-open
slap shot that beat Dafoe to the far side.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks earlier in Greensboro, the Bruins had trailed the
Hurricanes, two games to one, and trailed, 2-0, after two periods.
Those guys rallied with three quick goals at the start of the third
and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to have to be a major adjustment in our game,''
admitted Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to find it in yourself to come out and play hard,''
said Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost as a team,'' said Burns. ``Now we have to regroup.
It's disappointing. We have to make them believe it's possible.
This was disappointing. Now it depends on how we come back for the
next game in front of our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   It had better be better than Friday night. Bruins fans are a
discerning lot and will not tolerate another dog like Friday
night's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
