<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOXBLUEJAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BLANK BLUE JAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Two starts, two countries, two wins.
</P>
<P>
   The math doesn't get any simpler than that.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the geography.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Pena, born in the Dominican Republic, matured in Miami, and
made for Boston, won't be going back to Pawtucket any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old righthander, displaying the same unflappable
poise on this side of the border as he possessed in his major
league debut on Yawkey Way, shut out the Toronto Blue Jays on six
hits through seven innings in a 5-0 win before a modest gathering
of 22,186 in SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is easy out there,'' Pena said, betraying less
expression after the game than the one small gesture he allowed
himself as he came off the field, a barely discernible double pump
of his fists and a quick glance skyward. ``You have to work hard,
have to play the game, and leave all you've got.''
</P>
<P>
   With batterymate Jason Varitek hitting a two-run shot for his
first homer of the season and driving in another run with a double,
Pena struck out seven, walked two, and allowed just four balls to
reach the outfield in pitching the Sox to their seventh win in
their last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Blue Jays' six hits off Pena were infield hits,
including a bunt single. He was dismissed only because he'd already
thrown 115 pitches, and had made it abundantly clear that he'd be
needed again in another five days. Lefty Rheal Cormier made swift
work of the last five Blue Jay hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really picked us up,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams,
who in the absence of the injured Bret Saberhagen, the pitcher who
last season was the linchpin of the entire staff, has found an
unlikely candidate to stanch the bleeding. ``The (two starts) have
been special. Special just because of the kid. That's a youngster
out there that's pitching. He's really pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena, who paid little heed to the Mo Vaughn circus when he held
the Angels to a run on three hits in six innings last Saturday,
similarly showed no signs of being intimidated by his mound
opponent Friday night: David Wells, less than a year removed from
folk-hero status with the Yankees after being shipped back across
the border in the Roger Clemens deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid pitches in a vacuum,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan
said. ``It doesn't matter if it's home or away, grass or turf,
night or day. It doesn't matter. The kid is going to play his own
elevated game of throw and catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about making pitches, and this kid is fun to watch
because he's a pitcher. He's not a blower. He doesn't have a
dominating pitch. But he throws five pitches with location and
command, which is unusual for a young pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, the MVP of the American League Championship Series,
didn't allow a hit until Troy O'Leary's ground ball off third
baseman Tony Fernandez's glove in the fifth. But Boomer went belly
up before the kid did.
</P>
<P>
   Two outs later, Varitek doubled into the left-field corner to
score O'Leary, giving the Sox a 1-0 lead. With Jose Cruz Jr.
playing a shallow center field, Darren Lewis then drove a ball into
the left-center-field gap for a triple, scoring Varitek to make it
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Jeff Frye beat out an infield hit and Varitek
followed with a drive that just cleared the left-field wall. When
Varitek singled off the shin of reliever Tom Davey in the ninth, he
had his second three-hit game in his last three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I'm swinging the bat any better or worse,'' said
Varitek, who raised his average to .270. ``We've been constantly
working on keeping my swing short and more compact.''
</P>
<P>
   When Pena wasn't being deceptively clever, keeping Blue Jays
hitters off-balance with a street vendor's assortment of breaking
pitches, he was smart enough to be lucky, too. The Blue Jays hit
several balls hard Friday night, but usually right at someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come out unfazed by the big leagues,'' first baseman Mike
Stanley said. ``He doesn't seem to be nervous. He just doesn't
allow anything to show.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a night of exquisite defense by the Sox, starting with
Garciaparra's on-the-run throw from the hole to nab Toronto leadoff
hitter Shannon Stewart. Second baseman Frye made a diving stop to
throw out Mike Matheny in the third, then nabbed Stewart's liner
with a backhand catch and flipped to Garciaparra to double up Pat
Kelly with two on and no out in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all was the catch by Buford in the ninth, when he
sprinted almost to Buffalo before hauling in Fernandez's bid for
extra bases in front of the right-center-field wall in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the night was about the tall young Dominican
whose eyes betray anxiety only when he has to speak. Never when he
has a ball in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get rattled some time,'' Varitek said. ``Everybody does.
He'll give up some runs. Pedro (Martinez) gives up runs. But he's
not going to get intimidated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
