<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNSTON DOES DODGERS A FAVOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Shawon Dunston had the ball and the game in his
hands Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   He thought about how the St. Louis Cardinals had the rare
opportunity to beat Kevin Brown. He thought about how his slumping
team would get a boost from shutting down the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   And then he didn't think.
</P>
<P>
   His throw to an empty bag at third with the bases loaded touched
off a seven-run seventh inning that gave the Dodgers a 7-3 victory
in front of 48,036 at Busch Stadium. If that wasn't enough, Dunston
got doubled off first one inning later after forgetting the number
of outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing this game was my responsibility and that is not a nice
feeling,'' Dunston said. ``You don't get many chances to beat Kevin
Brown and I let that slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   The scorebook will show that Eric Young's slow roller would have
scored Todd Hollandsworth with the tying run. The pitching charts
will show that one batter earlier Cardinals starter Jose Jimenez
walked Brown on four pitches with two outs and two on.
</P>
<P>
   But in Dunston's heart, none of that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave this to them and it hurts me,'' Dunston said. ``Do you
know how much confidence you get beating a guy like Brown? He's one
of the best. We've been struggling and this would have gone a long
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had just two hits against Jimenez, who defeated the
Dodgers on April 23 in Los Angeles. In six of the previous nine
games, Cardinals starters did not get out of the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But after Jimenez (2-4) retired the first two batters in the
seventh, Hollandsworth and Mark Grudzielanek singled. Then Brown
walked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky,'' said Brown (4-2). ``The way I've been hitting,
I couldn't have hit it with a paddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals manager Tony La Russa added: ``Walking the pitcher
like that hurt a lot. Jose was starting to get his pitches up, but
I thought he was still OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he was just trying to make contact when his full
swing produced a perfect bunt up the third-base line. Dunston, a
longtime shortstop who is trying to stick around as a utility
player, thought he saw shortstop Edgar Renteria break for third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I saw was what I would have done as a
shortstop,'' Dunston said. ``All of a sudden the ball is rolling
down the left-field line and the lead is gone. I felt so bad for
Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   As Renteria raced to retrieve the ball, Grudzielanek and Brown
scored. Adrian Beltre made it 4-1 with an RBI single and Gary
Sheffield followed with a base hit to center. Clint Sadowsky took
over for Jimenez and Raul Mondesi, 9 for 21 on the recent home
stand with four homers and nine RBI, then doubled home two more.
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dodgers were happy to get a win in the first of
three games against the Cardinals, they also felt for Dunston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I seen that play?'' pitching coach Charlie Hough said.
``Hell, I've  &UR; !ital! &LR; made &UR; !off! &LR;  that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, who slid into first, didn't see Dunston's throw. He
didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has made that throw in their career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said he would have pinch hit in the
pitcher's spot for anyone but Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my ace,'' Johnson said. ``He pitched a gritty game and I
was going to let him try to win it. Almost anyone else would have
gotten pulled.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, coming off his best outing, an 8-1 victory over Florida,
limited the Cardinals to five hits and a second-inning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting better, but I still have some things to work
on,'' Brown said. ``It was a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown turned the game over to Alan Mills in the eighth. Mills,
who allowed a game-winning grand slam last Friday against Florida,
walked Mark McGwire, then gave up a two-run homer to Ray Lankford.
Dunston followed with a single. One out later, Eli Marrero flied to
right and Mondesi picked Dunston off first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was distracted, still thinking about that play in the
seventh,'' Dunston said. ``We had Kevin Brown on the ropes and I
fell apart.'' &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
