<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: KNICKS HAUNTED BY OLD LIABILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They became younger and more athletic at several
positions during the off season, but the New York Knicks failed to
address one glaring weakness on their roster. And as their offense
imploded in the second half of Game 4 on Friday night, the decision
to stay the course with their point guards may be prove to be a
major factor if they fall short of their post-season goals.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward played one of his better games for more than two
quarters, but after he left with a cut over his right eye with less
than 10 minutes left in the third period, Chris Childs was erratic
and the Knicks had no one to make good decisions and run the
offense efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ward re-entered the game, the Miami Heat was on its
way to a resounding 87-72 victory. Ward was just as much a culprit
as anyone during a disastrous 10-point fourth quarter in which the
Knicks again became the dysfunctional offensive unit they often
resembled in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Ward finished with 3 turnovers. Childs finished with no assists
in 20 minutes. The Knicks followed their disastrous lead. For all
their tenacious defense on Tim Hardaway in the first three games,
the backcourt duo self-destructed when it mattered most. Entrusted
with keeping the Knicks cohesive, they broke apart at crucial
junctures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were going well and then, you know, we relied
too much on jump shots,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``We were in
the fourth quarter, up four at home, and we didn't get the job
done. I mean, it's as simple as that. We lost our poise, and played
frustrated and got run over like they got run over in Games 1 and
3.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not just the fault of Ward and Childs.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell dribbled the ball off his knee and forced shot
after shot. Larry Johnson fell in love with the 3-point line and
forgot about working his way inside. And a meek Allan Houston could
not create any open space for himself.
</P>
<P>
   These were the misguided voyages of the Knick offense Friday
night at Madison Square Garden. In a series that keeps swinging
like a pendulum, they brought all their old regular-season
liabilities to bear.
</P>
<P>
   Little movement. Careless passes. A paltry 9 assists in 48
minutes. And 16 of the most disturbing turnovers this team has made
over the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   They threw away an 11-point lead in the second half. They were
outscored by 35-15 over an awful stretch in the third and fourth
periods. That stretch featured one field goal in seven minutes,
four turnovers and several ill-advised shots.
</P>
<P>
   For their awful effort, they earned an all-expense paid trip to
Miami Arena for a deciding Game 5. This is not where they wanted to
go, but it should suffice as punishment after what they put the
Garden's fans through.
</P>
<P>
   The game started to get away from the Knicks when Ward left the
floor with 9 minutes 49 seconds left in the third quarter.
Scrambling for a loose ball, he banged his head into Dan Majerle's
knee. Before Ward retreated to the locker room to have the cut
tended to, he had steadily directed the offense for three quarters,
converting three 3-pointers and delivering timely passes to his
teammates on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   When Ward returned with 3:59 left in the quarter, the Heat had
cut the lead to 55-51.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was down to his last point guard after Childs came out
with a bruised ankle and Ward picked up his fifth foul with 10:16
left in the game. Rick Brunson, the reserve point guard, came in
for 2 minutes. In his brief stint, he looked like a nervous
freshman trying to cut it on the varsity. Childs quickly went back
in, but he could not settle the offense down, either.
</P>
<P>
   The signs that it was going to be a long night for the Knicks
had begun earlier, when Ewing voiced his displeasure with Sprewell
in the second quarter, letting the sixth man know that he had been
open on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who shot 4 of 9 from the field, offered this analysis:
``I know when the ball moves, we get good shots and I play well,
the Knicks play well. I look at it as a challenge and an
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to miss shots, but you have to stay together. We
kind of fell apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks seemed to be on the cusp in Game 3, blending the
talents of Sprewell, Houston and Ewing into an offensive explosion
that produced a rout and seemed to signify a hurdle cleared in
their development.
</P>
<P>
   They shared the basketball. They cared about finding the open
man. But like a lot of other runaway games recently, it was a
facade. Friday night, without a floor leader, the Knicks were
clueless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
