<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8279 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POW-RAMIREZ-LADN     05-15 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POW-RAMIREZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER POW TALKS OF SUSTAINING POWER OF FAITH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- After a month in captivity, U.S. Army Sgt. Andrew
Ramirez said he was never more happy than when he saw Rabbi Steven
Jacobs walk into the Yugoslavian prison where he was kept to tell
him he was going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked into that room and saw somebody from my home, I
never had that much happiness,'' Ramirez said Friday night during
services at Temple Kol Tikvah in suburban Woodland Hills, across
the city from his native East Los Angeles. ``He told me the Dodgers
were in first place.
</P>
<P>
   Invited to speak by Jacobs about his experiences as a prisoner
of war, Ramirez told the audience of several hundred he had never
been in a situation where his freedom had been taken away before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to have faith in my country, faith in God and faith in
the people of the United States. Every day I prayed for a miracle.
I thank the delegation for putting themselves in that dangerous
situation. I myself was waiting for a Tomahawk cruise missile to
come flying into my room.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, 24, was captured along with two other Americans on
March 31 near the Kosovo-Macedonia border. Jacobs, rabbi at the
temple, was part of the delegation that met with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to help secure the release of the men.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson invited Jacobs to be part of the
delegation after they met in April at a memorial service in
Mississippi for three slain civil rights leaders. Representatives
from numerous faiths took part in the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never doubted for a moment even when the world told us
these boys wouldn't be released. They said we were foolish or
naive, but we believed,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation secured the release of the men May 1, including
Ramirez; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich.; and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On May 7, Ramirez arrived at Los Angeles International Airport
to a hero's welcome and has spent the last week savoring his
favorite foods, visiting with his family in Baldwin Park, attending
rallies and parades, and talking about his experience.
</P>
<P>
   Members of several area churches attended the service Friday,
including a gospel choir. The audience gave Ramirez a standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does this evening say about America?'' Jacobs asked.
``What does it say about our lives. I believe passionately we want
to celebrate life, not death.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised Ramirez's family for their strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a message about what happened. What his mother
taught us. They taught us not only about hope, but they taught us
how to cope.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said before the service that he struck up a friendship
with Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first week, his condition was terrible,'' Jacobs said.
``He was really beat up, and a bag was kept over his head. He was
in solitary confinement. They got by on their prayers, and their
faith brought them through.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs attributed Milosevic's decision to release the men to the
perseverance of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the art of not demonizing the enemy,'' Jacobs
said. ``Rev. Jackson has that ability. He told them (the soldiers)
are not trophies and they were no good to them in Yugoslavia. We
were determined not to be used, and we got them out.''
</P>
<P>
   After having been put in jail, suffering isolation, Ramirez
survived to teach us the great lesson of humility, Jacobs said at
the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no hero. He doesn't pretend to be a hero,'' Jacobs said.
``But he's a hero because he loves life, he loves his family and
he's willing to stand up for America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8280 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROTHERS-AZR &LR;      05-15 2039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROTHERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOVE/HATE SONG OF THE EVERLYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All brothers fight. But few do it in such a public fashion as
Phil and Don Everly.
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, 1973, rock and roll's most influential duo called it
quits. Phil smashed his guitar on a Knotts Berry Farm stage and
stormed off. His older brother was left to sadly tell the crowd,
``The Everly Brothers died 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next decade, the Everlys talked to each other exactly
once. It was at their father's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, of course, the pair that sang such timeless hits as
``All I Have to Do Is Dream'' and ``Wake Up Little Susie''
reunited. Sunday they will play a public concert in Phoenix for the
first time since their headline-grabbing 1983 reunion. But they
remain a prime example of the dangerous pitfalls that exist for
siblings who perform together.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's like taking a Sun Devil and a Wildcat, tying them
up in a bag and shaking the whole thing violently _ I wouldn't
recommend it,'' says Kevin Leman, a Tucson psychologist who wrote
``The New Birth Order Book: Why You Are the Way You Are.''
</P>
<P>
   Brothers in the music biz often have rocky histories. Oasis'
Liam and Noel Gallagher probably are more famous for their constant
feuding than for any of the music they created. For two years in
the '70s, Robin Gibb didn't speak to either of his siblings in the
Bee Gees.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes between Ray and Dave Davies of the Kinks are legendary.
John and Tom Fogerty of Creedence Clearwater Revival constantly
battled during the life of their band. When Tom died in 1990, the
two hadn't resolved their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs intensified the relationship between Cris and Curt
Kirkwood of the Meat Puppets. More recently, funk star Roger
Troutman of Zapp was shot to death by his brother, Larry. The elder
Troutman handled business affairs for his younger sibling and used
to be in the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you work together with family, there are simply these
big, added stresses to deal with,'' Leman says. ``It's never going
to be an easy road.''
</P>
<P>
   Leman should know. He's a regular on the talk-show circuit,
discussing his theories on siblings. Not only does he not recommend
that brothers work together, he thinks brothers in music face an
even higher rate of danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're talking about being a Rhodes Scholar or being a
lead singer, it's tough,'' he says. ``But imagine the pressures of
being brothers and being famous and being on the road _ would you
want that?''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence and Mark Zubia of the Pistoleros are aware of the
simmering tempers that can explode between siblings. The night the
Valley band signed a deal with Hollywood Records, a time when the
brothers should have been at their happiest, the two wound up in an
ugly row at Tempe's Long Wong's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a huge blowout on stage,'' recalled Lawrence, lead
singer and the eldest of the two. ``I can't even remember why it
happened. It was part of that family thing _ someone gives you a
weird look, and you're off. We were both lunging for each other. I
actually think I spit on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zubias can laugh about it now, but that
sometimes-frightening intensity is typical when brothers join
forces in business. It's amplified if it's in a field such as
music, a creative outlet that often forces people to expose their
vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier for people to get a little bit hurt,'' says Ben
Phillips, who is in a band with his two brothers. ``If I come up
with a song and my brother doesn't think it's any good, it's really
easy to get mad. If I was laying tile and he said it was crooked,
that's no big deal. But a song is more personal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Egos are on the line,'' says Leman, who studies relationships
between siblings. ``It's tough. Look at the Mandrell Sisters. You
know Barbara is the lead singer, but who can name the other ones?''
</P>
<P>
   Ben and his brother Nathan could probably relate. Along with
Randy Stowe, they make up zackphillipsband, a Glendale group built
around their oldest brother, Zack. And with Zack being the lead
singer, he's the obvious focal point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch us play, people are always staring at Zack,'' Ben
says. At age 23, he's the youngest member of the group. ``He's got
that ability to make people look at him. You want to see what he's
going to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great. I almost feel like it's a wave, and I'm
getting to ride along.''
</P>
<P>
   It's different for Nathan, however. Like Zack, he plays guitar.
The only reason he picked up the instrument as a child was because
Zack played it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that I wanted to be like him,'' says Nathan, who is
three years younger than Zack. ``It was that I wanted to be
``better'' than him.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't surprise Leman. He says siblings normally compete,
but a business relationship intensifies it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid, it's king of the hill,'' he says. ``The
whole point is supremacy. And the first born always has that. Think
of England: We've got the heir and the spare. The first born always
gets more than his fair due. Those second borns tend to want to get
their place in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Zack knows that. In the case of the Phillips brothers, the band
actually was formed around him when he needed a backing group. And
he acknowledges there's a competitive streak that exists between
him and Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like that with Ben,'' he muses. ``I think it's
because there's a few more years between Ben and me, but Nathan and
me kind of push each other's buttons sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The closer the kids are in years, there's going to be more
competition,'' Leman explains. ``If the age spread is bigger, it's
more of a `big brother/little brother' relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors exist in sibling relationships. On the positive
side, brothers know each others' sore spots, so they can tread
carefully around sensitive issues. On the negative side, that
information often is used to hit people in their weakest areas and
create a world of hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know each other ``too'' well,'' Leman says. ``You know
each other's spots. Fighting becomes an act of cooperation. You
know exactly what to say to escalate the battle further, and you
use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Zubia agrees. His brother may understand better than other
band members, but he also can annoy him more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it makes things easier,'' Mark says. ``I know my
brother, so I kind of know what he's going to say about certain
things. At the same time, when we disagree . . . well, your brother
can piss you off worse than about anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the saddest, most inevitable aspect of the whole thing
is that business often begins to override the familial
relationship. It's a constant danger when siblings work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamic with Mark and me is different than it is with my
other brothers and sisters,'' Lawrence offers. ``A lot of times, I
will ask them how Mark is doing, even though I see him more than
they do. We kind of stay out of each other's personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better that way. A lot of our time is spent with each
other, more than with any other family member. It's like we're
business partners and our relationship as brothers kind of falls by
the wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Phillips knows that feeling. When there's a family barbecue,
they talk about band business. When the band is together, they talk
about band business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The band is almost the only reason we see each other as much
as we do,'' Ben says. ``I don't talk to Zack on the phone. If
there's two weeks with nothing going on in the band, we don't see
each other, because we've all got other things going on. It's
almost like the band makes us personable to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a corporation,'' Leman says. ``You need to have
lots of meetings and lots of communication. If you don't,
everything becomes off center.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett and Brad Warner sing Everly-influenced harmony songs as
the Warren Brothers. The Tampa duo believe that by keeping their
business in order, the family ties won't be strained to the
breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't share money,'' says Brett, the lead singer. ``We
don't have a joint account. But that's the only thing we don't
share: We split publishing, sales and royalties right down the
middle. Nobody gets more than the other one. When we win, we both
win. When we lose, we both lose.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there are still signs of change in their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to stay out of each other's space,'' Brett says. ``We
have talent on our own. We can do things on our own. But when you
work with someone, it just gets different.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing business may not be the key to survival, however.
Leman says money should never be the driving issue when brothers
work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds as corny as ``Leave It to Beaver,'' but never
let money be the rule,'' he says. ``People are more important than
things.''
</P>
<P>
   As someone who has been both a casualty and a survivor, Don
Everly has his own ideas about how brothers can last in the music
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are the normal rivalries that exist in a family: Older,
younger, all that,'' he says. ``It's not easy _ it never has been.
But with a brother act, you have to bend over backwards, because
there's nothing equal. There just isn't. It's a hard thing, but
it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe how well people handle the strains can be traced back to
their families. For instance, all the Phillips brothers cite being
raised in a Christian household as a stabilizing influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up learning how to resolve conflicts,'' Zack says.
``We just couldn't stay mad at each other. It wasn't allowed. Now,
I don't think I've ever stayed mad at one of them for more than a
day. It just can't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad lives a block away from his brother,'' Nathan says.
``That's just how our family is.''
</P>
<P>
   And the opposite could be true, too. Don Everly almost seems
bemused when he discusses the 10 years of silence that existed
between him and his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not that unusual in our family,'' he says amiably.
``Mother didn't speak to our grandmother for 25 years. It's just
one of those things that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Everlys' split was one of the most public sibling tussles in
rock and roll history. Starting in the '50s, the brothers were
constantly seen on TV and heard on radio: Two similarly dressed,
similarly featured guys who sang gorgeous, amazingly tight
harmonies into one microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Don and Phil were never as close as the public believed,
it's hard to imagine they weren't at least very good friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that Phil and I had been working together
since I was 8 years old,'' Don says. ``We just got sick of each
other. I didn't have any feeling of self, of who I was as an
individual. I'd be alone in a room and people would say, `Where's
Phil?' ''
</P>
<P>
   There was a competitive streak between the brothers. Also, the
partnership was intrinsically lop-sided: Don always sang lead and
wrote more songs that the brothers recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were inborn, difficult things there,'' Don says.
``Also, there's the thing with being in a band. It's not an easy
thing. McCartney and Lennon had major problems. It's like a
marriage, and you're lucky if you have a marriage that works.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers reunited in 1983. Privately, they reunited with a
hug. Publicly, it was with two sold-out shows at the Royal Albert
Hall in London, then a series of concerts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the brothers tour a few months out of the year. Don,
62, lives in Nashville; Phil, 60, in Los Angeles. They only see
each other on the road, Don says, and they travel in separate
buses. They prefer separate dressing rooms. But it's working out
well for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good now,'' Don says. ``I think we sing closer than we
ever did, but now we have our own lives. Really, it's just easier
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   The voices don't sound much different from when they were
younger. Onstage, in fact, things seem pretty much the same.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, each brother has his own microphone. &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at 444-8096 or at
randy.cordova &LR;  &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
