<HEADLINE>
SHOW LOW MAN ANTES UP TO SAVE SENIOR LOBSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, it takes a big lobster to remind us that we have
feelers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Crusty the Crustacean is thousands of miles away, swimming
inside a tank at a Niagara Falls seafood restaurant. But the
20-pound lobster's fate has become the concern of a Show Low man
who is offering $1,000 to keep the marine life from becoming
seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good humanitarian thing to do,'' said George Morin, an
insurance broker, who saw a story about the large lobster air on
CNN on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of the senior shellfish softened Morin's heart like so
much melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thing should be out enjoying his old age,'' Morin said.
</P>
<P>
   Crusty was delivered to the restaurant on Thursday, crawling
amid his fishy friends from the Nova Scotia shore, said Gloria
Wall, co-owner of Fine Kettle of Fish in Ontario, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this one came out of the crate, we were a little
surprised,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The lobster caught the antenna of the local newspaper, which
came out for photographs. Television stations followed, and the
restaurant started getting calls from people who wanted Crusty
saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't doing anything with him at the moment,'' Wall said.
``He's our prize right now.''
</P>
<P>
   There's not a boiling debate about Crusty's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband (is) falling in love with him,'' Wall said. ``I
can't get rid of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall said local oceanography experts have estimated the
lobster's age at 65 to 75 years. Typical lobsters, weighing a pound
or two, are only a few years old, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does take a while to get to that size,'' Wall said.
``Usually, they're eaten by that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Market price at the restaurant is $14.99 a pound, Wall said. At
that rate, Crusty is worth a cool $300 boiled.
</P>
<P>
   Wall said most callers want to set up a Save Crusty fund or just
voice that they don't want Crusty to come out of his shell. She
said Morin's offer might be the only serious money that's been
floated.
</P>
<P>
   Morin said he just returned from a vacation in Hawaii, where he
felt attuned to ocean life. He wants to send Crusty to the Maui
Ocean Center for study.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy deserves a good retirement plan,'' Morin said.
``That's what I`m trying to give him.'' &QL; 
Richard Ruelas can be reached at (602) 444-8473 or at
richard.ruelas(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
