A8282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-1STLD-WRI     05-15 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY COUNCIL VOICES DISTRESS OVER EMBASSY ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs to update with Council's adoption of resolution, refinements
and additional details)   (bl)  
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A week after NATO missiles hit the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, China and the United States hammered out a
formal statement late Friday night expressing the Security
Council's ``deep distress and concern'' about the attack.
</P>
<P>
   A deal was struck shortly before midnight when China agreed to
drop an explicit statement of ``shock'' about the missile strike in
exchange for the milder language.
</P>
<P>
   China had initially insisted on a harsh statement that
``condemned'' and later ``deplored'' the attack. The United States
and other NATO nations objected, arguing that such wording
suggested the embassy bombing was intentional, not an accident, as
NATO maintains.
</P>
<P>
   China's insistence on a statement effectively delayed Council
action on other pending issues. Among them was a three-week-old
resolution on the plight of Kosovo refugees that endorsed
principles of a peace settlement adopted by the Western powers and
Russia earlier this month in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday morning, the Council finally adopted that
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Furious about the strike on its embassy, China maintained that a
formal statement on the embassy bombing needed top priority on the
Council's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   While many Council members sympathized with China's indignation
over the attack that killed three and injured 20 more, several were
exasperated by Beijing's decision, in effect, to hold the Council's
business hostage to the apology it wanted. One African nation
complained that China was holding up an extension of the
authorization of a peacekeeping mission in the Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   Five nations, including China, are permanent Council members,
and can veto any formal action. But on presidential statements,
like this one, the Council operates on consensus, making it easy
for unhappy members to disrupt or delay proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Even the weakened wording to ``deplore'' the bombing had been
unacceptable to the United States and its NATO allies. ``We will
not agree to deplore,'' Peter Burleigh, the acting representative
here, told reporters after he had sought instructions from
Washington on the latest Chinese draft.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials objected because they said it suggested that NATO
had intentionally attacked the embassy, a diplomatic installation
that under international law cannot be targeted. ``Would you
deplore a tornado?'' said one Western official, explaining
Washington's stance.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock was broken late Friday night after Burleigh huddled
with his counterpart, Chinese Ambassador Qin Huasun, Friday evening
and proposed that the Council regret the incident rather than
``deplore'' it.
</P>
<P>
   After an initial period of confusion, U.S. and NATO officials
have repeatedly apologized for what they have called a tragic
mistake. President Clinton succeeded in getting Chinese President
Jiang Zemin to accept his telephone call Friday expressing
condolences and apologies.
</P>
<P>
   After agreeing on the compromise wording, the Council members
met in a formal, televised session where they stood for a moment of
silence in memory of the three Chinese victims of the missile
strike. Then they approved the statement, the Council's first
official reaction to the embassy bombing. A second minute of
silence was observed for the victims of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Few diplomats said that they thought China would delay
considering a peace plan for Kosovo once NATO and Russia agreed on
a proposal to restore peace in the Balkans and return the Kosovar
Albanian refugees to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   But China earlier in the week blocked the resolution about the
refugees, which endorsed the principles adopted for peace in
Yugoslavia adopted earlier this month by the G-8 nations. The
resolution passed early Saturday with Russia and China abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and NATO wanted the Council to approve that
resolution because it was sponsored by influential developing
countries and Islamic states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
