<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SEATTLE-SPI &LR;      05-15 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUBDUED CLINTON ADDRESSES SEATTLE FUND RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY AND LISA STIFFLER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ President Clinton dropped into Seattle on Friday for a
serious, pensive and nostalgic speech to big Democratic donors in
which he defended NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia and called for
national resolve in curbing school violence.
</P>
<P>
   In sober talk not often heard at $5,000-a-head fund-raisers,
Clinton decried the atrocities committed by Serbs in the name of
``religion, ethnicity, an imagined history and old slights.'' He
also spoke of a national need to reach ``disconnected kids in
America'' before they commit acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 32-minute speech _ which often treated his
not-yet-complete presidency in the past tense _ dealt extensively
with the aftermath of the Littleton, Colo., school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Littleton happened, it broke a dam in the psyche of
America,'' the president said. ``We owe it to the families and the
kids who perished not to let this opportunity pass, and not let it
descend into finger-pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spun off figures on the decline in crime, said the
country is moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want to see our attempts to save our children
turned into Chapter 57 of America's ongoing cultural war for
someone's political advantage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to see is every single segment of our society
stand up and say, not that it's someone else's fault, but `What can
I do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The president's fund-raiser was unspectacular in its proceeds.
Democratic and corporate donors ponied up about $200,000 _ less
than insurgent Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley raised
here last month.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the 70 or so people who showed up at Seattle's
Rainier Club said they were moved by his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``His potential for charismatic and inspiring leadership was
never in question,'' Seattle Mayor Paul Schell said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Open and ebullient on previous Northwest visits, Clinton spent
his time Friday in the protective cocoon of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He did not answer questions about regional issues. His only
audience was seven tables of major donors behind closed doors at
the Rainier Club. He made a brief stop at the Elliott Bay Book Co.,
which later produced rush-hour tie-ups as traffic on Interstate 5
was held up to accommodate Clinton's motorcade on its swift passage
back to Boeing Field.
</P>
<P>
   The president who once loved to work crowds at Pike Place Market
rallies ducked into his limousine outside the Pioneer Square
bookstore with only a perfunctory wave to shoppers kept behind rope
lines a half-block away.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle stop opened a three-day fund-raising tour devoid of
public events. Clinton moved on last night to California's Silicon
Valley for a $25,000-a-couple dinner. On Saturday night he will be
in Los Angeles for a dinner _ starting at $25,000 a couple _ held
by Hollywood moguls and Dreamworks partners David Geffen, Steven
Spielberg and Jeffrey Katzenberg. The president will spend Monday
at similar events in San Diego and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit was different from past Seattle stopovers in
another respect _ he was greeted by chanting demonstrators
representing multiple causes and both ends of the political
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors, students and downtown employees on their lunch breaks
protested issues ranging from the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia to the
Makah's attempts to harpoon a gray whale to the alleged leaking of
U.S. strategic weapons information to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton, stop raping Serbia,'' one sign said. Another placard
said, ``By land or by sea, human or animal killing is still
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of protests focused on the bombing of targets in
Serb-dominated Yugoslavia, a campaign mounted to force withdrawal
of Serbian forces from the largely ethnic Albanian province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the leaders of the countries who want the war,''
retiree Emert Browning said. ``The thing that bothers me is that we
are spending billions of dollars (on the bombings).''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrived at 1:20 p.m., the demonstrators erupted
with the chant ``Stop the bombing now, Bill,'' easily drowning out
the handful of onlookers clapping and cheering in support of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Rainier Club, Clinton and his supporters _ including
veterans of Vietnam-era anti-war protests _ defended the NATO
campaign in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   King County Executive Ron Sims, co-chairman of the luncheon,
spoke of taking his three sons to the Holocaust Museum in
Washington, D.C., which recounts the Nazi extermination of 6
million European Jews during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky to have a president who decided that kind of
genocidal activity had to stop,'' said Sims, referring to the
ethnic cleansing in which Kosovo residents have been driven from
their homes and in some cases killed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spoke with China's President Jiang Zemin on his
flight to Seattle, repeated his apologies for last week's
destruction of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a terrible mistake with the bombing of the Chinese
Embassy, and I regret it more than I can say,'' the president said.
Clinton noted, however, that people can see Belgrade bomb damage on
CNN _ while the Serbian atrocities in closed-off Kosovo are ``what
you can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke of an incident in which 15 men allegedly were
roped together and burned alive, and of mass rapes committed
against Albanian women, who then face ostracism in their Muslim
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the promise of the 21st century to be overthrown
by the oldest poison in human existence,'' said Clinton, referring
to ethnic hatreds that have claimed thousands of lives and
dislocated more than a million people in states that formerly made
up Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The speech brought tears to the eyes to one listener, Maryann
Tagney Jones of Washington Conservation Voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking about the fact that they (Serbs) chose to rape
young women because they were Muslim, knowing what that would do to
their lives,'' she said. ``Just the thought of that, the base
brutality, made me cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
