<SLUG> BC-BBC-LONGBEACH-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH STATE SHUTS OUT NO. 1 FULLERTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave Snow, Long Beach State's baseball coach, was worried all
week how to get his Dirtbags sufficiently motivated following two
agonizing one-run Big West Conference losses earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   All he had to do, it turned out, was mention the ``F'' word.
</P>
<P>
   Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   The Dirtbags' Jeff Leuenberger and Jeremy Ward combined to shut
out the No. 1-ranked Cal State Fullerton Titans, 4-0, Friday night
before 1,575 at Titan Field.
</P>
<P>
   It's only the second time in 119 games the Titans have been shut
out, both times by Long Beach State the only times in the long
series the 49ers have blanked Fullerton. Mike Gallo shut out the
Titans, 12-0, in last year's Big West tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Leuenberger, in just his third start, restricted the
heavy-hitting (.349) Titans to just one hit over the first five
innings. He pitched out of a bases-loaded, one-out jam in the sixth
and allowed just five hits a season low for Fullerton before
leaving after eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ward pitched the ninth for his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, 49er coach Dave Snow became the Big West's
all-time winningest coach. It was Snow's 188th conference victory,
one more than Fresno State's Bob Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Jaeme Leal slugged his 20th home run, a two-run blow in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fullerton's Adam Johnson (9-3) absorbed the loss, his second
this season against Long Beach State, and his first in seven
decisions at home despite striking out 11 in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dirtbags are 31-20, 18-10 in Big West play. Fullerton, which
clinched its 17th Big West crown last weekend, is 43-10, 24-4.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson struggled with his control early on, issuing two walks
and hitting a batter, Leal, in the first two innings. He was wild
again in the third inning, and this time it cost him.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Redfox started the third by reaching first on a fielding
error by third baseman Ryan Owens. Johnson struck out A.J.
LaBarbera, but Chris Wright singled to center and Terrmel Sledge
walked, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson then hit Leal a second time, forcing home Redfox. It was
the 20th time Leal has been hit this season, and he was hit again
in the ninth. He's only three shy of Bryan Kennedy's school record,
established last season. Remarkably, Leal has been hit by a pitch
more times than he's walked (20).
</P>
<P>
   Greg Dobbs followed with a bloop single to left, that barely
eluded shortstop Murph Norris. Wright scored easily. But Sledge,
who held up until he was certain Norris wouldn't make the catch,
was thrown out at the plate on a strong throw by left fielder
Spencer Oborn.
</P>
<P>
   Leal's two-run homer in the fifth, which followed a leadoff
single by Sledge, jumped the Dirtbags' lead to 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Fullerton, meantime, managed to get only two runners get as far
as second base the first five innings against Leuenberger. But in
the sixth the Titans loaded the bases with one out on two walks and
a single.
</P>
<P>
   Leuenberger escaped by getting pinch hitter Sean Bischofberger
who replaced Chris Beck, a .421 hitter who was hit on the wrist by
a pitch his previous at-bat to foul out, then got Aaron Rifkin to
ground out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
