<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S ZITO STAYS UNBEATEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USC ace Barry Zito hardly had his best stuff Friday night, but
he didn't need it to keep the Trojans' slim hopes for the
Pacific-10 Conference title alive at least one more day.
</P>
<P>
   Zito allowed six runs in the first five innings, but with the
Trojans' offense scoring at will he managed to earn the victory as
16th-ranked USC defeated Washington 13-6 in front of 659 at Dedeaux
Field.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Zito (11-2) completed Pac-10 play with a
perfect 8-0 record, the first pitcher to go undefeated in
conference play since USC's Seth Etherton went 10-0 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Zito allowed nine hits in 61/3 innings but had his usual heat,
striking out nine. He has 37 strikeouts in his past three starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (32-22, 16-6) remained two games behind conference
leader Stanford, which defeated host UCLA 8-7 in extra innings
Friday. USC must win its final two games this weekend and the
Cardinal must lose both games for the Trojans to win the Pac-10
title.
</P>
<P>
   USC would win a tiebreaker with the Cardinal if the teams finish
with identical records.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Zito might not earn a decision until the Trojans
broke the game open in the sixth by scoring four runs.
</P>
<P>
   USC held a 7-6 lead when second baseman Dominic Correa hit a
two-run single and third baseman Beau Craig followed with a two-run
homer to right field that gave the Trojans an 11-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Craig's sacrifice fly had given the Trojans their 7-6 lead in
the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   If there weren't so much at stake in the conference race, the
game might be remembered for the 4-6-3-2 triple play that USC
catcher Eric Munson hit into in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Munson, who also homered, played his first game at catcher since
March 27, when he injured his hand against Washington State. He
demonstrated he had recovered in the second inning when he threw
out a runner attempting to steal third base.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans took their first lead in the fourth inning, but it
didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded, USC designated hitter Carlos Casillas
singled home a run to give the Trojans a 5-4 lead. Washington
starter Travis Anderson then walked Justin Gemoll to force in
another run and extend USC's lead to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington's Nick Stefonick homered in the fifth inning to
trim the margin to 6-5 and the Huskies (31-20, 11-11) tied the game
for the fourth time on Todd Linden's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Zito started off poorly, allowing a two-run homer to Huskies
catcher Dominic Woody in the first inning. It was Woody's 17th home
run, setting a Washington single-season record.
</P>
<P>
   USC cut the lead to 2-1 when Munson homered over the
center-field fence in the second inning. Correa followed with a
double and scored on a fielder's choice by Brad Ticehurst. USC took
the lead when Ticehurst scored on a passed ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies took a 4-3 lead in the third when Bryan Williamson
had an RBI single and scored on Todd Linden's bloop single.
</P>
<P>
   In the same inning, USC tied the game again after Greg Hanoian
doubled and scored on a wild pitch by Anderson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
