<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     05-15 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER EYES AREN'T THE ONLY ONES ON RODRIGUEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This is why Alex Rodriguez is going to cost some lucky
team all that money: Because he is so smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite missing the last 32 games recovering from knee surgery
and despite feeling nervous about his comeback Friday night,
Rodriguez helped turn a double-play in the first inning on the very
first ball he handled.
</P>
<P>
   Guess watching Derek Jeter and Nomar Garciaparra this past week
made the Mariner shortstop antsy to make something happen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kansas City leadoff hitter Carlos Beltran was sliding into
second and heading right toward that leg that Rodriguez knows will
take three more weeks before it's 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But there was A-Rod, gracefully stepping back out of the way and
looping that sidearm throw to first for the 4-6-3 that felt oh so
good for him and all his adoring fans.
</P>
<P>
   And this, too, is why Alex Rodriguez is going to cost some lucky
team all that money: Because he is the master of the big moment,
almost as much as his superstar counterpart in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Despite not having faced major league pitching in five long
weeks, Rodriguez stood in the batter's box in the bottom of the
first Friday and lifted a 2-0 pitch down and away for an opposite
field home run.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the diving stop he made in the seventh on
Jermaine Dyes' grounder between short and third. Ball in glove,
A-Rod pushed up onto his good knee and got off a throw to get Dye
out at first.
</P>
<P>
   Grace, power, style, confidence. Speed, too, although top speed
may be several weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was thrown out stealing in a strike `em out, throw `em
out double play in the third. But by the sixth, Rodriguez was
already a notch higher on the octane when he ran out a grounder and
wound up on first base, clapping his hands and laughing in relief
that the leg felt so sound.
</P>
<P>
   Then he stole second. Take that, torn medial meniscus!
</P>
<P>
   You know this guy can blow around the bases like he wants to get
to Cooperstown tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But in case you're still wondering if everyone was ecstatic that
Alex Rodriguez is back, consider this scene:
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez and his surgically repaired knee stood at short
during batting practice for the first time since the second game of
the season, this is what happened.
</P>
<P>
   First came Jay Buhner. The right fielder wandered over to the
infield and stood next to the latest arrival off the disabled list.
It was the unofficial welcome. It was Buhner's way of noting things
are back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Russ Davis, David Segui and Edgar Martinez. They all
but swarmed Rodriguez, making it look like it was going to be
shortstop by committee for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, David Bell joined the party _ everyone joking and
clustered around Rodriguez, who looked at Friday night's comeback
like it was opening day only without spring training.
</P>
<P>
   You bet the Mariners are thrilled to have their 23-year-old
40/40 man back, hitting in front of Ken Griffey and Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   And in the stands, the early arriving boys clamored for
autographs from their favorite player and the girls all screamed at
the ballplayer with the matinee idol looks and a growing list of
Hall of Fame credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners and their fans aren't the only ones interested
in seeing young Alex back at work.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are probably taking note of A-Rod's return. The
Mets, too. Maybe even Atlanta or Cleveland, despite the fact that
Rodriguez despises that team because of all the times Cleveland has
beaten the M's.
</P>
<P>
   But this is baseball in the high-rolling '90s. A few teams can
look at A-Rod and wonder how and when to make a bid because the M's
certainly will have to listen.
</P>
<P>
   And the way Jeff Fassero threw gasoline on the fire Friday with
another homer-plagued outing, the Mariners will have to take note
of any interest, if only to be smart, because by now they know they
are beyond desperate for pitching.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more than a handful of Mariner players were willing to
speculate that scouts from one or more of the big-money, big-time
teams might find their way to the Kingdome soon to watch Rodriguez,
just to get a glimpse of what their futures might hold, because the
M's will have to do something, one day.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets can afford to dream of having Rodriguez in their
lineup, batting in front of Mike Piazza and John Olerud. Meanwhile,
money is no object for anyone Rupert Murdoch wants to dress in
Dodger blue.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that is getting ahead of the game. For now, young
Alex belongs to the M's and the good citizens of Marinerville.
</P>
<P>
   The M's say it would be heresy for Rodriguez to never set foot
in the new stadium, even as monied teams like the Mets and Dodgers
might already be looking into a trade.
</P>
<P>
   For now, and through this season, A-Rod's place is with Griffey
and Martinez, Buhner and Segui.
</P>
<P>
   That much the Mariners have made clear, even when so many other
things seem up in the air, including the longballs the Mariners
shortstop can launch and the offensive numbers Rodriguez will post
in a career where the sky's the limit and the money he will command
will be even loftier.
</P>
<P>
   It's just too bad A-Rod can't throw a slider, too.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
