<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8311 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     05-15 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN, BELCHER LEAD ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ It was the power of the almighty Disney dollar, and it
was on display Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mo Vaughn hitting, Tim Belcher pitching, and just as
general manager Bill Bavasi planned it over his Christmas egg nog,
it was the Angels winning, 8-3 over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels shelled out $90.2 million on those two players over
the winter. Belcher has been slow to deliver returns but stemmed
the tide of an awful April with six quality innings. Vaughn
provided the offense, breaking a scoreless tie with a grand slam in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also had a chance to become the third player in the
majors this season _ and the 12th in major-league history _ to hit
two grand slams in a game when he came up with the bases loaded in
the seventh. But reliever Al Newman balked in a run before he could
deliver a pitch, and Vaughn settled for a two-run single, bringing
his RBI total on the night to six.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's slam, his first as an Angel, was received ecstatically
by the Edison Field crowd of 35,515. But it was Belcher who made
the Angels beam the brightest.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher left before reporters were allowed in the Angels
clubhouse, but Vaughn made sure his slam didn't overshadow the
right-hander's clutch outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest story (Friday night) was Tim Belcher,'' Vaughn
said. ``I'm just glad the guy pitched the way he did. Whoever gets
him the runs... we've all got to do our part. I was happy to help
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Angels manager Terry Collins: ``We got big innings from Tim
and the big hit from Mo. We keep doing that, we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays held a lengthy meeting before the game. They
couldn't have been going over how to face Belcher. That's barely a
discussion these days.
</P>
<P>
   He throws a fastball? Hit it. He throws a change? Hit it. He
misses over the plate? Hit it hard.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher entered with an ERA of 9.89. He had allowed at least
five runs in six of seven starts and had survived past the sixth
inning just once. Left-handers were hitting .427 against him, and
the Devil Rays' lefty-laden lineup was 16-12 against right-handed
starters.
</P>
<P>
   Not a good omen.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash had gotten so bad, Collins was forced to defend
himself on the street for sticking with Belcher in the rotation. He
couldn't sit down to breakfast at an Anaheim coffee shop without
hearing at least one snide remark from an adjacent table.
</P>
<P>
   Collins won't need to defend Belcher when he goes for his
morning latte today. Belcher's outing said enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo's hit was huge for us. It got us on the board,'' Collins
said. ``But the night belonged to Tim Belcher. He hit his spots and
pitched a heck of a game. He needed it and we needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher has typically come unglued in fifth innings. But he
emerged unscathed for once, again getting help from Troy Glaus.
Aaron Ledesma led off with a rocket that a diving Glaus stabbed on
the short-hop. Belcher then struck out Kevin Stocker and got
Quinton McCracken to fly out.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher (2-3) took a one-hitter into the seventh, extending the
scoreless streak by Angels pitchers to 25 consecutive innings. The
streak _ and Belcher's day _ ended after he gave up a Paul Sorrento
single and a two-run homer to John Flaherty that skipped off the
top of the short fence down the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's final tally: six innings, three hits, two runs, four
strikeouts, four walks. At long last, a quality start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody gets madder at themselves than Tim Belcher,'' Collins
said. ``So you know he was taking it hard. Now he knows that it
won't last forever. He's going to start giving us some good
innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' injury-depleted offense didn't get a baserunner
until the third inning and didn't get a hit off Devil Rays starter
Bobby Witt (3-1) until the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But Witt ran into trouble in the sixth, when Andy Sheets and
Darin Erstad hit consecutive singles, then Randy Velarde walked to
load the bases for Vaughn. Vaughn unloaded them with his seventh
homer of the season, a 408-foot low liner that cleared the
right-field scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   It was Vaughn's eighth career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean we celebrate,'' said Vaughn, in the
aftermath of the Angels' fourth consecutive victory. ``Momentum
doesn't last if you don't try to maintain it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
