<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHELS RALLIES TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE _ Rip Michels did his best Alex Zanardi impression
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Michels, like Zanardi did so often in winning the last two CART
titles, roared from the back and finished with a victory and donuts
at Irwindale Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Starting fifth in the Grand American 30-lap main event, Michels
passed Thousand Oaks' Larry Kreiger for the lead midway through the
race and then used a lapped car to pull away. He put circular tire
marks across the finish line with three donuts, just like Zanardi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just putting old tires down,'' said Michels. ``I hadn't
thought about it until I just did it. We're racing new tires next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   After the donuts, Michels got out of his car, took off his
helmet and raised both hands triumphantly, drawing the largest
cheer of the night from the 2,247 in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They better not charge me,'' Michels said of the paint that
will have to be added to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Gerritt Cromsigt of Pine Mountain won the 40-lap main
event in Late Model and La Verne's Scott Porter celebrated his 30th
birthday by winning the 20-lap Mini Stock feature race.
</P>
<P>
   Michels took the lead on lap 16 from Kreiger. A spin by Aaron
Staudinger brought out the caution on lap 25, just after Michels
had lapped Scott Bartels. Michels then used Bartels as a blocker to
pull away on the restart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when they put the lapped car between us that the race
was over,'' said Kreiger. ``What could I do? Rip was running really
fast and he used his experience, and luck, to get by that car right
at the yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Kreiger said the car was perfect during qualifying he was less
than a tenth of a second faster than Michels but it quickly became
loose.
</P>
<P>
   In Late Model, Cromsigt and Dusty McDonald who bettered his own
class track record during qualifying easily pulled away from the
rest of the 13-car field.
</P>
<P>
   Passing lapped traffic on Lap 27, Cromsigt went inside, McDonald
tried to pass Rossell White in the middle and the pair touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never touched, Cromsigt said. ``He kept looking, looking
and looking in his mirror and I wasn't there, Cromsigt said.
</P>
<P>
   Cromsigt said his oil temperature ran high while trailing Canyon
Country resident McDonald, who finished fourth. He would take the
car inside to try and cool it off. He said it is one of the reasons
he was able to pass make the winning pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got in front, it really cooled off, he said. ``It ran
really good.
</P>
<P>
   Rochard Hooper of Palmdale finished second 2.796 seconds behind
Cromsigt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 0237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
