A8313 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-15 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD RETURNS FOR ROYAL BEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Alex Rodriguez needed two hitters to turn a crisp
double play, three pitches to crack an emphatic home run. He was
back after a 32-game layoff, reclaiming what was once his.
</P>
<P>
   Now if the Mariner shortstop could just convince a few of his
teammates to try a similar approach.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fassero, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   While Rodriguez came off the disabled list in inspired fashion,
Fassero was pushed further into baseball oblivion, largely
responsible for a 12-7 defeat to the Kansas City Royals Friday
night at the Kingdome. Thus a six-game homestand began with a
resounding thud, dropping Seattle to 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a regular occurrence this season, the veteran
Mariner pitcher didn't have it. Nothing. Nada. Zippo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to figure it out all season long, and nothing has
worked at all,'' the lefty said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero (1-5) couldn't get through the fifth inning, the third
time that's happened in 1999. He served up a season-high 11 hits
and seven runs, one shy of his worst effort. A pair of unsung
Carloses, Beltran and Febles, each tagged him for a pair of
doubles. Equally unassuming Mike Sweeney slugged his first career
grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere to be found is the Fassero of two previous seasons, the
guy who won 30 games, including a playoff matchup at Baltimore. Or
the Fassero the Mariners traded for, a 28-game winner his last two
seasons with the lowly Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got hit around,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``I really
don't have any answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero couldn't pinpoint his troubles either, other than to say
it's not velocity. Batters are hitting good pitches as well as the
bad.
</P>
<P>
   He's given up five runs in all but two of his nine starts. Even
in his lone victory over Cleveland last week, he served up nine
hits and five runs in five-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Royals, he gave up homers to Sweeney and former
Mariner Chad Kreuter, giving Fassero a major league-high 15.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he's sure of, Fassero has never endured a stretch like
this in his eight seasons at this level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had one this bad that I can remember,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner relievers Brett Hinchliffe and Eric Weaver didn't fare
much better than the first man on the hill. The Royals collectively
punched out a season-high 19 hits against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for the pitchers,'' Piniella said. ``I hurt for
them. But I can't pitch for them. They've got to get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner pitching wasn't there Friday night, but the
shortstop was.
</P>
<P>
   Mention of Rodriguez's name over the public address system drew
loud cheers from the 25,445 in attendance. For his first time
at-bat, he was greeted by the theme song from the old sitcom
``Welcome back, Kotter.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned late Thursday night after a three-day rehab
assignment at the Mariners' training complex in Peoria, Ariz. He
went 11-for-20 in three contests that allowed him excess at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he recognized any of the pitchers on his rehab,
Rodriguez told reporters, ``I didn't know any of them. It was
probably one of your kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Rodriguez said he was going to pretend it was
Opening Night. Other than that, he was unsure what to expect.
Arthroscopic knee surgery no doubt had robbed him of speed and
explosiveness. The bat and glove might be there, but stolen bases
definitely were out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new beginning for me,'' Rodriguez said. ``I can't tell
you how happy I am to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   He was two-for-three on pregame forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez reached base his first four times up, homering to
right, singling to center, walking and capitalizing on a fielding
error.
</P>
<P>
   In the field, Rodriguez twice polished off double plays,
standing tough on aggressive slides to rifle relay throws. He also
dove to his right to spear a seventh-inning grounder hit by
Jermaine Dye and throw him out from a kneeling position.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also stole a base, though it took him two tries.
</P>
<P>
   Twice he was put in motion on double-steal attempts, drawing the
throw each time, but at different bases. He got tagged out at third
base in the third inning, but beat the ball to second in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Before the contest, Piniella said this of his supposedly rusty
shortstop: ``We'll bring him along as slowly as possible. He might
need a day off here and there. He'll probably feel his way for a
week or two.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
