 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, May 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (888) 346-9867. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Ned Kilkelly.
</P>
<P>
   The late supervisor is Henry Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATO/KOSOVO &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHES (Brussels) _ In a behind-the-scenes struggle over
military strategy and tactics, the Pentagon is blocking a plan by
the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, to send Apache
helicopters into combat against Serb troops. By Michael R. Gordon
and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Brussels) _ NATO acknowledged Saturday that it
had carried out an attack near a village in southern Kosovo that
the Yugoslav government said resulted in scores of civilian
casualties. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL NEWS: &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMPEACH (Moscow) _ With a flood of venomous oratory, the
Communist-led drive to impeach President Boris Yeltsin failed in
Russia's parliament Saturday as nearly 100 members of the
legislature unexpectedly stayed away from the session, and some
ballots were thrown out because they carried no names or were
defaced. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ On Yeltsin in the midst of crisis. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECTION (Jerusalem) _ During a bitter, protracted
election campaign, Israelis have grown weary of the way the
candidates advocate unity, yet underscore the many divides in this
small, complex society. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECTION-ARABS (Cairo) _ With just days to go before the
Israeli election, the Arab world is watching with a pretense of
neutrality, although Ehud Barak, the Labor Party leader, is plainly
the favorite. The apparent reason for the caution is concern that
overt Arab cheerleading for Barak or criticism of the current prime
minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, could backfire. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA (Washington) _ The Clinton administration, which once
hoped that a stronger China-United States relationship would be a
centerpiece of its foreign policy legacy, is now bracing for a deep
deterioration in bilateral ties that may not improve before Clinton
leaves office. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ZHU (Shanghai) _ The political stakes in China's current
outburst of nationalism are high, and the overriding question of
the day is: Has Prime Minister Zhu Rongji been hurt? By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-GREENS (Bielefeld, Germany) _ In government office for
the first time since the party was founded two decades ago, the
pacifist Greens have quickly found themselves backing a war. In so
doing, for some, they have betrayed the long struggle of a
generation. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURDS (Diyarbakir, Turkey) _ The Turkish government says
that few Kurds support the idea of Kurdish nationalism and that
nearly all are happy with the life Turkey offers them. But a
four-day tour through Kurdish provinces of the southeast indicated
that the opposite may be true. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-AGENT-ORANGE (Ho Chi Minh City) _ Officials here are
convinced that tens of thousands of deformed children of war
veterans and exposed civilians are the victims of the herbicide
Agent Orange, used by the United States during the war to deprive
its enemy of forest cover and food crops. But Vietnam's scientific
studies have been sketchy and its evidence is often anecdotal.
Until there is firm proof that chemical herbicides are to blame,
the United States says it cannot take responsibility. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DOLLAR-DEBATE (Monterrey) _ A major sticking point has
emerged in an intense debate in Latin American about whether to
abandon local currencies and embrace the legal tender of the United
States. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REBELS (San Vicente Del Caguan, Colombia) _ This muddy
cattle town and a sizable swath of jungle and savanna around it
have ceased to be a part of Colombia and are instead, with the
government's blessing, a dominion ruled by Marxist guerrillas. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TRIALS (Undated) _ Once clinical research was a staid
enterprise primarily administered by academic researchers driven by
a desire for knowledge, fame or career advancement. Now, it is a
multibillion-dollar industry, with hundreds of testing and drug
companies working with thousands of private doctors. And in this
new industry, patients have become commodities. By Kurt Eichenwald
and Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA-SCIENTISTS (Undated) _ Many Chinese scientists and
engineers in the United States fear that they are being unfairly
tarnished and their careers threatened by charges against another
scientist, Wen Ho Lee. Lee has been accused of stealing the design
of America's most advanced nuclear warhead, the W-88, and providing
it to China. By Fox Butterfield and Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER-GOATS (Denver) _ A sign at Babi Yar Park here says it
all: ``Goats at Work.'' The herd of about 100 Cashmere goats that
has been munching at the park since April is working for the city
of Denver this year as part of a program to fight invasive weeds
that have taken over native plants and wildlife habitats in the
park's natural areas. By Mindy Sink.
</P>
<P>
   N.C.-TRAFFIC (Research Triangle Park, N.C.) _ The traffic
problem is so worrisome here that top executives of Glaxo Wellcome
and Cisco Systems recently told Gov. Jim Hunt that their companies
could not continue to expand here if the problem was not relieved.
But any potential solution appears to face a dim future in the
state Legislature. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLERS-POLITICS (Glastonbury, Conn.) _ When Bob Backlund hits
the campaign trail as a Republican candidate for Congress in
greater Hartford, he is not asked about school vouchers or abortion
or Kosovo, but about the ``cross-face chicken wing.'' Backlund, the
inventor of the chicken-wing move and a champion of the World
Wrestling Federation, is leading a parade of professional wrestlers
who are turning to politics, hoping to duplicate last fall's upset
victory by Jesse Ventura, formerly ``the Body'' of the WWF and now
the governor of Minnesota. By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-CHARITIES (Undated) _ While Internet millionaires in
Silicon Valley have drawn attention for multimillion-dollar gifts
to higher education and major arts organizations, social services
charities there say they struggle with flat or shrinking support
and are often spurned by high-tech companies who see no link
between their business interests and social services. By David Cay
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PENN-STATION (New York) _ Beaux-Arts on the rebound? No. A great
act of civic vandalism undone? That was never in the cards. But if
you can set such golden platitudes aside, you may begin to
appreciate the intrinsic merits of the superb new plan to remodel
the historic James A. Farley Building, the old general post office
on Eighth Avenue between 31st and 33rd streets, into a future home
for Penn Station. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDIA-VIOLENCE (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ President Clinton
on Saturday urged the entertainment industry to voluntarily limit
the glorification of guns in movie advertisements and previews and
to consider whether PG movies contain excessive and gratuitous
violence. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FUND-RAISING (Washington) _ On the frontiers of
presidential fund-raising, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
shattered previous Republican records by quickly raising $13
million with help from ``the Pioneers'' _ an elite group of 150
supporters who have each agreed to raise $100,000 for Bush's
presidential exploratory committee. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-POLLUTION-FIGHT (Detroit) _ An administration proposal to
require cleaner gasoline and less-polluting automobiles,
particularly sport utility vehicles, has turned into the most
ambitious anti-pollution initiative of the Clinton presidency,
prompting heavy lobbying by environmentalists and industrialists
and strong interest by politicians eyeing next year's presidential
campaign. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Commentary by Maureen Dowd: The
pressure's on for Al Gore to relax.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Tunica County, Miss.) _ Commentary by Bob
Herbert: They just don't get it in Mississippi.
</P>
