<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-VIOLENCE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ITS APPEAL FOR KIDS, `STAR WARS' MOVIES' BODY COUNT
ALARMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- On the surface, the new ``Star Wars'' movie,
``The Phantom Menace,'' is no ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fantasy for children that, through three earlier films as
well as the new prequel that comes out Wednesday, has avoided
graphic gore even in its scariest moments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you want to bash movies for desensitizing children to
violence in an age when kids massacre kids in our schools, like
they did in Littleton, Colo., a month ago, ``Star Wars'' may be a
starting point.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of body count, the original 1977 space opera was the
most violent movie of its era.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, an entire, heavily populated planet was vaporized just
to demonstrate the Death Star's destructive capacity. The Death
Star itself, which was the size of a city with equivalent
habitation, was blown to bits as well.
</P>
<P>
   And those are just the mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its pseudo-spirituality and philosophical
pretensions, the central ethic of ``Star Wars'' is point and shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional lightsaber duel, laser-gun exchanges
and outer-space dogfights are the series' main methods for solving
problems.
</P>
<P>
   More than any film before or since, ``Star Wars'' glorified the
video game aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   The object was to knock out as many enemy targets _ TIE fighters
or stormtroopers _ as possible, without a thought for the sentient,
presumably soul-bearing entity inside that spaceship or white
plastic armor. Indeed, the stormtrooper uniform was specially
designed to obscure the wearer's face, the better to turn them into
dehumanized action figures rather than real men who felt real pain.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker George Lucas can hardly be accused of creating
anything like the brutal cinematic excesses that have punctuated
American cinema throughout the '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But he is nonetheless well aware of his science fiction saga's
fundamental violence ... and by his way of thinking, is responsible
about how he presents it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that the key issue about violence in the media
is the context in which it's portrayed,'' the 55-year-old filmmaker
said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a violent world and we always will live in a
violent world. Life is violent, and to deny that would be almost as
dangerous as glorifying it and making it an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has to do more with the context. I definitely think
that hurting people for fun, for enjoyment, is the central issue
here.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be an accident of history that ``Star Wars'' appeared at
about the same time that playing video games became a popular
childhood pastime. But it doesn't seem all that coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lucas' movies, games have a simultaneously interactive and
detached quality; you're more engaged with objects on the screen on
a sensory level but less empathetically than you would be with
fully fleshed-out movie characters.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make them easier to destroy without considering
consequences? The psychiatric jury is still out on that one, but
one thing's more certain: The four new video games that are being
spun off of ``Phantom Menace'' are expected to be monster hits.
</P>
<P>
   And let's face it: The series is called ``Star Wars'' for a
reason, and not because the less aggressive-sounding ``Star Trek''
was already taken. Creator Lucas also named its essential energy
the Force; not the, well, Energy, or the Spirit or the Stuff or
even something as comparatively neutral as the Power.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``Star Wars'' didn't start any of this.
</P>
<P>
   Violent movies have been as much a fixture on the American
landscape as violence itself for nearly a century now. The first
real narrative film, 1903's ``The Great Train Robbery,'' climaxed
with an outlaw firing a gun straight out of the screen at the
audience (some of whom, mostly in Western theaters, reportedly shot
back at the then-shocking image). Hollywood has demonized and
dispatched countless Indians, gangsters, Axis soldiers and other
enemies in the decades since then. There were even a couple of
worlds destroyed in cheesy '50s sci-fi movies.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of those years, even the most detached, sanitized
killings were usually done in a man-to-man, face-to-face manner.
There was almost always an opportunity, however faked or fleeting,
to see and share a dying man's agony.
</P>
<P>
   (second take to follow)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
