<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8368 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-VIOLENCE-2nd     05-15 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-VIOLENCE-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES:dying man's agony.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the decade before ``Star Wars'' appeared, the violence in
movies became much more graphic and shocking than ever before (and
certainly more so than in anything Lucas has imagined since).
</P>
<P>
   But directors in that mid-'60s-to-mid-'70s period, such as Sam
Peckinpah (``The Wild Bunch,'' ``Straw Dogs''), Stanley Kubrick
(``A Clockwork Orange''), Francis Ford Coppola (The ``Godfather''
saga) and Martin Scorsese (``Taxi Driver'') weren't just pushing
the envelope to see how much they could get away with. They were
exploring the nature and meaning of violence, trying to figure out
why it was still such a fundamental part of human behavior at our
supposedly advanced stage of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Their movies, however outrageous they might have gotten, were
all about the ugliness and consequences of violence. Following the
unprecedented popular success of ``Star Wars,'' however, filmmakers
started using violence as something to be enjoyed for its
excitement, shock and fantasy value.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas believes there must be more to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to fight for freedom, you have to sometimes fight for
your rights, you have to fight for self-defense and you have to
stand up for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, to torture other people, to make them
feel bad, to belittle them. ... Whether you're simply being
impolite and have bad manners or are making fun of somebody just
because it's a fun thing to do or whether you're getting guns and
bombs out and trying to kill people, it ultimately is the same kind
of mean-spiritedness.''
</P>
<P>
   An even knottier contradiction lies in the distinction between
rationalized and sadistic violence. Were the teen-age killers in
Columbine High School simply out to torment and murder their
victims, or did they feel they were taking righteous vengeance on
people who had hurt and oppressed them? Once you've taken the step
toward acting out violence, do such fine distinctions really
matter?
</P>
<P>
   Samuel L. Jackson, who has done his share of '90s-style action
blasts (``Die Hard With a Vengeance,'' ``The Long Kiss
Goodnight''), portrayed a hit man on the verge of a spiritual
epiphany in the widely misunderstood, influential and decried
``Pulp Fiction'' and a wise Jedi Council member in the new ``Star
Wars'' prequel _ who, significantly, never raises a lightsaber.
</P>
<P>
   While hardly one to be alarmed by any kind of violent filmed
image, Jackson feels that ``Star Wars'' delivers an underlying,
anti-violent message that indeed justifies all the slashing and
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Star Wars' is a pure morality tale, good vs. evil,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people can't see that, then fine. George has couched it in
entertainment, chase scenes and things blowing up, but it's
basically about good vs. evil, about how people deal with those two
things and how to overcome things _ and it's not always with
violence. Sometimes it's about having a thought process and
understanding what it is so you can deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom Menace'' dramatizes the barest handful of human (or
humanoid) deaths. The vast majority of things that get zapped are
battle droids, machines that look like metal ostrich skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   The climactic ground battle is fought exclusively between the
droids and amphibian creatures called Gungans, who speak, think and
feel but are noticeably more animal than manlike. This is all quite
calculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The droids really are the precursors to the stormtroopers,''
Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the same technique that I've used in all of the
movies. There's obviously an issue in the fact that I've got laser
swords in this one and I only had laser pistols in the other ones.
I was aware of the fact that I wasn't about to cut stormtroopers in
half.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the people-resembling bad guys that Keanu Reeves blows
away in ``The Matrix'' are, according to the film's scenario, just
computer-generated illusions with no more real life implied to them
than ``Phantom's'' larger number of blasted battle droids possess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix'' was criticized as gratuitously ultraviolent.
Critics complain ``The Phantom Menace'' is too juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   ``When `The Matrix' comes out on video, I might be able to see
it,'' said an indignant Jake Lloyd, who plays the 9-year-old hero
Anakin Skywalker in ``The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And you're 18,'' his mother, Lisa, added without missing a
beat. But by then, Jake and most of his contemporaries will have
seen the new batch of ``Star Wars'' movies over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Lucas is turning out a new generation of violent
teen-agers with the second ``Star Wars'' trilogy is to overhype the
potential.
</P>
<P>
   But with all the hype that's going to make the films must-sees
for kids of all ages, if the influence is there, could it possibly
be stopped?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
