<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-TRIMS     05-15 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-TRIMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ELECTION RANCOR, ISRAELIS EXPECT ALLIANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also ISRAEL-ELECTION-ARABS) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ During a bitter, protracted election campaign,
Israelis have grown weary of the way the candidates advocate unity,
yet underscore the many divisions in this small, complex society.
</P>
<P>
   This race, like many Israeli elections, has brought out the
blood passions in a country that sometimes operates like a large
extended family, complicated by intense sibling rivalries,
intermarriage and generational disputes.
</P>
<P>
   There were routine cries of ``traitor'' as political mates
jumped ship, and nasty name-calling battles between Jewish
immigrants of different national origins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has not been a time of healing, that's for sure,'' said
Yaron Ezrahi, a political scientist and fellow at the Israel
Democracy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Israelis finally vote on Monday, choosing between Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his key rival, Ehud Barak, many
will do so with the expectation that a coalition government will
eventually be forged _ perhaps even one that joins the major
parties these two men represent.
</P>
<P>
   Winning a race is one thing, after all, and governing Israel is
another.
</P>
<P>
   For the new government will face not only a stagnant economy and
roiling social tensions, especially between secular and religious
Jews, but also difficult, potentially destabilizing, diplomatic
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Israelis cast two ballots. One is for prime minister,
the other for parliament, in which 33 parties are competing for 120
seats. The leading candidate for prime minister must win more than
50 percent of the votes to avoid a runoff election on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Barak, the Labor Party leader, was ahead in the polls
by a substantial margin over Netanyahu, the Likud Party leader, in
what has been a five-way race. Barak, a highly decorated former
general who is running at the head of the One Israel coalition, has
been gaining ground so steadily that it seems probable he will
capture more votes than Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the elections, then, the key question is not whether
Barak will lead on Monday, but whether he will win outright,
eliminating the need for an unprecedented, costly second round.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure mounted late last week on three minor-party candidates
to withdraw from the race. Asmi Bishara, an Israeli-Arab candidate,
seemed most likely to do so, and polls indicated that this would
push Barak very close to a win.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli electorate is unpredictable, which is why many
repeatedly cite a local political adage: Israelis tell the truth to
the pollsters but lie at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   To Netanyahu's disadvantage, furthermore, Israelis are also
impatient, traditionally unwilling to give their leaders a second
chance. Since Menachem Begin won re-election to a second term in
1981, no incumbent prime minister has ever won re-election
outright. There were some draws.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most countries, holding power confers a clear advantage,
worth some 5 to 10 percentage points, to whoever has it,'' said
Nachum Barnea, a leading political columnist. ``In Israel, holding
power is an electoral liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Netanyahu's conservative coalition dissolved prematurely
in December, the country has been in a state of suspended
animation. The Israeli-Palestinian peace effort has been frozen,
and important social and economic decisions have been deferred.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyhau has continued to lead the country while fighting an
uphill battle for his re-election. He has been running Israel at
the same time as his supposed flaws have been dissected daily on
the public stage.
</P>
<P>
   For many Israelis, it has been an uncomfortable, dispiriting
dynamic. The election race has turned into a referendum on the
polarizing personality of their prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am running on the issues, but they are running against my
character,'' Netanyahu said in an April interview.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis say they do not see a big difference between the
two leading candidates _ both raised in elite Ashkenazi families,
both secular Jews, both educated in the United States, both
fighters in the same elite army unit at a critical time in Israeli
history, and both headstrong, ambitious men.
</P>
<P>
   And both men are leaning toward the political center that most
Israelis occupy. Barak, a former army chief of staff, does so from
a leftist party, and Netanyahu from a rightist one.
</P>
<P>
   Both say they support continuing the Israeli-Palestinian peace
effort from a point of pragmatism, as does Yitzhak Mordechai, the
former defense minister and Center Party leader, who is also
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm considering all three because I can't tell them apart,''
Yarden Ben Harush, 24, an education student in Beersheva, said .
``It's all a blur. The class I go to, we're 120 young people, and
we all feel that same way.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, stunning the country's political establishment,
Netanyahu won election by a mere 30,000 votes, or 1 percent, over
Shimon Peres, the Labor Party leader. It was a tense time.
</P>
<P>
   The country had not yet begun to recover from the assassination
of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, Peres' predecessor as the Labor
Party leader, by an extremist religious Jew. Israel was enduring a
spate of Palestinian terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu was the first prime minister elected directly in a
separate ballot. Until 1996, Israelis cast only one vote, for their
party, and the party's leader ran the government.
</P>
<P>
   To stitch together a majority government, he built a coalition
of unlikely bedfellows: Sephardic Jews, Russian immigrants,
ultra-Orthodox Jews and Jewish settlers from the West Bank. He
linked them together by appealing to their shared feeling that they
were shut outside the gates of power by the Ashkenazi elite.
</P>
<P>
   But keeping them together was another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the direct election system, one political personality
needs to embody all the different parts of the Israeli political
soul,'' Ezrahi, the political scientist, said. ``In order to
function well, he has to be ambiguous, or he risks his own
downfall.''
</P>
<P>
   That is partly what happened to Netanyahu. He led his
conservative Likud Party to betray its founding principle when it
decided last fall to support territorial concessions to the
Palestinians. Approaching the American-brokered peace negotiations
slowly, cautiously and with a blustery and suspicious attitude
toward the Palestinians, he brought many Israelis into the peace
camp.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But in doing so, he alienated his far-right supporters. And to
win them back, he distanced himself from his own accomplishment. He
declared the Palestinians to be violating their obligations, and,
in defiance of the American government, suspended Israeli
compliance with the most recent peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his tenure, Netanyahu managed to antagonize
personally many of his followers and his political associates. And
by the end, although close associates believe him to be a highly
principled man, he had led many Israelis to believe the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   By the weekend, Netanyahu had received no endorsement from his
trade minister, Natan Sharansky, and did not expect one.
Sharansky's constituency, Russian immigrants, is considered the
only large bloc of swing votes. Barak has courted them furiously,
making steady inroads, and the latest polls showed the two
candidates splitting the Russian vote.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has run a professional campaign, with little opposition
from within his own coalition, making few mistakes. Netanyahu, on
the other hand, has feuded with his associates in Likud, and may
have miscalculated what would appeal to his voters, repeating the
themes of his 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He entered this election race without two leading Sephardic
politicians by his side: David Levy, his former foreign minister,
who has joined forces with Barak, and Mordechai, his former defense
minister, who is running against him.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, whose persistence in the race represents the surest
obstacle to an outright victory by Barak, has played a pivotal
role. While his now doomed candidacy has been a somewhat quixotic
affair, Mordechai has served as a steppingstone.
</P>
<P>
   He has given die-hard Likudniks a way to walk away from the
party they were practically born into without betraying their
identities by going straight to the left. Now, however, many are
abandoning him for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Strategists in Netanyahu's party say that their goal is to
survive the first round, assuming that Netanyahu will fare better
in a one-on-one runoff. If a solid center-left majority wins
control of the parliament on Monday, it could galvanize swing
voters to return to Netanyahu. And the prime minister is presumed
to be the master of focused political combat.
</P>
<P>
   But many Israelis, even some who do not back Barak, are hoping
that the race ends Monday. They anticipate that whoever wins will
need to form some kind of coalition government, given that as many
as 20 parties could be elected to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   And they want the country to start moving forward again.
</P>
<P>
   What is on the immediate horizon are critical negotiations with
the Palestinians and the Syrians that will help define Israel's
size, its place in the Mideast and its identity as a secure or
threatened state _ a country at war or at peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see in front of us one of the most critical years in Israeli
history,'' Barak said in an interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
