general who is running at the head of the One Israel coalition, has
been gaining ground so steadily that it seems probable he will
capture more votes than Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the elections, then, the key question is not whether
Barak will lead on Monday, but whether he will win outright,
eliminating the need for an unprecedented, costly second round.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure mounted late last week on three minor-party candidates
to withdraw from the race. Asmi Bishara, an Israeli-Arab candidate,
seemed most likely to do so, and polls indicated that this would
push Barak very close to a win.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli electorate is unpredictable, which is why many
repeatedly cite a local political adage: Israelis tell the truth to
the pollsters but lie at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   To Netanyahu's disadvantage, furthermore, Israelis are also
impatient, traditionally unwilling to give their leaders a second
chance. Since Menachem Begin won re-election to a second term in
1981, no incumbent prime minister has ever won re-election
outright. There were some draws.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most countries, holding power confers a clear advantage,
worth some 5 to 10 percentage points, to whoever has it,'' said
