forming a network of parents and educators to persuade airlines
that young children should not be casually exposed to lurid movie
imagery of guns, bombs and mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere in society, parents are told they have a choice,''
she said. ``Change the channel, don't buy the kid the record or the
movie ticket or the video game. The idea of choice is the
entertainment industry's paramount defense against censorship. But
on an airplane, you have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   For months after her ``Lethal Weapon 4'' incident, Ms. Samples
called airline officials to discuss her concerns, and she said she
was met with a list of boiler-plate responses: In-flight movies are
always edited _ at a minimum to standards used by broadcast
television. It's impossible to please everyone. Surveys show that
the weary business travelers who pay the top fares demand the
latest hit movies, including action-thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't seem to hear what I was saying,'' Ms. Samples
said. ``The airlines don't seem to be interested in talking about
guidelines for excessively violent films _ the kind where if you
edited the violence out, you'd have no movie left to show.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline officials say violent movies are not very common, though
a survey of the top in-flight rentals from 1991 to 1997 showed that
about one-third were action-adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genres that work best are light adventure, comedy and
particularly romantic comedy,'' said Rob Brookler, a spokesman for
the World Airline Entertainment Association, a trade group that
represents more than 100 major airlines. ```You've Got Mail,' now
that was the perfect in-flight movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do consider that there are children, not to mention a
broader variety of people and cultural attitudes,'' Brookler added.
``The northern Europeans are very forgiving of adult sex matter but
are very sensitive to violence, whereas in the Mideast and the
East, they're more sensitive to adult matter and less to
violence.'' As a result, extra edits are made in some regions to
avoid giving offense.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines, he said, also have to deal with temperamental
directors and producers who say, ``Whoa, you're not going to cut
that scene just to show it on an airplane!''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are extra vigilant in editing out at least one kind of
movie violence: airplane crashes. ``Don't forget, you are in fact
flying through the air when you're watching the movie,'' Brookler
said. ``A certain number of people are fearful about flying, and in
a confined space you really don't want to excite that fear.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The airline industry isn't the only one to edit movies for
travelers. ``Titanic'' was a big hit on airplanes, but most cruise
lines declined to show it. Airlines showed ``Lethal Weapon 4,''
which has a scene of a speeding freight train smashing into a car.
But Amtrak frowns on train wrecks in movies shown in lounge cars on
some long-haul trips, said Rick Remington, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 thriller ``Speed,'' about a hijacked runaway bus, was
the second-most-popular in-flight movie that year (after the comedy
``Mrs. Doubtfire''), according to the airline entertainment
association. But airline passengers who saw it missed one of the
most spectacular scenes, in which the bus plows into a taxiing
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry spent $1.7 billion last year on high-tech
equipment like individual in-seat video screens, now available in
many first-class and business-class cabins and on some
international flights, which allow passengers to choose from a
variety of films and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, the airlines expect to have in-seat video
screens in nearly all first- and business-class cabins, and in
about 75 percent of all coach seats for international flights. But
the industry is less certain about when this expensive technology
will turn up in coach seats on domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves the basic issue unaddressed for most coach
travelers. ``The airlines keep saying that their surveys show
business travelers like these kinds of movies,'' said Ms. Samples,
who calls her new group Parents Against Violent Airline
Entertainment. ``But ask the right questions and the business
traveler who never thought of this before might say: `Oh, that's a
good idea. I will gladly give up my right to see ``Die Hard'' or
``Lethal Weapon'' on an airplane. I have kids myself.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
