<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8381 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REALITY-ARTS-REVIEW-6     05-15 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALITY-ARTS-REVIEW-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE JADED AESTHETE, A DOSE OF THE VERY REAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By ELIN SCHOEN BROCKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a moment in David Hare's ``Via Dolorosa''
when it becomes clear that the playwright's personal meditation on
Israel's emotional state also expresses something that is happening
in American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a painting, a painting of a starving man?'' Hare says,
replaying his reactions to Yad Vashem, the Holocaust memorial in
Jerusalem. ``What is a painting of a corpse? It's the facts we
want! Give us the facts!''
</P>
<P>
   It's the facts Americans are getting, more and more, not only in
traditional places like newspapers and television but also in the
arts _ ``a kind of headlong rush toward more and more reality,''
says Mark Rosenthal, curator of 20th-century art at the Guggenheim
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Via Dolorosa,'' Hare himself holds forth for 90 minutes on
his encounters with men and women on all sides of the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict. Unaided by scenery or props,
literally acting on his interviews and notes, he is the protagonist
in his own drama.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent review in The New York Times, Vincent Canby wrote:
``Nothing Mr. Hare has done before prepares you for `Via Dolorosa'
and its discoveries, including the demonstrated fact that he can be
such seriously invigorating company. But, then, there are no exact
precedents for what he is doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Deavere Smith's two theater successes, ``Fires in the
Mirror'' and ``Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992,'' were also based on
her reports of real-life events. But unlike Hare, she portrays the
people she incorporates into her work. ``Via Dolorosa'' is strictly
the theater of the observed, Broadway's answer to the memoir,
publishing's hottest genre.
</P>
<P>
   In the musical theater, ``The Civil War'' lays claim to what is
arguably the first score based entirely on authentic historical
documents, letters and newspaper articles.
</P>
<P>
   Documentary films are proliferating, particularly in cable
television, says Michelle Satter, founding director of the feature
film program at the Sundance Festival. So are network television
news magazines like ``48 Hours'' and ``20/20'' and real-life action
programs like ``Cops.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the visual arts, even Chaim Soutine, whose slaughterhouse
still lifes seem to drip blood, not paint, could not have foreseen
the visceral reality of Damien Hirst, Britain's
artist-of-the-moment, who saws livestock in half and displays the
carcasses in formaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
   On view at the Yale Center for British Art in New Haven, Conn.,
is a slightly tamer Hirst installation that displays real
butterflies impaled on house-painted canvases and ashtrays filled
with cigarette butts.
</P>
<P>
   The arts are no longer imitating life. They are appropriating
it. And the reason seems obvious: the sheer scale of current
events, amplified by the 24-hour magnifying mirror of television,
which operates in a continual state of repetition compulsion that
can make even the worst catastrophe feel unreal. In order to react,
jaded audiences need reality in larger, stronger concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the artists respond to that,'' Rosenthal says. ``You could
say it's in the air coming from both directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Or yet another direction. The present surfeit of reality in the
arts could be a response, Hare says, to a surfeit of fiction _ bad
fiction. Today's narratives are too often unreal, he said in a
telephone interview, citing ``these endless films with angels'' and
``films where the hero in the third act encounters the difficulty
in the ninth reel, which he resolves in the tenth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All art forms drift away from reality and become
self-absorbed,'' he adds. ``The revolutionary artist is always the
one who comes along and says: `Hang on! It doesn't look like that!
It doesn't feel like that! On the street that is not what is going
on.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reality has always been popular on the street. Michael Roth,
associate director of the Getty Research Institute for the History
of Art and the Humanities in Los Angeles, who is the curator of the
Sigmund Freud exhibition now at the Jewish Museum in New York City,
says it's not just the facts people want but also the genuine
artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would line up to see an original document from the
founding years of the United States,'' Roth says. ``But put in a
perfect facsimile that no one can recognize as a facsimile _ if you
tell people it's a facsimile, the lines disappear immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museum goers have an intense desire to be in physical
proximity to original materials that are connected to someone who
interests them,'' Roth says of the exhibition of Freud's
manuscripts, family pictures, favorite antiquities and other
Freudiana.
</P>
<P>
   So it doesn't matter to most visitors to the Jewish Museum that
they can't read either the German language or Freud's handwriting.
These are the real things. Freud's manuscripts, intact, right here,
iconlike, provide contact with him and, says Roth, the immensely
reassuring proof that death does not erase everything.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph, the filmed image, is always ``reality once
removed,'' says the photojournalist Steve Lehman, author of ``The
Tibetans: A Struggle to Survive'' (Umbrage Editions, 1998). In art,
as with the news, it could be argued, all reality is virtual. You
are not really there. If you were, it would mean enduring a lot of
dead time, which would be boring, which must be edited out _
unless, as with Andy Warhol, one of your favorite subjects is
boredom itself.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously `Via Dolorosa' is completely artificial,'' Hare says.
``It is as highly wrought as any of my plays. But basically all the
artifice is to disguise itself so you don't feel it's there. You're
attempting to make the artifice like a pane of glass that simply
leads you through to the subject _ not to decorate the bloody
glass.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how real things get, abstraction and fantasy will
endure in art for the simple reason that artists respond to
different subject matter in different ways. Hare, for instance,
wouldn't have dreamed of a nonfiction treatment for ``Amy's View,''
his other current Broadway play, which is about ``questions of the
heart,'' he says. It had to be a work of the imagination, performed
by actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be absolutely horrified to stand up on a stage and
talk about love and all these things,'' he says. ``You know, you do
that through the old methods.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
