<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-ANTITRUST-REVIEW     05-15 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-ANTITRUST-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD ON _ MAYBE WE'LL CONNECT YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The antitrust authorities barely whimpered last month when AT&AMP;T,
the United States' largest long-distance company, acquired
Tele-Communications Inc., the second-largest cable company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal advanced AT&AMP;T's audacious plan to feed phone calls and
Internet data over the same wire that carries video channels _
offering customers a svelte package of every electronic service
they can imagine. And this month AT&AMP;T moved to buy another large
cable company, Mediaone, and to bring Microsoft into its cable and
Internet operations.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Armstrong, the chairman of AT&AMP;T, predicts little
regulatory interference. And who knows? He may be right. Fifteen
years after the government split AT&AMP;T into pieces _ and even as it
is asking the courts to break Microsoft's stranglehold over
personal computing _ these two giants nevertheless are rushing to
dominate phone, cable and Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Has antitrust regulation been futile? Consumer advocates think
so. Others point out that existing antitrust standards are not
well-suited to handle telecommunications mergers. In such deals,
higher prices, the ordinary province of antitrust enforcement,
aren't as big a problem as the threat to diverse expression and
sources of information.
</P>
<P>
   So regulators have to learn to deal with decisions that could
concentrate control over the entertainment and information pouring
into the home. And right now they are groping for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Already critics are pressing them to act against AT&AMP;T. Gene
Kimmelman, the consumer advocate at Consumers Union, says,
``Regulatory cowardice could turn AT&AMP;T into a behemoth that
dictates what we see on the Web and watch on television.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T seeks to control cable systems that serve between 25
percent and 40 percent of the nation's cable customers, and to own
minority interests in systems that serve another 20 percent.
Kimmelman says no cable network could expect to thrive if it
couldn't buy its way into AT&AMP;T's systems.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Schwartzman, president of the Media Access Project,
another advocacy group, worries that AT&AMP;T could wall itself off
from competition by refusing to sell popular cable offerings that
it controls to satellite services, or by refusing to carry
programming owned by competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Werbach, managing editor of Release 1.0, a technology
magazine, points to a graver threat. ``The plan threatens to give
AT&AMP;T excessive control over the future high-speed Internet,'' he
says. Under AT&AMP;T's cable contracts, customers would be required to
connect to the Internet using AT&AMP;T's online service, At Home, if
they want high-speed connections. Customers who prefer to use the
content offered by America Online or some other service would be
forced to pay more money and suffer inferior service.
</P>
<P>
   This, says Werbach, ``threatens the crowning feature of the
Internet, an open network that allows anyone to do business with
anyone else without interference.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the looming presence of Microsoft. It will
write the software that provides electronic services for some of
AT&AMP;T's customers. And that could give Microsoft the toehold it
needs to dominate the cable world, much as it does the world of
personal computing.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the doomsayers are missing the larger picture.
Its complexities make it difficult for regulators to figure out how
to act, or even whether to act.
</P>
<P>
   John Rose of McKinsey &AMP; Co., a consulting firm, says AT&AMP;T's plan
would be ``a transforming event,'' giving customers the option to
drop the local phone company. Besides, Rose says, ``once AT&AMP;T
upgrades its cable service to provide snazzy digital features, so
too will all the other cable companies.'' In other words, there
would be greater competition and improved service.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sunshine, a former antitrust official at the Department
of Justice, points out that the antitrust authorities have been
right to proceed cautiously, because the AT&AMP;T cable purchases do
not violate the antitrust laws in any simple way. They replaced one
cable monopolist, TCI or Mediaone, with another, AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cicconi, general counsel of AT&AMP;T, says the critics see
threats of dominance where there are none. AT&AMP;T would own and
operate systems serving only about 25 percent of the market, he
says _ far short of a stranglehold. And, he argues, AT&AMP;T will face
competition from the regional phone companies and satellite
services that will make it ``impossible for any one company to
control programming.''
</P>
<P>
   So is AT&AMP;T destined to bring a fabulous array of inexpensive
electronic services? Or is AT&AMP;T about to squash competition in
video programming and crush some of the voices that communicate
over the Internet? The simple answer is that no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, for example, whether the phone companies have a
technology that can provide comparable Internet service or whether
satellite services will ever reach beyond a small, wealthy niche.
</P>
<P>
   In this environment of daunting uncertainty and real or imagined
threats to free expression, there are two options: watchful waiting
and preventive detention.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Litan of the Brookings Institution, who was once an
antitrust official in the Justice Department, preaches watchful
waiting. ``Premature reaction by regulators could needlessly stunt
innovation,'' he says, so the smart strategy is to wait, watch and
pounce when something goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman and Schwartzman counsel preventive detention: Block
AT&AMP;T's purchase of Mediaone. Waiting to react would give AT&AMP;T time
to design its cable systems in ways that would make it virtually
impossible to pry them open to competition in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine preaches a middle ground. ``There are many steps that
regulators can take short of stopping a merger outright,'' he says.
They could insist that AT&AMP;T open up its cable wires to America
Online and other Internet services if technically possible. Or
regulators might insist that cable operators lease their popular
networks for a fee to satellite services and other potential
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunshine offers a more challenging point. ``The antitrust
laws protect a company's right to bring forth new technologies
unless there is solid evidence of a threat to competition,'' he
says. That is the right standard for guaranteeing low prices for
shoelaces, cameras and other ordinary consumer goods. But it may be
the wrong standard, he says, when issues other than economic
efficiency are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The law gives the Federal Communications Commission the right to
hold up mergers to protect the public interest even in those cases
where the Justice Department decides there are no serious antitrust
problems.
</P>
<P>
   With the AT&AMP;T-Mediaone merger pending, the commission does not
have much time to figure out how to factor the information needs of
a democracy into its decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
