<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8383 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ENLIST-REVIEW-     05-15 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ENLIST-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO WAR DOESN'T DO MUCH FOR U.S. RECRUITMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A decade ago, Americans watched the United Nations' entry into
the Gulf war almost as if it were a video game, distant and unreal.
Each night's newscast brought a fresh batch of satellite pictures
of Iraqi targets exploding as smart bombs zeroed in.
</P>
<P>
   The victims of Iraq's invasion of Kuwait were seldom seen, and
the greatest moral issue for most Americans was probably that of
controlling the supply of oil or protecting Israel.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Kosovo Albanian refugees are all too real. Their
stories of mass rapes and massacres echo a level of brutality that
evokes the death camps of World War II. Washington is engaged in a
war where the overwhelming feature is not oil or geopolitics but
the morality of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   And yet many young Americans enlisted to fight Iraq in the Gulf
war.
</P>
<P>
   Today they have been sitting out the Balkan conflict, according
to military recruitment experts like John Sibley Butler, a
sociologist who is the Reserve Officer Training Corps faculty
adviser at the University of Texas. For a few years, the Gulf war
helped stem the steady decline in enlistment since the end of the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks largely to a healthy economy that has increased the
choices available to those entering the job market, the Army and
the Air Force have fallen short in their recruitment goals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with 1.36 million Americans serving in the military, the
United States for the moment runs no risk of a shortfall in troops
to face down the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But the dearth of recruits limits U.S. options, suggesting that
a long war may be problematical. And it raises intriguing questions
about attitudes toward military service and the meaning of modern
warfare to young people.
</P>
<P>
   The apathy of young people toward the conflict in the Balkans
comes at a moment when war is paradoxically at its most intimate
and most distant.
</P>
<P>
   Through television, Americans have access to virtually
continuous coverage of the war, be it NATO bombings in Belgrade or
briefings in Brussels, or the live reports from crowded refugee
camps in Macedonia and Albania. Through the Internet, they can
communicate directly with Serbs or Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the U.S. military wages war at a distance,
using methods that reduce the likelihood of casualties. Planes fly
higher to cut the chances that they will be shot down by Serb
forces, even if that means mistaking a civilian target for a
military one.
</P>
<P>
   For many young people, such ``safe'' strategies drain war of its
very meaning, said David R. Siegel, author of ``Recruiting for
Uncle Sam'' (University Press of Kansas, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   Although the military has relied on increasing pay and benefits
to draw recruits, Siegel's previous research suggests that young
people enlist for patriotic reasons, or to build character. A war
that carries risk to only one side strikes many of them as unfair,
or at least unworthy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they're saying, `I'm willing to lay my life on the
line, but my country won't let me,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nonwar in Kosovo,'' which batters Yugoslavia from the air
but does not risk troops, may be precisely what is keeping young
people away, Siegel said. They sense they are not needed, he says.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible that continuous television coverage of the
conflict has prompted people to tune out rather than tune in to the
war. ``War has become a movie that other people do, and something
we watch rather than something we engage in,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans reason that abominations ``are going on everywhere,''
he said, and they ask, ``But do we go everywhere to fight them?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
