<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMY-FISHER-REVIEW-480     05-15 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMY-FISHER-REVIEW-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 STILL GAWKING AFTER ALL THESE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The once-and-future queen of our tabloid domain was
released from a prison in upstate New York last week. After a
seven-year hiatus, Amy Fisher is among us again, and it seems that
since we cannot escape her, we may have no recourse but to pursue,
analyze and perhaps even worship her.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Fisher played her role to perfection, like
some ex-con Garbo. Her eyes shaded by sunglasses, her lips set in
that squirrel-cheek pout, she brushed past two dozen reporters
yearning for her to say something, anything.
</P>
<P>
   But she did deign to pose for a photograph in the chartered
airplane that returned her to her rightful place, Long Island, and
even released a statement suggesting that this was one paroled
felon Who Has Learned Her Lesson. She revealed that she wants to do
something positive with her life.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ms. Fisher's release, her lawyer has shared heartwarming
tidbits about the young woman's embrace of freedom, including
details about the long-awaited reunion with Muffin, her Yorkshire
terrier. ``The dog remembered her,'' the lawyer told the Daily News
(in an article carrying the headline ``Free Fisher Reunited With
Beloved Pooch''). ``She was pleased at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of us able to regain composure after imagining that
poignant scene must be wondering:
</P>
<P>
   Why do we care?
</P>
<P>
   Why did we ever care?
</P>
<P>
   The answers, say students and scholars of popular culture,
include the nature of the crime she committed, sex, the Lolita-like
elements of her relationship with a middle-aged man, sex, the
melodious surname of her paramour, sex, the self-promotional
tendencies of its principal characters, and sex.
</P>
<P>
   The story drew in everyone with its shameless tawdriness _
including the analysts and journalists who pondered its deeper
truths while fancying themselves somehow above it all. There have,
after all, been 233 articles in The New York Times mentioning Amy
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's implicated in it,'' says Neal Gabler, the author of
``Life the Movie: How Entertainment Conquered Reality'' (Alfred A.
Knopf, 1998). ``Those of us who consume it, those of us who analyze
it. It's a voracious maw.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who sniff that they have no time for such trash are
kidding themselves, he says, ``because what they are saying is `I'm
defining myself in relationship to Amy Fisher and Joey
Buttafuoco.''' He added: ``You live in a tabloid culture. This idea
that you can somehow escape _ escape it where? By going to the end
of the universe?''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Crispin Miller, a professor of media studies at New York
University, says cases like l'affaire Fisher expose the pundit's
dilemma. ``I don't think any of us can pretend to be immune to the
appeal of these images,'' he said. ``And if we were, we wouldn't be
qualified to talk about them. You have to understand the appeal in
order to comment on it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After all, the basic appeal of the Amy Fisher saga is
self-evident. Long Island. 1992. Sixteen-year-old girl finds love
and understanding in Popeye arms of 38-year-old auto-body-shop
owner. Dabbles in prostitution, becomes obsessed with her lover,
shoots his wife in the face. She gets five-to-15 for assault. He
gets six months for statutory rape. And the ever-loyal wife is left
with a partly paralyzed face.
</P>
<P>
   The general narrative has been told so many times, in
newspapers, books and three made-for-television movies, that
incidental details linger, from the white Dodge Daytona that Ms.
Fisher smashed up _ leading her to Buttafuoco's shop in the first
place _ to the name of the Long Island-based prostitution service
that briefly employed Ms. Fisher, ABBA Escorts. A Web site called
``Aimee: The Official Amy Fisher Organization'' even includes a
trivia section.
</P>
<P>
   How deeply the Fisher case has insinuated itself into the
collective consciousness was revealed to Gabler during a recent
trip to Los Angeles. A livery driver there told the author that he
was driving down Sunset Boulevard a few weeks ago when he spotted a
minor mob scene on the sidewalk. He pulled over and asked one of
the gawkers what the commotion was all about.
</P>
<P>
   Came the answer: ``Joey Buttafuoco.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher, now 24, and her supporting cast can proudly take
their place in the pantheon of the salacious, somewhere ahead of
the Bobbitts of dismemberment fame, but assuredly behind O.J.
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   And the Fisher ensemble continues to distinguish itself with
sheer shamelessness. Ms. Fisher did not allow cold prison walls to
prevent her from leveling lurid allegations against others, from
her first lawyer to the corrections officers who guarded her. And
rather than disappear into the fog of humiliation at a time when
his surname alone was a David Letterman punch line, Buttafuoco
moved to Los Angeles to pursue an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a major shift in our sense of shame and guilt and
celebrity in our culture,'' says Joshua Meyrowitz, a professor of
communication at the University of New Hampshire who explored that
shift in ``No Sense of Place'' (Oxford University Press, 1985).
``The parading of all these people who have exhibited very negative
behavior normally would be pushed out of our social spheres, but
instead are pulled in.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the inverse is true: People are sucked into the
Fisher-Buttafuoco sphere by developments that surpass the most
outlandish subplots of daytime television, and by the vaguely
unsettling sense that Amy, Joey and Mary Jo long ago determined
that the public glare provided them with a more natural light.
</P>
<P>
   At a court hearing last month, Ms. Buttafuoco provided the
ingredient necessary to secure Ms. Fisher's conditional freedom by
announcing that she had forgiven the young woman. Ms. Fisher wept
and reportedly mouthed the words ``I'm sorry.'' The wounded wife
and the chastened hussy reached out to touch each other, but an
officer stepped in to prevent any physical healing from taking
place in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The scene will surely be included in any sequel, one that would
also probably explore various allegations that she was raped in
prison, exploited by her lawyer and abused by her father. Indeed, a
family friend who is acting as her spokeswoman has said that Ms.
Fisher is being inundated with book offers and requests for
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York's ``Son of Sam'' law, a felon generally cannot
benefit financially from a crime. Fortunately for those not yet
sated, there is a provision that allows for profit if the victim
grants permission. And Mary Jo Buttafuoco's lawyer recently told
The New York Post that the woman who still carries a bullet in her
neck would be open to ``a major deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
