<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILWAR-REENACT-TEXT-REVIEW-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINE EYES HAVE SEEN THE COMING OF A LOT OF WACKY STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(Eds: Passages in italics are indicated by ``Begin italics'' and
``End italics.'') 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gertrude Stein put it best: ``There never will be anything more
interesting in America than that Civil War never.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the war rarely wanes, but it definitely waxes around
this time of year. After Memorial Day (which evolved from mourning
rituals for the Civil War's 620,000 dead), hardly a week will pass
this summer without a battle anniversary, a combat re-enactment or
a rite of remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   As Civil War buffs trek to battlefields and monuments, they can
bone up on the details from among 60,000 titles on the Civil War _
about a quarter of all shelf space devoted to American history at
the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, writers have approached the war with reverential
awe. But there is a large and growing body of material _ books,
magazines, Web sites _ that treats the war and its landscape not
only as hallowed ground but also as fertile soil for levity,
fantasy, fringe scholarship, even romance. Who says war is hell?
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts follow. _ TONY HORWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Grooming Tips
</P>
<P>
   (Begin italics)Many Civil War re-enactors go to extremes to
duplicate the look of 1860s soldiers. The most popular re-enactors'
magazine, the Camp Chase Gazette, named after a Union prison camp,
offers tips on how to achieve authentic Civil War hair, including
``hathead'':(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks before the event, give yourself a haircut
following these rules:
</P>
<P>
   a) You cannot look in the mirror while you cut your hair.
</P>
<P>
   b) Your hair must be dry when you cut it (for more dead ends).
</P>
<P>
   c) Try to use the dullest scissors you can find. A pocket knife
is even better.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin italics)Once at the event:(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   Go to the nearest water source. A horse trough is great, but
your canteen will be adequate. Soak your head. Then, pull your hat
down real tight and let dry.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin italics)Now for the beard:(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   Chew tobacco. Don't spit; drool instead.
</P>
<P>
   Eat a lot of cornbread, allowing the crumbs to collect in the
tobacco juice. This provides a nice textured look, plus it makes a
great snack on the march.
</P>
<P>
   Comb your beard with your fingers. Be sure to wash your hands
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Eatin' and Cussin'
</P>
<P>
   (Begin italics)A true re-enactor must not only resemble a
soldier, but also eat like one. The Watchdog, another re-enactors'
publication, tells how:(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   Looking for foraged items? You can try corn-on-the-cob (in the
shuck, and white corn only, as yellow corn was considered animal
feed) ... apples in season, country ham, eggs (will keep a week
without refrigeration). ...
</P>
<P>
   Confederate soldiers often made do with substitutes. Make corn
bread in place of soft or hard bread. Their snacks were not as
fancy and included such items as goober peas (nuts) or parched
corn. Look for ``roasted corn'' in Hispanic food stores or make
your own by parching organic (no pesticides or herbicides) seed
corn in bacon fat in a hot skillet. The end result should look and
taste like unflavored Corn Nuts.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin italics)Eat like a soldier, and also talk like one. These
suggestions come from a re-enactors' chat group on ``period
cursing,'' complete with definitions:(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   Mudsill: Low-life
</P>
<P>
   Twiddle-poop: Effeminate young man
</P>
<P>
   Mutton-thumper: Incompetent
</P>
<P>
   Jobbernowl: Idiot
</P>
<P>
   Bang-pitcher: Drunkard
</P>
<P>
   Condiddling: Thieving
</P>
<P>
   Dandisprat: Insignificant person
</P>
<P>
   Ear-wig: Malicious flatterer
</P>
<P>
   Fling-dust: Harlot
</P>
<P>
   Hog rubber: Yokel
</P>
<P>
   (Begin italics)Many women join re-enactments, usually as nurses,
laundresses and other civilians. They also bring a new perspective
to the war. This is an excerpt from an Internet chat room where the
topic was ``Civil War studs'':(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   THE DISHES
</P>
<P>
   R.E. Lee: A gerontophile's dream with sugar-daddy possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Little Mac (George McClellan): Definitely dishy with perfect
hair and goatee!
</P>
<P>
   Old Bory (P.G.T. Beauregard): Continental charm in Creole
packaging.
</P>
<P>
   THE DUDS
</P>
<P>
   Braxton Bragg: Less style than a Nehru jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose Burnside: Who'd be caught dead with a walking fashion
disaster like him?
</P>
<P>
   William T. Sherman: Sinister expression.
</P>
<P>
   Those Men in Uniform
</P>
<P>
   (Begin italics)Tenting on the ol' re-enactment campground
apparently can get mighty lonesome. So the Camp Chase Gazette also
runs personal ads:(End italics)
</P>
<P>
   SWM, 43, C.S.A., Officer ... is looking for his Southern Angel
who would enjoy being in a long-term relationship, possible
marriage, and an officer's lady. One who loves re-enacting, living
history, parades, genealogy, quiet evenings at home or secret
getaway weekends, who doesn't smoke, party or will be out every
night running around.
</P>
<P>
   SWM ISO SWF, 18-?, Confederate only. Must be in good shape and
ready for some hard campaigning. No bleeding-heart liberals. Photo,
phone/address.
</P>
<P>
   DWF would like to meet Gentleman between 45-55 who is engaged in
re-enacting. I portray a nurse. Color blind as to uniform.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
