</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POST-COLDWAR-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT THE COLD WAR BUT THERE'S A NIP IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ If a space traveler had returned to Earth last week
after 35 years, he could have been excused for thinking that
nothing had changed. Russia and China hated the West. Their leaders
and citizens were angrily flinging words like ``imperialism'' and
``hegemony.'' A strange war in an obscure corner of the planet
seemed to be the occasion for mounting global tension.
</P>
<P>
   No world leaders were seen banging any shoes, but a Chinese
president, after allowing jeering crowds to stone the American
Embassy, hinted darkly that if the United States did not mend its
ways, it would ``face doom.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the space traveler would have to be told that the Cold
War really was over, and that for 10 years the Americans, the
Russians and the Chinese had agreed that their most vital interest
was in the common pursuit of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, was how many Americans had come to understand
the new world.
</P>
<P>
   But in Russia and China, as events have shown, the picture was
not quite so straightforward. Whatever goals Russia and China share
with the United States, the crisis in Kosovo _ and especially the
mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia _
has revealed the degree to which these former enemies still
distrust Americans, and also the blinders that Americans wear as
they imagine how Russia and China perceive their own vital
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans might well believe that these two needy behemoths
are shooting themselves in their economic feet, with their
fulminating hostility over events in an inconsequential place
called Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But posing the issue this way, Chinese people say, reveals the
problem. There can be no doubt that China really wants to open up
and become part of the Western-led world economy. But it has other
profound interests and fears as well. And many people here have
felt with growing force that the United States simply doesn't take
China seriously _ that it blithely ignores China's vital security
concerns as it constructs a Pax Americana.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, dependent on the International Monetary Fund's
huge loans and suffering a political meltdown that includes an
impeachment drama and successive shuffles of the government, have
likewise stewed about what they regard as ignorant and
disrespectful treatment from the West.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders, having long been lectured by the Russians about
NATO expansion, knew the Russians would hate the decision to
bombard Yugoslavia, though they may have underestimated the
long-term damage to relations if the war persisted. China's vitriol
about the intervention in Yugoslavia was another matter. Though
surprisingly harsh, it didn't seem very important at first, because
it was only oratory. And Kosovo was so far away from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't make the connection between Kosovo and China;
they just don't see it,'' observed Jonathan Pollack, a military
expert at Rand Corp. in California.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Chinese, it is now clear, the decision by what it
pointedly called ``U.S.-led NATO'' to bomb Yugoslavia without U.N.
sanction was highly significant. Culminating with the attack on
their own embassy in Belgrade, the bombing campaign has ignited a
major reassessment here of global politics and relations with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing in Yugoslavia showed us that the United States can
do anything it wants to do,'' said Zhang Yunling, director of
Asia-Pacific Studies at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences,
which advises the government. ``We see that the United States will
use its supreme position, its high technology and its allies to
dominate the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Kosovo is far away, this has alerted the Chinese,''
Zhang added, noting that China could face similar demands for
international military intervention some day in Taiwan or Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing in Yugoslavia followed other perceived signs of
hostility _ including what is regarded as politically driven
opposition to China's entry into the World Trade Organization,
rumbles of major military support for the renegade province of
Taiwan and a broadened defense agreement with Japan.
</P>
<P>
   These created a powerful sense here that the United States was
worse than a neglectful friend. The United States, many people
feared, wants to stamp China down, just as it emerges as the world
power it was always meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   That fear turned into a certainty last week, after NATO bombs
killed three journalists in the embassy in Belgrade. However
outlandish the idea seems to Americans, almost everyone in Beijing
thinks the attack was deliberate, a belief encouraged by official
propaganda. The most common theory voiced by demonstrators was
simple: The United States wants to test the upstart China.
</P>
<P>
   So a Westernized generation of Chinese youths, the same people
who normally crowd any of Beijing's 44 McDonald's outlets and yearn
to attend UCLA, unleashed a fury of anti-Americanism.
</P>
<P>
   And this raised the possibility of real hostility growing
between the two countries. For however distant the old Cold War
hostilities have become, frictions are nevertheless inevitable as
China's growing power rubs against longstanding U.S. partnerships
and interests in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   For now, U.S. diplomats here feel their own sense of betrayal.
From Ambassador James Sasser on down, they had devoted the last few
years to building a web of friendly ties with China, trying to wall
off the obvious disputes over human rights. Last year, President
Clinton and President Jiang even inaugurated a hot line.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of using the hot line last week, Jiang initially
refused to take a call from Washington. The leaders pushed the
United States to the limit, busing in students and letting them
pelt the U.S. Embassy here for four days while the controlled media
fanned hatred.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, the popular furies had subsided to a slow burn,
and Clinton and Jiang had talked. But both sides knew that
Chinese-American relations could never be quite the same and both
governments were feeling their way toward new terms.
</P>
<P>
   China was clearly trying to turn down the temperature _ not only
by halting the demonstrations but also by making surprisingly
minimal demands for redress, including apologies, a public
investigation and punishment of those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Most remarkably, Chinese officials insisted that their economic
engagement with the West should not be affected by politics and
said negotiations for entry to the World Trade Organization should
pick up where they left off.
</P>
<P>
   In a monumental misperception of U.S. political realities, some
officials even suggested that the United States should now, in a
kind of reparation, relax its negotiating stance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
