 BEIJING: negotiating stance.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zhang, the scholar and adviser, said the embassy attack had
spawned a changing view of Chinese-American relations among foreign
policy specialists here.
</P>
<P>
   Many, he said, had believed that a generally cooperative
relationship with the United States was possible. ``But now it
seems the United States will dominate the relationship, and where
there are disagreements it may resort to military force,'' he
continued. ``China might even become a target some time in the
future,'' he said, noting possible conflicts in Taiwan or the
Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   In the new circumstances, China may well increase military
spending, Zhang said, although economic development would remain
the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   How deeply this new perspective would be entrenched, Zhang said,
would depend on how well the two governments manage their
