resolved.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombing of the embassy has had the ironic effect of
thrusting China into the center of the search for a diplomatic
solution in Yugoslavia. The approach Russia developed with the NATO
powers involves sending troops under a U.N. flag into Kosovo. This
would require China's assent, something likely to be given only
grudgingly.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the current crisis, the one-time enemies China and
Russia had realized that it was in their strategic interest to
foster better ties. Now more than ever, China the emerging power
and Russia the flailing one have been brought together by a shared
sense of exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   There is no basis for a serious strategic alliance, but ``China
has used friendly sniffs to remind the United States that they can
shift northward,'' said Richard Baum, an expert on Chinese politics
at the University of California at Los Angeles. ``Russia can't
offer what China needs for modernization,'' Baum said. What it does
