<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-KURDS-2TAKES-N     05-15 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONALISM IS MOOD IN TURKEY'S KURDISH ENCLAVES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIYARBAKIR, Turkey _ An elderly man who is among the most
respected denizens of Diyarbakir's twisting bazaar sat speaking
about his memories of Kurdish struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the 1930s, he told of rebellions he has seen,
villages he once knew that have been burned by military patrols,
friends he has lost to unknown assassins and what he said was the
fatal torture of his son.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of young men were sitting silently nearby, taking it
all in. They are the new generation of Kurds, eagerly absorbing
stories that fire their political commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish government says that few Kurds support the idea of
Kurdish nationalism and that nearly all are happy with the life
Turkey offers them. But a four-day tour through Kurdish provinces
of the southeast indicated that the opposite may be true.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the region, Kurds appear more conscious of their
identity than ever. It is difficult to find any who do not support
the nationalist cause and even the armed rebellion that has been
under way since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   This public mood suggests that unless the government accepts at
least some Kurdish demands, violence could continue indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The growing support for Kurdish nationalism comes at a time when
the rebel group known as the Kurdistan Workers Party, or _ more
commonly _ by its initials PKK, has suffered heavy losses,
including the capture of its leader, Abdullah Ocalan. These
reverses seem, if anything, to have emboldened ordinary people
here, many of whom revere Ocalan as ``our leader'' _ a vivid
contrast to language used elsewhere in Turkey, where he is normally
described as a terrorist and baby-killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother never had any particular sympathy for Ocalan or his
organization,'' said a businessman in his mid-30s. ``But when she
saw the pictures of him in handcuffs, she cried.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth of nationalist sentiment here is evidently a product,
at least in part, of Ocalan's rebellion. Even Kurds who expressed
doubts about his tactics said he had awakened a new generation to a
sense of common identity that their forefathers never felt.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurdish conflict has led to much criticism of Turkey abroad,
and has been cited as one of the main obstacles to Turkish
membership in the European Union. In recent weeks, commentators in
several countries have suggested that if the ethnic Albanian
majority in Serbia's Kosovo province deserves international
protection, so does the Kurdish majority in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of Turkey's estimated 10 million Kurds come from this
region. They constitute 90 percent of the population here, although
in the last decade many have migrated westward to large cities like
Istanbul. Turkish officials reject any comparison between Kosovo
and the southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any relationship between the two issues,'' Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem said when asked about it at a news conference
during NATO's summit meeting in Washington last month.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, voters in seven provincial capitals in the Kurdish
region dealt the government a sharp blow by electing leaders of the
Kurdish nationalist party as mayors. Here in Diyarbakir, the
largest city in the region, the nationalist candidate won an
astonishing 62 percent of the vote despite police harassment that
included banning and attacking his rallies and arresting many who
campaigned for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won because we talked about identity, about the fact that
there is a Kurdish population in this country that cannot be
ignored,'' said the mayor, Feridun Celik. ``Nothing can be achieved
by refusing to recognize us. This problem has existed since the
founding of the Turkish Republic, and it has to be confronted.
There is a great fear of diversity and the expression of diversity
in this country. That is the root of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Celik rejected government assertions that he and his party,
People's Democracy, support separatism and terrorism. But a case to
close the party is pending, based on the government's assertion
that it maintains ``organic links'' with the guerrillas. After the
recent elections, a senior prosecutor said he would seek to remove
all People's Democracy mayors from office because their elections
constituted ``terrorist takeovers'' of city halls.
</P>
<P>
   Although the newly elected mayors realize that they must speak
cautiously, many ordinary people feel no such constraints as long
as they are promised anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support this party because I'm a Kurd,'' said a woman in
Diyarbakir. ``What we demand is our identity. We want it to say in
our identity cards that we are Kurds. We want schools and
television stations in our language. We're happy under the Turkish
flag, but the government is still very afraid of us. They say that
if they accept our identity, we will want to govern ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bingol, another provincial capital where a People's Democracy
candidate was elected mayor last month, a well-dressed businessman
said: ``The state can't keep us down. They have to realize that
millions of Kurds want to be recognized as Kurds, and that we
support every organization that fights for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The government fears that compromise with the nationalist
movement would ultimately lead to the region's secession. Even
suggesting peace talks with the rebel group is a criminal offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PKK's claim to be fighting for Kurdish rights is nothing
but a preposterous and outrageous deception,'' the government
asserted in a recent statement. ``The PKK is not a popular
movement, but simply a terrorist organization operating through
intimidation, coercion and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the government in Ankara were not available
here, but at one of the many military checkpoints in the southeast,
several army officers eloquently expressed the official viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no political or social basis to this conflict,'' said
a major on his third tour of duty in the southeast. ``It is all
fomented by foreign countries. You say it is a war, but I have to
correct you. This is not a war. It is a peace operation. We are
defending the country from terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   A sergeant scoffed at the suggestion that People's Democracy
should be welcomed into the political system. ``This is not just a
radical party,'' he said. ``It is a party connected to Ocalan, a
man who is responsible for killing 30,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of People's Democracy strenuously deny that their party
is linked to the guerrillas. But many voters here agree with the
government's assertion that it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they are connected to our leader and his
organization,'' said one shopkeeper. ``That's why we voted for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about accusations that guerrillas have killed
schoolteachers and committed acts of terror, the shopkeeper
replied, ``Unfortunately that is true, but what we have suffered at
the hands of the Turkish army is much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Kurdish towns, it is no longer forbidden to
use the Kurdish language, and cassettes of Kurdish music, once
banned, are now widely available. But in dozens of interviews, no
Kurd could be found who did not believe that security forces here
are guilty of repression, torture and murder.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the conflict in 1984 until the end of 1998,
according to President Suleyman Demirel, 23,638 guerrillas, 5,555
soldiers and 5,302 civilians have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has long denied the Kurdish population, located
largely in the southeast, basic political, cultural and linguistic
rights,'' the State Department said in its most recent human rights
report. ``As part of its fight against the PKK, the government
forcibly displaced noncombatants, failed to resolve extra-judicial
killings, tortured civilians, and abridged freedom of expression.
The number of villagers forcibly evacuated from their homes since
the conflict began is credibly estimated to be about 560,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Though people in the southeast now speak more freely than
before, they are still circumspect. Asked if he knew of youths who
have joined the militants, man smoking a water pipe replied: ``We
wouldn't know about that. How could we know?''
</P>
<P>
   A friend sitting nearby smiled and said, ``That's a man who
knows how to survive in Diyarbakir.''
</P>
<P>
   One prominent figure who publicly encourages a change in
government policy is Mehmet Sirin Yigit, a Kurd who heads the
Diyarbakir Chamber of Commerce and Industry. He sees the recent
election as a positive step that could open new dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two different opinions live without contact with each
other, there is trouble,'' Yigit said. ``But if there is a chance
for the two opinions to communicate, which is going to happen now,
that's better. People from both sides are going to be sitting
together in meetings, talking to each other and learning to respect
each other's sensitivities. You can't resolve problems by using
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   On a back alley in Diyarbakir, a schoolboy wearing a jacket
several sizes too big for him said he thought People's Democracy
was ``very good'' and that the guerrillas were ``also very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to explain what was good about the guerrilla army, the
youth paused for a moment and then replied: ``I don't exactly know.
But I know it's good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
