<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LUIS-TIANT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiant teaching his brand of baseball
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ At 58, Luis Tiant's trademark Fu Manchu mustache
is full of gray, and his black pullover jersey strains to hold his
ample belly. But the former Boston Red Sox cult figure still can
baffle hitters with his corkscrew delivery, the number on his back
visible as always before every pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for his Savannah College of Art and Design hitters,
Tiant's right arm is tender, limiting him to only rare
batting-practice sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season, I throw all the time,'' said Tiant, who won 20
games four times in his 19-year major-league career and finished
with 229 victories. ``This year, my arm is not so good.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean this hasn't been a special season for
Tiant, in his second year as the unlikely coach of an unlikely
college baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   When Tiant can't throw batting practice, another Tiant does _
oldest son Luis IV. At home games, a third Luis Tiant often
attends. The littlest Louie is Tiant's five-year-old grandson, Luis
V.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family is everything,'' the elder Tiant said. ``It is even
more important than baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   It was baseball that took Tiant _ the winningest major-league
pitcher from Cuba _ away from his parents, and for many years it
kept him away from his three children for long stretches.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has reunited him with his oldest son, who was running an
air-freight company in Miami before agreeing to join his father as
an assistant coach at SCAD this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a special time for both of us,'' the son said.
``It's given us a chance to get close. Baseball used to take him
away. Now it has brought us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiant spent nearly all of his pitching career separated from his
own father, a former Negro leagues standout in the 1930s and '40s.
Luis Tiant II was not allowed to leave Cuba to see his son pitch
until the 1975 World Series. He died the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The passing of time has not lessened Tiant's bitterness toward
Cuban leader Fidel Castro. When he talks about the Cuban
government, the usually jovial Tiant's words come in angry bursts
laced with profanities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal relations, (never)'' Tiant says in his heavy Cuban
accent. ``We should never forget what has happened to the people in
Cuba for 40 years. . . . All baseball cares about is getting
players out of Cuba. It doesn't care about the suffering, just
money. . . . The Orioles shouldn't have gone to Cuba. This is a
free county, but that's the way I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiant, who pitched in the majors until 1982, faced his native
Cuba in the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta, when he was the pitching
coach for Nicaragua. He was a minor-league instructor for the
Chicago White Sox in 1997, then was hired by SCAD last year.
</P>
<P>
   SCAD President Richard Rowan had lured former college and NBA
star Cazzie Russell to head the school's NCAA Division III
basketball program the year before, but his hiring of Tiant was
even more stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had dreamed about being a college coach for a long time,''
Tiant said. ``But with no education, I never thought I would get a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bees were only 14-22 in 1998, but were assured of a winning
season this year with a 4-2 victory over nationally ranked Emory
last weekend. SCAD was 19-17 going into its season finale Saturday
at Methodist College in North Carolina despite only 10 home games
and no practice field to call its own.
</P>
<P>
   Since the minor-league Savannah Sand Gnats took over Grayson
Stadium in early April with the start of the South Atlantic League
season, SCAD's practices have been held at batting cages run by
former Atlanta Braves second baseman Felix Millan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get our own field,'' said Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   But with El Tiante as an attraction, SCAD has no trouble
scheduling road games. This season, the Bees made a six-game trip
to California and twice visited New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in Boston, I always feel like I'm home,'' said Tiant,
who proudly wears his 1975 American League championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   Tiant and his players were guests at a Boston Celtics game and
the Fleet Center crowd rose and broke into chants of ``Louie,
Louie, Louie'' when Tiant's presence was announced and he was shown
on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost cry, I feel so good,'' Tiant admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played up there, he couldn't go anywhere without
someone stopping him,'' SCAD shortstop Tony Blankenship said. ``It
was obvious how much they still love him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, no Red Sox pitcher is likely to match Tiant's
popularity. Certainly, no one will duplicate Tiant's funky
delivery, in which he released the ball from all angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing he hasn't tried to teach anyone,'' freshman
pitcher Josh Lane said. ``Only one person could pitch like that.
And it was him.''
</P>
<P>
   LUIS TIANT FILE
</P>
<P>
   Update: Baseball coach at Savannah College of Art and Design.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 58.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife Maria, son Luis, 36, daughter Isabel, 32, and son
Danny, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Had 229-172 record in 19 major-league seasons (1964-82)
with Indians, Twins, Red Sox, Yankees, Pirates and Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Won 20 games four times, going 21-9 with Indians in
1968 and 20-13 in '73, 22-13 in '74 and 21-12 in '76 with Red Sox.
Led American League in ERA with 1.60 in 1968 and 1.91 in 1972. Was
2-0 in 1975 World Series, when Red Sox lost in seven games to the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
