<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan not buying Hornets result of Shinn's latest folly
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A collective groan could be heard throughout North
Carolina _ and in the New York office of commissioner David Stern _
when Michael Jordan ended negotiations last week to buy the
Charlotte Hornets from George Shinn.
</P>
<P>
   Hornet fans and Stern were hoping quietly for Jordan to take
over, not only because he's Jordan but also because it would remove
Shinn from the picture. Shinn has legal troubles on a sexual
misconduct allegation from a young woman and a messy divorce, along
with a reputation for being a tightwad. He confirmed his reputation
as irrational when he blew an opportunity to become business
partners with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown was over autonomy. Jordan wanted total control.
Shinn reportedly offered 100 percent control of basketball
decisions and 50 percent of business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Jordan ante up $80 million and then allow business
decisions to be made by a man who has run a once-viable franchise
into the ground? Jordan showed that by ending negotiations he's a
more keen businessman than Shinn.
</P>
<P>
   Beam Scotty up
</P>
<P>
   Bet Dennis Scott now wishes that he had taken the advice of his
buddy Shaquille O'Neal, who urged the former Georgia Tech star to
sign with the Lakers in the offseason. Scott wanted the Hawks, who
didn't want him, and ended up with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually got cut and signed with Minnesota. However, the
Timberwolves did not include him on the playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say I'm disappointed,'' said Scott, who averaged 9.1
points in 21 games. ``I wouldn't want to say frustrated. I'd rather
be playing to help the guys out. But they decided to go a different
direction. It's part of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott wants to stay in Minnesota, but it's likely he'll be
searching for a new team in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Not-so-easy Rider
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Rider played well in the Trail Blazers' domination of
Phoenix in the first round and showed a modicum of restraint. But
he hardly was humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the reason why we started playing good again,'' Rider
said of Portland's decisive charge in Game 3. ``Our bodies were
looking scared, tentative. I cheered on my team and got in the
huddle and told guys to buckle down. I got us hyped. I kept us
together. I was the motivator. Yes, I was.''
</P>
<P>
   He did dominate the key matchup against Rex Chapman. He came
back from a sprained right knee in the third quarter. And he did
not fight Danny Manning when the Suns forward took him out on a
hard foul. Accomplishments, all, for Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Major star on the rise: forward Brian Grant, who shot 23-for-32
in the series. In the euphoric locker room, the Blazers, who hadn't
gotten out of the first round in seven years, loudly rooted for
Sacramento over Utah.Portland beat the Kings four times without a
loss this season.
</P>
<P>
   This 'n' that
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Tim Hardaway said that even though his knee is bothering
him he plans to participate in the Olympic qualifying tournament in
July in Puerto Rico. He missed the 1994 World Championships because
of knee surgery and the '98 World Championships because of the
lockout. . . . The Bulls will have at least $22.5 million under the
salary cap to spend next season _ and a lottery pick in the draft.
. . . The Cleveland Cavaliers plan a uniform change. ``It won't be
dramatic,'' owner Gordon Gund said, ``but it will bring it
current.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
