<SLUG> BC-DEER-MUZZLELOADING16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Muzzlers unleashed: Georgia can expect its first black-powder
deer season to be a quick hit
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By the time Georgia is into its second muzzle-loading
season in 2000, the state should have 150,000 licensed black-powder
hunters, according to one of the industry's ``big three,'' and the
Wildlife Resources Division of the state Department of Natural
Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hickey, CEO and owner of Connecticut Valley Arms, made his
prediction based on what has happened in other states inaugurating
new hunting seasons for primitive weapons.
</P>
<P>
   WRD's figure of 152,600 was derived from a 1992 survey studying
the feasibility of a muzzle-loading season. The survey also
projected a $50 million economic impact statewide, plus the
possible additional income of $1 million in new license sales. A
primitive-weapons license costs $8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia is the last state east of the Rockies to the party,''
CVA President Dudley McGarity said. ``When the word gets out,
there's going to be an explosion _ pardon my pun _ of black-powder
sales.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Sporting Goods Association,
muzzle-loading is ranked 12th among 59 sports in growth rate with
5.4 percent during 1998 and 3.1 million participants.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's first muzzle-loader season will be Oct. 16-22.
</P>
<P>
   WRD Director David Waller said Georgia had to find a place for a
muzzle-loading season. That didn't come about until last year, when
deer season was allowed to run from September to January without a
break in the Northern Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Public interest sealed the deal. ``We think it has the potential
to create a lot of excitement over a new way to hunt,'' Waller
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia, ever conservative, won't allow scopes on
muzzle-loaders, as other states did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept of using primitive weapons is it's more
difficult, more of a challenge to use, and the idea of putting a
scope on a muzzle-loading flintlock just defies logic,'' Waller
said. The same goes for the inline muzzle-loaders. Even though they
look modern, Waller said they're still muzzle-loaders.
</P>
<P>
   So, predictions are that a substantial number of hunters will
make the decision to get into muzzle-loading even though it is a
pastime that requires more work _ loading and reloading, having to
get closer to game, just as bowhunters do, and not having a scope
to help on long shots. But black-powder arms makers have made
millions selling the same rifles and pistols carried by Daniel
Boone, Davey Crockett, Kit Carson and Jeremiah Johnson, because of
a huge attachment to America's past.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious to anyone in Dahlonega last weekend for the Long
Branch Buckskinners Spring Frolic, where people dressed in antique
clothing, carried antique guns and knives, competed in shooting
contests and traded wares _ including some beautiful handmade
muzzle-loading rifles _ and celebrated the way our ancestors lived
before the 1840s.
</P>
<P>
   These traditionalists _ the buckskinners _ make up most of the
muzzle-loading crowd right now. But retailers think the new
muzzle-loading season will bring on a new breed.
</P>
<P>
   They will be modern deer hunters in every way except for their
rifles, which will get them an extra week of deer season.
</P>
<P>
   It starts that way, but in bowhunting, people started buying
compound bows and then moved into traditional longbows and
recurves.
</P>
<P>
   Some will be lured back to the basics, get a Pennsylvania
flintlock, a tomahawk, buckskin clothing, flint and steel for fire,
and become frontiersmen and women.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
