<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time and money tighten for remaining free agents
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reviews have been terrific so far for 321 Courtland,
the restaurant recently opened by former Georgia Tech defensive end
Marco Coleman and agent Brian Ransom. Given that Coleman is one of
the few quality free agent players remaining and that few teams
have sufficient salary-cap room, here's hoping business stays good
at the eatery.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman last week rejected a three-year, $4.5 million offer that
would have kept him in San Diego. The contract wasn't the free
agency windfall Coleman had hoped to land, and it included
compensation of just $1 million for this year.
</P>
<P>
   But time is running out even faster than money and Coleman is
among the 125 unrestricted free agents still trying to secure a
paycheck for 1999. Not many of them turned down the kind of $3.2
milllion-a-year deal Coleman could have had with Bobby Ross in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman still could land a deal more in line with his abilities,
but it could be difficult in this tight market. Once the most
feared pass-rusher in the college game, he has just 33 1/2 sacks in
seven seasons. Since collecting a career-best 6 1/2 sacks in 1995,
he has just 9 1/2 more.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is one of the Chargers' veteran leaders and a good
player to have in the locker room, GM Bobby Beathard desperately
wanted Coleman back. But just hours after Coleman turned thumbs
down on the team's latest offer, Beathard signed defensive end Al
Fontenot instead.
</P>
<P>
   During every free agent signing period, some players and agents
overplay their hand or erroneously gauge their bargaining position,
and they eventually see the market go away from them. The group
this year includes WR Eric Metcalf (Arizona), CB Ashley Ambrose
(Cincinnati), LB Anthony Davis (Kansas City), CB Ryan McNeil (St.
Louis), OG Matt O'Dwyer (New York Jets), LB Kurt Gouveia (San
Diego), LB Jeff Brady (Carolina), CB Darrien Gordon (Denver) and SS
Stanley Richard (Washington).
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose or McNeil might benefit from the toe injury to Cowboys
cornerback Deion Sanders, but Dallas owner Jerry Jones has given no
indication yet that he is ready to make such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Former Arizona linebacker Jamir Miller turned down a two-year,
$6 million offer to return to the Cards and had to settle last week
for a one-year, $1.3 million deal from Cleveland. Seven of the last
18 veterans to sign received the minimum salary of just $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not by accident that the biggest deals in free agency
typically get done in the first weeks of the signing period,'' said
agent Ralph Cindrich, whose preference for quick deals is well
known. ``That's when teams have cap room and agents have the
ability to actually negotiate, rather than have something jammed
down their throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   To collect most of his $68 million contract, Heisman Trophy
tailback Ricky Williams must average 1,600 yards for his first four
seasons in New Orleans. ... Tennessee GM Floyd Reese restructured
the contracts of offensive tackle Brad Hopkins and wide receiver
Yancey Thigpen last week. That created enough cap room for the
Titans to finish a deal with center Bruce Matthews, who months ago
agreed to a four-year contract worth $14.65 million. ... Agent Tank
Black, under investigation by the state of Florida and the NFL
Players Association for alleged recruiting violations, has enlisted
the aid of the Rev. Jesse Jackson. ... The Falcons still have some
interest in free agent offensive guard Ian Beckles. ... Cable
television magnate Charles Dolan, who also owns the New York Knicks
and New York Rangers, is the early-line favorite to land the Jets.
The list of potential owners, though, will be a long one. Whoever
gets the franchise will want to move the Jets back to New York once
the lease at Giants Stadium expires after the 2007 season. ...
Former Auburn fullback Tony Richardson is having an impressive
offseason in Kansas City and could supplant Pro Bowler Kimble
Anders as the starter. ... Carolina probably will release guard
Corbin Lacina after June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
