<HEADER>
A8406 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHKID-ADVENTURES1     05-15 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHKID-ADVENTURES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medical mentors help boost learning
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eugene Semple reached into the white plastic tub of
body parts and pulled out another puzzle for the students from
Renfroe Middle School in Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anyone know what this is?'' he asked, holding a weird,
red, saucer-shaped organ in his gloved right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A placenta?'' seventh-grader Jessica Rowland tentatively
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' Semple replied, pointing to the umbilical cord before
explaining its function in the uterus. ``We examine the placenta
just like all other tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Semple, an assistant pathologist, easily was the highlight of a
recent Saturday morning for students participating in their
``Health Adventures'' lesson at DeKalb Medical Center in Decatur.
Repeatedly, they asked Semple to show another post-surgical organ
from the pile he was examining for signs of disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``A heart. Do you have a heart in there?'' one boy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, but let's see what I can find,'' Semple said.
</P>
<P>
   He produced a tiny brown stone, then a moldy gallbladder. His
audience winced, curled noses and managed to ``eew-yuck'' in
unison.
</P>
<P>
   The only such program of its kind in Georgia, Health Adventures
is a national initiative designed to reach vital terrain: young
people's brains. While learning about the medical field, they
improve mathematical and science skills. And, through a mission
statement and one-on-one adult mentors, they learn what it takes to
become a heart surgeon, a pediatrician, a physical therapist or
another specialist in the health field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to see the labor and delivery floor, and after that I
was inspired to become an obstetrician,'' said Zaneta Johnson, an
eighth-grader at Renfroe. She's paired with Dr. Caroline
Charles-May, a pediatrician in private practice. About half the
mentors are DeKalb Medical Center employees.
</P>
<P>
   The program is one of the many mentoring programs of ``America's
Promise'' Alliance for Youth, endorsed by former Joint Chiefs of
Staff Chairman Colin Powell. The program was developed three years
ago by the American Society of Directors of Volunteer Services.
</P>
<P>
   Theresia Snelling, education coordinator for DeKalb Medical
Center laboratories, presented the most recent lesson with an
hour-long lecture and slide show about what goes on in a hospital
laboratory. Part of the slide show: what parasites, red blood
cells, sperm cells and yeast cells look like under the microscope.
</P>
<P>
   That led to discussions of disease and some practical advice:
``I'm telling you young ladies, if you're wearing your bluejeans
really tight in August in Georgia, you will get a yeast
infection.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with explicit, repeated ``do not touch anything''
instructions, the children walked through the numerous labs,
watching white-coated microbiologists and blood bank technicians in
action.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers say those who take part in the program always talk
about the weekend adventure come Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four of my students are in the program, and it's really
helped,'' said Beverly Cockerham, a reading and math teacher at
Renfroe. She also assists with the Saturday-morning sessions, which
are held once a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their self-esteem has flourished and they feel good about
themselves,'' Cockerham said. ``They appreciate the T-shirts, the
lunches and the special attention paid to them.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 5, the 15 middle schoolers in the program will
``graduate'' with a cookout and trip to the Sci-Trek science
museum.
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb Medical Center pays for all the educational supplies, the
red-and-blue Health Adventure shirts and the box lunches that end
the four-hour sessions. A bus deposits them at the hospital at 9:30
a.m., prime Saturday snooze time for most adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to give up the sleep at first,'' admitted Dylan
Foley, 13. ``But I got to like it because they're not just telling
you. You get to see where people work and you get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
