<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSIONARY-ABUSE16-CO     05-15 1795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSIONARY-ABUSE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Church is reaching out to those abused in its school
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Decades later and half a world away from the defunct
West African boarding school where they suffered abuse as children,
dozens of adult offspring of Christian missionaries are meeting
this weekend in Gwinnett County to confront the anger, fear and
pain of the past and to move toward the future.
</P>
<P>
   They have been invited to Simpsonwood Conference and Retreat
Center by the Christian and Missionary Alliance, the denomination
that ran Mamou Alliance Academy, the school where, as young as 6,
they were beaten, fondled and forced to sit in their own waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to attempt some healing and reconciliation and
closure,'' said Robert Niklaus, director of communications for the
alliance, a conservative denomination of about 300,000 members with
missions in more than 50 countries. ``The basic premise is that
although the school is closed and these events took place years
ago, we do feel a responsibility to those who have been injured. We
want to do the right thing by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamou (Mah-MOO) Alliance Academy in Mamou, Guinea, operated from
the 1920s until 1971 in the fertile mountains of West Africa,
educating the children of missionaries serving in four countries
for the alliance and other evangelical groups.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the alliance has spent more than $400,000
investigating allegations of mistreatment of children at Mamou
during the 1950s and 1960s, providing therapy for former students,
disciplining former staff and establishing procedures to prevent
future abuse. After considering the testimony of about 80
witnesses, a six-member Independent Commission of Inquiry, made up
of mostly non-alliance members, found:
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff members beat children, sometimes to the point of
bruising or bleeding, with their hands, belts, a strap and, in the
case of one staff member, a rubber slipper, for offenses as minor
as ``getting his Sunday shoes wet.'' Among the victims was a child
whose arm had just been broken in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   _ A female teacher routinely turned over desks with students in
them, pulled hair, stabbed children with a pencil and shook,
pinched, slapped and scratched her pupils. She withheld permission
to go to the bathroom and forced children to sit in their own urine
and feces. A report by the independent commission described her
presence in the classroom as an ``ongoing reign of terror and
sadistic behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A male staff member fondled elementary school girls and
invoked public humiliation for children who were incontinent.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than one staff member made children eat their own vomit.
</P>
<P>
   The independent commission found seven former staff members and
two former students committed some form of abuse. Three of the
people were dead, two had left the CMA, and four had retired when
the commission made its report. Of the accused people who were
confronted by a disciplinary committee, one confessed, apologized
to students on videotape and agreed to a psycho-sexual evaluation
and recommended treatment. One was excused from disciplinary
hearings because of advanced Alzheimer's disease. Two were found
guilty, and a disciplinary committee was unable to render judgment
of another.
</P>
<P>
   In response to recommendations by the independent commission,
the alliance issued formal apologies to victims of abuse, reviewed
policies for evaluation of missionary school personnel, and is
establishing an Advocacy Network for Missionary Children and a
Sensitive Issues Team to deal with any future allegations of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The independent commission also suggested the Simpsonwood
retreat. Officials expect about 80 Mamou alumni and 50 of their
spouses and parents to attend. Some whole families will come _
parents, grown children and their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm angry, really angry,'' said Beverly Shellrude-Thompson,
47, a Toronto language school director who attended Mamou from age
6 until age 16, and says she was psychologically and sexually
abused there. ``But I want to at least give them the chance to do
this right. I want there to be at this retreat enough space for
people to be able to tell our stories to one another for parents,
for alumni, for spouses to connect with one another and have the
impetus to move on in our journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Shellrude-Thompson, her older sister, her younger brother and
their father will be at Simpsonwood.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Beardslee, 72; his wife, Ann, 70; and their two sons will
also be there. The Beardslees' boys both attended Mamou briefly in
the late 1950s but changed schools after the Beardslees left the
Christian and Missionary Alliance because of theological
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left them when they were little,'' said their mother. ``Now
we can be by their sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The older Beardslees, now retired and living in New Hampshire,
learned of problems at Mamou only last year after an article about
the investigation appeared in Christianity Today magazine. When
asked, their sons, Keith, now 48, and Howard, 46, confirmed the
details of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live with those regrets,'' said their father, who went on
to spend years in the mission field with the American Bible Society
and last worked as a pastoral psychotherapist before retiring. ``So
do a lot of parents, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a hard time forgiving myself for having sent them to
that school,'' said their mother, who served as associate director
of Church World Service, a disaster relief and refugee resettlement
program of the National Council of Churches. ``It never occurred to
me in those days that I could say `no,''' she said. ``Obedience to
God for me meant obedience to the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   When children were mistreated, or even when they struggled with
their studies, they were not allowed to let their parents know.
Mail was censored, the students were told, to make sure they were
not distracting their parents from their duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents would not be able to do the work of the Lord, and
then people would go to hell,'' said Shellrude-Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   She said she blotted out the abuse she was subjected to at Mamou
until the 1980s, ``when I was 30 and falling apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the worst part was and always will be separation at
age 6,'' she said. ``Being away eight months a year for a
6-year-old is very destructive. Also, within evangelical and
fundamental communities, people have difficulty with expression of
emotion. Normal grieving was turned into something evil and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents went on about their work, trusting their colleagues at
Mamou to care for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression then was good,'' said Doloris Burns Bandy, 75,
who sent four children to Mamou while she and her husband worked
among people in Mali. The school, she said, ``provided an education
for my children. It provided peer interaction that I could not have
given them on an isolated bush station.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few years ago, Bandy, who now lives in Florida, learned
three of her four children had been abused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were beaten on a routine basis,'' said her son, Stan Burns,
50, a wedding and family photographer living in Lawrenceville.
``Not hanging up a washcloth after a shower. Not taking a shower.
Leaving articles of clothing out of place in the room.'' Bandy and
her children, who will attend the retreat, have dealt with the
abuse, she said. ``I'm very grateful that it's all come out, and
they were able to express their hurts with me. We've talked about
it. We've prayed about it. We've asked forgiveness of each other.
It's been difficult, but every experience makes us stronger in our
walk with the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   For some of the adults who spent time at Mamou as children, the
abuse has caused long-ranging effects. The independent commission
cited numbed emotions, accentuated or diminished memory, wariness,
difficulty with authority, sexual addiction, fear of intimacy,
spiritual insecurity and alienation from God as some of the results
reported by Mamou alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stan Burns nor Shellrude-Thompson is involved with a
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got too much of it when I was a kid,'' says Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in God,'' said Shellrude-Thompson. ``I actually am
quite spiritual. I've tried not to be, but I can't get away from
it. But I'm not sure I will ever again be able to be part of an
organized community.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Mamou alumni have stayed with the church and become
theologians, pastors, denomination officials and missionaries. One
of Burns' three sisters is a missionary on medical leave. Another
now works at a missionary school in the Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Burns and his mother praise the Christian and Missionary
Alliance for its handling of the Mamou allegations, which began to
come to light in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The denomination has openly, publicly acknowledged that this
happened, that the things that happened were wrong,'' said Bandy.
``I feel they have gone the second, third and fourth mile to
rectify the situation. I greatly appreciate what the Christian and
Missionary Alliance has done.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Mamou alumni say the denomination should go further and
that other denominations who had children at Mamou and other
missionary schools should examine their effects on children.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard Darr, 44, who was a leader in drawing attention
to abuse at Mamou, is now one of the founders of a new organization
called the Missionary Kids Safety Net. Darr, his two brothers and
his sister attended Mamou while their parents did mission work for
the Gospel Missionary Union, an independent missionary-sending
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Since word began to spread about the Mamou investigation, he
said, former students have come forward to tell of abuse at other
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Darr, a United Methodist minister in Illinois, said his group
sees the Simpsonwood retreat ``as a beginning, really, to open up
allegations of abuse at four or five other boarding schools.'' He
rattled off the names of schools in Ecuador, Gabon, Malaysia and
the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 evangelical denominations and organizations send
missionaries out today, said Darr. Those missionaries have about
12,000 children in about 120 schools. Since many of the
missionary-sending groups cooperate on other projects, they should
work together to address past wrongs and protect their children, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge, huge problem,'' he said. ``They need to reach
out to these missionary kids who were so grievously wounded. Their
failure to do so, when these missionary kids come to them, in my
estimation is a repudiation of the very Gospel they repute to be
spreading around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
