</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-ADVANCE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers hope for first pick in lottery
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the odds generally are stacked against expansion
teams for immediate success, today the Thrashers have a chance to
overcome their first hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is one of five NHL teams in today's 12-team lottery with
a chance to secure the No. 1 pick in the June 26 entry draft in
Boston. Tampa Bay, which had the worst record in the league this
season, has a 26 percent chance in the weighted lottery to secure
the first pick, followed by the Thrashers and Vancouver at 16.9
percent, the New York Islanders at 10.8 and Nashville at 8.3.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will pick no lower than third in the first round
and will be slotted second in all other rounds. Teams can move up
no more than four spots from their current seeding and drop no more
than one. Each team will be assigned an allotment of numbers, and
hope that one matches the one on pingpong balls. The contest will
take place at NHL headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting excited about this,'' said Thrashers general
manager Don Waddell, who recently returned from the World
Championships in Norway. ``I wasn't going to go originally, but now
I'm glad I am. If we finish third, I'll be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus two best players available in the draft are Czech
center Patrick Stefan and right wing Pavel Brendl from Calgary,
although Stefan's series of concussions has clouded his status.
</P>
<P>
   The entry draft will come one day after the Thrashers' begin to
stock their roster in the expansion draft by selecting one player
off each of the existing 27 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
