<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-WADDELL16-COX     05-15 2799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WADDELL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM Waddell hits the road to scout talent
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Last June, Don Waddell was entrusted with the
responsibility of building a hockey team. The expansion Atlanta
Thrashers named Waddell, an assistant general manager of the
Detroit Red Wings, as their GM and primary architect, giving him
the authority to hire the coaching and scouting staffs and draft
the players.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking the job, Waddell has been running a race against
the draft deadlines of June 25 and 26, when the original Thrashers
will be formed by the expansion and amateur drafts, respectively.
He has traveled through the U.S., Canada and Europe, scouting
thousands of players in hundreds of games in the NHL, minor
leagues, juniors, colleges and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Jeff Schultz
accompanied Waddell on a scouting trip to Milwaukee; Calgary;
Medicine Hat, Alberta; and Red Deer, Alberta; to gain some insight
into the general manager's task.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Chicago . . . .
</P>
<P>
   Where there is hockey, there is a tooth story, and it seems like
an appropriate time for Don Waddell to tell his.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager of the expansion Atlanta Thrashers is behind
the wheel of a rental car heading north along Lake Michigan. But
thoughts of scouting the evening's minor-league hockey game between
the Milwaukee Admirals and Detroit Vipers do not warm him on a
chilly evening.
</P>
<P>
   It feels like somebody is operating a jackhammer in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's killing me _ we've gotta stop for some aspirin,'' Waddell
says, trying not to sound like a chipmunk as he touches the back of
his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, his problems will be the defenseman who won't take the
body or the winger who would lose a match race with a Zamboni. But
now, the problem is a bridge that dates back to Waddell's playing
days. It has given him problems off and on, but the pain peaked the
night before in Calgary, where Thrashers scouts congregated at the
annual NHL Prospects Game.
</P>
<P>
   That's what you get for winning your dental work in a football
wager. So the story goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing in Saginaw one year and I bet the team dentist
on the Super Bowl,'' Waddell said. ``I had my jaw broken and lost a
tooth in a game, so I needed a bridge. If I lost the bet, I
would've had to pay for the bridge, not that I had the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Waddell was rewarded with defective bridgework.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, he would have flown from Calgary to Atlanta to
visit a dentist had he not committed to meeting a reporter in
Chicago for the last four days of his latest marathon scouting
trip. An IHL game in Milwaukee; a juniors game in Medicine Hat,
Alberta; an NHL game in Calgary; another juniors game in Red Deer,
Alberta; then back to Calgary for a flight home. Four days, four
games, three leagues, two currencies and enough coffee to keep
several generations of Folgers children in silk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've cut down _ no more than three pots a day,'' Waddell says,
proud of his accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   He is serious. When Waddell is in Atlanta, rare these days,
office employees regularly bring him a fresh cup if they happen to
be near a coffee stand. On the road, he's on his own. The
coffee-maker in his hotel room never goes unused. The two-hour
drives from civilizations to frozen arena towns invariably includes
a stop at Tim Horton's Donuts, Canada's Krispy Kreme.
</P>
<P>
   The last stretch of this trip isn't considered hellish on the
Waddell scale of road swings. He has been home two days in the last
24, one week in the last eight. He estimates that he and his staff
of 12 will have at least eight reports on each of as many as 300
amateur prospects, 400 to 600 NHL players and 200 AHL and IHL
players. The GM and a dozen scouts will fly, drive, eat and stay in
enough motels to account for approximately $1 million in
expenditures by the time the bulk of the Thrashers' inaugural
roster is formed with the June 25-26 drafts.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell probably doesn't need to see as many games in person as
he has. As team president Harvey Schiller told him, ``That's what
you have scouts for.'' But Waddell says, ``I want to see the
players for myself.'' He puts down his cell phone, having returned
two messages from other league GMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I figured this out before Christmas. I have
something like 500,000 air miles in my account. And if I ever lose
my job, I can stay at a hotel for six months, and I can rent a car
for over two years. So we'll be OK for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Milwaukee
</P>
<P>
   Why an IHL game in Milwaukee? ``Milwaukee is Nashville's farm
team,'' Waddell says. ``This allows me to get a feel for their
depth and whether they made the right decisions in their expansion
draft when they got all those compensatory picks (for not drafting
certain veterans). It could affect our thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a chance one of Detroit's unattached players might
be worth signing for the Thrashers' farm team. But when it's time
for the opening faceoff in the Bradley Center, Waddell is standing
in a corridor behind the Milwaukee bench, talking to the Admirals'
team dentist, who gives the NHL's newest executive two options:
take a prescription for painkillers until he gets back home or have
minor surgery _ now.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell chooses the latter, and accompanies the dentist to his
office a few blocks from the arena. As far as anybody knows, he
becomes the first general manager of an NHL expansion team to have
his gums cut into and a tooth drilled during a scouting trip. It
causes him to miss most of the game, but he makes it back for the
third period. Hey, he's tough _ he's a hockey executive. When he
returns to the press box, he is wearing a crooked smile as he says
what sounds like, ``Feels a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   He returns in time to see Detroit rally for a 4-3 win in a
shootout and takes a few mental notes, right down to what player
the Vipers choose to take their final faceoff in regulation. ``You
know those famous seven words in hockey: `Final minute of play in
the period.' Some scouts never hear those because they leave early.
Now I know who Detroit's best faceoff man is.'' He drives back to
Chicago. An early morning flight to Calgary awaits.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell is used to the travel, but he says: ``This is worse than
normal because we don't have any home games yet. Normally, I
wouldn't be running all over the world trying to catch these guys
for the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Canada
</P>
<P>
   Waddell spots a Tim Horton's in the Calgary airport and
pronounces, ``That'll be our stop on the way to Medicine Hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Medicine Hat. Not to be confused with Saskatoon or Regina
or Kamloops or Red Deer or Prince Albert, some of the outposts that
make up the junior leagues. There are 53 teams in three leagues _
Western, Ontario and Quebec Major _ spread out mostly over the
Canadian provinces, with some in the United States, everything from
the Moose Jaw Warriors to Les Mooseheads de Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   The system is significantly different from baseball's. In
baseball, players are drafted out of high school or college. In
Canada _ where kids skate almost from the time they can walk _ boys
are playing organized hockey from the time they are five, are
scouted by junior teams at 12 and can be drafted as young as 14.
Most players in the league are 17 to 19, and they often remain in
the juniors even after being drafted in the NHL. But because the
junior teams are not affiliated with NHL clubs, a player's future
pro team has no control over how he is coached in the amateurs.
Players live with local families, receive a weekly stipend and have
their education arranged by the team. They play a schedule nearly
as long (70 games) as an NHL team's (82). They also can be traded.
</P>
<P>
   In Alberta, the towns are small and remote, separated by miles
of natural gas fields or farmland or nothing. For variety, there
are snowdrifts.
</P>
<P>
   Medicine Hat is known as ``The Gas City'' because of it's
reserves of natural gas. According to legend, the Cree's medicine
man deserted the tribe during a war with the Blackfoot and lost his
headdress as he tried to cross a steam. The Cree were slaughtered
and the site was named, ``Saamis,'' an Indian word meaning
``Medicine Man's Hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell is less interested in the legend or ``The World's
Tallest Tepee'' off Highway 1 than he is in Jamie Lundmark, a
player for Moose Jaw, which faces the Medicine Hat Tigers in a
Western League game. Fights are so prevalent in this league that
two teams are not allowed to take their pregame skate at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, Moose Jaw and Medicine Hat play a rather uninspired
game. But Lundmark notches a goal and two assists in a 7-3 win,
showing the quick hands and decision-making that impress Waddell
and John Gill, the Thrashers' West-based scout.
</P>
<P>
   Lundmark is from Edmonton and grew up watching Wayne Gretzky,
Mark Messier and Jari Kurri. He is asked if he's ever been to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but I've been to Seattle,'' he says. ``Is Atlanta on the
West Coast?''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to the east.
</P>
<P>
   ``Near Detroit?''
</P>
<P>
   Keep going south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell smiles later when told about it. A knowledge of world
geography won't affect his selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't draft a guy we haven't interviewed,'' he said. ``Some
of these kids leave home when they're 15 or 16. It's tough for a
lot of them to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to project where a youth will play at the NHL level
in five or six years. The majority, if not all, of the Thrashers'
amateur draft picks won't play in the league next year. The player
most likely to make an immediate impact is Czech native Patrik
Stefan, who already is playing among older and stronger athletes in
the IHL. But Stefan has had injury problems, and making him the
first pick of a new franchise could be risky.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will draft first, second or third in the first
round. The team's personnel department is 12 deep, not including
Waddell. At the amateur level, there are about 40 teams in Europe
and 40 in U.S. colleges with players. All are graded on a scale of
1.0 to 5.0, and reports are filed via laptop computers into a
mainframe in Waddell's offices in CNN Center.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell can access the reports at any time and does _ in the
early morning, late night or midday between flights, with a coffee
cup at his side. His computer includes software enabling him to
narrow a search for a certain type of player: a left winger at
least 6 feet tall and 200 pounds, as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get anything I want without talking to my (scouts),''
Waddell said. ``I can see what each scout is doing, but they can't
see what the other scouts' reports are, and they can't see my
stuff. I want their own opinions. If five guys tell me the same
thing about No. 20 for Medicine Hat, we have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to Calgary
</P>
<P>
   The focus shifts to the expansion draft as Waddell heads back to
civilization for an NHL game between the Flames and Los Angeles.
The Thrashers will draft for the present the day before they draft
for the future, selecting one player from each of 26 teams;
first-year Nashville is exempt.
</P>
<P>
   One fact is plain: The original Atlanta Thrashers will be
leftovers. First- and second-year players are exempt, and then
teams will protect 15 more players from their 24-man rosters. The
Thrashers must choose at least three goalies, eight defenseman and
12 forwards. Of the remaining three players, Waddell said, two will
be goalies.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's roster's early fortunes will hinge on hockey's great
equalizer _ goaltending. Goaltending is a strength in the league,
and because they come into the league alone next season, they don't
have to worry about the selections of another team. The next
season, 2000-01, Minnesota and Columbus come in together.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell already has a pretty good fix on teams' protected lists.
And as the Flames and Kings are two nonplayoff teams, neither will
be providing the Thrashers with a centerpiece, particularly in
goal. The Kings are one of five teams exempt from losing a goalie
because it had one selected by Nashville. Calgary, because of
injuries and inadequacies, played a league-high six goalies this
year. In other words, any potential Atlanta player from these teams
is likely to be a fourth-line forward or minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Only one player stands out as the Kings and Flames play to a 2-2
tie: Flames goalie Fred Brathwaite, who stops 31 of 33 shots. But
5-foot-7 goalies seldom excite general managers. The game was worth
seeing for one reason, though. Afterward, Los Angeles coach Larry
Robinson vents to the media about the game's officiating, calling
it, ``The worst I've ever seen in my career.'' It's merely the
latest sign that Robinson, a Hall of Fame player, might not be cut
out for head coaching, hurting his potential candidacy for a job in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   On to Red Deer
</P>
<P>
   The caravan grows. Waddell and Gill meet with another scout,
John Perpich, before making the 90-minute drive north to Red Deer.
(Worth noting: In 1992, a contest was held in England to determine
the world's dullest postcard. The winner among 382 entries was a
picture of the Red Deer museum.) Gill and Perpich live a scout's
life. They typically see five to seven games per week and are home
no more than a week out of a month.
</P>
<P>
   There are other places Perpich would rather be _ such as
Southern California. The schedule originally called for him to
watch Stefan, playing with the IHL's Long Beach Ice Dogs, for a few
home games. But a concussion knocked the player out of the lineup
and Perpich out of the sun and into Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to that trip,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell is in the driver's seat for the drive to Red Deer. He
won't be a passenger if he can help it. Don't get between Don
Waddell and a coffee pot or a steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   During the drive to Red Deer, somebody mentions that Erie (Pa.)
forward Tim Connolly suffered a broken leg the other night.
Connolly is rated by the NHL's Central Scouting as the fourth-best
player in the juniors, behind only Stefan, Calgary's Pavel Brendl
and Lundmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you have to see these guys early,'' Waddell says.
</P>
<P>
   Team Thrasher pulls into the parking lot at the Centrium, a new
6,000-seat arena, in contrast with some of the barns on the
circuit. At least two dozen scouts are in attendance, mostly to see
Moose Jaw's Lundmark or another touted prospect, forward Justin
Mapletoft of the Red Deer Rebels (Web site: www.ripsnort.com).
</P>
<P>
   After his pregame coffee and separate chats with Gill and
Perpich, the three leave the scouts room and head into the stands,
sitting in different sections. Gill, in fact, is seated nowhere
near another scout.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these guys hang around together, travel together,
even talk to each other about players,'' Waddell says. ``It's
scouting by consensus. John has a reputation of being kind of a
loner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill has an impressive resume _ 11 years with Pittsburgh, three
with Colorado. He didn't know Waddell until seeing the new GM's
name on a news ticker along the bottom of his TV. ``I sent him a
resume the next day,'' Gill said. ``I wanted the chance to work
with an expansion team.''
</P>
<P>
   Moose Jaw travels well. The Warriors, with a significant
cheering section for the second game in a row, win 3-2. Lundmark
looks tired and goes pointless, but Mapletoft scores one of Red
Deer's goals.
</P>
<P>
   Gill and Perpich speak in generics when asked if the Thrashers
are looking for a certain type of player. But Waddell makes it no
secret that he loves speed. If you are looking for a model for the
team, look at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   But this amateur draft is getting more confusing than ever.
Stefan is out with his second concussion of the year. Lundmark is
talented but inconsistent. Brendl is on a scoring tear but some
scouts think that he ``floats'' too much. The top-two-rated
Europeans are Swedish twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin. But some
question their ability to play apart. Now word is that Henrik will
not declare himself eligible in June, keeping alive the chances he
can be drafted by his brother's team in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell met with his staff recently at a Prospects Game in
Calgary. ``We talked about five players for two hours,'' he said,
``because we all see things differently. There's still legitimately
six guys who can go No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Home alone
</P>
<P>
   Waddell, Gill and Perpich return to Calgary. The scouts have
flights the next day to different ponds. Waddell is returning to
Atlanta to see a man about a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the guy in Milwaukee did was temporary until I got back
to Atlanta,'' he said. ``I've never been so glad to get home just
so I can have root canal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
