<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-15 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BILL SAYS CHILL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The pressure's on for Al Gore to relax.
</P>
<P>
   I bet he is in a room somewhere right now playing Barry White
CDs and struggling to get mellow.
</P>
<P>
   It's painful to picture the coiled vice president trying to
uncoil.
</P>
<P>
   Will the father of the Internet soak in a soothing aromatherapy
bath or ask those Buddhist monks for a mantra? Will the hero of
``Love Story'' try reflexology on his feet? Will Farmer Al darken
his West Wing office and get daily 90-minute massages with that New
Age music that sounds like whales mating?
</P>
<P>
   He has no choice. He has to loosen up and dress down. It's a
presidential directive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told him to go out and have a good time, talk about
what he would do in the next four years, just enjoy himself and let
people see him the way I see him,'' President Clinton told Richard
Berke, the chief political correspondent of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy himself? That's easy for Clinton to say. After all, a new
Fox poll asked, ``Who do you think would be more fun to hang out
with, the president or the vice president?'' Forty-nine percent
chose Bill and only 19 percent chose Al.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the reasons are piling up for Gore to stay uptight.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassingly, he is losing the women's vote to W., the same
vote that Saturday Night Bill kept solid despite sexual harassment
charges, despite an affair with an intern, despite humiliating his
wife, despite a rape accusation. Gore, ever the faithful husband,
ever the champion of diversity, shows up with posies and chocolates
and women voters slam the door in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassingly, W. has already raised $13 million sitting on his
porch in Austin, while the vice president has endured a
cross-country marathon and reported only $8.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassingly, Gore, who got in trouble over money, recruits as
his campaign chairman Tony Coelho, who got in trouble over money.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all this, the president rushes in to infantilize his
vice president, calling Berke to offer an extremely rare interview.
The president meant to praise his friend but ended up broadcasting
his fears that Gore's rigor mortis could be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's idea of shoring up his vice president is to say the
Gore campaign is not as bad as it was eight weeks ago. He notes
that his partner is ``smart'' to put distance between them on the
campaign trail, and be his own man. But at the same time, he plays
the puppeteer, Gore's Dick Morris. It's classic Bill Clinton. By
endorsing the distancing tactic on the front page, he undercuts it.
That'll teach Al to try to escape Bill's embrace.
</P>
<P>
   The call to the Times was remarkably revealing. You'd think _ or
hope _ that the commander in chief would have something more
important to do than Lanny Davis-style deadline spinning for Al
Gore. Doesn't he have enough problems? Shouldn't he be focusing on
bombing the Serbs instead of the Chinese _ who could soon have a
warhead they stole from us aimed at us?
</P>
<P>
   Clintonites say that getting advice on politics from Bill
Clinton is like getting advice on basketball from Michael Jordan.
But with his rescue-spin call the president's shot a brick.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's counsel for Gore to get casual and lose the blue suit
illustrates the box Gore finds himself in. The next time Gore
saunters out in his khakis and a polo shirt, he'll just look like a
tight guy who had his clothes laid out by a loose guy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is in a spiral of self-consciousness. He's also in a bind.
On the one hand, his numbers are depressed by the fact that people
are holding him accountable for an administration that has
exhausted everyone with its big and small scandals. That is why on
the campaign trail, the vice president never mentions the
president's name. On the other hand, he needs the Clintons' help.
</P>
<P>
   The president is determined to have Gore succeed him because he
is convinced _ wrongly, I think _ that it will validate his own
legacy. Also, Clinton's two loves are campaigning and being the
center of attention. Without a campaign of his own, it is
inevitable that he will try to inject himself as campaign
strategist, for either Al or Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore crowd is livid about the president's interview. The
vice president himself is unhappy that his inevitability has become
evitable. He must be steamed at the president.
</P>
<P>
   That will make it even harder for Al to chill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
