<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8422 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAPS-REVIEW-AR     05-15 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAPS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART BOMBS, DUMB MAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Oh, for the want of a good map. So went the lament
last week from Pentagon and CIA analysts in the wake of NATO's
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, an accident blamed
largely on the use by targeting experts of a faulty map.
</P>
<P>
   The air war over Yugoslavia is now almost solely reliant on
bombs dropped with pinpoint precision. But the hundreds of cruise
missiles and satellite-steered 2,000-pound bombs, including three
from a stealthy B-2 bomber that ripped into a building the CIA
confused with a Yugoslav arms agency down the street, are only as
accurate as the information on which they are based.
</P>
<P>
   And as Pentagon planners unleash the full fury of air power not
only on isolated Yugoslav military bases but on headquarters
buildings in downtown Belgrade, pressure is mounting on military
mapmakers to be more precise than ever in identifying which targets
are fair game and which definitely are not.
</P>
<P>
   To avert another such mishap, Defense Secretary William Cohen
announced a series of corrective steps last week, including
speedier updates from government analysts to the military's
so-called no-strike list: churches, schools, embassies and cultural
shrines.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the billions poured into building B-2 bombers or
launching secret spy satellites, the art of military mapmaking and
analyzing reconnaissance photographs has been given short shrift in
the post-Cold War budget battles here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big sexy things are easier to convince people to buy than
the infrastructure to support them,'' a senior intelligence
official said..
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, the number of mapmakers at the National
Imagery and Mapping Agency, the military's chartmaker, has dropped
by about one-third, and the number of photographic analysts is down
by nearly half. Meanwhile, the workload has escalated. ``It's a
reaping of the harvest of the underinvestment in our intelligence
capabilities,'' said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who heads the House
Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the Cold War, the Pentagon and Congress thought
the country could afford fewer experts tracking Soviet missile
silos.
</P>
<P>
   But with today's diplomacy more often than not enforced by
laser-guided bombs, targeters demand enough exactness to put those
bombs down the air shafts of buildings in Baghdad, Khartoum or
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping up with fast-paced events and unpredictable hot spots is
tough on cartographers, a painstakingly studious bunch who normally
take months to churn out a detailed paper map.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it's no surprise that just a few months ago, the
federal mapping agency awarded a $600 million contract to 15
commercial mapmakers and imagery companies to help keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Cohen noted another problem last week: Other
government agencies, including the State Department, apparently
failed to alert the mapping agency of the Chinese Embassy's new
location. Which only underscores that the mapmakers, like the smart
bombs themselves, are only as good as the information they get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAPS-REVIEW-AR     05-15 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAPS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART BOMBS, DUMB MAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Oh, for the want of a good map. So went the lament
last week from Pentagon and CIA analysts in the wake of NATO's
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, an accident blamed
largely on the use by targeting experts of a faulty map.
</P>
<P>
   The air war over Yugoslavia is now almost solely reliant on
bombs dropped with pinpoint precision. But the hundreds of cruise
missiles and satellite-steered 2,000-pound bombs, including three
from a stealthy B-2 bomber that ripped into a building the CIA
confused with a Yugoslav arms agency down the street, are only as
accurate as the information on which they are based.
</P>
<P>
   And as Pentagon planners unleash the full fury of air power not
only on isolated Yugoslav military bases but on headquarters
buildings in downtown Belgrade, pressure is mounting on military
mapmakers to be more precise than ever in identifying which targets
are fair game and which definitely are not.
</P>
<P>
   To avert another such mishap, Defense Secretary William Cohen
announced a series of corrective steps last week, including
speedier updates from government analysts to the military's
so-called no-strike list: churches, schools, embassies and cultural
shrines.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the billions poured into building B-2 bombers or
launching secret spy satellites, the art of military mapmaking and
analyzing reconnaissance photographs has been given short shrift in
the post-Cold War budget battles here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big sexy things are easier to convince people to buy than
the infrastructure to support them,'' a senior intelligence
official said..
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, the number of mapmakers at the National
Imagery and Mapping Agency, the military's chartmaker, has dropped
by about one-third, and the number of photographic analysts is down
by nearly half. Meanwhile, the workload has escalated. ``It's a
reaping of the harvest of the underinvestment in our intelligence
capabilities,'' said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who heads the House
Intelligence Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the Cold War, the Pentagon and Congress thought
the country could afford fewer experts tracking Soviet missile
silos.
</P>
<P>
   But with today's diplomacy more often than not enforced by
laser-guided bombs, targeters demand enough exactness to put those
bombs down the air shafts of buildings in Baghdad, Khartoum or
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping up with fast-paced events and unpredictable hot spots is
tough on cartographers, a painstakingly studious bunch who normally
take months to churn out a detailed paper map.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it's no surprise that just a few months ago, the
federal mapping agency awarded a $600 million contract to 15
commercial mapmakers and imagery companies to help keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Cohen noted another problem last week: Other
government agencies, including the State Department, apparently
failed to alert the mapping agency of the Chinese Embassy's new
location. Which only underscores that the mapmakers, like the smart
bombs themselves, are only as good as the information they get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
