<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIRK-FORDICE16-COX     05-15 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIRK-FORDICE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legislators glad contrary Mississippi governor must go
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. _ He has been called a bulldog who taunts his
enemies with nicknames, speaks to legislators in vetoes and touts
Christian family values while having public battles with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   As Kirk Fordice finishes out his final term as Mississippi's
first Republican governor since Reconstruction, he has been exactly
what he said he would be: thequintessential anti-politician,
uncoached and uncoachable. And while his straightforward style may
play well with voters _ some observers say he would win a third
term if the law allowed _ it has been a dismal failure with the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just doesn't talk to legislators, period,'' said state Sen.
W.L. Rayborn, a Democrat. ``The Mississippi Legis- lature works
like this: You come in with your hat in your hand and say, `Please
do this.' His mentality was, `Do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   During this year's session, Fordice brought his dog to the state
Capitol and played fetch with it in the halls, prompting a lawmaker
to propose a resolution banning pets in the building. The bill
died, but not without some debate.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of his standoff with the Democratic-controlled
Legislature, Fordice's agenda died year after year. And major bills
in the last eight years, many of which were designed to improve the
state's schools, have passed over his vetoes. The veto overrides
often were initiated by Republicans, who then suffered public
harangues by the governor. During this year's legislative session,
Fordice invited the Republican lawmakers to the Governor's Mansion
for a social event, then blasted them as ``traitors'' for
overriding one of his many vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Farmer's Almanac, there's Leaf Day and Flower Day.
Fordice was born on Contrary Day,'' said Joseph Parker, a political
science professor at the University of Southern Mississippi. ``He's
just a contentious, difficult guy, and he'll be that way until the
end. There is no sign of him mellowing out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fordice, 65, who refused to be interviewed for this article, has
offended everyone from his wife to entire racial groups. He refers
to Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove, a Democrat, as ``that pencil-neck
guy'' and calls state Attorney General Mike Moore ``Flashbulb''
because of his highly publicized lawsuit against the tobacco
industry. Fordice passionately opposed Moore's lawsuit, which was
the first of its kind and led to a national settlement between the
states and the tobacco industry over public health spending to
treat sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Fordice has offended blacks on several occasions. He wore a
Confederate tie when he blocked funding for a minority business
loan program. He invoked dark civil rights-era memories when he
said he would call out the National Guard if the courts ordered the
state to spend more on Mississippi's historically black colleges.
And he is an outspoken supporter of the Council of Conservative
Citizens, a Southern organization widely considered to be racist.
</P>
<P>
   On at least three occasions, Fordice has humiliated his wife of
43 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he announced he and his wife had ``irreconcilable
marital differences'' and implied divorce was imminent. Pat
Fordice, in turn, announced that she had no intention of getting a
divorce. The couple made a public show of reconciling a week later.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, on Election Day, Fordice was driving alone on
Interstate 55 from Memphis to Jackson when his Jeep Cherokee veered
off the road, flipped and caught fire. The crash was called a
``mystery'' by authorities, but even more mysterious was the
governor's whereabouts before the crash. He was seen at a Memphis
restaurant with a middle-aged woman. Fordice offered no
explanation, saying only that he had no memory of that day. He went
on to condemn President Clinton when his affair with intern Monica
Lewinsky became public.
</P>
<P>
   In April, several Jackson media outlets revealed that Fordice
had bought a house in a Jackson suburb _ a house his wife said she
knew nothing about. ``I know it is not for me,'' Pat Fordice told a
television station.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Fordice's relationship with the Legislature that has
stirred the most controversy. He quickly developed a reputation for
answering legislative proposals with a veto and no discussion or
alternative. He has vetoed 126 bills, more than the last two
governors combined. Early in his first term, the Legistature
overrode his veto of a sales tax increase for education, in large
part because the governor offered no alternative to aid the state's
notoriously poor-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature overrode a veto in order to pass a politically
risky sales tax increase _ in an election year,'' Parker pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Mike Chaney, a Republican, is an old friend of
Fordice's, but admitted that Fordice ``jumps'' on the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not been kind in his remarks to the Legislature,'' said
Chaney, who led the charge to override Fordice's veto of a major
education bill. That bill, passed in 1997, gives more state money
to schools in poor areas where local funds are short. Mississippi
was the first state to pass an ``adequate education'' program.
Seventeen states have been forced to do so by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor may not agree with me, but we are still
friends,'' Chaney said.
</P>
<P>
   Most legislators are not so forgiving. During Fordice's final
State of the State address in January, not a single person clapped
during or after his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Fordice has led the state through times of unprecedented
prosperity. Thanks to the booming casino industry, the state is
enjoying a budget surplus and has more jobs than people to fill
them. But critics say his inability to come up with progressive
ideas have hurt the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he missed some great opportunities,'' Rayborn said.
``We've been a little flush with money and having good times. If
we'd had a governor with some good ideas, maybe Mississippi could
have caught up to the rest of the country. We're always so far
behind on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   How Fordice's eight years will affect this year's governor's
race is unclear. Observers say that historically Mississippians
vote for a candidate, not a party. Neither of the front-runners for
the Aug. 3 primaries _ former U.S. Rep. Mike Parker, a Republican,
and Musgrove, the Democratic lieutenant governor _ has the
in-your-face style of Fordice, but both have extensive experience
in government, also unlike Fordice.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who served in Congress for 10 years, first as a Democrat
then as a Republican, says he is not as confrontational as Fordice
and that he has the experience of working with legislators,
something Fordice lacked. But he praises the governor for leading
the state through good economic times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fordice brought business principles to play in state
government,'' he said. ``He made state agencies more accountable.
We're on the cusp of some really fantastic changes and we're
looking forward to continued growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Musgrove, who as a state legislator helped write the adequate
education legislation, says he will work with the Legislature, not
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like Fordice because he speaks his mind,'' he said.
``But I also believe they want someone who has been taught to
respect other people and who believes other people's opinions are
valid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
