</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-REVIEW-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AMERICAN JEWS, ISRAELI POLITICS IS A WORLD AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the Upper West Side of Manhattan the other
evening, Jonathan Jacoby, an expert on Israeli politics, ended an
hourlong forum on the fractious national campaign going on in
Israel with a question to his audience: How much interest was there
among American Jews in the contest for prime minister?
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby really didn't have to ask. The answer was right in front
of him, in the empty chairs and unimpressive number of people (19)
who turned out to hear about Israeli politics five days before the
election, in the heart of a patch of real estate that is as
politically passionate, and as Jewish, as any part of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   There is a five-way contest under way for prime minister, and by
all indications it could end _ with Monday's vote or a run-off in
three weeks _ with the defeat of Benjamin Netanyahu, the
belligerent Likud Party figure who has led the nation since 1996,
by Ehud Barak, the Labor Party challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the notable exception of people like Jacoby and the
religious Jews in the United States who have long kept closer tabs
on Jerusalem than they have on Washington, there is surprisingly
little interest among many American Jews about what is taking place
in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume seems to be turned down,'' said Ronald Lauder, the
chairman-elect of the Conference of Presidents of Major American
Jewish Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   New York state Assemblyman Dov Hikind said he was startled by
the subdued attention to the campaign in his own back yard: Borough
Park in Brooklyn, where the sidewalks are filled with men with
flowing beards and black hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that the level of enthusiasm and excitement is similar
to what it was three years ago would be lying to you,'' said
Hikind, a Democrat and one of Netanyahu's most prominent American
supporters. ``There is less, period. Even in the Orthodox
community. Isn't that interesting?''
</P>
<P>
   The muted reaction to the Israeli elections of 1999 is evidence
of the increasing distance that many American Jews, especially
younger ones, have put between themselves and the country that for
so long has had such a strong emotional draw for say, their parents
and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   But the lukewarm U.S. involvement is partly mirrored in Israel,
suggesting there is not enough to this campaign to merit the kind
of trans-Atlantic attention that Israeli politics has typically
commanded in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For many American Jews, the current contest is a shadow of most
of the elections that have gripped the country since the 1967 Yom
Kippur war _ particularly the contest of 1996, when Netanyahu was
elected.
</P>
<P>
   That campaign was viewed as a political watershed for a nation
whose very existence seemed once again in peril. It was fought in
the aftermath of the assassination of Yitzhak Rabin, the prime
minister who made peace with Yasser Arafat, and was shadowed by
random Arab terrorist bombings that Netanyahu incorporated into his
nightly television advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The relative merits of the tough-talking Netanyahu and the
dovish Labor candidate Shimon Peres was, along with the future of
the Arab peace process, the subject of vigorous debate in Jewish
community centers, synagogues and Jewish neighborhoods in New York,
Los Angeles, Chicago and Miami, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy Jews found ways to circumvent Israeli laws barring
foreign contributions to Israeli campaigns, while in Orthodox
neighborhoods, hundreds of Jews who held dual citizenship traveled
on chartered planes to vote for Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that is going on in the 1999 contest. But many Jewish
leaders say such intensity is relegated to corners of American
Jewish life and is the exception, not the rule.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of reasons for this. The political
maneuvering by Netanyahu and Barak _ following, not incidentally,
the advice of U.S. political consultants who have decamped there
for the election _ has served to blur the distinctions between the
Likud and Labor candidates, and their supporters. While that might
make political sense in Israel, it has dampened passions in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last race was more a battle about issues, with competing
concepts of security dominating the debate,'' Lauder said. ``This
year's election has been more a clash of personalities. And
frankly, a personality contest doesn't inflame interests the way
issues do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, for example, Netanyahu, under the tutelage of Arthur
Finkelstein, the Republican consultant from Irvington, stirred
conservative support in Israel and America by asserting that Peres
``will divide Jerusalem,'' or cede part of Israel's capital to the
Palestinians. This time, Barak outflanked Netanyahu by declaring
his fealty to a unified Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with both candidates moving to the center, it is often
difficult to determine, from their words at least, how different
they are on the question of peace, one of the issues of most
concern to American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Even the debate in Israel that has so concerned many American
Jews _ over whether those who converted to Judaism under
non-Orthodox auspices should be recognized by the state as Jews _
has not drawn the attention that many Israelis expected from the
United States, where most of the Jewish population is reform or
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Although Netanyahu has strong ties to the religious community,
and Barak to secular Jews, neither has emphasized the issue. In the
United States, several Jewish leaders and journalists suggested,
the whole discussion may have nudged Americans away from Israel
altogether.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole `Who is a Jew?' issue has created a sense of
distance,'' said J.J. Goldberg, a syndicated columnist who writes
for Jewish newspapers in the United States and has written on the
declining interest he has found in his travels within the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, all of this has seemed to sap much of the
enthusiasm of supporters who live 5,000 miles away from the
election. Religious Jews in New York were elated when Netanyahu won
the election in 1996. But they have turned suspicious after three
years in which Netanyahu has made the kind of centrist peace
gestures that his Orthodox supporters had not expected when they
boarded planes to vote for him. ``People feel disappointment,''
Hikind said.
</P>
<P>
   If Netanyahu's following in the United States is disheartened,
Barak's is largely nonexistent. He has rarely visited America,
unlike such former Israeli leaders as Rabin, or appeared on
television. ``He doesn't have a lot of charisma and television
presence, and he has relatively low name recognition,'' said Rabbi
Eric Yoffie, president of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations.
</P>
<P>
   The low interest comes amid an overall decline in interest in
Israeli affairs among American Jews, especially younger ones. ``The
trends are unmistakable, supported both by survey evidence and
direct interviews with rank-and-file American Jews,'' said Steven
Cohen, a sociologist at Hebrew University in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the ties between American Jews and Israel, it would
be risky to draw too many long-term conclusions. At another time,
with different candidates, the dynamics could surely be different.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Fein, director of the Commission on Social Action of the
Reform Jewish Movement, said he had also seen a ``fairly dramatic
distance from intimate involvement with the intricacies of Israeli
politics and society.''
</P>
<P>
   But not, he added, in his own circle. ``It is probably an
indication of nothing at all that I have three invitations to
election parties on the 17th,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
