<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8473 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-DESIGN-REVIEW-74     05-15 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-DESIGN-REVIEW-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DETROIT, A SEX CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Run your eyes over the Dodge Durango, one of the
newest sport utility vehicles on the road. Muscles seem to ripple
under its shiny sheet metal, causing its fenders to bulge. Its hood
is lifted above the brawn, like the short neck of a wrestler rising
from beefy trapezius muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers imagine the Durango whispering huskily that it is strong
and dependable. And many of its brother trucks at the forefront of
Detroit's design efforts are even burlier.
</P>
<P>
   Now think back to Detroit's design heyday in the 1950s. Then as
now, cars were big. But they were Eves to today's Adams, Marilyn
Monroes to our Hulk Hogans. In the '50s ``there were hood ornaments
and bumpers that were bulbous and busty,'' said David Lewis, a
professor of business history at the University of Michigan.
``Nowadays there is no question that a lot of these sport utility
vehicles are masculine.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, cars looked like women. Now they look like men.
</P>
<P>
   Auto historians and designers puzzle over why. Some say the
booming economy gives Americans a go-anywhere, do-anything
confidence represented by brawny sport utility vehicles and trucks.
Or perhaps the designs have changed because more women are buying
cars. Others believe the world feels less safe, causing people to
look to their cars for protection, as if their daily commutes
require bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, it is as if Detroit's metal has had a
sex-change operation. Today's design kings are nothing like the
voluptuous Chevrolet Corvettes built between 1968 and 1982, the
ones with the sultry silhouette of an hourglass on its side.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s Cadillacs had chrome bumper guards in the shape of
breasts _ the 1953 model was a real looker. Here in Detroit they
are still known as ``Dagmar'' Cadillacs, after the tall, blonde
television starlet who went by the single name Dagmar and was known
for her ample chest.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, machismo filled the air at General Motors. ``It was
certainly sexual, but it was the sexual fantasies of men,'' said
Jerry Hirshberg, a GM designer in the '60s and '70s who is now
president of North American design for Nissan. ``When we lapsed, we
were doing design pornography.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what everyone suspected. ``The psychologists have thought
for years that the automakers, subliminally or otherwise, would
build cars with sex appeal, mostly to appeal to men,'' said Lewis,
the historian. Women in tight sweaters appeared in television ads
for cars, and men got the point: ``Here you have a curvy model and
a curvy fender.'' No more. Today, we have muscle cars. Back in the
'60s, of course, ``muscle'' referred to horsepower, not design.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's first sport utility vehicle, the Pathfinder, was
nicknamed the ``hardbody,'' and designers described the ``triceps''
around each wheel. There are the square-shouldered Jeeps, born of
the battlefields, with a look DaimlerChrysler calls ``chiseled.''
Other sport utility vehicles have been growing bigger and bigger,
as if the highways have become a survival-of-the-fittest contest:
The Ford Explorer spawned the Ford Expedition, and it evolved into
the enormous, soon-to-come Ford Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Each designer or auto historian seems to have a theory about the
changes. ``In the '90s, people started moving away from the
weaker-looking cars to the stronger-looking trucks,'' said Edward
Golden, Ford's truck-design director. ``It has to do with the end
of the Cold War and people feeling more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Or more endangered. ``I don't think there were drive-by
shootings in the 1950s,'' said Neil Walling, design vice president
at DaimlerChrysler, which builds the Dodge Durango. ``One of the
allures or attractions to trucks and sport utility vehicles is that
they carry a very protective image.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps now that women buy about half of all new vehicles, they
are objectifying men just as men objectify women. ``Women would
really rather have a vehicle that's more masculine than a vehicle
that is more feminine,'' said Jerry Palmer, director of design for
GM's North American Design Center. ``People still like vehicles
that are sexy,'' he said, and today's popular models ``are
masculine but they still have that sex appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it sex or is it power? ``A lot of women are buying trucks and
sport utility vehicles, and I believe that they don't want to be
seen as the weaker sex,'' said Golden, the Ford designer. ``They
want to be seen as equals.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, not all the latest models get such expressive
designs. The nation's best sellers are midsized cars like the Honda
Accord, the Ford Taurus and the Toyota Camry.
</P>
<P>
   Designers say those boy-next-door cars still carry messages.
Walling of DaimlerChrysler said cars like the Camry are saying,
```I'm not trying to be powerful, I'm not trying to be fashionable,
I'm not trying to be leading-edge. I'm the friend who is always
here _ I'm not the Arnold Schwarzenegger.'''
</P>
<P>
   But even sports cars seem less sexy now. Today's Corvettes have
just a slight air of femininity _ they are nothing like the
Playboy-magazines-on-wheels of the 1960s. The latest Corvettes and
other sports cars are more like the ``boys with breasts'' of Tom
Wolfe's latest novel, ``A Man in Full'' _ the thin, fit, females
found climbing stair machines at the neighborhood gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '50s and '60s, just when I was fantasizing about
Dagmar, automobiles were not only a status symbol but a sex
symbol,'' said Clive Chajet, a corporate-identity consultant in New
York. ``Driving is no longer sexy,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Why have bulging metal muscles replaced soft steel curves? The
men in the auto industry are still puzzling it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a sports car is a man's mistress, what is a pickup truck?''
asks Robert Casey, curator of transportation at the Henry Ford
Museum in Dearborn, Mich. ``Is it his buddy?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1417EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
