<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-ART-2     05-15 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-ART-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA REBELS REIGN IN CEDED AREA 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  
 Refiling to add art note (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, Colombia _ There are no immigration or
customs controls at the rustic landing strip that passes for an
airport here. But in most other ways, this muddy cattle town and a
sizable swath of jungle and savanna around it have ceased to be a
part of Colombia and are instead, with the government's blessing, a
dominion ruled by Marxist guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   At the main square here, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, known as FARC from its Spanish initials, has taken over
what used to be the local Institute of Culture and Tourism and made
it a headquarters. Rebel commanders in dark green uniforms move
about the streets, heavily armed bodyguards trailing behind, and
conduct document checks, summon residents to ideological meetings,
or stride into the mayor's office at will to confer with municipal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farclandia'' is the name some local residents have given to
this odd new state-within-a-state, created when the central
government in Bogota ceded an area of roughly 15,000 square miles _
larger than New Jersey and Connecticut combined _ to guerrilla
control as an inducement to peace talks that might end Colombia's
35-year-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement was envisioned as temporary, but signs abound
that the guerrillas, who have informally but effectively collected
taxes around here for 25 years, are cementing their control and
taking steps to insure they cannot be expelled if the process
breaks down. Less clear, however, is whether the experience gained
has given the rebels a real taste for governance, rather than
insurgency against a democratically elected Colombian government
that they maintain serves only a domestic elite and foreign
interests.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, several Latin American countries, the latest of
them Guatemala, have negotiated settlements to their long civil
wars. But it is unprecedented for a government to hand over a swath
of territory to its adversary. Local residents are not pleased that
they have been made guinea pigs in a political experiment while
being excluded from the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as if a couple of guests have come to stay in your
house, and they decide to throw a party,'' said Omar Garcia
Castillo, the mayor here. ``Not only do they not consult you, they
don't invite you.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90,000 residents of the area have had to live with this
unusual arrangement since last November. After much maneuvering,
the Colombian government and the rebel group agreed early in May to
begin formal peace talks, which are expected to get under way by
the end of the month and to prolong guerrilla control of the region
during the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The original agreement for the withdrawal of the government
supposedly applied only to its military and security presence,
including the national police, who have been replaced by a
60-member ``civic police'' that has half of its personnel appointed
by the mayor and the other half by the guerrillas. But the
guerrilla group recently expelled a government prosecutor they
found troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have made mistakes, and we have complained to them about
those mistakes,'' Victor G. Ricardo, the government's chief peace
negotiator, said when asked about the incident. ``What they did
with the prosecutor was one of those mistakes, and they recognize
it as such.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, no replacement has been sent here, and only a
handful of officials from the ombudsman's office remain as
representatives of the government.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla leadership has also demanded that the Roman
Catholic Church remove two parish priests who have objected to the
rebels' behavior and policies. One of the priests has now been
reassigned, for reasons the church hierarchy maintains are
unrelated to his dispute with the rebels. The other, Miguel Angel
Serna, remains an outspoken critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in Colombia right now, but in something that is the
prelude to an independent state,'' Serna said in an interview at
the rectory here. He said that the rebel movement had ``imposed its
law'' on people here, creating a militia called ``Citizen
Vigilance'' to intimidate potential opponents and ``to spy on
civic, religious and business groups,'' while ``accusing anyone who
does not agree with them of being an enemy of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Colombian news magazine Semana, the
Roman Catholic bishop for most of the region, Hector Lopez, said
the rebel group had also engaged in ``forced recruitment'' of
children as young as 13. In some rural areas he regularly visits,
he added, the guerrillas were ``bringing together the whole
population between the ages of 13 and 60 for two or three days'' at
their encampments, where ``they train them in the use of heavy
weapons'' and indoctrinate them in Marxist-Leninist theory.
</P>
<P>
   Local people said the guerrillas have also imposed labor duty in
rural areas, either to repair existing roads, most of which are in
precarious shape, or to build new ones. Better roads are a boon to
ranchers and farmers who have had difficulty getting crops to
market, but have a military use as well.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence analysts say that the guerrillas have reconditioned
airstrips in the bush and have organized several flights,
presumably of weapons and ammunition but perhaps also of drugs,
which have been an important source of income for years. Colombian
government officials acknowledge that such activities have been
taking place, but minimize their importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been doing that all along,'' Minister of Defense
Rodrigo Lloreda said in an interview in Bogota. ``They may have
taken some advantage, but not so dramatically. What worries me most
is not this, but that the civilian population may have been
abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, the mayor, said that he was aware of about six instances
in which residents had been ``detained'' by the rebels and held
illegally. He added that he was powerless to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents now seem resigned to the presence of the
guerrillas, and indeed worry more about when they leave. ``Our
greatest fear is that the peace process falls apart, the
paramilitaries come in here and accuse us all of being
collaborators and kill a lot of people,'' said the middle-aged
owner of a beauty salon as she trimmed a customer's hair.
</P>
<P>
   Crime is way down. According to local authorities, only four
killings have occurred in the six months since the guerrillas took
control, compared with about 10 a week in the months before their
arrival. Robbery, theft and rape have dropped almost as sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are highly centralized and it is difficult to obtain
information about their policies or a response to complaints made
by religious and civic leaders here and in Bogota. Three guerrilla
commanders assigned here declined to discuss these issues, saying
comment would have to come from superiors, who were at a base in
the jungle and therefore unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very delicate matter and a very delicate time,
especially here in town,'' Comandante Juan Pablo, a guerrilla
official, said as he stood outside the rebel group's headquarters,
decorated with photographs of Lenin and Simon Bolivar. He
maintained, though, that many of the complaints were exaggerated,
an assertion contradicted in several interviews with local
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the priests are saying is correct, but I would not say
that out loud,'' one store owner here said. ``Nobody wants trouble
with these people, so they keep quiet. You know what they say: keep
your mouth shut, and flies won't enter.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the guerrillas assigned to duty in town seem to
enjoy life out of the bush. Teen-age soldiers flirt with local
girls when their superiors are not looking, and other rebel leaders
are using the respite to learn to play musical instruments or
acquire other skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost 40, and have been a guerrilla for 19 years,'' said
Mauricio, the rebels' community liaison officer, breaking off a
conversation to head for his first driving lesson. ``I never
learned how to drive a car, so now I am going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Governance is hazier, not extending much beyond paving a few
streets, painting some revolutionary murals and holding many
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guerrillas have learned from this experience that
they are not prepared to run the country,'' said a European relief
official who spends much of his time here. ``Their senior leaders
are very intelligent, but they lack the midlevel cadres they
need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
