<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-FUND-RAISING-2TA     05-15 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUND-RAISING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S NETWORK FOR CASH WAS SET UP IN '98 AT LUNCHES IN TEXAS
CAPITAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Texas, Fla., Mich., Washington, D.C., Md., Ga.,
Ariz.)   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the frontiers of presidential fund-raising, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas has shattered previous Republican records
by quickly raising $13 million with help from ``the Pioneers.''
</P>
<P>
   An elite group of 150 supporters, ``the Pioneers'' have each
agreed to raise $100,000 for Bush's presidential exploratory
committee. A dozen members of the Pioneers have already met their
$100,000 goals. In just 10 weeks, they have helped collect an
unprecedented windfall for the Texas governor, who has not attended
a single fund-raising gala.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, unlike his Republican and Democratic rivals, including
Vice President Al Gore, Bush has collected vast sums without ever
leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been crisscrossing the country to attend a heavy
schedule of fund-raising receptions, remaining in Austin, the Texas
capital, while the Pioneers do most of his prospecting. So many
Republican money men want to join Bush's finance team that there is
a waiting list to have lunch with him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has managed to set a new early season Republican
fund-raising record without breaking his promise to the people of
Texas that he will remain focused on the state's business until the
current legislative session ends in late May. He will not begin
active national campaigning until next month, with a much
anticipated trip to Iowa. In June, his campaign will also hold its
first fund-raising banquets in Florida, Michigan and Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But he has hardly played a passive role in his exploratory
committee's fund-raising effort.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year ago, Bush quietly began assembling a network of
the nation's most powerful and influential Republican fund-raisers,
several supporters said in interviews this week.
</P>
<P>
   He did it by inviting groups of eight or 10 fund-raisers to
Austin to have lunch with him, either in the governor's mansion or
at a local restaurant, several supporters said. Some of the invited
guests were supporters of Bush's father, former President George
Bush, the supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor usually began the lunches by bemoaning the need to
raise so much cash for his presidential bid. ``He made it very
clear to people that it was simply a necessary thing to do but not
something that he relished doing,'' recalled Shelly Kamins, a
developer and co-chairman of the Bush campaign in Maryland who
attended one of the Austin lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would then describe his vision for America and answer
questions. By the end of the lunch, most of the fund-raisers
committed themselves to raising money for Bush, supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 500 fund-raisers have come to Austin in the last several
months. In recent weeks, the demand to attend one of Bush's Austin
lunches has outpaced the number of seats at the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lunches give people the chance to listen to him,'' said
Ron Weiser, one of the leaders of Bush's campaign in Michigan.
``Until you know what he stands for, it is hard to make that kind
of commitment. Most people like what they hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides demonstrating Bush's commitment to the campaign, which
has not yet formally begun, the lunches also managed to enlist most
of the Republican Party's top fund-raisers by March. The move took
his rivals completely by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very stealthy, and people did not realize it was
happening,'' said one longtime Republican fund-raiser who has not
decided yet which candidate to support. ``It was an amazing thing
to watch. While he was doing his legislative work, he has sat down
and had lunch with people from around the country _ basically
letting the money people come to him. He pulled some of the top
fund-raisers off the table, and the other Republican candidates did
not know what hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican rivals have struggled to establish strong
national fund-raising organizations. Elizabeth Dole, the Republican
hopeful who is second in the polls behind Bush, has gotten off to a
slow start raising money. In the first three months this year, Mrs.
Dole raised $685,253, although she has been much more active
raising money since early April.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, both Vice President Gore and former Sen.
Bill Bradley of New Jersey have racked up impressive numbers. Gore
raised $8.9 million in the first three months of this year, a tally
that his supporters say far exceeded their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers demonstrate that the 2000 presidential race will be
the most expensive election in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the strategy of inviting the fund-raisers and some
big-money contributors to visit Austin has paid dazzling dividends.
After announcing the formation of his exploratory committee in
early March, Bush raised $7.6 million in just 28 days, a total that
far outpaced the rest of the Republican field.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle finished second, with $2
million, and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was third, with $1.8
million, in the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bush's supporters said the windfall was even more
impressive because it had come in response to a single solicitation
letter that announced the formation of Bush's exploratory
committee. But in fact, his large national network of fund-raisers
had begun tapping their friends and colleagues for $1,000 checks,
the maximum allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $7.6 million raised by Bush, there were 5,237 checks for
$1,000, or 22 percent of the 23,339 contributions. More than half
of the checks were signed by Texans.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the real tributes to George Bush is that the first
seven or eight million dollars came without the benefit of a single
event,'' said Haley Barbour, a Washington lobbyist who is a member
of Bush's exploratory committee and the former national chairman of
the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reflection of Gov. Bush's political strength and that's
a very, very positive thing that your political strength alone
generates so much financial support.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said the fund-raising efforts were driven by a campaign
that refuses to take anything for granted despite Bush's large lead
in most polls over all potential challengers, including Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nomination is not going to be given to him on a silver
platter,'' Barbour said. ``He is going to have to earn it. George
understands that better than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who owes some of his strong showing in the early polls to
his image as a candidate with few ties to Washington, has also
benefited from the support of some influential Republicans in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Barbour, his effort there is being assisted by business
consultant Wayne Berman, James C. Langdon Jr., a partner at Akin,
Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld and an old friend of Bush's from Texas,
Joseph B. Gildenhorn, ambassador to Switzerland under President
Bush, and Ron Kauffman, a lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   The first Washington gala that the governor will attend is
scheduled for June 22 at the Washington Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proceeds of this fund-raiser will make a very strong
statement,'' said Kamins, the developer and one of five chairmen
for the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said Bush hoped to break the Republican record set in
1996 by Bob Dole, who raised $31.2 million. With individual
contributions limited to $1,000 and a much larger Republican field
vying for contributions, Donald L. Evans, Bush's national finance
chairman, conceded that the goal posed a very difficult challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters said Bush's goal was to raise $45 million or
even $50 million by the end of the year. If he raised $50 million,
Bush would have the luxury to choose to forgo accepting nearly $15
million in matching funds from the presidential public campaign
financing system. Candidates who accept federal money must limit
their spending to $33.5 million in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we made a decision to go nonmatching, we'd need to raise
$50 million,'' said Evans, an oil company chief executive from
Midland, Tex., and Bush's best friend. ``Going from being able to
raise $32 million to $50 million is a significant leap. That's an
option that we are in the very, very early stages of even thinking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said that he credited Bush's early money success with a
very strong national organization, including several governors,
notably his younger brother, Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida, and Gov.
John Engler of Michigan. Supporters say the Bush campaign hopes to
raise $4 million in Florida alone.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also been assisted by his parents, who have both
attended what the campaign calls surrogate fund-raising events. On
May 21, his mother, Barbara Bush plans to attend a fund-raiser in
Birmingham, Ala., and the next day, she and the former president
plan to headline an event in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The nascent campaign has had the kinds of glitches that other
candidates would probably not mind having. The governor's
exploratory committee failed to identify the occupations of 25
percent of his donors in the first quarter, as the rules require,
even though some are well-known Texans, including Allan Shivers,
who was the treasurer of Bush's 1998 campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to comply with the rules, campaign workers wrote ``Info
Requested'' next to donors' names. A campaign spokeswoman said that
with so many checks flowing in, there simply was not enough time to
complete the paperwork before the deadline for reporting
contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
