<HEADER>
A8481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-POLLUTION-FIGHT-     05-15 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-POLLUTION-FIGHT-ART-1130(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT OVER AUTO POLLUTION PLAN DRAWS ENVIRONMENTALISTS, INDUSTRY,
POLITICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Mich., Texas) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ An administration plan to require cleaner gasoline and
automobiles that emit less pollution, described by officials as the
most ambitious anti-pollution initiative of the Clinton presidency,
is drawing heavy lobbying by environmentalists and industry and
strong interest by politicians eyeing next year's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency estimates that imposing the
higher standards would reduce respiratory illnesses and save the
lives of up to 2,800 Americans a year. These improvements would
come at substantial cost _ $3.5 billion annually, five times as
much as any other Clinton administration rule aimed at specific
sources of pollution, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Industry critics, particularly oil refiners, say the costs would
be far higher. Emboldened by a federal appeals court ruling on
Friday rejecting the administration's plans for tighter national
air quality standards in the future, oil industry lawyers warned
that the gasoline and auto initiative may not hold up in court. But
an EPA official said the appellate court ruling would not stop the
agency's plans.
</P>
<P>
   By requiring substantial reductions in car pollution and the
elimination of 95 percent of emissions from sport utility vehicles
and pickup trucks, the gas and auto rules would drastically cut
smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest action by the Clinton administration to
protect the environment and the health of the American people,''
said Carol M. Browner, the regulatory agency's administrator.
</P>
<P>
   With such high stakes, advocates and opponents are trying to
influence the administration and Congress during the public comment
period, which ends on Aug. 2. Environmentalists and automakers
generally support the plan while seeking limited modifications.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies are implacably opposed to the requirement for
cleaner gasoline and are encouraging Republicans in Congress to
step in, having concluded that the administration is not likely to
make any significant changes before the rules become final at the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has strongly backed the pollution
initiative. Republicans are keeping a close eye on his comments,
particularly regarding sport utility vehicles, in hopes that they
can be used against him in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of position on this kind of an issue is
tailor-made'' for television advertisements, said Gov. John Engler
of Michigan, a Republican who is one of the 10 members of Gov.
George W. Bush's presidential exploratory committee. ``I do think
it's a good issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The future of the administration's initiative is clouded by
Friday's decision by an appellate court in the District of
Columbia. The court rejected only the administration's plan to set
more stringent national targets for smog and soot in the air. The
plan did not specify which industries would actually reduce
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But F. William Brownell, lead lawyer for the industry coalition
that won the case, said that unless the EPA won an appeal, it could
no longer prove a need for the stringency of the new gas and auto
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials and environmentalists disagreed, saying that
because the administration initiative was partly based on
longstanding national air quality goals predating the Clinton
administration and unaffected by Friday's decision, the court's
ruling should have no effect. EPA officials, planning an appeal,
said they would proceed with public hearings on the auto emissions
and gasoline proposal next month without modifying it.
</P>
<P>
   Sparring over the air pollution plan is likely to intensify this
summer. The Public Interest Research Group, a liberal advocacy
organization, is planning to send volunteers to knock on the doors
of four million households in a bid to muster 135,000 postcards to
federal regulators in support of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Other environmental groups, including Friends of the Earth and
the Sierra Club, are backing the administration plan, although they
are calling for faster cuts in pollution by sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Oil lobbyists contend that the plan could add 6 cents a gallon
to the price of gasoline instead of the 1 or 2 cents estimated by
regulators. The lobbyists expect the administration to change the
rules little if at all after the public comments.
</P>
<P>
   So the industry is preparing for two hearings in the Senate this
week by one of their allies, Sen. James M. Inhofe, R-Okla., who is
drafting legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Top American and foreign auto executives met in Washington on
Wednesday to map out their strategy. The industry has been pleased
with the cleaner gasoline rules, which will make it easier to build
cleaner-burning engines.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly interested in improving their environmental image
and irritated by criticism of pollution by sport utility vehicles,
auto executives have been reluctant to criticize the Clinton
initiative, instead proclaiming their ``general support.'' But the
industry is asking regulators to extend by two years, to the 2011
model year, the deadline for large sport utility vehicles and
pickup trucks to meet car pollution standards.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he thought that the administration would prevail in
imposing tough rules this year. ``It has taken several years to get
to this stage and we of course don't have the final rule yet, but
I'm optimistic,'' he said in an interview this month.
</P>
<P>
   But if Republicans win next year's presidential election, they
might be able to revise the gas and auto emissions standards,
possibly citing Friday's court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been watching Gore's comments on automotive
issues closely. President Bush ran television advertisements in
Ohio and Michigan in 1992 warning that Clinton and Gore would
tighten fuel-economy standards and force tens of thousands of
autoworkers into unemployment. Engler said similar criticisms could
be leveled against Gore next year.
</P>
<P>
   Engler, who has won three consecutive races for governor in this
fiercely contested industrial state and is a possible Republican
vice presidential candidate, said American families liked the
interior space and perceived safety of big sport utility vehicles.
Voters in general and autoworkers in particular will be leery, he
said, of a Democrat whose environmental views could be portrayed as
advocating a return to ``little tiny cars'' of the sort still seen
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Though top auto executives may see tighter rules as inevitable,
there remains an undercurrent of hostility here toward any limits
on automobiles. An editorial cartoon in The Detroit News on May 8
showed Gore in an immense 18-wheeler labeled ``Big Gov't,'' honking
the horn while tailgating a sport utility vehicle. The explanation
at the top of the cartoon read, ``Al Gore's plan to get oversized
SUV's off the road.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives have warned that large sport utility vehicles
might have to be made smaller or less powerful to comply with the
latter stages of the new rules, which will be phased in between
2004 and 2009. But Gore made a point of saying in a speech here
that he thought the new regulations provided enough flexibility to
industry to avoid reducing consumers' choices.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., who has been consulted by Gore on
electoral strategy in the Upper Midwest, said he strongly doubted
that voters would hold the new regulations against the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore isn't cracking down on sport utilities _ the EPA is,''
Dingell said, also pointing out the willingness of auto executives
to go along with more stringent rules.
</P>
<P>
   Edward V. Sarpolus, a vice president of EPIC/MRA, a polling firm
in Lansing, Mich., which works for both parties and the news media,
said there was little evidence that the 1992 Republican
advertisements had been effective. Michigan workers tended to blame
corporate downsizing, rather than regulatory policy, as the main
cause of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA estimates that beginning in 2004, the new rules will add
$100 to the cost of a car and $200 to the cost of a sport utility
vehicle or pickup truck. Auto lobbyists say those are
underestimates, but Sarpolus said the price increases were small
enough and far enough in the future to play down their political
importance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry studies indicate that sport utility vehicles
are not especially safe; their occupants are just as likely as
those in cars to die in crashes, while more likely to kill other
people in collisions with other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe has been trying to draft legislation that would alter the
gasoline provisions of the administration plan without starting
another broad fight over the Clean Air Act, a controversial piece
of legislation covering all aspects of air pollution that tied up
congressional leaders for months in 1990. But Dingell said it was
impossible to make any changes in the law without reopening the
whole issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Act authorizes the EPA to draft national air
quality standards, but the appeals court found on Friday that the
agency behaved unconstitutionally in not asking Congress for
detailed instructions on drafting the standards.
</P>
<P>
   The auto and gasoline rules do not cover fuel economy. In the
interview, Gore said he had been talking with auto executives about
ways to triple the fuel economy of sport utilities through joint
research programs with the government to explore alternative fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore advocated tighter fuel-economy rules when he was in
the Senate, he and Clinton largely abandoned that position in 1992
after the Republican television campaign, calling instead for
federal research subsidies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
