<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALRAIL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ripken's aching back
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken's back discomfort is not just disk-related, as first
diagnosed, but is the result of stenosis, a narrowing of the spinal
nerve canal. The condition might have stemmed from a herniated disk
he suffered two years ago, but his current pain emanates from a
spur that has grown into the canal.
</P>
<P>
   What caused the stenosis to flare up now might be the saddest
part of what has been a sad year for the Ripkens.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It) could have been the time I spent in the hospital (before
his father's death), sitting and standing for hours,'' he said.
``During my dad's viewing and funeral, I stood up for about 10
hours a day. It's possible that kind of loading on your nerve
caused the irritation.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   New York manager Joe Torre reported vastly improved stamina in
the past two weeks and told reporters he hopes to set his date for
returning to the dugout sometime this week. ... Cuban export
Rolando Arrojo is testing Tampa Bay's patience. After starting 1998
at 10-5, Arrojo is 5-11 since, including a 1-4 start this year. ``I
do not care if you go out there and give me what you've got and you
get beat,'' Devil Rays manager Larry Rothschild said after the
Twins pounded Arrojo last week. ``But don't get beat giving me less
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Unknowing White Sox
</P>
<P>
   With five rookies making their major-league debuts with the
White Sox already this season, and 11 others having done the same
last year, prospects for Chicago's early success were not high. And
they still aren't, even as the Chisox took a 15-14 record into a
current string of 12 games against New York and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But in a division ruled by the Indians' iron fist, Chicago still
sees itself as a wild-card candidate. The current Sox do not seem
aware that just two seasons ago, the roster was dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we winning?'' asked catcher Brook Fordyce. ``Because
we don't know any better. We don't look series to series, we look
inning to inning. We're not stupid, but maybe a little ignorant.''
...
</P>
<P>
   Detroit manager Larry Parrish took his club apart in a half-hour
closed-door address Wednesday night. ``This ain't no beer-league
softball game where you come here and you have fun and you laugh
and talk and maybe you get some hits and maybe you don't,'' Parrish
said. ... Cleveland's amazing Manny Ramirez just emerged from a
127-game stretch during which he drove in 150 runs.
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   What the Mariners lack
</P>
<P>
   Seattle general manager Woody Woodward has hit the air-raid
siren, placing outfielders Butch Huskey and Matt Mieske on the
trading block and sending out feelers for an experienced starting
pitcher. The club's plan to go with five rookie pitchers is a
failure made worse by shoulder surgeries to Mark Leiter and Butch
Henry.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have been in touch with Minnesota about the
availablity of relievers, foremost Rick Aguilera, but might have a
better shot at Boston's Jim Corsi or Kip Gross. But one trade will
not cure this club, at least according to a former M, who sees the
club's struggle linked to something deeper than a taped-up bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played for the Seattle Mariners last year and they had some
super-duper stars,'' Phillies outfielder Rob Ducey said. ``But this
(Philadelphia) team has more spirit than that team will ever have.
This team wants to win at all costs.'' ... Texas' Juan Gonzalez
recorded a career first Tuesday when he went into his home-run trot
in Toronto, strained his right hamstring somewhere on the base
paths and was forced to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
