</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Los Angeles languor
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a fifth of the season complete, tepid early
reviews have been posted in Los Angeles, where the hot air expended
during the winter has equated to a lukewarm spring performance.
</P>
<P>
   At 20-15 as the weekend opened, the Dodgers were testing the
results of yet another team meeting in which the players agreed
things should be better. The front-running San Francisco Giants,
13-10 since the loss of Barry Bonds, hardly have been the masters
of their domain, but the Dodgers haven't seen even a share of first
place since the season's fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Group is not shelling out $79.3 million for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been games where we played great, and there have
been games where we played poor,'' manager Davey Johnson said. ``To
be truthful, I'd say we have played fair so far. It's tough to play
up to your billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a little winning streak going to keep the
talk-radio guys off my (rear). They can start talking about the
Lakers and them choking.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles last week became the first team to lose a series to
the Florida Marlins, which suggests some lack of initiative. While
the Dodgers have been worthy against winning clubs, they also are
9-11 against sub-.500 teams. Hence, second baseman Eric Young
called a team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've got a good club, and we can win this
(division),'' Young said. ``But there are things we're doing that
we need to do better, stuff you can't do if you're a contending
club. It's not one guy or even one thing. It's a lot of little
things that add up.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Kevin Brown has not had the desired updraft on
the pitching staff yet. Los Angeles entered the weekend with a 4.29
ERA, fifth in the league and nearly a half-run higher than last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Darren Dreifort, the most consistent starter in the
early stages, is fighting lower-leg pain related to offseason
surgery for shin splints. Left-hander Carlos Perez gave up three
homers Tuesday against Chicago in his first game since missing a
start because of discomfort in his right leg and knee. Perez denies
a widespread rumor that he hurt himself on a street curb while out
one night with former Montreal teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Dodgers' new profile has taken shape. With
Young leading the way, the team is on pace to steal well over 200
bases, more than the franchise record of 198 set in 1962, when
Maury Wills went for 104. The team batting average of .265 is tied
for 11th in the NL with Atlanta but still is 13 points higher than
a year ago, and the club is scoring nearly a run more a game at
4.8.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie third baseman Adrian Beltre has fit in nicely, hitting a
team-high .336, and could become the youngest Dodger to bat .300.
Raul Mondesi is on pace for a 62-homer season. Those are not
numbers indicative of a team that needs team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be playing a lot better than we are,'' right fielder
Gary Sheffield said. ``We just sit around, have one big inning,
take the next five innings off and let the other team back in it.
Then we finally play with a sense of urgency in the eighth and
ninth innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play like it's your last game,'' Sheffield said.
``You've got to play with an intensity that intimidates the other
team, that makes the other team play flat. I know we're not
intimidating anybody now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
