u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ITEMS16-COX     05-15 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ITEMS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giant steps help stomp the Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Giants apparently got the best of the Braves in
more ways than one while taking two of three from Atlanta at 3Com
Park last week. For starters, with gusty winds pushing the wind
chill into the 30s, San Francisco catcher Brent Mayne made sure the
Braves were aware of how uncomfortable they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy who came up, I said to him, `Isn't this terrible?' I
think it got into their heads,'' Mayne said. ``They said, `Yeah, I
can't believe you play here every day.' I guess I just reaffirmed
the obvious in their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Marvin Benard, the Giants' leadoff man who was
riding a 1-for-27 slump when the Braves hit town. Brett Butler, an
ex-Giant and now a Braves employee as their newest TV announcer,
had a suggestion for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he said to me was, 'When you're not swinging right, don't
forget about the bunt,' `` Benard said. `` 'It could be your bread
and butter.' He said to just keep trying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Benard had two bunt singles in leadoff at-bats, scored both
times and showed Giants the way to 12 first-inning runs during the
series.
</P>
<P>
   SHHHHHHH
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates don't want baseball people thinking they snookered
Cleveland on the Brian Giles-Ricky Rincon trade. Giles just won NL
player of the week, was hitting .314 with 27 RBIs heading into the
weekend and already has established himself as one of the league's
best right fielders. Rincon, the left-handed reliever who saved 14
games for the Pirates last year, has spent almost the entire first
six weeks on the disabled list with a tender elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like when people write that we stole Brian Giles,''
Pirates GM Cam Bonifay said. ``It's not a fair assessment.
Cleveland happens to have such a deep and talented club that it
couldn't afford Brian Giles a chance to play every day. We got
lucky in the fact he was available.''
</P>
<P>
   And luckier still that the Indians thought Rincon was worth a
future All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   STREAKING
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez's 25-game hitting streak in Arizona is the best
reminder of how often these things come around. The longest hitting
streaks in the majors since Pete Rose set the NL record in 1978:
</P>
<P>
   YEAR _ PLAYER, CLUB _ STREAK
</P>
<P>
   1978 _ Pete Rose, Reds _ 44
</P>
