<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RANDYJOHNSON16-CO     05-15 1573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RANDYJOHNSON16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First Falcons quarterback Johnson struggles to rebuild life
shattered by alcohol
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Only 50 yards from Randy Johnson's room at the Banana
Bay Waterfront Motel in Port Charlotte, Fla., late-model
convertibles cruise U.S. Route 41 and onto shiny Gilchrist Bridge.
Behind the motel is a pristine beach lapped by the waves of
sparkling Charlotte Harbor. Nestled among the palm trees less than
a 10-minute drive away are a pair of championship golf courses. On
the roadside, a billboard prominently displayed by one of several
real-estate companies in the area reads: ``Paradise awaits you.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people are drawn to Charlotte County, 25 miles north of
Fort Myers on the Gulf Coast, for the fishing, the golf, the
climate or just the lifestyle of a community known for its
well-manicured lawns and tony condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the first quarterback in the history of the Atlanta
Falcons and a first-round selection in the franchise's initial
draft, went there to die.
</P>
<P>
   Out of money, out of hope, out of touch with his two daughters,
and with his insides ravaged by three decades of alcohol addiction,
Johnson, 54, decided four weeks ago to toss himself either off the
bridge or into the traffic. Sitting on the beach at 4 a.m., with
less than $20 in his pocket and his stomach on fire, Johnson
chugged-a-lugged the remains from a quart of cheap vodka, vomited
blood into the wet sand and decided that he'd had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I had hit rock bottom with a big thud,'' Johnson, who
still is unable to explain the life-saving 911 call he made on his
way out the door of the motel, said late last week. ``You reach a
point where you don't want to hurt yourself anymore, and you don't
want to hurt anyone else who's close to you. For about the past
month, I had spent my days drinking, staring out at the harbor and
feeling sorry for myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, you realize that's no way to live. Your life
seems worthless and kind of lifeless, and you wonder if there's any
point continuing. When your spirit is that sapped, suddenly the
alternative doesn't seem so (unthinkable) anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That he survived his would-be suicide attempt, Johnson said, is
testament to a lot of people unfamiliar with his NFL background and
with little more reason to help him than just basic human altruism.
The one-time golden boy, admired by the earliest Falcons fans for
his on-field grit and off-field charisma, has reached a point where
his life was saved only through the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The 911 operator who prefers to remain anonymous and the
paramedics dispatched to Johnson's motel room that morning in late
April got him admitted to Bon Secours-St. Joseph Hospital. He was
diagnosed for a third time since 1981 with pancreatitis, a
condition that resulted directly from heavy drinking. Caseworkers
at the hospital attempted to find an alcohol-treatment program, but
the only one available locally required upfront payment, and
Johnson couldn't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he was taken in by Judy Jones, whose double-wide
trailer in nearby Punta Gorda also serves as headquarters for the
Bread of Life Mission, the only homeless shelter in Charlotte
County.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who weighs 300 pounds, and good-naturedly refers to
herself as ``the Refrigerator's sister,'' an allusion to former
Chicago Bears defensive lineman William Perry, is equal parts
mother hen, father confessor, den mother and life-saver. Not far
from where the Peace River meanders through streets lined with palm
trees before emptying into the Gulf of Mexico, Jones has ministered
quietly to the county's homeless for the past 20 years, using
Christianity as the central theme for her mission.
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks, Johnson has washed dishes, answered the phone
for Jones and stacked donated food. Working in a place he described
as ``only a small step above homeless,'' he also has counseled
down-on-their-luck men and has served as a sort of public-relations
man for expansion efforts. Most importantly, Johnson is heading
into his fourth week of cold-turkey sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowly but surely,'' Jones said, ``he's getting it turned
around. But it's a process, and I think he realizes there's no
shortcut. You've got to pull yourself out of that spiral.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson moved from Atlanta to Port Charlotte in late February
when a friend promised him a management position at a check-cashing
and car-loan business he hoped to start. But the sudden collapse of
the proposed business was just the latest in a string of setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson played five of his 10 NFL seasons with the Falcons,
appearing in 46 games from 1966 through 1970. He completed 435 of
904 passes for 5,538 yards with 34 touchdowns and 65 interceptions.
Defining the term ``journeyman quarterback,'' he also played with
the Giants, Redskins and Packers and the Honolulu Hawaiians of the
old WFL. When he was 34, he retired, having earned $90,000 in
salary each of his final three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Johnson suffered three concussions, broken
ribs, a knee injury and had two operations on his right, throwing
shoulder. Former teammates Tommy Nobis and Jeff Van Note recalled
last week the beatings that Johnson took while playing behind a
makeshift offensive line for the expansion Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one game where I just couldn't handle the guy in
front of me,'' Van Note said. ``I actually apologized in the huddle
to Randy (for the hits he was taking). Randy was a good player, and
early on he was `The Man' in Atlanta. He was a sharp-looking guy,
dressed well, rubbed shoulders on the golf course with important
people in town. But we got that poor guy killed just about every
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the physical beatings he endured might have
contributed to his drinking, but he refused to use football as
``the convenient excuse'' for his own weakness. The only
shortcoming Nobis recalled was Johnson's inability to refuse any
person seeking his time. Nobis, the team's first draft pick, met
Johnson while they were growing up in San Antonio. The two played
against each other in junior high school but not in high school or
college. During their years with the Falcons, the men and their
wives became good friends. Johnson acknowledges an irony that Nobis
spent virtually his entire adult life working for the Falcons while
he has knocked around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys get into trouble trying to be something they're
not,'' Nobis said. ``But that wasn't Randy. Instead, he'd get
himself into jams trying to be good to people. He was a charmer,
but not a con man, and, boy, what an athlete. He had this city in
his corner. He had so much going for him, and I'm sure he regrets
he let opportunity slip by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months after his retirement, Johnson filed for bankruptcy,
and his wife, Penny, divorced him. All but broke, he was forced to
take his $600-per-month league pension early. Johnson worked as a
television sportscaster in San Antonio, then went into real estate
and solar-energy development before a friend gave him a job
supervising security at the Scottish Inn in Marietta. Most of the
positions ended the same way, with Johnson dismissed because of
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Former Falcons wide receiver Alex Hawkins and NFL Players
Association executive director Gene Upshaw, a college teammate at
Texas A&AMP;I, tried on several occasions to help Johnson, but he
declined their attempts at intervention.
</P>
<P>
   He has been through alcohol-treatment programs twice, served
jail time because of what police termed a business scam, spent time
in two mental institutions and has been diagnosed as manic
depressive. Worst of all, he hasn't seen daughters Ashley, 28, and
Jennifer, 26, in 20 years. All he knows is that they live somewhere
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my wife and kids, I was about as irresponsible as a man
could be,'' Johnson said. ``Basically, I abandoned them, and
they're probably better off without me. Sometimes, I think the less
they know, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did find out four days ago that he is a grandfather. The
news that Jennifer recently gave birth to a daughter is, he
admitted, bittersweet. The experience is the latest twist from
which he must recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terribly humbling experience, and I wouldn't wish it
on anyone else,'' he said. ``But with whatever time I've got left _
and right now my health is awful _ I'm trying to make some things
right. I just want to go out with some dignity and character, and
maybe keep someone else from making these kind of mistakes. There's
no need anymore for me to be manipulative or anything. There's
nothing left for me to hide or hide from.''
</P>
<P>
   RANDY JOHNSON'S CAREER
</P>
<P>
   Born: June 17, 1944 in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   College: Texas A&AMP;I.
</P>
<P>
   Falcon highlights: Drafted in first round (15th overall) in
1966. ... Earned job as expansion team's first starting
quarterback. Played five seasons (1966-70) in Atlanta, completing
435 of 904 passes for 5,538 yards with 34 touchdowns and 65
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   NFL highlights: Played with the Giants (1971-73), Redskins
(1975) and Packers (1976) in the NFL and the Honolulu Hawaiians of
the WFL (1974). . . . His NFL career numbers included 647
completions in 1,286 attempts for 8,329 yards with 51 touchdowns
and 90 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
