<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pressure's on Hull to deliver for Stars
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If this is the playoffs, they must be Stars no more.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas has set a franchise record for points in the regular
season three years in a row and this year was the runaway winner of
the Presidents Trophy with a record of 51-19-12. After being
stopped just short of the finals by Detroit last year, the Stars _
in a move dictated by owner Thomas Hicks _ signed Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   But several personnel directors have questioned the Stars'
chemistry this season, and now we see why. Lost in the fact that
Dallas swept a severely undermanned Edmonton in the first round was
that all were narrow one-goal wins _ including a triple-overtime
game _ that could have gone either way.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas went into its second-round series against St. Louis with
an edge in goaltending, defense and depth up front. The Stars
played well in winning the opener but were outplayed in the next
three, taking Game 2 in overtime, but losing two in a row in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, expected to be the missing piece, has been just plain
missing. He was scoreless in the Edmonton series and, despite
scoring twice in the first three games against the Blues, was
demoted from the first line to the third by coach Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   If that move seemed a little radical by Hitchcock, he can be
excused. The Stars signed Hull thinking it would make them better
than Detroit and Colorado in the West. Hicks would not take well to
another early elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Doug Jarvis would not bite the other day when
asked about possible ramifications of a series loss by the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even thinking about that,'' he said. ``Our thoughts
have to just be on our opponent and our next game. We can't afford
to think any farther ahead than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems occur when the owner is thinking ahead to the Stanley
Cup finals, and his team doesn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Money talks
</P>
<P>
   Although there's still a chance Mario Lemieux's reorganization
plan will be approved in time to save the Pittsburgh Penguins, a
possible bid by Paul Allen to buy the team changes everything.
Allen has made billions from Microsoft and represents the steady
ownership that commissioner Gary Bettman is seeking for league
franchises. The Penguins also would be moved to Portland, targeted
along with Houston by the NHL as viable for franchise relocations.
While maintaining that he still prefers that the Penguins remain in
Pittsburgh, Bettman now is opening the door to a possible move.
``In the last 10 or 14 years, these type of problems have been
epidemic of all sports leagues,'' he said. ``You've had four or
five (NFL) franchises relocated at the end of the season, be it
Cleveland, Baltimore, St. Louis or Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers update
</P>
<P>
   IceForum owner Jack Burton still thinks that the Thrashers'
practice facility in Duluth will be completed by mid-August, well
in time for training camp in September. But permit delays prevented
workers from pouring the concrete until a few days ago, and general
manager Don Waddell is concerned enough that he has held off
completing plans for camp. The Thrashers probably will open camp in
Orlando in September and spend at least one week there. After
returning from Europe last week and discovering that work had not
started, Waddell said, ``We need something to happen here soon, or
we may have to look at other alternatives.'' He then was reassured
by Burton that the project wasn't in danger. . . . Dr. Scott
Gillogly of Atlanta has been named the team's primary orthopedic
and team physician. Gillogly played football at West Point. . . .
When Colorado defenseman Adam Foote was asked who had the biggest
influence on his career, he said, ``The drive my parents had
definitely helped me. Also, Ted Nolan. I was fortunate enough to
have him as a coach for three years in junior. He really helped me
become a better character.'' Nolan might be a candidate for the
Thrashers' coaching vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   They'll love this in Ottawa: Senators star Alexei Yashin,
playing for Russia, high-sticked his NHL teammate Daniel
Alfredsson, playing for Sweden, in a World Championships game in
Norway this past week. The result was a facial cut that required
nine stitches to close. Alfredsson later said he didn't realize it
was Yashin but added only, ``It happens.'' Yashin, meanwhile,
declined to answer questions. . . . Road teams won 30 of the first
55 playoff games (.545), the highest winning percentage since
expansion in 1967 and 16 percentage points higher than the record.
. . . Expect the NHL to officially approve the Bill Davidson
purchase of the Tampa Bay Lightning next week, clearing the way for
Davidson to decide what to do with coach/general manager Jacques
Demers. . . . Former Los Angeles coach Larry Robinson, who owns a
home in Florida, could join the Lightning as an assistant coach. .
. . Mark Recchi's new five-year, $25 million deal with Philadelphia
includes a no-trade clause. The significance is that he has been
traded three times since 1992. . . . . The Flyers probably won't
re-sign free-agent defenseman Steve Duchesne, acquired from L.A.
just before the deadline. . . . The NHL has declared Ottawa
defenseman Lance Pitlick an unrestricted free agent. The Senators,
who thought that Pitlick was restricted, now probably will lose
him. . . . It would be stunning if there's anything to rumors that
New Jersey will deal for Yashin, who is seeking an $8
million-a-year extension. Devils GM Lou Lamoriello is not known for
his shopping sprees and is more likely to let a player go for
salary reasons than to strain the payroll. Yashin would be making
double the next-highest-paid Devil, Scott Stevens ($4 million).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
