<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Produce ... or else
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   What it might accomplish is open to question, but Florida
manager John Boles is serious about his threatened widescale
demotions if six or seven Marlins do not improve. Without naming
names, first baseman Derrek Lee, left-hander Jesus Sanchez,
outfielders Preston Wilson and Todd Dunwoody and relievers Antonio
Alfonseca, Rafael Medina and Archie Corbin are the logical
suspects. Lee and Alfonseca, it should be noted, came to the team
from San Diego in the Kevin Brown trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't continue to spin your wheels at this level without
there being some repercussions,'' Boles said. The Fish opened the
weekend with a .273 winning percentage, which translates to a
118-loss season. It could mean good news for ex-Brave Danny
Bautista, who is hitting .316 at Class AAA Calgary. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter says there is no explaining his 1-4 start in New York.
His 5.55 ERA is more than three runs higher than during his 17-win
season a year ago, and he already has given up five homers in his
first seven starts. He served up eight in 1998. ``I'm trying to
figure out what the hell is different from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Emergency ward
</P>
<P>
   A brutal week in Houston. Hitting coach Tom McCraw was diagnosed
with prostate cancer and left the team to begin treatment. First
base coach Jose Cruz took a leave of absense for treatment of an
irregular heartbeat. Rookie catcher Mitch Meluskey underwent
season-ending surgery to tighten up his right shoulder. And
reliever Doug Henry was placed on the DL with bone chips in his
right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Whether venting frustration or just plain venting, the Astros
proceeded to sweep three games in Pittsburgh by a combined 31-10
score, including a record 19-8 thumping Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us to a pulp, and we just watched them,''
Pittsburgh's Al Martin marveled. `` Wohlers watch
</P>
<P>
   To ease clubhouse anxiety, pitching coach Don Gullett found an
old crash test dummy and now stands it up at the plate when Mark
Wohlers works out. ``We call him Pitcher's Pal,'' Gullett said,
``but if he could talk, I'm sure he wouldn't think that's his name
right now.'' Wohlers has consulted with Los Angeles clinical
psychologist Richard Crowley, who worked with Steve Sax during his
bout with wildness.
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Oh me, oh Myers
</P>
<P>
   Whether San Diego's decision to claim reliever Randy Myers off
waivers last August was strictly an attempt to keep him out of
Atlanta's bullpen might never really be known. But what is sure is
that the move was one of the Padres' worst of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Pads still owe $12.5 million over the next two years of
Myers' contract, although the tear in his left rotator cuff could
mean he might not pitch again. Although this is just his first
stint on the DL, Myers turns 37 this season and will determine in
the next two weeks if he will have surgery. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Round III of the Padres-Greg Maddux rumble. After the Braves
left town last weekend, some Pads said they thought Maddux was
throwing a spitball, usually in a two-strike count. . . . Ex-Brave
Chris Brock was mostly gracious after beating Atlanta at 3Com Park
last week. The San Francisco right-hander said he knew there was no
place for him in the Braves rotation, but then added, ``They're
going to have their top four or five starters. If you're No. 5 and
don't do it after a couple of chances, you're out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
