<SLUG> BC-SLOVAKIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOVAKIA CHOOSING PRESIDENT BY DIRECT ELECTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ For the first time since Slovakia was
created in 1993 from the peaceful split of the old Czechoslovakia,
its voters Saturday chose their president by direct election.
</P>
<P>
   While the vote was new, the two leading candidates were not. The
front-runner, Rudolf Schuster, 65, is the official candidate of the
four-party coalition government, a political veteran who was once
the Communist leader of Parliament, served after the anti-Communist
revolution of 1989 as Czechoslovakia's ambassador to Canada, and is
now the widely respected mayor of the eastern Slovak town of
Kosice.
</P>
<P>
   His prime challenger is Vladimir Meciar, 57, who served as prime
minister for all but nine months from 1992 until losing
parliamentary elections last year, and who is widely blamed for
stalling Slovakia's efforts to join NATO and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicated that Schuster had what should be a comfortable
lead of 8 percent over Meciar, whose victory would probably cast a
pall over the coalition government's so far successful efforts to
bring Slovakia back into the club of Central Europe's
post-Communist success stories _ the Czech Republic, Poland and
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven other candidates, the most prominent of whom is
Magda Vasaryova, a popular former actress and successful
Czechoslovak ambassador to neighboring Austria. The former Slovak
president, Michal Kovac, whose term ended in March 1998, gave up
his candidacy on May 11 and asked his supporters to vote for
Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Saturday's election is a bellwether for Slovakia and
the efforts of its new prime minister, Mikulas Dzurinda, to restore
the reputation tarnished by Meciar. Slovakia has been without a
president since Kovac's first five-year term expired in March 1998,
and grave disagreements prevented either direct election for a
successor, or a choice made by parliament.
</P>
<P>
   After Meciar lost power, the new government was able to amend
the Constitution and hold Saturday's election.
</P>
<P>
   If none of the candidates gains over 50 percent of the vote _
which local observers believe is unlikely, the top two finishers in
Saturday's vote will go forward to a second round to be held on May
29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
