<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Very pleasant weather is expected from the northern Middle
Atlantic region to the eastern Great Lakes and all of New England
on Sunday as high pressure dominates. The center of the fair
weather system will drift off the Maine coast. This will allow a
clockwise circulation from the east to transport ocean-cooled air
into coastal communities from Cape Cod to the Carolinas. Farther
inland, breezes from the south will direct rather warm air
northward.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and some rain will continue to dampen southern Virginia
and eastern North Carolina. Winds will gust to gale force at the
beaches and tides will average several feet above normal with
flooding of low-lying areas expected. Lighter winds from the north
should bring less humid air into the Southeast, but some clouds
will persist along the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico will produce
varying amounts of clouds in the Mississippi Valley and Plains. A
few thunderstorms may erupt in east Texas and southwest Arkansas.
Clusters of thunderstorms are likely in the Middle West. Jet stream
winds should guide residual moisture into the western Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A chill rain will fall in parts of the Dakotas adding to a
record wet May. The leading edge of cool air from the North Pacific
will reach the western Plains. Isolated strong storms will form in
eastern Colorado and the Texas panhandle. Colder, moist air over
the northern and central Rockies will promote rain and snow showers
Sunday afternoon. The Northwest will stay very cool while the
Southwest is seasonable and becomes windy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snow King &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine 6 inches of snow falling everyday from November 1 until
May 13. Then you can conceive the magnitude of snow that fell on
Mt. Baker in northern Washington state this season. Of course, the
snow never fell with such regularity, but the accumulation totaled
the same, a remarkable 1,124 inches. The sky was stingy to release
the final 2 inches this past Wednesday, unofficially making this
peak, the snowiest place on earth with weather observations. The
record, surpassing Mt. Rainier's 1971-72 seasonal tally of 1,122
inches, will have to be validated by the National Climate Extremes
Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
