<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE BRACES FOR LOSS OF BONDS WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CHINA-ZHU, U.S.-CHINA-SCIENTISTS) 
(mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, which once hoped that
stronger bonds between China and the United States would be a
centerpiece of its foreign policy legacy, is now bracing for a deep
deterioration in relations that may not improve before President
Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   From the Chinese point of view, NATO's mistaken bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade summed up almost everything that China
finds offensive about the United States: the raw exercise of
hegemonic power by Washington and its allies, ganging up on China
and its interests.
</P>
<P>
   In American eyes, China's outrage, expressed in diplomatic
demarches and in the undiplomatic marches of enraged citizens at
the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, has seemed overblown, even irrational.
</P>
<P>
   As important as this heightened mutual mistrust is, a larger
casualty of the bombing could well be the administration's idea of
a ``strategic partnership' with China, the notion that the two
countries have shared interests in the Asia region, a number of
former Clinton administration officials and China experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The putative partnership, which already had been called into
question by administration critics in the last six months, may
indeed be turning abruptly into a regional rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Just one week after the bombing, the administration is cautious
in describing its long-term fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too early to tell,'' is the phrase most used by the White
House about the potential effects of the bombing on specific
administration interests, like China's membership in the World
Trade Organization. On Friday, Clinton discussed this and other
matters with President Jiang Zemin in a telephone call, their first
conversation since the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But a White House official said that the clout of Jiang and
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji _ the two leaders with whom Clinton had
closest contact _ could be undermined by the internal power
struggles that some people detect in Chinese politics since the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   These struggles pit more modernizing leaders like Jiang and Zhu
against more conservative ideologues. Because Clinton has
personalized his dealings with the two leaders, their difficulties
would present a major stumbling block to improving the chilled
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy strike came at a time of mounting quarrels between
Washington and Beijing over alleged espionage by China in the last
20 years involving nuclear secrets at American laboratories; over
the administration's enthusiasm for a theater missile defense
system that could involve Taiwan, and over human rights.
</P>
<P>
   In the next several weeks, the congressional committee headed by
Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., that investigated illicit
technology transfers to China is expected to release its
long-awaited report, an event likely to worsen the strained ties
with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like us, the Chinese are beginning to ask whether the
strategic partnership is workable,'' said Robert Suettinger, until
recently the CIA's senior analyst for Asia and now a visiting
fellow at the Brookings Institution. Though never clearly defined
by the administration, Suettinger said, the basic premise of the
partnership was that China would have a ``good relationship with
the United States, build an economy and have peace in the region
and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the United States and China move toward an ``adversarial
relationship'' now hangs in the balance, Suettinger said.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the China-U.S. relationship was proving to be
like ``a bad marriage, which at the core is pretty hollow,'' said
David Shambaugh, a former member of the National Security Council
and now a China expert at George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no strategic glue holding it together,'' he said.
``There is no common agreement in Asia, and I see it as a
relationship of strategic competition in Asia and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the disagreements in Asia are quarrels over Washington's
strengthening of defense ties with Japan and the administration's
recent decision to approve the sale of an early-warning radar
system to Taiwan, the island that China considers part of its
territory. The Chinese government warned last month that the actual
deployment of the radar system _ designed to detect a missile
launch by China _ would have a ``serious negative impact'' on
relations with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The theater missile defense system was originally intended to
protect Japan and South Korea against the threat of missiles from
North Korea. If extended to Taiwan, as some in the administration
favor, it would be designed to protect Taiwan against missiles from
China.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of theater missile defense for Taiwan has been
described by the Chinese as another example of the United States
playing the hegemonic power that wants to contain China.
</P>
<P>
   American intelligence agencies, for their part, have been
warning about Chinese efforts to deploy new and better nuclear
missiles, perhaps with stolen American technology.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That the NATO bombing of the embassy occurred in 1999 is viewed
by some Chinese as symbolic. At the end of every decade since the
Communists took power in China in 1949, major events have occurred
that have dictated Beijing's relationship to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   To name the most recent, the United States and China normalized
relations in 1979 during the Carter presidency, and in 1989 the
West turned away from China because of the killing of civilians by
the army in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, China may turn away from the United States, China
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   In talks with Chinese officials since the Belgrade bombing, a
former American diplomat to China, Chas. W. Freeman Jr., who has
been a voice for strengthening ties, said he saw a grim outlook.
Unless there is ``miraculously deft handling'' by the two sides,
any movement on issues of importance to Washington will grind to a
standstill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Chinese government is paralyzed and can't make any
gestures,'' Freeman said in a telephone interview from Hong Kong.
``That kills human rights, nonproliferation and the World Trade
Organization. It hampers cooperation on issues like North Korea.''
Washington has tried to persuade Beijing to get North Korea to curb
the spread of nuclear technology on the Korean peninsula and to
persuade Pyongyang to seek a peaceful accommodation with Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   China's most immediate ire may be apparent at the United
Nations, an arena that Beijing sees as its most important
international platform and that it believes Washington has ignored
in favor of other instruments, like NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate aftermath of the embassy bombing,
administration officials suggested that China would not block
efforts to resolve the Kosovo crisis at the United Nations. As
anger mounted in Beijing, that confidence ebbed, and administration
officials now say it is quite likely that China may at least
frustrate or delay U.N. efforts to end the Balkan war as a way of
showing its rage and getting Washington to pay a price for its
actions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
