<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8508 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-APACHES-TRIMS-     05-15 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-APACHES-TRIMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON BLOCKS HELICOPTERS FROM COMBAT IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON with ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ In a behind-the-scenes struggle over military
strategy and tactics, the Pentagon is blocking a plan by the NATO
commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, to send Apache helicopters into
combat against Serbian troops, Pentagon and NATO officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to boost allied firepower, Clark has pressed the United
States to authorize the final combat preparations for the
helicopters, which are part of a U.S. Army ground force in Albania.
Although 24 of them, along with their accompanying Army rockets and
artillery, have already been deployed, the Pentagon has balked,
fearing the mission is too risky.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute adds a new strain to the alliance's seven-week-old
air campaign. NATO's generals have often found themselves hemmed in
by political constraints.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance this time, though, is not coming from allied
diplomats. It is coming from the Army leadership at the Pentagon,
Defense Secretary William Cohen and Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is that Clark is being aggressive, and there is some
resistance to doing what he wants to do,'' a senior American
official said. The Apache is the Army's premier tank-killing
weapon. It can fly low, at night, in bad weather and is equipped
with a sophisticated infrared system that generates images from the
heat of its targets.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter is armed with laser-guided Hellfire anti-tank
missiles and 30-millimeter guns.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clark first requested them 48 hours after NATO's
airstrikes began on March 24, the Apaches have been a particularly
sensitive matter for the Clinton administration, which has been
reluctant to use combat troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It took weeks for Washington to agree to Clark's request to
deploy the Apaches. Then it took weeks more to lug the men and
supplies for the helicopters and the Army units that accompanied
them to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Washington only agreed to send the Apaches and rockets
on the condition that they not be used in combat without the formal
approval of President Clinton. That approval, which Apache
commanders expected by early May, has yet to take place, largely
because top Pentagon officials have refused to recommend such a
step to the White House, fearing the possible domestic and
international consequences if the missions fail.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the Apaches allowed to conduct ``live fire'' exercises
without the Clinton administration's consent. Such exercises, in
which the helicopters fire their guns and missiles, are an
essential prerequisite for employing them in combat.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have pledged to give Clark whatever weaponry
he says he needs to wage the air war. Pentagon officials still
recall Defense Secretary Les Aspin's fateful decision in 1993 to
turn down the military's request for tanks and AC-130 gunships in
Somalia, a judgment that cost Aspin his job after 18 Army soldiers
were killed .
</P>
<P>
   But Clark wants to conduct the ``live fire'' test by shooting at
targets in Kosovo, and he still has not received permission to do
so. Two of the helicopters have already crashed during training
missions, killing two pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no concept of using the Apaches just as a feint,'' a
NATO official said. ``Clark would not have asked for them if he did
not have every intention to use them. The Serbs are using
helicopters against civilians in Kosovo. Why can't we use
helicopters against the Serbs?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clark flew to Albania Saturday to meet with the Task Force
commanders and review their tactics and preparations. He declined
to be interviewed regarding the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton indicated this week that the Pentagon was concerned
about the risks and complexity the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a relatively complicated operation, very similar to
running any other type of air operation, same types of resources
required in terms of electronic warfare, support aircraft, the
suppression fire that has to be in place.'' he told the Senate
Appropriations Committee. ``And all this has to be rehearsed, and
then you weigh the risk versus the gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24 Apaches are part of Task Force Hawk, a 5,000 Army soldier
unit in Albania, which also includes surface-to-surface ATACMS
rockets, MLRS artillery, Bradley Fighting Vehicles and M1-A1 tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The task force is under the overall command of Lt. Gen. John
Walker Hendrix, who also serves as commander of the U.S. Army's V
Corps in Germany. It is very unusual for such a high-ranking
officer to head up such a small task force, and his appointment
reflects the United States' anxiety over the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache squadron is commanded by Brig. Gen. Richard A. Cody,
one of the Army's most respected helicopter officers. One of Cody's
most notable exploits took place in 1991, when he led Task Force
Normandy, the Apache helicopter unit that fired the opening shorts
of the Persian Gulf war. The Apaches blasted two clusters of Iraqi
early-warning radars, firing Hellfire missiles and 30-millimeter
guns.
</P>
<P>
   But the mission in Kosovo is far more complex and dangerous.
Serbian troops are armed with SA-7 shoulder-fired missiles,
anti-aircraft artillery and SAM surface-to-air missiles, which pose
a major threat to the helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough mission that they're being asked to
perform,'' Cohen told reporters on Wednesday. ``It's very harsh
terrain under very difficult circumstances. These Apaches and their
training requires great skill and a full training measure before
they are actually employed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Task Force Hawk has been developing the tactics to take
on the Yugoslav military. First, the task force would blast a path
through the Serbian air defenses, using ATACMS rockets, which have
a range of about 100 miles and rain down as many as 950 deadly
bomblets per rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Barrages of MLRS rockets, which have a range of 18 miles, would
also be fired. Each rocket carries nearly 700 armor-piercing
fragmentation bomblets.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Apaches would attack, hugging the earth and popping up
to attack Serbian troops and armored vehicles. To provide
themselves an additional measure of protection, they would attack
at night.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When Clark briefed allied ambassadors on the air campaign at a
closed-door meeting Tuesday evening, several diplomats asked why
the Apaches they had heard so much about were not fighting in
Kosovo, according to two diplomats were were present. None
expressed concern about using the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clark replied that the helicopters needed to conduct ``live
fire'' exercises. The NATO commander did not say that it was the
Pentagon that was holding up those exercises.
</P>
<P>
   A major Pentagon concern is that the mission is too risky. As
long as the weather is good, NATO should rely on attacks from
combat planes that bomb from high altitude, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army's concern is that this is a very dangerous mission,''
a Pentagon official said. ``The avenues into Kosovo are limited,
and the opportunity for shoulder-held weapons is very real. We have
to really have all our act together. No one thinks the mission
can't be done, but in an age when the American people believe we're
in a zero-defects war, there's real apprehension we're going to
bring solders back in body bags.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that if attacks deep into Kosovo are too
dangerous, the Apaches could still be used to attack Serb forces
during one of their regular incursions into Albania. Or the Apaches
could fire at Serb troops just across the border while hovering
over Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pentagon objection pertains to barrages of rockets and
artillery that would precede the Apache attacks. While the rockets
would be aimed at air defenses, there are no NATO ground troops in
Kosovo to direct the fire, raising the prospect of civilian
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said, though, that the risk might be minimized by
using unmanned reconnaissance drones.
</P>
<P>
   A final Pentagon argument is that launching Apache and
surface-to-surface rocket attacks against Serb forces might prompt
the Yugoslav military to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you begin attacks with Apaches out of Albania with
artillery fire, you're escalating the conflict and inviting the VJ
to come across the border,'' said a Pentagon official, using the
acronym for the Yugoslav military. ``They're not just going to take
that kind of beating and sit still. That's at the top of the issue
list here and at the State Department.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials say that Serb troops are already attacking across
the border and that the risk of a major division level attack is
overstated. They assert that real concern of U.S. Army officers at
the Pentagon is to avoid being drawn into the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs are already attacking into Albania,'' a NATO
official said. ``We are passed that point. It does appear that the
Air Force is prepared to accept more risk than the Army.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is unclear if the Apaches will ever be used, NATO is
already using the helicopter threat as part of its psychological
operations against the Serb military.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaflets dropped in Kosovo warn Serb troops that the
alliance will relentlessly attack them from every direction if they
stay in Kosovo. Showing a fearsome picture of an Apache swooping
down on a tank, the leaflets warn: ``Don't Wait For Me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
