<HEADER>
A8513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-GREENS-NYT &LR;      05-15 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-GREENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GENERATION OF GERMAN PACIFISTS AT ODDS OVER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIELEFELD, Germany _ Like many Germans of the generation born at
the end of World War II, Heidi Bauer has spent much of her life
opposing war, driven by an intimate sense of its horror and its
indelible scars.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1944, Ms. Bauer, a schoolteacher, campaigned in the
Peace Movement in the 1970s to protest the Vietnam War, fought
against the deployment in Germany of U.S. Pershing II missiles
during the 1980s, joined the Green Party in 1984 to express her
pacifism, and rejoiced in 1989 at the Cold War's quiet end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had won at last,'' she said. ``We had contributed
to the end of the Cold War without a big bang. I believed there was
no more need for NATO because there was no more mission. To me, a
lot of what is happening in Kosovo is about trying to prove that
NATO is still relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bauer was one of many party members in an indignant mood
during a Green Party congress here last week. In government office
for the first time since the party was founded two decades ago, the
pacifist Greens have quickly found themselves backing a war. In so
doing, for some, they have betrayed the long struggle of a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   That generation is the one in power today, born at war's end or
just afterward, driven to ask their parents, if they were alive,
what they did under Hitler between 1933 and 1945, suffocated and
pushed to protest by the rigid conformity of postwar Germany,
living for most of their lives at the explosive fulcrum of the
East-West conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the Green foreign minister, is another member
of that generation. He was born four years after Ms. Bauer, and his
career followed a similar arc of interrogation and protest. For
many years, his answers were similar, based on anti-war agitation,
pacifism and the defense of human rights through international law.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1994, three years into the Bosnian war, Fischer was
still entrenched in such positions. The idea of sending German
forces to combat was still abhorrent to him. ``To send German
soldiers to the Balkans, where the forces of Hitler went crazy in
World War II, would not appease the conflict but worsen it,'' he
said that year.
</P>
<P>
   But a year later, the Serbian massacre of Bosnian Muslims at
Srebrenica completed Fischer's conversion to the idea, now
passionately held, that pacifism was no answer to crimes of
religious, ethnic and racial killing on European soil. Those
crimes, Fischer decided, had ultimately to be met with force.
</P>
<P>
   He became an advocate of what Ulrich Beck, a German
intellectual, has called ``NATO's new military humanism'' _ the
notion, defended by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, that the
defense of human rights is a form of mission.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Fischer and Ms. Bauer, a composed and thoughtful
woman from the Hesse region, found themselves on opposing sides
during the Greens' tumultuous congress. The split clearly ran right
through the party, and may in the long term cause many defections
by members who feel betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing can never be a means to impose human rights,'' Ms.
Bauer said. ``It is a clear violation of international law, and
over seven weeks it has only made matters worse. I am nervous,
nervous for my children. I have a sense we may be embarking on
World War III. How long can Russia tolerate being ignored?''
</P>
<P>
   But Fischer defended bombing as the only answer to what he
called the evil of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. His
arguments were similar to those of Rudolf Scharping, the Social
Democratic defense minister, who has said that to turn away from
combating the brutal ethnic purges in Kosovo would suggest that
Germany has not learned from its own history.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the differences in the Green Party lie two views of NATO.
The first, that of the German government and the Green ministers in
it, portrays the alliance spreading the human rights and rule of
law on which Europe must now base its identity.
</P>
<P>
   The second, that of Ms. Bauer and many other Green Party
members, sees NATO arrogantly attempting to extend the domain of
free markets and capitalism under the mask of a universal mission
to defend human rights. They are deeply suspicious of the way
military humanism, in Beck's words, ``fills a vacuum by giving
enemy-free institutions a cosmopolitan mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate on these issues is particularly intense at the heart
of the Green Party, but it is also a reflection of tensions
throughout Germany as the Kosovo war changes the country's
self-image.
</P>
<P>
   Active in the bombing campaign and leading the diplomatic quest
for peace, Germany is behaving, perhaps for the first time since
World War II, as if it need have no qualms about flexing its
political muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer has said repeatedly that the country should take pride
in the fact that, in the Kosovo war, ``Germany is on the right side
for the first time this century.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gina Mertens, a doctor and Greens supporter, said she saw
these changes as perilous. ``For Germany to start believing you can
bomb your way to peace is wrong,'' she said. ``I strongly believe
the Greens must be a force for pacifism.''
</P>
<P>
   She said many members of the Green Party would leave it for the
former East German Communists, now known as the Party of Democratic
Socialism, which has resolutely opposed to the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bauer said: ``The Green Party has no right to survive
because it is not the party of pacifism anymore. If we were in
opposition today, we would be strongly against the war, but
unfortunately we won the election.''
</P>
<P>
   But a small majority of Greens backs Fischer and believes that
two surprises _ first power, then war _ have made a new outlook
inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is bitter, the truth is sad,'' said Daniel
Cohn-Bendit, a 1968 student leader and a leading Green. ``But the
truth is we are right to choose force in the Balkans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1531EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
