<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES FILM INDUSTRY TO LIMIT VIOLENCE ON SCREEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Nev.)   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ President Clinton urged the entertainment
industry Saturday to voluntarily limit the glorification of guns in
movie advertisements and previews and to consider whether movies
rated PG-13 contain excessive and gratuitous violence.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Clinton was to appear at a Hollywood dinner
given by top movie executives that was expected to raise $1.7
million for Democratic candidates for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio broadcast, the president criticized the
Senate for passing a gun-control measure on Friday that he said was
``riddled with loopholes'' allowing unrestricted firearms purchases
at gun shows and pawnshops. But he also praised some gun
manufacturers for their support of administratio gun-control
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The president thus continued to weave a middle path between
condemnation of Hollywood and attacks on the gun lobby in his
effort to begin a national campaign to reduce violence by
teen-agers in the aftermath of the school shooting in Littleton,
Colo., in April.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton convened a White House meeting on youth and violence
last Monday that some in the entertainment business refused to
attend because they thought it was an effort to demonize Hollywood
for the prevalence of violence in American society. The president
emphasized then, and again Saturday, that he was not engaged in a
hunt for scapegoats but rather trying to spark some soul-searching
on the part of movie and television executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many creators and purveyors of violence say there is
nothing they can do about it,'' Clinton said in the radio address.
``But I believe they are wrong. Every one of us has a role to play
in giving our kids a safe future. And those with greater influence
have greater responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should see movies and music, TV programs, video games and
advertising for them made by people who made them as if their own
children were watching,'' he added. ``Members of the entertainment
community can make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The president asked the industry to consider revising the rating
system to make movies rated PG-13 less violent. He suggested that
films now rated PG-13 as appropriate for teen-agers contain
material that is suitable only for older viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also urged owners of theaters and video stores to
enforce the current R rating, which means that children under 17
should not view the material unless accompanied by a parent or
adult guardian.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Gallup Poll cited by the White House, half of
American teen-agers say they have seen an R-rated movie in the last
month.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that the president's proposals on
movie advertisements and the rating system were not a threat but a
suggestion, not censorship but a plea for self-restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Several entertainment executives said this week that they were
willing to consider voluntary measures to limit access to violent
material. But most insisted that the easy availability of guns and
the turmoil of adolescence were the chief causes of violent
behavior by teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted studies that show that the average American child
will see 40,000 dramatized murders by the time he or she reaches
age 18. He also cited research indicating that celluloid mayhem
desensitizes children to violence and may lead to aggressive
behavior by troubled and alienated youths.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to Democratic donors near here on Friday night,
Clinton said that parents, teachers and religious leaders, along
with Hollywood executives, had a responsibility to provide
alternatives to children so that they did not ``drift off into the
darkness'' of violent fantasy, or worse, action.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think is that we now understand _ I hope we do, as a
people _ that if we're going to make America a safer place for our
children, we have to stop pointing fingers at one another and start
assuming responsibility,'' Clinton told contributors at the home of
Walter Shorenstein, a San Francisco developer.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to appear at a fund-raiser Saturday night
in Beverly Hills given by the founders of the Dreamworks studio,
David Geffen, Steven Spielberg and Jeffrey Katzenberg. The 100
guests will include many of the top names in Hollywood who have
been among the president's most loyal patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen said this week that he and most of his friends in
Hollywood continued to support the president despite Clinton's
recent criticism of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   From Los Angeles, Clinton travels to San Diego and Las Vegas to
complete a four-day fund-raising trip that was expected to net the
Democratic Party more than $3 million. He returns to Washington on
Monday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
