<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ZHU-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BLAST CHURNS CHINA'S POLITICAL TEA LEAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Why did Zhu Rongji, China's popular prime
minister, cry on TV?
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a tumultuous week when student-led protests and
government-run media dovetailed in a remarkable show of nationalist
frenzy, one of the main questions haunting Politburo-watchers in
China is why Zhu shed tears when he and other leaders appeared at
memorial services for three journalists killed in NATO's accidental
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the first reason, that even a politician as hard-boiled
as Zhu was genuinely overcome by emotion for the tragic deaths of
three fellow citizens, Chinese analysts and journalists say that
politics also helped darken Zhu's demeanor. The political stakes in
China's current outburst of nationalism are high, and the
overriding question of the day is: Has Zhu been hurt?
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, seen by many ordinary Chinese as the best hope for
combating corruption and transforming the moribund state sector of
the economy, is suddenly vulnerable to accusations by rivals that
he is too soft on the United States, the country Chinese seem both
to love and to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from his trip to Washington in April, when he made broad
concessions on trade issues but failed to win entry to the World
Trade Organization, Zhu is being accused of humiliating his country
by selling out its interests and getting nothing in return,
particularly by officials threatened by Zhu's reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Now that China's extensive political machinery is issuing
spirited nationalist edicts and speeches to be studied and recited
by local officials in every province of China, Zhu's reform program
appears certain to be slowed. Even if Zhu's political standing is
not seriously diminished by attacks from opponents, he will
doubtless have to delay or soften his more aggressive reforms.
</P>
<P>
   For political scorekeepers who scour the media for clues to the
power struggle that inevitably intensifies during a crisis, even
though it remains hidden, the main event last week was television's
news broadcast Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   It showed little besides a formal mourning routine by six of
China's top leaders at ceremonies for the three journalists,
recorded in minute detail. Yet in China, even a simple event may
offer hints whose political implications are debated by viewers for
days afterward.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday's broadcast, starting with President Jiang Zemin,
each leader performed the same solemn triple bow before photographs
of the dead, and then moved slowly down a receiving line of
relatives, shaking hands and giving condolences.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast was clearly intended to convey the leadership's
sympathy for the victims of the bombing, since leaders are
sensitive to accusations, from students and military officers and
conservative politicians, that the official response to the bombing
has been too weak.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, whose nickname among Chinese journalists is the Actor
because of his attempts to stage his appearance at news events,
looked saddened and solemn as he shook hands with the grieving
families.
</P>
<P>
   Next in line was Li Peng, chairman of China's legislature, who
is deeply unpopular for presiding over the crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators in 1989. Li appeared to avoid looking
at the people with whom he shook hands, achieving less than the
desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Zhu. He looked each relative in the eye, in silence.
His distressed expression said it all: This is unspeakably sad, and
I feel your pain. By the time he reached the end of the line, Zhu
was crying and looked genuinely moved. It was a virtuoso
performance, several Chinese journalists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhu is already the most popular leader among common people,''
said a magazine editor in Beijing. ``In a crisis, everyone looks to
see how the leadership acts. Zhu did best, in that one moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Zhu's tears also meant something more, the editor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His expression said, `This is a terrible thing for China,' ''
the editor explained. ``Not just the families, not just China's
image, but also the whole economic reform process, which could be
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Other close observers of the week's events debated whether Zhu's
tears were a warning to sophisticated viewers, or an appeal for
support from fellow Communist Party members, or something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were seriously under attack, he would not appear on
television at all,'' said an official at a state-run company. ``I
think he was trying to look humble.''
</P>
<P>
   The official pointed to another clue, which came on the
following day's television broadcast, where China's leaders were
shown going to the hospital to visit several Chinese diplomats who
were wounded in the bombing of the embassy in Belgrade, and have
returned to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than show each of the top leaders comforting separate
wounded people, as such broadcasts often do, Jiang, Li, Zhu and
three other top leaders trooped into each hospital room together.
It involved awkward camera work to get them all on screen at the
same time, but the effort was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one reason to show them all together, rather than
separately,'' the official said. ``The message is that they are
united. Whether or not it is true, that is the message.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Almost exactly 10 years ago, China's leading political reformer
and Communist Party chief at the time, Zhao Ziyang, made a tearful
appearance on television as he visited hunger-striking student
demonstrators in Tiananmen Square just two weeks before the violent
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   It was the last time Zhao was seen in public. He has been under
house arrest ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu does not seem to be in any imminent danger of dismissal.
China's media, by the end of the week, were reporting the
activities of Jiang, Li and Zhu in that order, in keeping with
their ranking in the Communist Party hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chinese journalist pointed out that many people took
note when Zhu said just before going to the United States in April
that he actually did not want to go, but that Jiang had insisted
that he do so.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders take few important decisions unilaterally, the
journalist said, so Zhu's statement, though it sounded simple,
indicated that it was a collective decision of the leadership that
he should go ahead with his trip, implying that a collective
responsibility must be borne if things did not go well.
</P>
<P>
   In the 14 months since he was named prime minister, Zhu has won
loyal admirers and enemies by taking bold steps to kill off
unproductive sectors of China's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The concessions he offered in Washington in April were aimed at
winning entry to the World Trade Organization, but more generally
aimed at forcing open change-resistant parts of China's
telecommunications, banking and financial services industries.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu is also said to be resented by some of his top colleagues,
with less talent for public speaking, because he is so appealing,
direct and humorous in public.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one of Zhu's weaknesses, Chinese analysts say, is that he is
so popular among Western businessmen and officials, who appreciate
his direct manner. At a time of strong anti-American sentiment,
that vulnerability can only become more pronounced.
</P>
</TEXT>
