<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.C.-TRAFFIC-ART-NYT &LR;      05-15 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.C.-TRAFFIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE PARK'S BUCOLIC APPEAL IS LOST IN TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. _ Years ago, the office talk at
Glaxo Wellcome's U.S. headquarters here was primarily the weather
or the ease with which Duke's basketball team had just clobbered an
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come to the office now and complain about the
traffic,'' said Bill Shore, the director of community affairs at
Glaxo Wellcome. ``It's frustrating. I don't care if you're in Los
Angeles or Raleigh, if you're in a dead stop in traffic, you're in
a dead stop.''
</P>
<P>
   When Research Triangle Park was founded in 1959 by business
leaders in an area between Raleigh, Durham and Chapel Hill, it was
designed to be a 10-square-mile preserve where corporations could
grow without the urban ills of crime and pollution. Strict rules
maintained the sense of tranquillity. Even today, companies that
move to certain parts of the park's forests can build on only 15
percent of their land, with the rest remaining largely woods.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that the concept has become too successful. About
50,000 people now go out to the country each day to work inside
Research Triangle Park at such corporate giants as International
Business Machines, Cisco Systems and Novartis Biotechnology, and
nearly all of them get there by car.
</P>
<P>
   The result is rush-hour jams along the roads that serve the park
_ notably Davis and Alexander Drives _ that can take an hour to
clear. Rain or a traffic accident along the primary highway serving
the complex, Interstate 40, can stretch the normal 15-minute drive
to Chapel Hill into a 90-minute ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   The congestion is so worrisome that top executives of Glaxo
Wellcome and Cisco Systems recently told Gov. Jim Hunt that their
companies could not continue to expand here if the problem was not
relieved.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic problems plaguing Research Triangle Park are common
to many metropolitan areas, but to civic and business leaders in
the Research Triangle, that is precisely the problem. What makes
North Carolina gridlock different, they say, is the easygoing
culture of the state, which has drawn so many people and jobs here.
Even city dwellers in North Carolina expect their lives to be
hassle free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being stuck in traffic for an hour and a half is not the way
communities should live,'' said Smedes York, a former mayor of
Raleigh who is co-chairman of the Regional Transportation Alliance,
formed earlier this year by business and civic leaders to organize
efforts to relieve congestion around the park. But many of the
alliance's ideas face a dim future in the North Carolina
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Research Triangle Park may be home to some of the state's
largest employers, but some members of the Legislature appear
determined not to give the area special consideration.
Representatives from rural areas have succeeded in having much of
the money allocated for new roads divided equally across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the traffic horror is the design of the park itself.
Even though the campus is two miles wide, it has no residential
space, which makes all workers commuters. The only mass transit is
a limited bus service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were working from a model that was popular in the 1950s and
1960s,'' York said. ``Nobody wanted to live downtown. That's why
the park was built that way. You just couldn't live close to where
you worked, heaven forbid.''
</P>
<P>
   When the park opened 40 years ago, the area's small towns
welcomed the new commuters. The reputation of Research Triangle
Park as a high-tech promised land soon spread nationwide, drawing
an influx of companies and well-educated, well-paid employees.
</P>
<P>
   In the past eight years, the population of the six counties
surrounding the park increased 23.7 percent, to one million. The
average salary of those working in the complex last year was about
$56,000, compared with $23,800 for the state.
</P>
<P>
   But the surrounding communities soon began to struggle from the
boom. Nine years ago, Cary, near Raleigh, the state capital, had
only 44,397 residents. Today, Cary has around 85,000 and must buy
water from Raleigh and Durham.
</P>
<P>
   One problem that has vexed Cary and other towns near the park is
the lack of industry within their own city limits. Without an
inflow of corporate income taxes, Cary has had to use bond
referendums to finance many of its road and water programs.
</P>
<P>
   To solve the area's traffic woes, the Regional Transportation
Alliance has come up with proposals that include a 5-cent-a-gallon
gasoline tax in the six counties around the park and building toll
roads within the counties.
</P>
<P>
   The gasoline tax, toll fees and other initiatives would raise $2
billion over the next 10 years for new roads that would connect the
park to surrounding cities, as well as for road expansions. While
the plan appears feasible, some members of the Legislature want to
make the gasoline tax statewide so that their areas would share in
the proceeds. But a statewide tax would require approval of the
full Legislature, where it would face a battle. Jim Black, the
speaker of the house, has said there would be no tax increases for
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Some help is on the way, however. The state Department of
Transportation is planning to add a fourth lane to Interstate 40.
The Triangle Transit Authority, created by the Legislature and the
several municipalities to develop a long-term plan for
transportation for the area, is expected to build a $250 million
rail system to connect the park with several communities. But
neither of the projects is expected to be completed before 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders believe this will not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of one way being correct and one not,'' York
said. ``We just need to respond to the area's growth. But we also
need to remember that North Carolina has a history of solving its
problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1604EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
