<SLUG> BC-BKN-KINGS-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME 5 SETUPS: JAZZ AND HEAT IN SURVIVAL OF THE FITTEST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ It was a hard lesson in playoff survival
learned by the upstart Sacramento Kings against the two-time
Western Conference champion Utah Jazz in Game 4 of their
first-round series here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Seven seconds was all that separated Utah from a shockingly
early exit and the Kings from their first post-season
series-clinching victory since the franchise moved to Sacramento in
1985. The sellout crowd of 17,317 that packed Arco Arena was
sensing the kill, and Utah knew it had absolutely no margin for
error.
</P>
<P>
   No one understood this better than Utah point guard John
Stockton. He calmly took the inbound pass, ran the pick-and-roll at
the top of the key with forward Karl Malone _ as he has so many
times in his career _ freed himself on the right side and drained a
22-foot jump shot with seven-tenths of a second remaining.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of Sacramento preparing to play the Portland Trail
Blazers in the second round, the 90-89 Utah victory has forced a
decisive Game 5 in Salt Lake City on Sunday afternoon. For
Stockton, who also made a buzzer-beating 3-pointer in Game 6 of the
1997 Western Conference finals to propel the Jazz to its first NBA
finals appearance, clutch jumpers are nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's right up there,'' Stockton said when asked
where he would rank Friday's last-second basket. ``We were going
home for the summer. But that's just one shot. The plays leading up
to it won't get the credit they deserve. Shandon was incredible on
both ends of the floor,'' he said of forward Shandon Anderson, who
scored 8 of Utah's last 12 points. ``We're not even in the position
to make a last-second shot if he didn't do what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's 8 points came in a one-minute stretch to turn an
81-78 deficit into an 86-84 lead with 31 seconds remaining.
Anderson scored 10 of his 16 points in the final period,
essentially carrying the scoring load down the stretch. Although
Malone scored 23 points to go with his game-high 16 rebounds, he
struggled through a 9-for-21 shooting night and was in constant
foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Utah also showed an uncharacteristic lapse in poise, getting
assessed with three technical fouls in a four-minute stretch
halfway through the third quarter that put the Jazz in a 9-point
hole. A more experienced team might have put them away, although
the Kings came very close.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be ready to go on Sunday,'' Stockton said.
``They played well and with confidence, and we're going to have to
play a better game than we played tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Jazz pulled out Game 4, it realized that fate
can only be tempted so many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that we're not out of the woods yet,'' Malone said.
``We're going back home, but we're playing a young team who have
everything to gain and nothing to lose.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
