<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNSTILE JUMPER KILLED BY SUBWAY TRAIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KIT R. ROANE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A fare dodger was crushed to death by a subway train
in Brooklyn early Saturday after he leaped onto the tracks trying
to escape two transit officers, police said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The turnstile jumper, Ronnie Perkins, 18, of Brooklyn, was
declared dead at the scene, police said. He was caught between the
platform and a southbound J train as it arrived in the Chauncey
Street subway station about 2:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they arrested one of two young men who jumped the
turnstile with Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   The arrested man, Remi Perry, 18, also of Brooklyn, was charged
with theft of services for not paying the $1.50 fare, police said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police account, the plainclothes transit
officers were standing on the platform when they spotted three
young men jumping over a turnstile without paying.
</P>
<P>
   When the officers moved toward them, the suspects split up,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   One ran back out of the station, while the other two jumped onto
the tracks below just as a J train was arriving on the southbound
side.
</P>
<P>
   Perry ran to the northbound tracks, but Perkins froze in the
headlight of the approaching train, then dashed back to the
platform, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the activity ahead, the train's conductor slammed on his
brakes but could not stop in time. The train caught Perkins as he
gripped the side of the platform trying to pull himself to safety,
police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
