<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIG-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REFUGEES ARRIVES IN NEW YORK FOR SETTLEMENT WITH RELATIVES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - A group of 208 Kosovo refugees, who have relatives
ready to support and house them in the United States, arrived at
Kennedy International Airport Saturday from camps in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second group of refugees _ the first arrived May 8 _
who were able to walk directly into the embrace of family members
instead of being transferred to Fort Dix, N.J., and waiting for a
private agency to resettle them.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives in New York City and New Jersey are sponsoring the
largest number of the newly arrived ethnic Albanian refugee
families. Others were put on planes to meet relatives in Texas,
Michigan, Illinois, Arizona, California and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has agreed to help resettle 20,000 of the
hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanians who have been forcibly
expelled from their villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee agencies have estimated that 40 percent of them will
eventually be housed in the New York City area with relatives who
sponsor them or in apartments that are arranged for them by
resettlement groups like the International Rescue Committee.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NYT &LR;      05-15 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING ERA REACHES A DRAMATIC CROSSROADS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Latrell Sprewell walked into the New York Knicks'
locker room Friday night, a thick cluster of reporters migrated in
his direction. Suddenly there was a clear view of a solitary
Patrick Ewing sitting in his royal blue bathrobe, staring down the
fibers in the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   His chin was cupped in his hand, and he was perfectly still, as
if modeling while Rodin chiseled ``The Thinker.'' Any number of
issues could have been circling Ewing's mind, like the pain in his
left Achilles' tendon that was plunged into two feet of ice, the
devastation of losing Game 4 to the Miami Heat after the Knicks had
foolishly danced on their rivals' grave with an 11-point lead, and
the weight of what is before him.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just a series-deciding Game 5 that will play out
here on Sunday. If the Knicks are eliminated by coach Pat Riley's
Heat, the outcome could also send into motion the firing of coach
Jeff Van Gundy and cloud the future of the Ewing era in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't playing for Phil Jackson,'' Ewing said after the
Knicks lost, 87-72, and allowed the Heat to tie the series, 2-2, at
Madison Square Garden. ``If they bring Phil Jackson in here, they
can trade me.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be management's plan if the Knicks falter in the first
round. One Eastern Conference official, speaking on the condition
of anonymity, said the Knicks will explore trade possibilities
involving Ewing if they begin a hot pursuit of Jackson, the Bulls'
former coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would put things in place for Phil,'' the official said,
referring to the type of players Jackson would want for his
triangle offense. ``The Knicks wouldn't be so old, and they'd be
more versatile. Phil has never needed a pure center. In the
triangle, you need interchangeable parts.''
</P>
<P>
   The salary cap logistics would make a trade difficult, though.
At age 36, Ewing has two years and $30 million left on a $68
million contract. Also, Dave Checketts, the president of Madison
Square Garden, said Friday that he hopes Ewing retires as a Knick.
However, he added that no Knick is untouchable if the right trade
scenario developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay attention to the things players say; I won't pretend I
don't,'' said Checketts, who is aware of Ewing's position on
Jackson and loyalty to Van Gundy. ``But they don't make key
decisions. But I will certainly listen to what Patrick has to say
in the off season.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever unfolds will hinge greatly on what happens Sunday
afternoon in Miami Arena. In a cruel symmetry, Riley has a hand in
deciding Van Gundy's fate. Here is the former Knick coach who was a
mentor to Van Gundy, gave him the Cliff Notes to develop his own
style, and prepared him to take over the team when the opportunity
came. Yet, a Heat victory could leave Van Gundy's job security in
peril.
</P>
<P>
   Always loyal to Riley despite two volatile playoff series in the
last two years, always respectful of him even though their
relationship has been wounded by two playoff-deciding fights, Van
Gundy might be at the mercy of the Heat and at the whim of his own
moody players.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the Knicks flash unlimited potential, just as they did
by crushing the Heat in Games 1 and 3. Other times, they seem as if
they have lost the character that defined the old Knick teams,
which may not have always won with grace, but gritted out tough
fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   There is a leftover core to those Knick teams: Ewing, Larry
Johnson, Allan Houston and Charlie Ward. These players have
supported Van Gundy and would be shattered if he departs. There is
also a new niche in the locker room, led by Marcus Camby and
Sprewell, both of whom have less allegiance to a coach who has been
slow to trust them, and has placed them in roles less glamorous
than what they are accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy needs them all to beat Miami and advance to the second
round, becoming only the second No. 8-seeded team to topple a No.
1. Houston, in particular, is pivotal to the outcome. Over three
years, Houston's ability to find his range has often determined how
the Knicks have finished against the Heat in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Knicks lost Game 7 in Miami after Houston
began the day 1 for 9. Last year, Houston led an undermanned Knick
team with a 30-point outburst to take Game 5 and end the series in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to be myself,'' Houston said. ``I'm not going
to put any extra pressure on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston and Sprewell have a chance to come together, once again.
Their ability to blend as one during this series has meant
victories. When they have been a part of an offense that does not
move the ball and leans on taking their man one-on-one, they have
failed, as they did in Games 2 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can play together,'' Houston said. ``We know that
when we do play together, we can be very effective.''
</P>
<P>
   How effective can Ewing be, though? He has so much to play for,
and yet the franchise center has started off well only to fade as
the game progresses.
</P>
<P>
   During the fourth quarter in this series, Ewing is only 1 for 2.
The blowout nature of the games _ which has limited Ewing's late
minutes _ has something to do with that. Still, Ewing's offensive
impact and defensive mobility have dropped off as the games have
gone on. In the first quarters of the series, Ewing is 8 for 15. It
is hard to know what Ewing will have left should one of his
career's most important games come down to a
survival-of-the-fittest fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to be ready to play,'' Ewing said, answering a
question about the state of his health. ``That's all. Both teams
are competitive, and you know they're not going to go down without
a fight. That's the way I look at it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
