<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-76ERS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
  
 76ers ROUT MAGIC AND WIN SERIES BY 3-2  
(mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ For one brief but monumental moment, the youngest
player on the court made the nine great athletes around him look
like old men glued to the hardwood. Larry Hughes, Philadelphia's
20-year-old rookie, leaped from outside of the painted area, timed
the carom of his teammate Eric Snow's missed shot perfectly, caught
it with two hands and slammed it through the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in the air on his dynamic finish, Hughes finished off the
Orlando Magic with the play as the Philadelphia 76ers went on to
win, 101-91, before a boisterous capacity crowd Saturday at the
First Union Center. The tip-slam gave Philadelphia a 93-86 lead,
completed a 9-0 run and shut the door on a furious rally that saw
the third-seeded Magic come back from an 18-point third-quarter
deficit to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway, who finished with 17 points but missed 14 of 17
shots, followed Hughes' moment with a 3-pointer, but Allen
Iverson's running jumper seconds later insured the victory and gave
the underdog 76ers the series, 3 games to 1. It was the Sixers'
first playoff series victory since sweeping Milwaukee in the first
round in 1991. They will meet the Indiana Pacers, a team they
defeated two of three times in the regular season, in the Eastern
Conference semifinals, beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson, who had every defense in the book thrown at him by the
Orlando coach, Chuck Daly, led everyone with another monstrous
performance, scoring 37 points and handing out nine assists. Eric
Snow followed with 20 points, and Hughes added 14. Nick Anderson
led Orlando with 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia outscored Orlando, 13-6, over the last six minutes
of the second quarter for a 47-36 lead at halftime and looked
poised for a blowout early in the third. Continuing his assault
which began shortly after tip-off, Iverson scored 13 points in the
first seven minutes to reach 30 points with nearly a quarter and a
half left to play.
</P>
<P>
   When Iverson nailed his fourth 3-pointer of the game at 7:33 of
the third quarter, the Sixers went ahead by 62-44, seemingly
shredding the Magic. But out of nowhere, Orlando mustered up a 20-6
run that put them back in the game. Nick Anderson was the catalyst,
scoring 15 of the Magic's 35 points in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Showing a resolve that seemed to have been swiped from them, the
Magic muscled their way to the foul line and hit 17 of 21 free
throws in the quarter. Philadelphia held onto the lead through the
third and took a 77-71 advantage into the fourth, but the Magic
closed the gap in less than four minutes when Darrell Armstrong's
3-pointer tied the score at 79-79 with more than eight minutes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Besides finding its offense and courage, the Magic made its run
with strong defense on Iverson. After reaching 30 points at 4:59 of
the third, the league's most explosive player was held scoreless
until 4:55 remained in the game. The short jumper gave Philadelphia
an 88-86 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, who seems to have become public enemy No. 1 in
Philadelphia, started with intentions of avenging himself. Booed
severely in Game 3 on Wednesday, mocked with chants of ``Penny's
soft,'' he vowed to score points in Iverson-like fashion.
</P>
<P>
   After attempting just two shots in Wednesday's pivotal first
half, Hardaway was quoted in The Philadelphia Daily News as saying,
``I'm coming out firing, no matter what. I don't care if I miss 20
or 30 shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But Philadelphia altered Hardaway's plans immediately. With Eric
Snow, the Sixers' burly point guard, muscling him, Hardaway was not
able to do what he envisioned. He attempted five shots in the first
quarter and missed them all. If it were not for three free throws,
the Magic's leading scorer would have been scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that his careless comment about missing ``20 or 30
shots'' had a chance of coming true, Hardaway took just two shots
in the second quarter. But the results were unchanged and he took a
0-for-7 line into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   With their main man caged, the Magic lacked the firepower to
keep up with the energetic Sixers. Anderson did his best, scoring
14 points, but the mission was nearly hopeless. While they were not
as reckless as they were Wednesday, when they committed 20 of their
27 turnovers in the first half, the Magic were clearly frazzled by
the Sixers' quickness.
</P>
<P>
   With Snow bumping, Iverson swarming and Larry Hughes swatting
down at the ball, Philadelphia rushed Orlando's perimeter players
to the point where avoiding turnovers became the chief objective.
Running the offense became a secondary concern.
</P>
<P>
   This happened early when, after falling behind by 7-2, the
Sixers turned up their defensive intensity, and fear began setting
in on the Magic. Back to back steals by Iverson and Tyrone Hill led
to baskets and gave Philadelphia its first lead at 13-12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
