A8547 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-ZONING-NYT &LR;      05-15 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-ZONING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S BAFFLING ZONING CODE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, May 16:
</P>
<P>
   New York City's antiquated zoning code runs about 900 pages and
rivals the Internal Revenue Code in complexity. Unless you are a
member of the coterie of zoning lawyers, the odds of accurately
interpreting one section of the code in relation to another are
slim to none. City Planning Commission Chairman Joseph Rose now
plans to rewrite parts of the code so that rules for building
height and other crucial standards are not only clear, but sturdy
enough to withstand attempts to twist them into pretzels.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency of this undertaking is visible on both sides of the
East River. Developers and neighborhood groups have already squared
off over the skyscraper Donald Trump wants to build near the United
Nations and David Walentas' plans for a retail and entertainment
complex on land near the East River waterfront in Brooklyn. Both
disputes reflect the muddled state of city land-use policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under Rose's plan, parts of the 1961 zoning code, which he calls
a ``hodgepodge of conflicting visions and objectives,'' would be
reformulated to encourage innovative design while respecting
neighborhood character. Among other things, he would set height
limits for buildings outside Manhattan's Central Business District,
create a process for granting occasional waivers for buildings of
exceptional design, reopen some manufacturing zones to community
uses and rethink commercial-use rules for doctors' offices and
other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important is his plan to abolish plaza bonuses for
residential buildings. Time and again, this tradeoff _ more square
footage for a developer in exchange for a plaza _ has saddled the
city with unattractive and inaccessible public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   As useful as it is, Rose's reform agenda ought to be treated as
an invitation to think more broadly about zoning issues and
land-use opportunities. When he unveiled his ideas in a recent
speech, he expressed a preference for pursuing a short list of
reforms. A full-scale review of the code, he fears, would be
paralyzing. But rethinking land use does not have to result in
civic meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   A number of American cities, including Pittsburgh and
Minneapolis, have developed fresh land-use principles, written a
new code and survived  &QC; the process. New York's 50-odd community
boards, various civic groups, architects and builders should be
invited to compile their own lists of the most vexing zoning
problems. A comparison of all these lists should make it possible
to choose between full-scale review of the entire code and taking a
triage approach by focusing on the top 10 to 20 issues.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue Rose has opened should logically lead everyone to
grapple with two other areas _ redeveloping the city's vast but
often dilapidated waterfront and identifying the environmental
values that should be loaded into the building, zoning and tax
codes. The dog days of summer that New Yorkers dread will be
testimony to the wisdom of examining environmental issues. During
extremely hot weather, New York creates heat islands.
</P>
<P>
   Dark road pavement, buildings with dark roofs and other
impervious surfaces boost already uncomfortable temperatures and
help produce ground-level ozone. Planting trees, a zoning code
issue, and requiring the use of reflective materials on roofs and
streets can lower temperatures. As New York reinvents itself, it
should not be hamstrung by a Sputnik-era rule book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
