u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARMITZVAH-QUADRIPLEG     05-15 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARMITZVAH-QUADRIPLEGIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPED BY TECHNOLOGY, BOY WITH CEREBRAL PALSY HAS BAR MITZVAH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mich.)  ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ``to do'' lists the Stulbergs drew up for their
youngest son's bar mitzvah included a mixture of items, from
standard and stressful to extraordinary and complex.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside ``caterer'' and ``pick up dry cleaning'' were such
details as ``follow up computer file loading'' and ``insert tropes
_ need download.''
</P>
<P>
   When their son Joey finally took his place before 156 guests at
the Kane Street Synagogue in Brooklyn on Saturday, his parents
eased into the intricate day of services and celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Joey, 13, a quadriplegic with severe cerebral palsy who can
barely move and cannot speak, was having his special day, thanks to
a convergence of advanced technologies.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, planning for Joey Stulberg's bar mitzvah began in
November 1985, three months after he was born with an inability to
control motor movement, a severe form of cerebral palsy called
athetosis. At that time, a newspaper article described how a boy in
Pittsburgh with the same disease took part in his bar mitzvah,
using a special computer that gave him a voice.
</P>
<P>
   Joey's father, Robert Stulberg, recalled that his own father
sent him the article with a note attached: ``You may want to save
this for Joey's bar mitzvah. It's never too early to plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Stulberg, a labor lawyer, filed away the clipping, only to dig
it out last year.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the computer's designer, John Eulenberg,
director of the Artificial Language Laboratory at Michigan State
University, the Stulbergs embarked on a journey that tested the
limits of technology, the family's perseverance and the
malleability of an ancient ritual. Yet Stulberg says, ``What's
unusual about this is that it's so usual. He's doing what boys and
girls have done for thousands of years, and has learned enough to
participate in his tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   For Joey, who communicates by tapping a talking portable
computer with a pointer attached to his baseball cap, synagogue is
``GOOD,'' but he looked forward to the ``FREEDOM'' of completing
his Bar Mitzvah studies so he can return to writing plays and
watching sports.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Stulberg's apartment, next to Brooklyn's
Prospect Park, was the site of deliveries, last-minute plans _ and
a small technological miracle, as words, movement and melody came
together.
</P>
<P>
   For nine months, using a Hebrew software program, Joey
laboriously tapped out six different passages of Scripture and
commentary _ hundreds of characters each. He then e-mailed the
files to Eulenberg, who converted the text into audio signals and
gave Joey's words a voice.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Eulenberg arrived from Michigan and transferred the
files into Joey's portable computer, which until that moment spoke
only English. As the Stulbergs _ including Joey's brother, Jacob,
15, his sister, Sally, 10, and their mother, Mickey Green _
clustered in the living room, Joey tapped his screen to bring up a
menu of Hebrew passages. From that, he tapped again, and out poured
the chanting of his Haftarah, the ultimate synthesis of his
word-processed texts.
</P>
<P>
   Joey is, at once, severely impaired and highly gifted. He weighs
50 pounds and must use a wheelchair. Yet he can study, paint and
write at the Henry Viscardi School for the disabled that he attends
in Albertson. Ask him about Wayne Gretzky's retirement and a look
of anguish crosses his face.
</P>
<P>
   He is likely to have a normal life span, said his doctor,
Stephen Ajl, associate professor of pediatrics at Downstate Medical
School.
</P>
<P>
   But planning a special event is difficult. Joey's bar mitzvah
was originally planned for last October. But it was postponed so
that he could undergo four operations to reshape his hip bones so
they would not slide out of their sockets.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the slow recovery, he continued to study Hebrew,
meeting with a tutor. There were other mishaps. Stulberg recalled
with a smile that Joey first painstakingly tapped in the wrong
Haftarah passage, or biblical teaching. Joey roared in laughter at
the memory of the frustrated effort. The right Haftarah passage
turned out to be the longest one there is.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, a group assembled at the synagogue, where a
long black ramp to accommodate Joey's wheelchair dominated the
aisle. As a congregant wired the sound system to project Joey's
synthesized voice, Rabbi Sam Weintraub _ in Talmudic fashion _
pondered the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ordinary, in that there is a young boy who has an
attachment to the synagogue, who is very nervous, and who is going
to lead the congregation in study,'' he said. But as Eulenberg
attached Joey's computer to stereo speakers and chanted Hebrew
resonated, Weintraub said, ``That is not ordinary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
