u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     05-15 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GRUNFELD STILL ROOTS FOR HOMETOWN TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is one longtime fan who thinks the New York
Knicks ``have a good chance'' to win the deciding game in Miami on
Sunday afternoon. He is Ernie Grunfeld, who, until April 21, was
the president and general manager of this erratic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a big Knicks fan,'' Grunfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not always. Maybe not in Romania, where he was born, but
certainly in Forest Hills, Queens, where you could press your ear
to the subway grating and imagine you heard the crowd roar in
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Grunfeld came to run his hometown team, the one with the
massive mood swings, between the energy and purpose of the first
and third playoff games against Miami and the anarchy of the second
and fourth games.
</P>
<P>
   If it all goes down Sunday, the current ownership of the Garden
must look at everybody, everybody, in the basketball chain of
command and ask, What did they know and when did they know it? As
the coaches say, it's a team game, but only Grunfeld was sent to
the showers before the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I had a plan,'' Grunfeld said. ``We were going with
more athletic, younger players to take the pressure off Patrick. We
wanted more diversity, more options. It's finally coming
together.'' He said that before Friday night's 87-72 loss, in which
the Knicks once again reverted to looking like strangers, clanging
impromptu shots off the rim after they had taken an 11-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed,'' said Grunfeld, who watched with friends
in New Jersey. ``This was a winnable game. They were leading in the
fourth quarter and couldn't hold it.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld sounded as mystified as the coaches about the
scattershot basketball of this ad hoc season. He has worked with _
a nice neutral phrase _ both coaches. How alike they are, after
all. Pat Riley and Jeff Van Gundy both seem morbidly shocked by
letdowns in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our poise,'' Van Gundy murmured after Friday's loss.
``We didn't get the job done.'' And then Van Gundy added, ``In this
day and age, when the offense goes, the defense goes with it,'' not
exactly a hearty endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Riley's assessment of his team: ``We were
humiliated twice. Sometimes it does wonders for you. But we gain
nothing _ other than a trip home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like nobody can win. Both teams have problems that seem
beyond home-court advantage or coaching strategy or one crucial
injury or one hot hand. Nobody can get his act together this year.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld has stayed away from the Garden. He still has tickets,
but has no idea when he will feel like using them, or what the
future holds.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that way since that epic evening a month ago when
Dave Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, took him
out to dinner and said, in effect, ``Ernie, could you pass the
rolls? Oh, and by the way, I'll be taking over your duties.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld has not made any public complaints, and is laying low,
courting college players for the Knicks, and rooting. The inner
Knicks fan allowed him to exult over Wednesday night's victory,
when Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby energized the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a three-time all-star, a first-team all-pro the year
Michael Jordan was away playing baseball,'' Grunfeld said of
Sprewell, for whom he traded John Starks. ``He's great in the open
court, great in transition, and now he's more comfortable in the
half court.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Knicks suffered when Sprewell suffered a stress
fracture to his heel on Feb. 7. Grunfeld said, ``He needs time to
get in shape all over again, and it's halfway through the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby came over from Toronto in a trade for the durable and
popular Charles Oakley. On Friday, Grunfeld said, ``Obviously, in
the off-season I had to make tough decisions. They were not popular
decisions but they were in the best interests of the organization.
I felt he was athletic, younger, a shot-blocker.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby had not looked disciplined in two years at Toronto, but
Grunfeld said, ``I felt he was in a situation where we could
surround him with players with a better work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were struggling with a 21-21 record when Grunfeld was
replaced and then they won six of eight and slipped into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of hurt,'' Grunfeld said about his dismissal.
``I was surprised, shocked. I did my job for nine years and had the
fourth-best record during that time. I'm proud of what I
accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not deny that it has been hard for his wife, Nancy, and
their children, Rebecca, 17, and Danny, 14, to not be part of the
Garden life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been harder on my family than on me,'' Grunfeld said.
``I've had more time to be with my family. We're still a basketball
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The basketball family will sit in front of the television
Sunday. Does he have any advice for his old team? ``They know what
to do at game time,'' he said. ``It's always tough to win a final
game on the road, but they can do it.'' Grunfeld is rooting for the
team of his childhood, but it is human nature that he is also
rooting for his own judgment, his own reputation, toward the end of
this strange, truncated season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
