<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FRISK-CIVIL-RIGHTS     05-15 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FRISK-CIVIL-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPITZER THREATENS SUBPOENA ON FRISK DATA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer on Saturday
threatened to subpoena thousands of documents in his inquiry into
whether the New York City Police Department's stop-and-frisk
procedures systematically violated the civil rights of minority
residents.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani Saturday afternoon,
Spitzer said that the city had suddenly refused Friday to
voluntarily hand over the records, after having agreed to do so for
eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely essential for restoring confidence in law
enforcement that the concerns raised about potential abuses of stop
and frisk be addressed quickly,'' he said in an interview shortly
after sending the letter, ``and we will use all legal remedies,
subpoenas, litigation, to make this come about.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``For the mayor to have gone through eight weeks of
deceit like this is wrong and begs the question of what the mayor
is trying to keep from the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's corporation counsel, Michael Hess, responded in a
written statement, arguing that Spitzer's investigation was
redundant and that the attorney general had both ``overstated the
uniqueness of his investigation'' and ``stepped into this matter
belatedly.''
</P>
<P>
   The escalation in words comes as the Giuliani administration
finds itself under increasing pressure from a variety of law
enforcement and government organizations intent on uncovering any
abuse of authority by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The stop and frisk procedure is intended to protect officers by
allowing them to pat down suspects for weapons before questioning
them on the street.
</P>
<P>
   But critics have charged that it has become an excuse for
officers who are trying to make drug or weapon arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations by the state attorney general, federal
prosecutors and the City Council, as well as a class-action lawsuit
seeking to shut down the department's elite Street Crime Unit,
followed the shooting death of Amadou Diallo at the hands of four
street crime officers on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   That incident raised questions about the department's policy for
approaching and searching people on the street. According to the
1968 Supreme Court decision, Terry vs. Ohio, that gave way to the
procedure, the police can pat down a suspect for weapons when the
police ``reasonably'' believe that a suspect is armed and that
criminal activity is taking place. While allowing broad latitude
for such searches, the department's Patrol Guide instructs officers
to search for weapons only ``if you reasonably suspect you or
others are in danger of physical injury.''
</P>
<P>
   According to police officials, a preliminary analysis of reports
filed last year in more than 20 precincts where the Street Crime
Unit has been active shows that 63 percent of all people frisked
were black. The analysis also found that 71 percent of all crime
suspects were described by victims as black, and 68 percent of all
arrests in those precincts were of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Street Crime Unit's 360 officers _ more than 80 percent of
whom are white _ searched 45,000 people in 1997 and 1998, and made
9,500 arrests, according to the Police Department. Spitzer is
seeking records for all such searches in the city during these
years.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said that he also believed that many officers do not
always fill out a required form, called a UF250, and this has been
acknowledged privately by police officers and prosecutors. Spitzer
said that conversations with officers have led him to believe the
form is filled out in only one of every five stops.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping short of accusing the department of systematic abuse in
this area, the attorney general said Saturday that the city was
making any impartial investigation impossible by refusing to hand
over evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is demanding and has the right to know both the
policies and the realities of the NYPD's stop-and-frisk
practices,'' Spitzer said. ``The city's refusal to cooperate with
our investigation is an affront to every one of its residents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
