<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-ABORTION-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION REFERRAL GROUP SUES OVER REJECTED ADS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Wash., Washington, D.C., Calif. Ohio, Ill. and Ga.)   By TOM LASSITER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's mass transit system, which accepts
advertising from a local church-financed agency that promotes
adoptions over abortions, has refused advertisements by a national
organization that refers clients to abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   The abortion rights group, the National Abortion Federation, has
sued in response, contending that the decision, by the Metropolitan
Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority, violates the federation's First
Amendment right to free speech and 14th Amendment right to due
process.
</P>
<P>
   MARTA has regulations that forbid advertising it deems
controversial. In a letter explaining its decision, its advertising
representative, Transportation Displays Inc., suggested that a
message supporting abortion rights fit that category and would
offend some Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, as we are in the `Bible Belt,' MARTA cannot
accept advertising on subjects of controversy,'' Lisa Michaelson, a
Transportation Displays vice president, wrote in the letter to the
abortion federation.
</P>
<P>
   MARTA has until 5 p.m. Monday to file a response to the
federation's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements at issue, which would have been displayed
inside Atlanta buses, sprang from a new campaign by the National
Abortion Federation, based in Washington. They were aimed in part
at discouraging harassment of abortion patients and violence
against abortion providers, and they have been accepted by transit
systems in seven cities: Miami, Washington, Seattle, San Francisco,
Cleveland, Chicago and New York. Only in Atlanta have they been
turned down.
</P>
<P>
   The federation's lawsuit, filed April 27 in the U.S. District
Court in Atlanta, turns centrally on its assertion that MARTA, a
government agency, has created a constitutionally protected public
forum in its advertising practices, accepting advertisements
dealing with a variety of public issues like the dangers of HIV and
of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The suit cites a total of five decisions by four federal appeals
courts to the effect that in a designated public forum, the state
may not exclude speech that it considers controversial,
particularly if it has a history of permitting other speech that
could be deemed controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts have defined the contours of a public forum, and we
think this case fits in them,'' said Lynn Bregman of the Washington
law firm of Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering, who is serving as counsel
for the plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Coenen, a professor specializing in constitutional law at
the University of Georgia, agreed that the question of
discrimination against a certain viewpoint was crucial to such a
case. Coenen cited a 1974 Supreme Court decision, Lehman vs. Shaker
Heights, in which the Justices ruled, 5-4, that a municipal bus
system could decline to run political advertisements only if it
prohibited all such advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of precedent is a contentious one.
</P>
<P>
   MARTA's chief counsel, Mike Sloan, said the suit's arguments
could be countered by a 1998 decision of the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the Ninth Circuit. In that case, Children of the Rosary vs.
City of Phoenix, retired Supreme Court Justice Byron R. White,
sitting by special designation and writing for the appeals court,
said that the city's bus advertising panels were not necessarily a
public forum and that the city had an interest in maintaining
neutrality on contentious political and religious issues and in
preserving an environment attractive to commercial advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to carrying warnings on the dangers of HIV and
gambling, MARTA runs advertisements for the Atlanta Care Center, an
agency listed in the phone book under ``Abortion Alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pregnant? Worried? We Care,'' these advertisements say, and
offer a phone number for those interested in pregnancy testing or
counseling. The center, which promotes adoptions as an alternative
to abortion, is financed mainly by an interdenominational coalition
of churches.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan acknowledges that the center is anti-abortion but says
that its advertising campaign offers a service _ counseling _ and
that the National Abortion Federation's advertisements are of a
more political nature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
