<HEADER>
A8569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-HOMES-REAL-730&AMP;     05-15 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HOMES-REAL-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-TIME `CUSTOMS,' NOT COOKIE-CUTTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MORRIS NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHINO HILLS, Calif. _ The home-buying experience of Kevin and
Danniele Flora in this community 35 miles east of downtown Los
Angeles may be a bellwether of current trends in home building,
especially in the first-time home-buyer market.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Flora, 30, is an account executive for a computer company,
and his wife, 28, is an account executive for a clothing
manufacturer. In August 1998 they committed to buying a house,
their first, in Ridgeview, a subdivision of more-or-less
conventional single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
   What was unconventional was the degree of control that the young
home buyers exercised over the design of the house and such things
as types of floors and fixtures, which in new construction is
usually given only to buyers of more-expensive move-up housing. The
Floras paid about $230,990 for a house with 2,141 square feet of
space.
</P>
<P>
   Before the house was built, the couple selected one of about a
dozen floor plans, with an extra-large kitchen and master bedroom,
all included in the basic package priced at $220,990. But because
the Floras opted for such things as a brick-and-vinyl facade and
special bathroom fixtures not included in the options, they had to
pay an extra $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Floras were even encouraged to visit the home under
construction, and were given a camera to document its progress by
the home builder, Kaufman &AMP; Broad Greater Los Angeles Division, a
unit of Kaufman &AMP; Broad Home Corp., both based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We added our own touches,'' said Kevin Flora. ``It felt almost
like a total custom home.'' The couple moved into the house last
November.
</P>
<P>
   The Floras' experience in buying a home in the Ridgeview
development exemplifies the strategy Kaufman &AMP; Broad has been
pursuing in the last four years to maintain a hold on the
first-time-buyer market.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy is driven, in large part, by consumer-preference
surveys, conducted among buyers of both new and used homes in each
of the company's 16 market areas. Such surveys are common in many
industries, but not in home building, according to Bruce Karatz,
the company's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   While the company builds homes in several price ranges, Kaufman
&AMP; Broad is particularly interested in following the tastes of the
youngest segment of buyers aged 24 to 34, which it calls ``baby
zoomers.'' The name hints at the professional ambition,
fast-growing income and high material expectations of many people
in that age group.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys found a desire for greater choice among first-time
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   With the current strong economy and low unemployment ``people
don't feel boxed in, they have lots of choices,'' Karatz explained.
</P>
<P>
   Home buyers ``want it their way,'' added Jeffrey Charney, the
company's senior vice president of marketing. ``They don't want a
cookie-cutter house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys also showed that many buyers value practicality over
display, according to Glen Barnard, a senior vice president who is
regional general manager of the company's Denver office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation may be less interested in glitz and more
interested in functionality,'' he said. The current generation, he
added, are ``more utilitarian than other generations.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend corresponds to a ``back-to-the-basics'' theme in both
car design and volume-discount retailing, according to Barnard.
</P>
<P>
   One response to the desire for choice was to offer up to 12
floor plans, each of which allows further permutations. Previously,
Kaufman &AMP; Broad offered two or three floor plans.
</P>
<P>
   Some buyers opt for nontraditional features not often found in
tract housing, such as media centers, sleeping lofts, Jacuzzi
bathtubs, or kitchen islands.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the surveys revealed that buyers in the 24-to-34 age
group were interested in buying enough space for growing families,
and something more luxurious than the traditional image of a
starter home.
</P>
<P>
   The most sought-after amenity, it turned out, was size,
according to Barnard. ``In every market that we have surveyed, the
single most important factor, beyond just being able to buy a
house, is getting the most square footage for the money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That trend, he observed, is a ``reversal from the '80s, when
people wanted upscale amenities,'' such as cathedral ceilings, bay
windows, marble-floor entries, chandeliers and other symbols of
affluence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Maximizing space was a deciding factor for Benjamin Jackson, 30,
an emergency-response social worker, and his 30-year-old wife,
Charlotte, a tax auditor for the state of California.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jacksons, who have two children, had originally
looked at existing houses near their place of work in neighboring
Orange County, ``I was looking for as much space as I could
possibly get for the money,'' said Jackson, who said he liked to
retreat to ``a little corner of the house'' after stressful days at
work. ``This space allows me to do that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The three most important places to add space in developments
like Ridgeview with larger than usual starter homes, according to
Barnard, are kitchens, master bedrooms and storage areas,
particularly closets.
</P>
<P>
   Often home buyers are willing to ``trade off'' or live without
other home features to maximize the size of those amenities,
Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, buyers are often willing to accept smaller garages
or fewer bathrooms. They will settle for smaller living rooms, or
for consolidating the dining room and living room into a single
``great room.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyers also have a choice of facades. ``If somebody is an
achiever and wants his or her house to make a statement, we've got
the elevation that allows them to do that,'' Barnard said. On the
other hand, he added, if people with ``inner-directed values and
lifestyle prefer that a house does not make a statement, we've got
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the surveys, Kaufman &AMP; Broad executives sensed that
current home buyers were often experienced consumers and wanted to
make home buying more of what Karatz calls ``a retail experience.''
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize that ``retail experience,'' Kaufman &AMP; Broad has
created large showrooms, sometimes as large as 20,000 square feet,
in most of its major markets, where prospective home buyers can
select fixtures, paint colors and such things as carpets, tile,
cabinet styles, bathtubs and fireplaces for their future houses.
</P>
<P>
   The showrooms are intended to make home buying into something
more like shopping, to make buyers feel more comfortable, more ``in
control'' during the often intimidating process of making a
six-figure purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take the mystery and anxiety out the home
purchase,'' Karatz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Floras, for example, opted for a carpet with extra padding
to extend the life of the carpet, as well as tile, ceiling fans,
his-and-her bathroom sinks and windows for the garage door.
</P>
<P>
   For Karatz, the good reception of Kaufman &AMP; Broad's recent
developments may augur some changes for the home-building industry
away from the cookie-cutter sameness that has typified American
home building since Levittown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the assembly line,'' he said. ``We are going to
build 22,000 homes this year, one at a time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
