<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NUKE-WASTE-ART-2TA     05-15 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NUKE-WASTE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAIN FUTURE FOR NUCLEAR PLANT SHORT ON WASTE-STORAGE SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHANAN, N.Y. _ All the fuel that the Indian Point 2 nuclear
reactor has ever used since its first chain reaction 26 years ago
is here at the bottom of a 40-foot-deep pool about the size of a
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Plant engineers say the pool, its water made to appear a
Ty-D-Bol blue by the boron that smothers further nuclear reactions,
is very safe and very clean. But it is also nearly full. Within a
few years, the plant will run out of space to store the radioactive
waste.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the spent fuel and the plant itself is very much
up in the air, caught in a tangle of questions about the economics
of nuclear power, the deregulation of the energy industry and the
environmental safety of nuclear waste disposal. And the uncertainty
has left some neighbors of the plant, 35 miles north of Manhattan,
deeply uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and others who have long opposed the plant
would like nothing more than to see it shut down forever. But under
one possible outcome, they could end up living next to both an
operating nuclear reactor and a nuclear waste storage site. (A
near-twin of the reactor, Indian Point 3, is operated by the New
York Power Authority. But it is younger and has a bigger pool for
spent fuel, so it faces no immediate crisis.)
</P>
<P>
   The plant's owner, Consolidated Edison, says it would like to
send the spent fuel more than 2,000 miles west to a proposed
storage site near Salt Lake City, but that plan has run into fierce
opposition in Utah. The alternative is to keep the spent fuel at
the plant here, encasing it in giant sealed containers made of
steel and concrete, a process known as dry-cask storage.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the picture is the possibility that Con Ed
may not be allowed to own Indian Point 2 much longer. Under state
energy deregulation rules, the utility has already sold most of its
non-nuclear generating plants, and it is awaiting a decision from
state regulators on whether it will have to sell the reactor here,
too.
</P>
<P>
   If Con Ed keeps Indian Point 2, it could apply for permission to
extend the plant's operating license and to build dry-storage casks
for its spent nuclear fuel. That would require public hearings and
approval from the state's Public Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   If a private company bought the plant, it would probably have
fewer hurdles to clear to keep the reactor going. And some of
Indian Point 2's neighbors, realizing that the plant could keep
running for decades with even more radioactive fuel kept at the
site, find this possibility extremely disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't think we should do on-site cask storage in
order to allow it to continue to operate,'' said Mark Jacobs,
director of the Westchester People's Action Coalition, a nonprofit
group that opposes Indian Point 2. ``It should be very clear if we
do not know what to do with the nuclear waste, we should stop
producing it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the salad days of nuclear power, the 1960s, the federal
government had grand plans for the nation's spent nuclear fuel. A
commercial plant, the first of several planned, was built near
Buffalo to reprocess uranium and plutonium for reuse in reactors.
But virgin uranium turned out to be cheaper, and President Jimmy
Carter, concerned that the spent fuel could be turned into nuclear
weapons, banned the process.
</P>
<P>
   Then the government promised that by 1998, it would have a place
to bury the waste permanently. But now, the Energy Department is
saying that site will not be ready for at least 11 years. So scores
of nuclear plants around the country will soon find that they, too,
have run out of room to store spent fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Several plants have already put their fuel into dry-cask
storage. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission routinely approves such
a step, but state public utility commissions can veto cask
construction if they think the expenditure is unwise.
</P>
<P>
   And opponents of nuclear power have used political pressure to
prevent dry-storage casks from being built at some sites, hoping
that this pressure will force the plants to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   But then deregulation came to the energy industry. New York and
about a dozen other states are encouraging private companies to
provide electricity, hoping that the competition will mean lower
prices for consumers. Those states are either forcing utilities to
sell their generating plants or are considering doing so. Nuclear
plants are not the easiest properties to sell. But while it costs
more to generate nuclear power than it does to generate electricity
from water, gas or coal, a private company that can buy a reactor
cheaply enough can still be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Point 2 could flourish in a deregulated market, said Neil
Carns, senior vice president for nuclear operations at Con Ed. He
said he could foresee keeping the plant open 20 years beyond 2013,
when its current license expires.
</P>
<P>
   But to keep the plant running, Indian Point 2 needs more storage
space for spent fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a major point of vulnerability for Con Ed,''
said Edward Smeloff, executive director of the Energy Project at
Pace University Law School in White Plains, ``if they have no place
to take the fuel and they have significant local opposition to
siting a dry-storage facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts, including Smeloff, say dry storage can be safer
than storage in pools, because fuel can corrode in water and pools
can leak. Smeloff was the head of the Sacramento Municipal Utility
District in California when its reactor was shut down, and he
supervised the construction of such casks.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists favor storing spent nuclear fuel on
reactor sites because shipping the waste creates even more hazards,
they say. And many environmentalists are opposed to an agreement
Con Ed and other utilities signed with the Goshute Indians to rent
storage space on their reservation west of Salt Lake City, calling
it environmental racism. In any case, the Utah deal may never come
to pass because of opposition from officials there.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Con Ed signed a contract with the Energy Department,
which promised to begin accepting fuel for burial by 1998 in
exchange for payment of a 1/10 of a cent per kilowatt-hour that
Indian Point generated over its lifetime. Con Ed has paid $117.5
million, but the Energy Department has not yet determined whether
the site, Yucca Mountain near Las Vegas, is suitable, and now says
that it will not be ready until 2010 at the earliest. Con Ed has
sued to be relieved of future payments, and a resolution is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the fuel stays in this village of about 2,000 people
on the east bank of the Hudson River. The pool has 1,374 holes for
storing the spent nuclear assemblies vertically, and 917 are
filled, making the grid look like a giant game of tic-tack-toe that
is coming to an end. By 2005, Con Ed will have to move some of the
assemblies out or close the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no choice but to bet on every horse in the race,''
said John Sanchez, the project manager for high-level waste at Con
Ed.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone likes all the horses. ``We don't want these big
concrete things,'' said Susan Tolchin, a spokeswoman for
Westchester County Executive Andrew Spano. ``We want it out of
there; that's the bottom line. We don't want the construction of
these things to hold this nuclear waste.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear, though, what leverage the county has. Con Ed
would need a permit from the village of Buchanan to build
dry-storage casks, and the village has made it clear that its main
concern is to keep its jobs and its tax base steady.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester County would like that, too, said Martin Rogowski,
chairman of the county's Public Utility Service Agency. But
Rogowski, who formerly worked at the Energy Department on nuclear
waste problems, expressed some uneasiness about the dry-storage
idea. ``You never know. How good are these casks?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Rasmussen, Con Ed's assistant controller, said building
enough dry casks to make space in the pool for an additional
two-year fueling cycle would cost about $3 million, an increase of
about 2 percent in the plant's operating and capital expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the fuel sits in a room certified as safe from
earthquakes and hurricanes. The water is a steady 97 degrees,
warmed by the radioactive decay and cooled by a whining set of
pumps. A white bathtub ring has built up from the boron. Bubbles,
created for the most part by air pulled in by the cooling pumps,
wobble their way to the surface occasionally. The radiation levels
on the walkway surrounding the pool are minuscule, the utility
says.
</P>
<P>
   Four times a day, a technician checks the pool for changes, but
there are rarely any, said Denis Cornax, a watch engineer. Every
few days, a worker checks the water chemistry to insure that there
are no chlorides or other rust-inducing chemicals present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cleaner water than you have in your house,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
