<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-2TA     05-15 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY'S PERKS MAY BE PITFALLS IN RACE FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent Friday morning, an Air Force jet carrying Hillary
Rodham Clinton left Andrews Air Force Base for Buffalo, N.Y., where
a motorcade assembled by the Secret Service took her to a
fund-raiser for a Democratic congressman. From there, it was on to
an AFL-CIO forum jammed with cheering women, where Mrs. Clinton
spent an hour discussing the Democratic issues with which she has
identified herself in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone considering a run for senator from New York, a
category that includes Mrs. Clinton, it could not have been a
better day. The first lady lent her name to the state Democratic
Party and to a powerful labor union. In a room packed with
television cameras, she addressed an audience of potentially
crucial voters _ women _ about the very issues that she is likely
to embrace should she run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And best of all, it did not cost Mrs. Clinton a dime.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the trip was paid for by taxpayers because, Mrs.
Clinton's aides said, the AFL-CIO forum was an official first lady
event, no matter what political benefits it might have provided.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone needed evidence of the advantages that will accrue to
Mrs. Clinton if she runs for Senate, there was no better place to
look than Buffalo during her recent visit, one of eight the first
lady has paid to New York this year. Her position as first lady is
one of many reasons Democrats are so enthused at the prospect of a
Clinton candidacy. They are increasingly convinced that she will
run, and expect her to signal her decision when she returns from a
family vacation in Florida in early June.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mrs. Clinton's advisers contemplate the unprecedented
event of a sitting first lady running for office, they are
beginning to realize that there are pitfalls as well as advantages
inherent in Mrs. Clinton's status.
</P>
<P>
   From the daily encumbrances of her security, to the conflicts
with her duties as first lady, to the vexing logistics of trying to
run for office 300 miles from the white house she calls home, Mrs.
Clinton's biggest electoral asset could very well throw more than a
few wrenches into any attempt at embarking on this new career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that she is Hillary Clinton is her biggest
advantage,'' said Hank Sheinkopf, a Democratic consultant based in
New York. ``And the fact that she is Hillary Clinton is her biggest
disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits are certainly considerable, and not all of them are
immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Most obvious, the government will pay for a lot of her travel to
New York, and the bills are substantial. It costs $836 an hour to
operate one of the C-9s Mrs. Clinton tends to fly, in addition to
the costs of the motorcade and hotel rooms. Mrs. Clinton travels
with a trip director, an issues adviser, a White House photographer
and a press secretary, all of whom are on the White House payroll
and whose travel expenses are also covered.
</P>
<P>
   If she does makes any unambiguously political appearances, like
appearing at a congressional fund-raiser, then a percentage of the
travel costs, apart from security, are billed to the political
sponsor of the event. The rest, though, is paid by the White House,
at least until she declares her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton can also expect to benefit, in a less obvious way,
from the motorcades and Secret Service agents that shepherd her
around the state: The trappings of the White House provide an
immediate stature before she steps out of her car. And that Secret
Service, as Mrs. Clinton's husband well knows, can provide an
additional advantage _ a cordon that keeps a distance between her
and the reporters who may try to shout questions. Mrs. Clinton has
taken reporters' questions only once during her visits to New York.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, there is arguably a downside to nearly every one
of these benefits. Already, aides to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the
Republican who is also thinking about running for the Senate, are
questioning why taxpayers should pay for her visits to New York.
Giuliani's aides said the mayor would make an issue of Mrs.
Clinton's reliance on federal money.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's campaign finance chairman, John Gross, strongly
suggested that the Giuliani campaign would push Mrs. Clinton to
reimburse the cost of her travel so far, should she enter the race.
``Given the fact that she's testing the waters, an argument could
be made that her trip to Buffalo, and for that matter all her trips
to New York, should eventually be charged to her campaign,'' Gross
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her trips are beginning to draw criticism from nonpartisan
quarters as well. Charles Lewis, the executive director of the
Center for Public Integrity, a watchdog group, said that if Mrs.
Clinton entered the race, her trips to date would clearly cross the
line between a first lady's duties and a candidate's campaigning,
and would raise questions about reimbursements. ``The issue is, how
much is it costing the taxpayer for this person to seek office?''
Lewis said. ``And should the taxpayer be paying for that?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's advisers have responded to this criticism by
saying that she has not declared that she is running for office,
and thus does not have an exploratory committee in place that would
permit her to raise money to reimburse the government. (Under
federal policy, she would have to pay the government first-class
air fare for her seat on the C-9 to New York for trips that were
deemed political; her staff would be charged coach rates.)
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not a candidate,'' said Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's
spokeswoman. Referring to Mrs. Clinton's events in New York, Ms.
Berry said. ``If you look back at what she has done as first lady,
this is exactly what she does.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel, a Harlem Democrat who is one of Mrs.
Clinton's biggest supporters, said the first lady was doing nothing
different from what incumbent politicians have done in running for
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long a member of Congress can go without
paying for trips,'' Rangel said. ``I don't know how long a mayor
can go without paying for trips. I don't know how long a vice
president can go without paying for trips.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides said his upstate travel was paid for by his
political committees. And the fact that Mrs. Clinton has moved up
the date by which she intends to signal her intentions, from late
summer to June, suggests concern about such questions.
</P>
<P>
   The logistic difficulties of a campaign by someone of Mrs.
Clinton's stature were described by many New York Democrats as
daunting, though not insurmountable. In last year's New York race
for the Senate, for example, advisers to Charles Schumer, the
Democratic winner, typically did not decide how Schumer would spend
his next day _ from what he would say to where he would go _ until
the very last minute, to accommodate the changing demands of a
fast-moving campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a problem for Mrs. Clinton. Secret Service agents
arrive at least a day before the first lady to inspect places she
plans to visit, and they seal off the site before she arrives.
There is no such thing as hopping into a car or a plane for a quick
news conference on the issue of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big state, with a lot of territory to cover,''
Sheinkopf said. ``You can't get away without going to Utica. You
have got to go to Buffalo. Moving her around _ with all the
problems that a first lady has to worry about _can be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be an additional complication because one of the
things Mrs. Clinton needs to do in the months ahead, her advisers
say, is get a feel for both New York, where she has never lived,
and civilian life outside the White House. ``Has she ever been to a
movie in New York?'' one Democrat asked, outlining the kind of
real-life tutorial she should ideally undergo before meeting
voters. ``Has she ever bought a loaf of bread in New York? Has she
ever walked down a street? That's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The press office of the Secret Service did not return calls
seeking comment on a potential Clinton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is likely to take an apartment in New York City to
establish a presence, not to mention a residence, her advisers
said. But she remains first lady through the end of 2000, and will
be under pressure to return to the White House to tend to duties
like state dinners. Mrs. Clinton's advisers are contemplating the
fact that she could come under attack in other parts of the country
if there is a perception that she is neglecting the White House for
her own political pursuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
