<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CLEVER GENE SARAZEN'S CENTURY OF PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the day Gene Sarazen died, Tiger Woods shot 61 in the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic. To anyone who remembered a conversation at
the 1996 Masters, it was as much a connection as a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Eldrick (Tiger) Woods was a two-time U.S. Amateur
champion, a 20-year-old golf phenom who would win another Amateur
title that summer and the Masters a year later. And after hitting a
ceremonial tee shot at that 1996 Masters, Sarazen, then 94 and
wearing his plus fours, was answering questions on the Augusta
National clubhouse porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering Tiger's age,'' somebody asked, ``how would you
rate him?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Sarazen said, ``when I was 20, I won the U.S. Open and
the PGA.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen wasn't bragging; he was just reminding his listeners
that golf has had other phenoms and he was one of them. It's called
perspective. And as someone who spanned the 20th century before
dying Thursday at 97 of complications of pneumonia, his perspective
on golf was unique.
</P>
<P>
   He will always be remembered for his double-eagle 2 with a
4-wood at the par-5 15th hole that put the Masters on the golf map
in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time in Hong Kong, someone introduced me as `Mr. Double
Eagle,''' he once said with a laugh. ``They must have thought I was
an Indian.''
</P>
<P>
   But the feisty little man born Eugenio Saraceni in Harrison,
N.Y., the son of an immigrant Italian carpenter, hit many other
important shots in winning seven major titles _ the 1922, 1923 and
1933 Professional Golfers' Association Championships, the 1922 and
1932 U.S. Opens, the 1932 British Open and that 1935 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first to win all four major titles; Ben Hogan, Jack
Nicklaus and Gary Player are the only others.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the best shot I ever hit,'' Sarazen once said, ``was in
the 1931 Ryder Cup at Scioto. On this short hole, I hooked my tee
shot over the green into a refreshment stand. I found my ball in
the middle of the stand in a crevice in the concrete. No free drops
back then, but a window toward the green was open. I played the
ball through the window and onto the green about eight feet from
the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen made his putt for a par. When his opponent, Fred Robson,
three-putted, Sarazen won the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robson laughed and said, `That was a nice throw,''' Sarazen
recalled. ``I said: `That was no throw. I played the shot out of
there.' He lost the next five holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarazen said golf was more cutthroat back in the 190s and '30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't tell anyone anything,'' he recalled. ``If the green
was fast, we hoped they wouldn't find out until it had cost them
some strokes. And the only thing we hoped about the other fellow
was he'd break both legs. That sort of spirit made golf.''
</P>
<P>
   His ingenuity made the sand wedge, which made golf a little
easier for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up with Howard Hughes in his airplane and he told me,
`Gene, pull back on that stick,''' Sarazen once said. ``And it
flashed into my mind that some weight on the back of a niblick
could make a club and a ball bounce out of the sand the same way
that plane bounced into the air.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone else, Sarazen could assess the century's best
golfers because he saw and played with all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even played with Harry Vardon,'' he once said, referring to
the six-time British Open winner of a century ago. ``It was at the
1923 North British at Royal Lytham and St. Annes. On the first
hole, a par 3, the wind was coming from the left. Vardon floated a
baffy in there about 10 feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a 1-iron, a low, boring ball that stayed left despite
the wind and wound up in a bunker. Walking off the tee I remember
saying, `I can't understand how the wind didn't take that ball,'
and I heard Vardon say, `The way you hit it, the wind had nothing
to do with it.' I took that as good advice.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1982 article for Golf Digest magazine, Sarazen, then 80,
rated the century's top 10 golfers, men and women:
</P>
<P>
   1. Jack Nicklaus; 2. Bobby Jones; 3. Ben Hogan; 4. Walter Hagen;
5. Harry Vardon; 6. Gary Player; 7. Sam Snead; 8. Arnold Palmer; 9.
Lee Trevino; 10. (tie) Byron Nelson and Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   1. Joyce Wethered; 2. Glenna Collett Vare; 3. Mickey Wright; 4.
Kathy Whitworth; 5. Betsy Rawls; 6. Louise Suggs; 7. Babe Didrikson
Zaharias; 8. JoAnne Carner; 9. Donna Caponi; 10. Patty Berg.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Sarazen wasn't sure if Nancy Lopez's swing would
hold up, but if he had selected a women's top 10 in recent years,
she would probably have been in it. The men's top 10 would probably
be unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   In judging golfers on longevity and the ability to win majors,
he called Nicklaus ``a far greater player'' than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever had Jack's power and his putting touch,'' Sarazen
said. ``And he's had to play in the major championships before the
TV cameras with the lead at stake. In the years long before
television, Jones usually teed off early and established a score
for everybody else to shoot at.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice that Gene Sarazen didn't rank himself, saying, ``My wife,
Mary, told me I can't.'' But privately, he confided, ``I'd be
somewhere around eighth, ninth or 10th.'' That's about the proper
perspective. After all, when he was 20, he won both the United
States Open and the PGA. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
