<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-EX-CRIP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY TARASCO'S AGENDA: GANG LIFE TO YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio _ Tony Tarasco is speaking so quickly and
expressively about his love of baseball, the lure of gangs and the
legend of Jeffrey Maier that he gags on his own cigarette smoke
just to continue talking. This happens three different times as he
drags on one Marlboro, but it would be foolish to interrupt.
Tarasco has too much to say.
</P>
<P>
   Rain is pelting the seats at the rickety minor league ball park
here, but Tarasco, an outfielder for the Class AAA Columbus
Clippers, does not care. He is too engrossed in a conversation that
he turns into a dialogue. For Tarasco, there is always something
intriguing to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Like how he belonged to the Santa Monica Graveyard Crips gang
while growing up in California. How he has honored the memory of
his slain best friend and fellow gang member with two tattoos on
his thick body. How he now can laugh at questions regarding Maier
robbing a fly ball from him and helping the New York Yankees swipe
a post-season game from the Orioles three years ago. How he has
been the premier hitter for the Yankees' top minor league affiliate
and could return to Yankee Stadium in a much more enviable capacity
than as Maier's foil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing well and I know someone is watching; if George
Steinbrenner calls me,'' Tarasco said of the Yankee owner, ``I'll
get the job done. I'm not going to tell you it's a lifelong dream
to play for the Yankees. I want a ring, I want to make some cash
and I want to have an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tarasco had uttered these words on March 26, when the Yankees
signed him as a minor league free agent, they would have sounded
ludicrous. At that time, the Yankees had Chad Curtis, Ricky Ledee
and Shane Spencer sparring in left field and a rehabilitating
Darryl Strawberry lurking as a possibility, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Strawberry was arrested on charges of cocaine possession and
solicitation of a prostitute, Spencer was sent to Columbus, Ledee
and Curtis sputtered in their auditions and Spencer and Ledee have
now traded places.
</P>
<P>
   Tarasco, the insurance policy, is hitting .364 with 7 home runs
and 25 runs batted in, and waiting patiently. Considering that he
almost retired two months ago, Tarasco's rapid ascension has
surprised even him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told God one night I was going to walk away if something
didn't happen,'' the 28-year-old Tarasco said. ``I said my prayers
and went to sleep. The next day my agent woke me and told me I had
a job with the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Tarasco is smiling, the wisp of black hair below his lower
lip getting wider. Tarasco, who was born in Manhattan and lived in
the Bronx until he was 7, said his father, Jack, was a vendor at
Yankee Stadium, so his new job was definitely a sign. ``I knew God
was telling me something by putting me with the Yankees,'' he said.
``He wasn't finished with me.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Brian Cashman said the Yankees ``jumped'' on
Tarasco, a .241 career hitter in the majors, after Kansas City
released him this spring. He can play three outfield positions, has
solid power, good speed, a decent arm and post-season experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very much aware of him because of his performance and
the way that he's gone about his business,'' Cashman said. ``I'm
not saying he's moved ahead of anybody on the depth chart, but he's
on the depth chart now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarasco's demeanor is an unusual mixture of bravado and
politeness. He will tell a visitor a story about how he once missed
a drive-by shooting at a fast-food restaurant because he was in the
bathroom in the same casual tone that he uses to discuss the
intricacies of his sturdy left-handed swing. He will tell you how
his neighborhood was on the cusp of South Central Los Angeles and
that this made it inevitable for a 13-year-old to join a gang, and
then he will elaborate on his passion for writing.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Tarasco the baseball player has separated himself
from the gang scene in Santa Monica, where he said six of his
friends were killed, he conceded that home is still home. Tarasco
is nicknamed ``Baby Jacc'' after his father. Tarasco spells it with
a c instead of a k because he said ``hood language'' does not allow
the k to be used in certain words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never a soldier in the gang,'' said Tarasco. ``Soldiers
do everything. I was into the hustle so I could make a few bucks
and dress nice for the girls. I was never into the raw dog, dirty
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   One glance at Tarasco's left forearm is all that it takes to
begin to understand the world where he has lived. Tarasco has a
tattoo he designed of a blue cartoon figure with baggy blue jeans
swinging a bat and bashing a baseball that bears a screaming face..
Home plate has C.P. and R.I.P. etched on it, in memory of Chris
Pickett, Tarasco's friend for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tarasco said Pickett was killed by a Los Angeles police officer
on March 23, 1992, when the officer thought that Pickett was a
robbery suspect. He died on the spot, one day after his 22d
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened around the time of the Rodney King trial,''
Tarasco said. ``It was an unlawful shooting. There were
investigations. I went home for the funeral, but I couldn't stay
when they delayed it for an autopsy. That dragged me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickett was one of the gang members who watched Tarasco play at
Santa Monica High School and told him to devote himself to baseball
instead of the Crips. Tarasco, who said he never committed a crime,
explained that his friends realized his talent might be wasted.
Forget about wearing the blue and quit the Crips, they told the
16-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So Tarasco did. He was drafted out of high school by the Braves
in the 15th round in 1988 and made it to the majors with them in
1993. He was traded to Montreal in 1995 and hit .249 with 14
homers, 40 runs batted in and 24 steals, the last time he spent a
full season in the majors. Baltimore obtained Tarasco in 1996,
which was mostly an injury-scarred season for him until that
fateful Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   With the Orioles leading the Yankees, 4-3, in the eighth inning
of the first game of the American League Championship Series,
Tarasco replaced Bobby Bonilla in right field in what was his third
appearance in five months. When Derek Jeter clubbed a high shot to
right, the 6-foot-1-inch, 205-pound Tarasco was poised to catch it
until the 12-year-old Maier leaned over the fence and helped pull
the ball into the seats. Umpire Richie Garcia ruled it a home run
instead of interference and Maier was lionized by the news media
after the Yankees won, 5-4. Tarasco never had nightmares about the
overzealous Maier.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to find me in a mental home with posters of
Jeffery Maier on the wall,'' said Tarasco. ``When I signed with the
Yankees, someone asked me why I did and I told them so that if
anyone wants to lean over and take the ball from me again, then
they'll land in the Hudson River. Had it been the other way around
and O'Neill was in right, they would have hated that kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarasco, who refused numerous invitations to appear with Maier
after the wacky play, called it ``destiny'' for the Yankees and
claimed that the notoriety has enabled him to secure tables in New
York restaurants without reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing I could have done differently,'' Tarasco
said. ``If I knew the kid was going to interfere, I would've
climbed the fence, grabbed him and then caught it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was almost time for the Class AAA game and Tarasco was
finishing up, actually saying that he is not obsessed with being
called up by the Yankees. He was briefly silenced when asked how he
would feel if he continues to produce snazzy statistics but remains
mired in the minors in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too far ahead,'' Tarasco finally said. ``You don't know
what might go bad for you and you don't know what might go good for
you. I just make myself ready and, when that door cracks open a
little, I jump through it. I'll be through and I'm not looking
back.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIEGOING-REAL-NYT &LR;      05-15 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIEGOING-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN BUILDS 24-SEAT THEATER IN HIS MANSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Conn., N.J., N.Y., Ohio) (rk) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's too bad that Charles S. Cohen has to go to work. Or
anywhere, for that matter. Because underneath his 16-room mansion
in Greenwich, Conn., he has built a movie theater so evocative of
the past, with its plush red velvet seats and ornate moldings, that
emerging into the daylight, even on a spectacular spring day, is
annoying. Who wants to go out into the real world when the fantasy
has been so perfectly realized?
</P>
<P>
   Movie theaters may not be popping up in every
multimillion-dollar house, but for people who have at least
$100,000 to spend on the technology, an approximation of quality
moviegoing can be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cohen's movie theater was constructed several years ago
from a design by Theo Kalomirakis, he wants it to have the best
available video images, and so a few weeks ago he upgraded the
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the videotape images in his theater are clearer, brighter
and more like film, which has a three-dimensional quality that
video doesn't quite match.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the match is close enough for an ordinary movie fan, and
the surroundings are familiar even if they were never experienced
in such a perfect, pristine form. The 24-seat theater was modeled
on the old Paramount in Times Square, and the brass handles on the
doors were taken from the original before its demolition. A
chandelier is from the old Centrum Theater in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a scene from ``A Bug's Life,'' it's easy to forget this
is a home. It feels like a glorious theater in a very rich city
where moments of rapture or pain or fun cannot be destroyed by
someone talking, chewing gum, cracking their knuckles, kicking the
back of the seat, answering a cell phone, or doing any of those
other annoying things that humans insist on doing.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cohen is now president of his family's commercial real
estate business in Manhattan, Cohen Brothers Realty Corp., he
originally wanted to be a movie director, and as a student at Tufts
University he made a short film satirizing Bruce Lee that was shown
on a cable channel. But while his passion for movies is reflected
in the theater, it doesn't sound as if the life of a real estate
magnate leaves a lot of time for hanging out in the home theater.
</P>
<P>
   His subterranean palace is used most often when his two
children, who are 10 and 14, stay with him on the weekends when
they are not with their mother in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the lobby of the theater has bowls filled with candy
and a microwave for instant popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy of a ``real'' theater is sustained at every turn,
with icons meant to seduce.
</P>
<P>
   On descending the stairs into the space, built 30 feet
underground, the first sight is of a female ticket taker, a cloth
creation named Edna who sits in a glass booth. On the wall are some
of the theater posters that Cohen has collected, from movies like
``Vertigo'' and ``Sands of Iwo Jima.''
</P>
<P>
   Posters from more obscure films hang on the walls of his game
room and gymnasium, movies like ``Bad for Each Other,'' ``Never
Steal Anything Small,'' ``How to Be Very Very Popular'' and ``Babes
in Baghdad.'' The posters were less expensive than those for the
better known films.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all not-great movies,'' Cohen says, ``because
not-great movie posters are not in demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The machines used to create the images on the 16-by-13-foot
screen are stacked in towers in a small room behind the theater.
Cohen's consultant, Eric Eidelman of Audio Video Interiors in
Hillsdale, N.J., recently installed new equipment to improve the
quality, including a Sony VPHG90 video projector that is compatible
with high definition television, and a Faroudja Labs VP400A line
quadrupler, which enhances the picture by getting rid of the scan
lines that indicate video rather than film is being shown.
</P>
<P>
   Eidelman, who develops home theaters all over the country, but
especially in places like Aspen, Colo., and Los Angeles, says that
some home theaters can be put together with $50,000 worth of
equipment but that getting the newest and best technology usually
leads to a bill two or three times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   People like Cohen, he says, are aware of changes that can
produce a better image, and so they usually need to upgrade every
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, in the mansion he built with his wife shortly before
they split up, Cohen has other temptations that compete with the
theater, like a tennis court and a swimming pool. It's the first
house he has built, but he designed it to be his dream house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have everything here,'' he says, ``that I could
want to do.''(BBOX) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
