<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RED-WINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS ARE LOOKING TO THEIR STOPPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Before Chris Osgood and the Red Wings flew to Denver
for Sunday's playoff game, the injured goalie practiced with his
troubled team, genuflecting repeatedly on his tender right knee
like a reverent man in church. Up and down went Osgood, bouncing
the padded knee off the ice, flexing it as he kicked at pucks.
</P>
<P>
   Directly behind his net, on the boards below the rink glass in
Joe Louis Arena, a blue and white advertisement for a health-care
company showed big crosses and shields. Should Osgood return to
uniform, Detroit feels it might again have net protection after
yielding 11 goals in its last two games. Without him, they are
merely the Wings and a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood is recovering from a serious sprain that kept him out of
the first four games against the Colorado Avalanche in the Western
Conference semifinals of the Stanley Cup playoffs. The Wings,
seeking their third consecutive cup, won the first two in Denver
behind backup Bill Ranford, who was described by coach Scotty
Bowman as an insurance policy. But Ranford faltered badly and had
to be pulled from the next two, both Colorado victories in Detroit
that tied the second round of the four-of-seven games series. The
third-stringer Norm Maracle replaced Ranford both times.
</P>
<P>
   If Osgood's knee feels strong enough Sunday, he will be back in
goal for Game 5. Should he be unable to play _ or fail to play well
after 19 days of idleness _ the Wing dynasty could end at two as
soon as Tuesday in Game 6 in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better now,'' Osgood said. ``I was down. I was frustrated.
I thought I was going to miss the entire series. Right now, I don't
know. I'm optimistic. I'm not sure. Every day I feel better. I
probably won't know until Sunday. It's an on and off thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole series has been that way. The official hype has this
as ``the best rivalry in sports'' in the 1990s, but this round has
not yet risen to the level of passion of 1996, when the Avalanche
eliminated the Wings en route to the cup, or of 1997, when Detroit
eliminated Colorado on its way to the title. True, there have been
some good individual performances by players such as Detroit center
Steve Yzerman and Colorado goalie Patrick Roy. And there have been
several bloody faces, including a 40-stitch cut to Detroit's
Brendan Shanahan when Peter Forsberg rammed him into the glass from
behind. That foul got Forsberg ejected from Game 1, a 3-2 Wings
victory in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But that game was ragged and the next three were one-sided, with
the losing team playing poorly. Hockey fans not aligned behind
either team are hoping both clubs will play well at the same time
to create the classic series they envisioned. As for the partisans,
the pessimism of Colorado fans and news media has been transformed
to a ``pinch-me'' sort of glee while the smugness of the Detroit
fans and journalists has been shaken by tremors of doubt. Some fans
booed the team and left Joe Louis early Thursday night. Even Osgood
found it hard to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't watch much after we were down 5-0,'' Osgood said of
Thursday's game, a 6-2 Avalanche victory. ``Pretty painful to sit
in the back and watch that. We were so hopeful when we came home
2-0. In a matter of four days, things turned around the exact
opposite. Things weren't working out. Frustrating things just
seemed to pile up, one thing after another.''
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that Osgood is being cast as the savior. Last
spring, he was less than Detroit's best player when he gave up
several goals on long shots. Some thought the Wings won despite
him. Now, they hope he will lift their spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you lose two games in the fashion we lost them, you
hope to be one of the guys who gives the team a boost and maybe
energizes them,'' Osgood said. ``But I don't really overestimate
the power of one or two players changing around a whole series. I
don't necessarily think I'll be the total difference. I know if I
do play, I'll be ready and give the team a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Detroit's ennui extends beyond the goal posts. Veterans
Chris Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson and Wendel Clark, who arrived along
with Ranford at the trade deadline, have played ineffectively in
the last two games and may be weary. Obtained from Chicago, the
Rangers and Tampa Bay, they are not accustomed to playing this late
in recent springs.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman, whose wife gave birth to a daughter Friday, played his
worst game of the tournament Thursday, losing a key face-off, then
throwing himself out of position before Colorado's first goal. He
finished with a minus-two in the plus/minus ratio and scored no
points.
</P>
<P>
   The trades at the deadline, which cost Detroit several future
draft choices, helped the Wings spurt to a strong finish. But now,
they again look like the lethargic bunch that settled for
inconsistency and mediocrity for most of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   No National Hockey League team has won three consecutive cups
since the New York Islanders won four from 1980 through 1983. The
six-month regular season, followed by a two-month tournament, makes
it difficult for a team to maintain the health and the intensity
necessary to prevail. Physically and psychologically, the Wings are
teetering, knees buckling. In Game 5, they could be as good as
Osgood. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
