<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: OPTIONS TO BE CONSIDERED BEFORE HOLDING TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a married couple buy a house or apartment, the
couple usually take title in the name of both spouses. And since
most houses and apartments are purchased with at least some
borrowed money, that means that in most cases, both spouses assume
equal responsibility for repaying the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   But while shared ownership may contribute to matrimonial
harmony, lawyers say, it may not always be the smartest way to own
real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many times you'll see a husband and wife buy
a piece of property and sign both their names to a 30-year mortgage
without really thinking about what they're doing,'' said David
Clurman, a Manhattan real estate lawyer. ``And I don't think a lot
of lawyers give the subject a lot of thought either.''
</P>
<P>
   Clurman explained that as property values have increased over
the years _ particularly in the metropolitan area and even more
particularly in Manhattan _ it has become increasingly important
for those buying property to consider carefully the impact that
real estate can have on estate planning.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual these days for a couple who own a home or an
apartment to have a combined estate that exceeds $650,000 _ the
point at which an individual's estate becomes subject to federal
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, in our increasingly litigious society, it has
become more important than ever for people who may have exposure to
liability _ particularly professionals and those engaged in
unincorporated business enterprises _ to think long and hard about
the implications of having their name on a deed, mortgage or
promissory note.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very common for people who are buying property to go to a
bank or a mortgage broker and sign loan applications before they've
even made an appointment with their lawyer,'' Clurman said. ``And
sometimes decisions that are made on the spur of the moment can
reverberate with great pain many years in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Kravet, president of Royal Abstract, a title insurance
agency in Manhattan, said that there are various ways in which
title to real estate can be held. A person can hold title
individually, for example, either in the person's own name or in
the name of a corporation or other legal entity owned by that
person.
</P>
<P>
   Title to property can also be held ``personally'' by more than
one individual, Kravet said. Two or more individuals, he said, can
take title as ``tenants in common,'' as ``joint tenants with rights
of survivorship,'' or as ``tenants by the entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   With a tenancy in common, he said, each owner's interest in the
property passes on death to that person's heirs or beneficiaries.
With a joint tenancy with rights of survivorship, on the other
hand, each owner's interest passes automatically on death to the
surviving owner or owners.
</P>
<P>
   A tenancy by the entirety, Kravet said, is a form of joint
tenancy available only to married couples. However, he said, unlike
a joint tenancy with rights of survivorship, which can be converted
to a tenancy in common by any owner selling his or her interest to
a third party, a tenancy by the entirety will remain so for as long
as the joint tenants remain married.
</P>
<P>
   Only divorce or the mutual agreement of the parties can convert
a tenancy by the entirety to a tenancy in common, Kravet said.
</P>
<P>
   And while most married couples take title to a home or apartment
as tenants by the entirety, there are often situations in which
that may not be the wisest thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We frequently recommend that professionals put property in the
name of a nonworking spouse or the spouse with the least exposure
to liability,'' said Martin L. Lepelstat, a real estate lawyer in
Woodbridge, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle encountered when trying to put property in the name
of a nonworking spouse is getting a lender to lend money to someone
with little or no ability to repay it. That can be accomplished by
persuading the lender to let the income-producing spouse guarantee
payment but not require that person to be included on the deed and
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be up front with the lender and you have to get to
someone who can make these kinds of decisions,'' Lepelstat said.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason married couples might want to take title to real
estate in individual names or as tenants in common would be to
minimize, or even eliminate, federal estate taxes on their combined
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Joel E. Miller, a Queens tax lawyer, said that it is almost
always possible for married taxpayers to avoid paying such taxes on
the death of the first spouse. Real estate owned jointly by spouses
is not subject to estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Any other property owned by the first spouse to die can also be
shielded from taxes by making sure that it is all left to the
surviving spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving everything to the surviving spouse, however, can
ultimately result in the payment of taxes unnecessarily because the
strategy frequently fails to take full advantage of both spouses'
unified credit.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Miller said, the unified credit exempts the first
$650,000 of an individual's estate from federal gift and estate
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the basic goals of estate planning is to avoid wasting
either spouse's unified credit,'' he said, explaining that is just
what happens when the first spouse to die leaves everything to the
surviving spouse.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Miller said, if a married couple own a $1 million
house as tenants by the entirety, and one spouse dies, the
surviving spouse automatically becomes the sole owner and no estate
tax is due. When the second spouse dies, however, and the house
then passes to the couple's children, only $650,000 is exempt from
taxes as a result of the unified credit; the remaining $350,000 is
subject to federal estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Miller said, if the same $1 million house
were owned by the couple as tenants in common, the first spouse to
die could bequeath his or her interest in the property to what is
known as a credit shelter trust. Such a trust can be designed to
allow the surviving spouse to remain in possession of the property
until death, at which time the property passes to beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Since the value of the property placed in trust _ $500,000, the
deceased partner's half share of the home's $1 million value _ is
less than the $650,000 unified credit, no tax is imposed on that
transfer. And since the surviving spouse is also entitled to a
$650,000 unified credit, that much of his or her estate will be
exempt from taxes as well.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Miller said, a couple who successfully combine both
unified credits can pass to beneficiaries up to $1.3 million in
assets without paying any federal estate taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
