u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BRADLEY     05-15 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHEN WILL BRADLEY ENTER THE CHARISMA PHASE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was somewhere near the New Hampshire seacoast that Bill
Bradley declined to tell reporters what books he likes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go down the road of favorite novel,'' he said,
during a three-day campaign tour of youth centers, senior centers
and many variations on the theme of the presidential-candidate
forum. There was a credibility issue at stake here. What, he
demanded, would the press say if he picked one book now and then
changed his mind six months down the line? And what if he mentioned
something like ``Crime and Punishment''? The reporters might
theorize that he was identifying with the murderer-hero. No, we're
not going there.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, you see, is in the Vision Phase of his campaign, and,
as he firmly explained earlier in the New Hampshire tour, you do
not talk specifics when you are in Vision Mode. ``It's discipline
and sequencing,'' he said, in a tone that suggested the reporters
would really not respect him in the morning if he lathered them
with details of his health-care initiative that night. Sometime
this summer, he plans to kick into the Principles Phase, to be
followed in the fall by the Policy Phase, when he will be prepared
for ``taking the necessary hits you get when you are specific.''
After that comes the Action Phase, in which the candidate responds
to the hits and, presumably, comes back with a few good licks of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley staff swears he did not pay a consultant to think
this up.
</P>
<P>
   It may be an indication of the Bradley campaign's
self-confidence that it does not seem particularly desperate for
attention at this point in the game. Unlike most long-shot
candidates, Bradley does not accept invitations to appear on cable
television shows. He resists photographers' attempts to get him
near a basketball or a hoop. He is a serious candidate, and if you
do not believe it, just try listening to him tell a group of
Manchester citizens his opinion on the Uruguay round of the
international trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it all seems to be working pretty well. The voters at
the forums, coffees and house parties appear to like the Vision
Phase, particularly Bradley's rather fuzzy but seemingly heartfelt
concern about ``values.'' His fund-raising pales next to Vice
President Al Gore's mountain of cash, but money can't buy you love.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore candidacy is so wobbly that President Clinton recently
assumed the role of Spinner in Chief. He said Gore's leaden
speeches and inert staff add up to inevitable victory.
</P>
<P>
   Follow Bradley around during Phase One and you will learn that
what he is most concerned with is children, particularly poor
children who do not get enough parental supervision. He has a vague
but intense preoccupation with getting people to think of
themselves as part of a larger community, a greater cause. The
rhetoric of self-realization sometimes sloshes over into other
areas. ``Before somebody's going to join the international economy,
they have to be comfortable with their identity where they are,''
he said during a discussion of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As a former basketball star, Bradley, unlike most politicians,
has never had to beg for attention. This seems to have given him a
quietness that allows him to draw people out by simply sitting
there _ head down, chin tucked in, peering up with a look of
slightly amused interest _ and waiting for them to volunteer some
information.
</P>
<P>
   It works particularly well with young people, whom he asks to
describe what they are ``most afraid of,'' with sometimes
remarkable results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid of not making it,'' piped up 17-year-old Jose Rivas
in Nashua. ``What if I've come this far and it's as far as I can
go? It's not as far as I want to go, but what if it's as far as I'm
allowed to go?'' He told Bradley that he wanted to attend cooking
school but might not be able to raise the tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the same calm confidence that makes Bradley a
good listener makes him a dreary public speaker. Even his most
dramatic speech, a really admirable call to re-address the issue of
racial division, is devoid of applause lines. It would be a
profound problem in a different year. But no matter who wins the
presidential primary, boring is something the Democrats are just
going to have to learn to live with.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to comparing himself with the vice president,
Bradley says ``specific issue differences will be laid out in the
fall,'' when it is time for the harvest and Phase Three. If all
goes according to plan, sometime around August Bradley may also
volunteer that he likes historical fiction, and before Thanksgiving
the campaign may reveal that he has read ``Ragtime'' twice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
