<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENN-STATION-ART-NYT &LR;      05-15 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENN-STATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW' PENN STATION HAS A BLUEPRINT, BUT STILL NEEDS MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty-six years after New York City tore down the
original Pennsylvania Station in an act so widely condemned that it
spawned a campaign for historic preservation, President Clinton in
a visit to Manhattan on Wednesday is to inaugurate the renovation
of the old station's surviving sister, the General Post Office on
Eighth Avenue, into a new railroad terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit promises to provide political momentum to a
project that has been planned and debated for six years and still
lacks the final commitment of government funds to cover its
expected budget of $484 million, say officials involved in the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Although a White House spokeswoman, Julie Goldberg, said
Clinton's visit was intended simply to ``inaugurate the project,''
federal officials said it was envisioned as a way to draw public
attention to the architectural work that is now proposed, and to
encourage Congress to approve the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a terrific design and we thought it was time to show
the world what is being planned,'' said Tony Bullock, the chief of
staff to Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who has been the leading
proponent of the project in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Another federal official who has been at the center of planning
for the project, Robert Peck, the commissioner of the Public
Buildings Service, a branch of the General Services Administration,
said that discussions in recent weeks had ``put us in striking
distance'' of fully financing the project.
</P>
<P>
   The original Penn Station was widely regarded as one of the
city's best early 20th-century examples of neo-classical design
before it was demolished to make way for Madison Square Garden, but
the railroad station now being planned would be anchored by a
distinctly modern addition of glass and steel girders.
</P>
<P>
   Several involved in the project, including its principal
architect, David M. Childs of the firm Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill,
said the design might surprise those who envision something closer
to the ornate grandeur of the original Penn Station. But they said
the demands of modern technology and huge crowds dictated a
different approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who likes true classicism and takes the attitude of
`don't touch anything' is likely to be on the other side of the
table from us,'' Childs said. But he added that his design would
``honor the relationship between the modern and the classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip K. Howard, the chairman of the Municipal Art Society, an
organization that has championed historic preservation in the three
decades that followed the demolition of Pennsylvania Station, said
he had reviewed the new design and fully supported it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our principal concern has been to make a train station at a
scale that would accommodate millions of visitors and tourists, and
you can do that with modern design as well as classical design,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Moynihan has led a campaign that focused largely on
reaching an agreement for shared use of the General Post Office,
formally known as the James A. Farley Building, by the Postal
Service and the proposed rail terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Under agreements mediated in recent months by Peck, the Postal
Service has agreed to vacate roughly a third of its space in the
vast structure of 1.4 million square feet by the time construction
begins. Peck said the Postal Service had also agreed to vacate the
entire structure at an unspecified point in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrangement of shared space resulted from years of
hard-fought negotiations in which some proponents of a new Penn
Station had maintained that the postal operations should simply be
moved out, and the Postal Service fought tenaciously to stay in
what is one of the nation's largest and historically distinguished
postal buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Post Office deserves a lot of credit at this point,'' said
Charles A. Gargano, the senior economic adviser to Gov. George E.
Pataki and chairman of the Pennsylvania Station Redevelopment
Corporation, an agency established in 1996 with commitments of $75
million from the state and $25 million from the city.
</P>
<P>
   From its inception, the project has depended on far greater
commitments of Federal funds, particularly because its anticipated
costs have risen. The current estimate of $484 million, provided by
Gargano, is far higher than estimates a year ago that it would cost
less than $350 million, and officials say the construction taking
place elsewhere in New York City is likely to increase the cost
more by creating a shortage of workers and material.
</P>
<P>
   So far, commitments from Congress, the Department of
Transportation and other federal agencies have added $250 million
to the amount available, but such aid remains contingent on
congressional votes in the future.
</P>
<P>
   One fear, according to people involved in the project, is that
members of Congress will reverse themselves and divert money from
the project now that Alfonse D'Amato is no longer in the Senate
after many years as a powerful voice on the Senate Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Even if no money is diverted, Gargano said, the project is still
$134 million short of the present cost estimate. In any case, he
said, the development agency he heads plans to adhere to a schedule
of breaking ground in 2000 and completing the project in 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
