<HEADER>
A8588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CHINA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      05-15 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CHINA BLIND SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, May 16:
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine a more damaging U.S. security failure than
the serial hemorrhage of nuclear-weapons secrets and other military
information to China over the last two decades. Each new disclosure
adds to a picture of breathtaking incompetence by federal agencies
and lack of vigilance by Republican and Democratic administrations
alike. The United States might as well have dumped its most
sensitive defense secrets on Pennsylvania Avenue for Chinese spies
to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Clinton administration's inert response to
possible Chinese campaign contributions in 1996, and the Justice
Department's lack of interest in tens of millions of dollars that
flowed from China into a small Los Angeles bank the same year.
Little wonder that both Republicans and Democrats in Congress want
to know whether the administration willfully ignored all these
Chinese provocations so it could improve relations with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Jeff Gerth and James Risen of The New York
Times have described three serious security breakdowns, two at
nuclear weapons laboratories and one involving work by a private
defense contractor. In all cases, there seems to have been a loss
of critically important information to China that could be used to
modernize Beijing's small arsenal of nuclear weapons or help it
develop other military technologies. In each instance, security
measures were lax and federal criminal investigations proved
ineffectual.
</P>
<P>
   One case, at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in
California in the late 1970s or early 1980s, may have helped China
develop a small but especially deadly warhead. China is planning to
place the warhead on a new, truck-based mobile missile that may be
operational within three or four years and will be able to reach
Western regions of the continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   Another episode, this one at the Los Alamos National Laboratory
in New Mexico, began in the mid-1980s with the possible theft of
another warhead design. Astonishingly, this espionage effort may
have extended until earlier this year and included the transfer of
U.S. nuclear computer codes that serve, in effect, as a physics
blueprint for warhead design work. The primary suspect, Wen Ho Lee,
an American scientist, was dismissed by the lab only this year and
his computer was not examined by investigators until March, nearly
three years after he first came under suspicion. In 1997, the
Justice Department inexplicably turned down a FBI request to put a
covert wiretap on Lee. He has not been charged and denies the
espionage allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In the third case, an American scientist working for TRW, the
defense contractor, appears to have given Chinese officials secret
information in 1997 about an advanced radar technology being
developed to track submarines. The company itself was not involved
in his activities with China. The scientist, Peter Lee, was not
prosecuted for espionage because the Navy refused to let
prosecutors disclose information about the technology in court,
despite procedures that safely permit the use of classified
information in federal criminal trials.
</P>
<P>
   This is no way to run a government. The nuclear labs were
negligent about security, and the Energy Department, which runs
them, failed to fix the problem until Bill Richardson took over as
secretary. The Justice Department was indifferent and the Navy was
obstructionist. The White House, which should have kicked these
agencies into action and insured that there was a coordinated
response, failed to react to initial alarms and only last year
ordered tightened security at the labs.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, President Clinton's top national security
advisers received a secret government report warning that China
presented an ``acute intelligence threat'' to the nuclear labs. If
they had been paying attention, they might have reached the same
conclusion years earlier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
