<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CIPRIANI-RESTAURAN     05-15 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CIPRIANI-RESTAURANTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIPRIANI RESTAURANT EMPIRE UNDER FIRE, AND NOT JUST FROM UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Inside the catering hall, among the soaring
Corinthian columns illuminated by rose-colored spotlights, waiters
milled about serving Bellinis _ cocktails of sparkling wine and
peach juice _ to a black-tie crowd of 500 publishing executives,
writers and editors.
</P>
<P>
   But the genteel murmurs within the basilica-like space belied
the racket outside on East 42nd Street, where union members
chanted, blew whistles and shouted catcalls at those who crossed
their picket line.
</P>
<P>
   The protest-marred gala for the writers' group PEN last
Wednesday at Cipriani 42nd Street, a converted bank building across
the street from Grand Central Terminal, was in many ways emblematic
of the tumultuous quest by the Cipriani family to become kings
among New York City's restaurant owners and caterers.
</P>
<P>
   In two years, the Ciprianis _ led by Giuseppe Cipriani, whose
grandfather founded Harry's Bar in Venice _ have gone from relative
obscurity as the owners of two modest-size restaurants to a force
in the city's dining industry, with some of its largest, most
spectacular and expensive catering halls. The halls have become hot
spots for celebrities and the city's power elite _ TV news anchor
Peter Jennings, designer Giorgio Armani and financier Leon Black
are among those who have recently booked them.
</P>
<P>
   But in building their business, the Ciprianis have waged pitched
battles with union labor, specifically Local 6 of the Hotel and
Restaurant Employees Union, while at times antagonizing clients,
investors, food critics and others in the restaurant industry.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging the Ciprianis' initial successes, some
restaurant experts cite the family's union troubles and other
perceived missteps as evidence that its domination of the industry
is far from a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the obstacles, Giuseppe Cipriani, who with his father,
Arrigo, runs Cipriani International, is thinking big. He said he
expected to have about $90 million in sales when his six
restaurants and catering halls in Manhattan are fully operating
next year, up from $7 million four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Harry Cipriani, the family's original New York
restaurant, Cipriani also runs Downtown, a hipper version of Harry
Cipriani in Soho, manages the Rainbow Room in Rockefeller Center,
and plans to open two restaurants in Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has restaurants in Italy and Argentina and a
line of packaged foods, and even plans to bottle its signature
Bellini cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   The Cipriani magic _ both friends and critics call it that _
includes a high level of service and the ability to get wealthy
customers to pay $30 for a bowl of pasta whose charms might
otherwise escape the attention of food critics. Frequent diners get
a warm hello from Giuseppe Cipriani and the waiters, who memorize
their customers' favorite drinks and deliver them before anyone is
seated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely knows how to relate to a high-end clientele,''
said Mark Packer, a friend of Cipriani and the owner of the
Harley-Davidson Cafe and Angelo &AMP; Maxie's, a steakhouse in the
Flatiron district.
</P>
<P>
   But more than one hotelier and party planner said that the
Ciprianis' high-handed approach to the business has many people in
the industry rooting for the union. The first shot in the labor war
was fired in December, when Cipriani took over management of the
Rainbow Room and let go the 250 longtime union employees who helped
made the landmark restaurant high atop 30 Rockefeller Plaza one of
the most successful in the country. Many of those workers have been
picketing the Rainbow Room since then.
</P>
<P>
   That dispute has taken on broader social import because the
Cipriani family has also limited public access to the Rainow Room
and its revolving dance floor as they convert the complex to a
high-end catering hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a terrible thing for the city and for Rockefeller Center
to close off the public from the high-end tourist attraction in New
York where people imagined themselves to be Fred and Ginger,'' said
Tim Zagat, chairman of the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau.
``The way they handled the union was particularly stupid. And they
didn't just open one catering hall; they opened three mega-sites at
the same time. It seems to me this guy has made one significant
mistake after another.''
</P>
<P>
   significant mistake after another.''
</P>
<P>
   Cipriani's labor war came at a particularly bad time. Local 6
has amassed a $1 million organizing fund and can ill afford to lose
one of the most high-profile restaurants in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a picket line in front of the Rainbow Room for a
hundred years if that's what it takes,'' said Peter Ward, president
of the Hotel Trades Council and business manager of Local 6. ``All
we want is a contract that represents fairness and equity for the
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Cipriani, 34, said the union and his critics had it wrong. A
union contract, he said, hurt him financially and strangle his
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose not to have a union, because having a union is very
expensive,'' Cipriani said. ``It's always bad to have a picket
line. I'll live with it. There've been places 10 years with a
picket line. I hope mine will last less.''
</P>
<P>
   But the labor conflict has only escalated. Only two days before
last Wednesday's dinner, Cipriani sued Local 6 for $5 million,
claiming that its criticism of him had prompted General Motors,
George magazine, Polytechnic University, HBO and others to cancel
lucrative events at the Rainbow Room and Cipriani 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a picket line in front of the Rainbow Room for a
hundred years if that's what it takes,'' said Peter Ward, president
of the Hotel Trades Council and business manager for Local 6. ``All
we want is a contract that represents fairness and equity for the
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cipriani seems unlikely to budge. He is backing an effort to
toss the union out of Harry Cipriani, which, according to two
people who have seen the figures, generated a net income of about
$2.5 million on revenues of $8.5 million last year, a profit rate
more than double the industry average. ( Cipriani says the figures
are lower, although by his own numbers the union payroll consumes
only 16 percent of revenues.)
</P>
<P>
   At the catering halls, Cipriani has tried to avoid paying union
wages by hiring Michael Alexander to supply the waiters, who are
treated as independent contractors and paid $22 an hour. Other
caterers, such as Glorious Foods, treat the waiters as employees
and pay taxes accordingly. The union claims that Cipriani keeps the
22 percent service fee he charges, rather than turning it over to
the waiters as a gratuity. Cipriani contends that the fee is not a
gratuity, but is used to pay the waiters.
</P>
<P>
   That dispute prompted the Rainforest Foundation, which held its
annual fund-raising dinner at Cipriani 42nd Street in April, to
send Cipriani a critical letter and vow to pay the waiters the
difference between Cipriani's wages and union scale. (With a
gratuity, that scale is about $36 an hour.)
</P>
<P>
   The Cipriani reign in New York has been marked by great success
and periodic blow-ups with food critics, investors and the union.
Arrigo Cipriani opened Harry Cipriani in 1985, at the urging of his
friend Lord Charles Forte, whose hotel company, Trusthouse Forte,
had the lease for the space at the Sherry Netherland Hotel on Fifth
Avenue. But when the Ciprianis opened a competing restaurant 20
months later called Bellini at what is now the Michelangelo Hotel
at Seventh Avenue and 50th Street, Trusthouse ejected the Ciprianis
from the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The Ciprianis were invited back to the Sherry Netherland in
1991, after the Trusthouse lease expired. Three years later, the
Ciprianis abruptly closed Bellini, refusing to pay more than
$200,000 in wages and benefits to the union employees, and the
Michelangelo was forced to pay the bill. Cipriani said his family
closed Bellini to focus on Harry Cipriani, but a Michelangelo
executive said that the Ciprianis had fallen out with an investor.
In any event, Arrigo Cipriani was not keen on doing room service or
cooking hamburgers for the hotel's customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to say, `Cipriani doesn't do hamburgers,''' said
Elisabetta Fabri, president of the Michelangelo. ``They have their
own style, and if you want to be partners with them it has to be
their way. The product is good but it's not out of this world.
Still, I was sad to see them go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ciprianis did not attempt to expand again until 1996, when
Giuseppe opened Downtown in Soho, with backing from another
longtime customer, Richard Rubin, the former chief executive of
Donnkenny Inc., who pleaded guilty in February to federal charges
of securities fraud. Rubin, Cipriani said, also helped him
financially at Cipriani 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurateur's friends say that Giuseppe has cast off his
playboy image and become something of a workaholic. A former race
car driver, he now travels in a chauffeur-driven Mercedes 500 and
has dropped out of the club-hopping circuit, settling into a
three-year-long relationship with a fashion model, Steevie
VanderVeen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a misperception that he's growing too quickly,'' said
Jeffrey Goldberger, a real estate investor friendly with Cipriani.
``He's absorbed those acquisitions with great ease. He's really hit
the ground running, doing business from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Ciprianis' attempt to become a major restaurant and
catering company has raised hackles with more than just Local 6.
The same hubris that led the family into what could be a no-win
battle with the union, many people in the restaurant industry said,
has fueled its their decision to open what are essentially
competing catering halls.
</P>
<P>
   The family, which has very firm ideas about everything from the
size and shape of its tables _ small, round and short-legged _ to
its billing procedures, has alienated some of the party planners
and clients who have used Cipriani 42nd Street or 55 Wall Street,
which they all describe as breathtaking venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the more frustrating experiences I've had,''
said Fern Mallis, executive director of the Council of Fashion
Designers of America, which had booked its annual gala into 55 Wall
Street last year. ``There was a manner of doing business with us
that I found to be less than accommodating. The range of food
services are not quite as vast as the other top caterers'.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ciprianis have also had to retreat. Cipriani has scrapped
plans to revive the Fashion Cafe, a theme restaurant, at Grand
Central Terminal. And he is leaving the hotel and catering project
at 55 Wall Street, which was called Cipriani Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Cipriani had teamed up with Stanley Kimmel, the chairman of
Jones Apparel Group, who bought the landmark marble rotunda in
1997, to create a hotel and catering hall in the financial
district. Cipriani booked Jennings' wedding, Sean (Puffy) Combs'
birthday party and a Giorgio Armani fashion show. He also started a
concert series in which patrons paid $120,000 for a table to see
performers like Rod Stewart and Aretha Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, however, Kimmel and his partner, T. Richard
Butera, brought in Regent International Hotels to run the project.
Butera said that there had been construction delays and cost
overruns on the hotel, while Cipriani needed to concentrate on the
Rainbow Room and Cipriani 42nd Street. The concert series had lost
a small fortune, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too big a job,'' Butera said. ``Running a restaurant is
something the Ciprianis do out of their back pocket. But it's a
different thing to run a five-star hotel. There was a mutual
realization that we were heading for difficulty.''
</P>
<P>
   Butera said it was an amicable decision. Kimmel, who did not
return calls requesting comment, bought out Cipriani's management
contract at 55 Wall Street. And with Cipriani needing money for
renovations at the Rainbow Room and at Cipriani 42nd Street, Kimmel
doubled his stake in Cipriani International to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Butera said he continued to admire Cipriani's talent as a
restaurateur and businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they could be the largest restaurateurs in New York,''
Butera said. ``I hope he gets through his problems with the union.
He has to somehow come to grips with them. Other than that, the kid
is unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
