<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW STRONG IS THE INFLATION PRESSURE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Does a one-month inflationary blip on the Consumer
Price Index radar screen signal the end of U.S. price stability?
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the financial market's initial reaction to Friday's
CPI report, it seems reasonable to think so. The revelation that
consumer prices took their biggest monthly jump in nearly nine
years put Wall Street in retreat, as stock prices tumbled and bond
rates surged.
</P>
<P>
   The overall CPI rose 0.7 percent last month, which wasn't much
higher than consensus expectations. What jarred the markets,
however, was a 0.4 percent gain for the so-called core rate, which
excludes the volatile food and energy components.
</P>
<P>
   Most forecasters had expected only a 0.1 percent rise for the
core rate, based on assumptions that rising oil prices would fuel
most of the CPI's gain. As things turned out, the energy
component's increase was not only a record, but also was
accompanied by serious price pops over a broad range of items.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street seldom does anything in moderation, and Friday was
no exception. A good rule of thumb, however, is that the greater
Wall Street's overreaction, the better the chance things aren't as
bad as they seem.
</P>
<P>
   Perspective, as always, is key. Friday's report, for instance,
made much of the fact that the core rate's surge was the sharpest
monthly jump since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   So what? Think back to what has been happening since. Looking
beyond the core rate, the overall CPI rose 2.5 percent in '95. The
following year brought a slight resurgence, as the CPI rose 3.3
percent in '96. A cooling period then followed, with the inflation
rate dipping to 1.7 percent 1997 and to 1.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   This lack of inflation, incidentally, was all the more
remarkable in the context of a strong economy and a tightening
labor market that pushed the jobless rate down to levels not seen
in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping things in perspective demands taking the long view of
economic developments. It also demands taking into account all of
inflation's contributing factors, of which the cost of labor is the
most critical. Despite the tight job market, subdued labor costs
are a primary reason for the recent absence of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are signs that the U.S. economy is entering an
era of strong productivity gains fueled by computers, which will be
to the early 21st century what electricity was to the early 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   In order for inflation to occur, there must be inflationary
dynamics in play. So far nothing happening in the U.S. economy
provides valid evidence of incipient hyperinflation except energy
prices. Energy price scares have been a cyclical thing for the past
20 years, though. Nevertheless, periods of energy price spikes have
been short-lived, while the periods of relatively low energy prices
have been long.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there is monetary policy to consider for those who
believe inflation is strictly a monetary phenomenon. On this count,
there seems little to worry about as long as inflation hawk Alan
Greenspan remains Federal Reserve chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation, in other words, is a chimera. There's much out there
that might bring the good times to an end, but inflation isn't one
of them in the absence of inflationary dynamics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
