<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLARK _ TASK FORCE HAWK HEADQUARTERS, Albania _ Despite
Yugoslav claims to the contrary, NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark
said Saturday that rebel forces in Kosovo are growing stronger.
(Albright, Cox News Service) 10. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ELECTIONS _ JERUSALEM _ From Gaza to Washington to
Damascus, the world is waiting to see the results of the elections
in tiny Israel. For months, the region has been on hold _ Arafat
has held off his declaration of statehood, Syria held off
negotiations over the Golan Heights, Bill Clinton has set aside
efforts to restart the Israeli-Palestinian peace process. The
Israeli choice comes down to consummate politician Benjamin
Netanyahu against decorated general Ehud Barak. Most world leaders
want Barak, because they see him as more flexible on the peace
process. That might be exactly why most of Israel, still nervous
about its future among hostile neighbors, could choose hard-line
Netanyahu. Will wrap in recent news in the election and touch on
parliamentary situation. NOTE: This is only first round. Second
round is likely June 1. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CANDIDATES _ Word boxes on the major candidates. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, May 13. Will be updated and re-sent on
Saturday, May 15.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-CHILDREN _ SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ They joke and
laugh and draw pictures, just like so many children the world over.
For a moment, it's easy to imagine the 8- and 9-year-olds in
Hamdija Pasic's art class are just like other children. But these
children have seen the worst the adult world has to offer. Three
years after the war ended here, many of Bosnia's children are still
reeling from the horrors they lived through. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., May 12.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FIRES _ LAS CHIMALAPAS, MEXICO _ Scorched pines seem to
scream against the sky here, victims of the devastating fires that
swept through Mexico last year and sent plumes of choking smoke
thousands of miles north into the United States. Forestry experts
say parts of the Chimalapas wildnerness in Oaxaca state _ which
includes Mexico's last virgin rainforest _ won't recover within our
lifetime from the blazes. In addition to threats from future fires,
the forest is under pressure from continued slash-and-burn
agriculture, illegal logging and poaching of animals and even drug
traffickers who burn parts of the forest to grow illicit crops.
Domingo Jimenez, a Zoque Indian who grew up here, is on a slow but
uphill mission to save this extraordinarily biodiverse forest by
converting his fellow peasants to completely organic cultivation
methods that avoid the use of slash-and-burn and chemicals.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service). 30. WITH PHOTOS AND MAP INFORMATION.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., May 13, including locator map information.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-PAY _ WASHINGTON _ Beginning pay for teachers remains
low, complicating the nation's task of replacing millions of
teachers and hiring 100,000 additional ones over the next decade.
(Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TEACHER-PAY-DATA by state. MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-CANDIDATES _ WASHINGTON _ This time around, every
presidential candidate has a Web page. But who has the best one,
and how does it help the candidate and curious voters? We scan the
field, note the niftiest features, and pin the blue ribbon on our
favorite site. (Glass, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON _ CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ Descendants of Thomas
Jefferson, including for the first time descendants of slave Sally
Hemings, gather for an annual family reunion at Monticello in
Virginia. (Burritt, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LEADERSHIP _ Gov. George W. Bush is known in Capitol
corridors as a bipartisan team player who comes up with ideas,
seeks input and then works behind the scenes to make things happen.
``This is not a dictatorship,'' is a phrase he is fond of. How has
Bush's role in the Legislature played out so far in his year ``in
the bubble'' of presidential politics? We talk to lawmakers,
staffers, state officials and lobbyists to examine Bush's
leadership style and whether it's changing as he makes the
transition to a national stage. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MISSIONARY-ABUSE _ From 1950 until 1971, children in the Mamou
Alliance Academy were routinely abused, physically, sexually and
psychologically. The African school served about 200 children of
missionaries from the U.S.-based Missionary Alliance (now the
Christian and Missionary Alliance) and other missionary
organizations until it was closed in 1971. When, decades later,
accusations of the long-grown children came to light, the Christian
and Missionary Alliance, which had run the boarding school, did not
take legal advice to deny and ignore the whole scandal, but ordered
a full-scale, independent investigation that confirmed many of the
allegations. Reports made public in late 1998 concluded that scores
of acts of repeated abuse occurred at the school _ from children
being forced to eat their own vomit, to bloody beatings with a
piece of rubber tire to repeated molestation by both male and
female staff members of both male and female students. Many of
those former children and some denominational officials are
gathering in Gwinnett County at Simpsonwood Retreat Center in
mid-May for a reunion. They will hold a press conference on Sunday,
May 16. We advance the reunion. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KIRK-FORDICE _ JACKSON, Miss. _ The last days of Kirk Fordice.
Mississippi's governor came out eight years ago and was the first
Republican since Reconstruction to win the job. But he has since
fallen from grace, to say the least. He is reviled by both
Democrats and Republicans, who say he is cruel, vicious, and
impossible to communicate with. He is the ultimate anti-politician
- whatever the legislature wants, no matter how hard it would be to
oppose, he opposes. He's practically the only politician who has
publicly come out in full support of the Council of Conservative
Citizens, the group that got Trent Lott in so much trouble. The
Legislature tried to pass a law banning dogs in the capitol because
Fordice kept walking his through. And what about that mysterious
wreck several years ago, after the three-hour lunch with a woman in
Memphis? We look into this veto record, and talk to legislators and
others around the state about what happened to this guy.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
