<HEADLINE>
UPSTART TEAMS SHOWING NO RESPECT FOR THEIR ELDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allen Iverson scooted past Anfernee Hardaway in Orlando. Jason
Williams and Chris Webber didn't respect their Utah elders. And a
team that relies heavily on Isaiah Rider cruised into the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   All around the National Basketball Association last week, a
league few old-school curmudgeons wanted kept emerging. From
Sacramento to Philadelphia, the tried-and-true notion that stable,
veteran teams compete for titles _ and neophytes with tattoos don't
_ took a beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you even saw in the second game of the Minnesota-San
Antonio series,'' said Madison Square Garden president Dave
Checketts. ``The Minnesota kids _ and they're really all young kids
_ were playing very aggressively, playing with a lot of confidence,
hitting big shots at the end of a game. So there is a newer breed
of youth, energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think that's even more the result of this whole thing
really being up for grabs. I don't think anyone is heavily favored
to win it all. It is wide open. A team that plays well and with
energy has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Convention in the NBA once said you needed a team to stay
together for a while to do well in the post-season, and that
entrusting your playoff hopes to 20-something players with limited
experience would only mean trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Before John Stockton hit a clutch jump shot Friday night with
less than a second remaining to force a Game 5 in Utah on Sunday,
Williams and Webber had helped put Sacramento on the brink of a
monumental upset. For most of the series, the Kings have played
with the exuberance of children at the park while the Jazz has
stodgily plodded upcourt, viewing each possession as a
life-altering moment.
</P>
<P>
   No one can keep up with Iverson, who staked the 76ers to a 2-1
in their first-round series against Orlando. Kevin Garnett was
giving the San Antonio Spurs of David Robinson all kinds of
problems in Game 2. And beyond all the problems Shaquille O'Neal
and Kobe Bryant were creating for Houston's geriatric ward, the
once-combustible Portland Trail Blazers swept Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   None other than Pat Riley, his team facing long odds before it
evened the series with the Knicks on Friday, seemed to realize the
future was quickly becoming the present, that building a team of
aging warriors may not be the way to get the job done in the NBA
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a different freshness; there's a new kid on the
block,'' Riley said last Thursday. ``And the new kid on the block
is hunger, excitement, enthusiasm and a chance to perform on a
platform they've never been on before.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I see that being the difference from some of the teams
that have been there before, that are sort of used to the routine
and getting into the playoffs and having good regular-season
records. Those teams are running into some ferocious energy on the
part of teams that may have been out of it, and all of a sudden the
hunger and enthusiasm is rising above the talent.''
</P>
<P>
   If this indeed is the advent of a new era, the counterculture
hero is making a big push for those marketing dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it be Iverson, Rider, Webber, Williams or, yes, Latrell
Sprewell, players with controversy and calamity in their past are
moving to the forefront in the playoffs. The NBA is not about
Michael Jordan peeking at Bugs Bunny through a Warner Brothers hole
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It is about Sprewell having cornrows sowed into his hair,
looking at the camera and intoning: ``Some people think I'm what's
wrong with sports. Some people say I'm America's nightmare.'' With
Jimi Hendrix's version of ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' blaring in
the background, Sprewell ends his new And 1 commercial by adding,
chillingly, ``I say I'm the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento Is Sweet on Kings
</P>
<P>
   Like the Jazz before them, the Sacramento Kings appear to be
that rare small-market franchise enrapturing its homespun town
after years of futility. Everyone in California's capital, it
seems, is gaga over the league's most entertaining team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a national perception, but truthfully, it's not very
accurate,'' said Jerry Reynolds, the team's vice president of
player personnel, who has been with the organization since it moved
West from Kansas City in 1985. ``Our fans even have short memories
and have jumped on the bandwagon to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, we've been bad before. But it hasn't exactly been
Clipper stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, though they're making only their third playoff
appearance since the franchise moved, the Kings sold out Arco Arena
for 10 straight seasons at one juncture. Only three seasons ago,
the Kings had top-seeded Seattle on the ropes in the first round
before Gary Payton miraculously pulled out Game 3 in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Having had a taste of the post-season, Kings fans finally became
fed up with their beleaguered team last season. With Mitch Richmond
asking for a trade and the franchise floundering, the atmosphere
became venomous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time they really turned on us, where it got
nasty,'' Reynolds said. ``I guess after all the loyalty they showed
early on, you couldn't blame `em.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing Vlade Divac, drafting Jason Williams and trading
Richmond for Chris Webber, general manager Geoff Petrie overhauled
the roster and assembled a free-wheeling bunch of passers and
scorers, the team that is going the distance against Utah on Sunday
at the Delta Center. Outside of professional wrestling and tractor
pulls, the Kings are again the hottest ticket in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a couple got together, got really mad at each other
and broke up for a while,'' Reynolds said. ``Then, they find out
they really like each other after all and get back together. But it
got ugly for a while, no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond making personnel decisions, Reynolds, 55, has scouted,
coached and performed every imaginable duty for the organization
since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Before teams began bringing in five-person coaching staffs,
Reynolds was an assistant coach when teams had only two people on
the bench. Besides his current duties, he is also the general
manager of the Monarchs, Sacramento's Women's National Basketball
Association franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they have three guys do what I did and pay them three
times what I made,'' he said laughing. ``Looking back, I guess I
feel cheated.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the league's more colorful characters, he is the
second-most-popular person in his hometown of French Lick, Ind. As
he is fond of saying, ``People know Larry Bird just a tiny bit more
than they know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy Goes Unappreciated
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy may coach his last game with the Knicks on Sunday
in Miami. Amid the perception that he simply did not prepare his
talented team well enough over the last three years, he will most
likely be relieved of his duties if the Knicks lose in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   As with Patrick Ewing, when Van Gundy is gone, maybe then he
will be truly appreciated for not only his effort but also his
foresight and talent.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to motivate injury-prone players with major
chemistry and character problems will most likely shine through
once someone else is hired to coach this overhyped team.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, other people in the organization are taking credit for
the sudden development of Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   When his job was in jeopardy earlier this season, Van Gundy
stuck to his guns and made the timid Camby earn his playing time.
He was taken to task for not starting Sprewell, but that energy
infusion off the bench finally seems to be paying off after a long
adjustment period.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he could be petty and too often he treated basketball as
war, as did Riley before him. And maybe the politics of the Garden
finally got to him, and made him something more than a coach,
something that even he never wanted to be. But whatever happens, no
one could have taken this group of players farther.
</P>
<P>
   He is a very good coach in charge of some very flawed New York
teams. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
