<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WPA-WRITERS-KAN &LR;      05-15 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WPA-WRITERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S VIBRANT SPIRIT BLOOMED WHILE WORKING WITH WPA WRITERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Betrenia Bowker is a petite and dignified
86-year-old woman who once ran with the wolves.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting recently in her pleasant Kansas City home, talking
quietly of old times, she dropped only the faintest hint that in
summer 1936 she fell in with the wildest bunch of writers,
painters, brawlers, poets and raw-jaw radicals who ever knocked
back a boilermaker in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that summer in St. Louis was hot,'' is what she said.
</P>
<P>
   And that can be taken two ways. Because it was hot that summer,
literally hot, 100 degrees for weeks on end.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got to St. Louis, I actually saw the mercury
shoot right through the top of a thermometer on a building,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She saw other things: Depression homeless sleeping in doorways;
union picket lines and unemployment demonstrations; radical
speakers on almost every corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   And the heat to which she alluded had more than one source.
Fresh-faced and fresh out of Drury College in Springfield,
Mo.,Bowker had unknowingly leaped into a political cauldron.
</P>
<P>
   She had been hired by the Works Progress Administration to help
put out the Missouri edition of the now-famed WPA state-guide
series. The guides were prepared by unemployed writers hired by
President Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the guide was way behind schedule,'' she said, ``and the
people in Washington were getting impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowker saw the problem immediately. Missouri's project
administrators were at war with the guide's writing staff, a group
that included Missouri-born Jack Conroy, already noted for his
classic Depression novel ``The Disinherited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conroy and the other writers wanted to produce an honest,
literary portrait of Missouri,'' Bowker said. ``But the
administrators, real political hacks, wanted a sanitized,
chamber-of-commerce tourist guide.''
</P>
<P>
   When Conroy wrote a section on Missouri culture that highlighted
Ozark folk ballads and black music, he was ``reprimanded'' for not
hyping tonier subjects such as the symphony orchestras in St. Louis
and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle was on,'' Bowker said, ``and it was getting hotter
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Writers' Program was based on the ninth floor of
the Civil Courts Building in downtown St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was a short ramble to the old Mississippi
riverfront levee, where the writers gathered almost nightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go down to the river at about 10 p.m. and stay until 2 in
the morning, drinking and talking about writing and politics,''
Bowker said. ``And when all those fascinating, worldly people
discussed their views on social justice, well, they made sense to
me. I became a left-wing New Dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowker had grown up in southern Missouri, one of seven children
in a very proper, very conservative home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had twin sisters, two years older than I was,'' she said.
``And when they turned 16, they each asked for a raisin pie and
permission to say `Gosh.' That should give you an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, though, Bowker had read of Voltaire and the Age of
Enlightenment, and she dreamed of finding true companions to match
her secret rebel spirit.
</P>
<P>
   She found them on the St. Louis riverfront, eight or nine
kindred souls who made her feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fascinating part is that Betrenia was so plain-spoken and
intelligent that she more than held her own with those wild,
hard-living characters,'' said Douglas Wixson, a social historian
and Conroy biographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She proved tough and savvy, and they all fell in love with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy was the leader of that literary wild bunch. Raised in a
tough mining camp, barrel-chested, stentorian-voiced, he bellowed
even in private conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have a beer with him and imagine he was addressing a
huge throng of coal miners,'' Bowker said.
</P>
<P>
   He was bellowing more than usual that summer. In a constant rage
about the state guide, he blew off steam in riverfront saloons.
</P>
<P>
   His regular drinking crew included poet William ``Wallie''
Wharton and other guide writers such as Edwa Moser, Jean Winkler,
Jack Balch and Milton Lomask. They adopted Bowker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I'd always wanted to see a barroom brawl, and they kept
trying to find me one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took me places (strip joints and honky tonks) where women
did things I didn't know human beings could do. We went to bars
with sawdust on the floor and people singing and making speeches
and reciting poetry from on top of the tables.''
</P>
<P>
   She was enchanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this your first cigarette? they'd ask me. Is this your
first shot of whiskey? Of course, they never took me along to the
really rough places where they hung out in East St. Louis. They
were very protective of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of showing her barroom brawls, they wrote her about them
after she returned to Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fightin', fightin', all night,'' Winkler wrote in one letter
to Bowker. ``One man'd go down and the winner would take on
somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   And though they excluded her from the harder side of their boozy
nights, they did include her in their almost daily escapades, often
led by Wharton, a brilliant satirist and merry prankster.
</P>
<P>
   ``A men's clothing association was trying to popularize shorts
for men that summer,'' Bowker recalled. ``So they offered free
drinks to any man who walked into a bar wearing shorts. Wallie
walked in wearing his underpants. He got the free drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Wharton also enjoyed playing a world-weary cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang on to your pure and lovely innocence, Betrenia,'' he
would intone. ``Oh, if I could just recover mine once more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever recover it?'' she once asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, yes, many times, but I just keep losing it again.''
</P>
<P>
   After that summer, Bowker went back to Springfield to work as
the guide's regional editor there. She left the project entirely in
1937, as did most of her friends.
</P>
<P>
   The WPA Guide to Missouri remained mired in conflict. The book
was not published until 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The fears expressed by Conroy and the others proved
well-grounded. Most of their work was edited out and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we would have produced,'' said Bowker, who
taught school for a while, married, moved to Kansas City, raised a
family and became a successful free-lance magazine writer.
</P>
<P>
   In time she lost touch with most of the St. Louis bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years,'' she said, ``1936 seemed long, long in the past.
But recently those memories have been coming back to me. And I've
been thinking more and more about that wonderful hot summer in St.
Louis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-HOUSING-REAL-     05-15 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-HOUSING-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE MANY LIFESTYLES OF HOUSING FOR THE ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Maine, N.Y., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time was of the essence to Michele Edwards and her three
siblings during the winter of 1998. Her mother, May, who was then
86 and who suffers from memory loss, had broken her hip and had
been moved out of her home in Greenwich, Conn., and into the
rehabilitation wing of a local nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   But the move soon proved to be a mistake. Despite a good
reputation, the nursing home had a rigid, unfeeling edge to it
that, Mrs. Edwards said, manifested itself among other things in a
strict bathroom policy: Assistance was allowed only at certain
scheduled times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the family began to scramble for alternative living
arrangements _ screening a dozen facilities for the elderly
nationwide _ they ran into a new set of problems.
</P>
<P>
   First, they had to pin down exactly what their mother's needs
were. And then they had to learn the differences among a
bewildering array of terms, like special-care facilities, skilled
nursing and assisted living, with each term representing a class of
services that seemed to have almost as many variations as price
tags.
</P>
<P>
   Their quandary is hardly unique. In recent years the options for
people who are often making what may be their last move have
exploded both in terms of numbers and complexity of choices. For
many consumers, the options have fostered a sense of relief; no
longer do they, or their loved ones, have to stick to one of two
basic choices: minimal-care retirement homes or medically intensive
nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are lots of variations in between. There are still
plenty of independence-oriented retirement centers where services
are usually limited to housing and meals. But many nursing homes
have broadened their service palette by adding facilities for both
independent living and what is called assisted living, designed for
residents who generally need help with just two or three daily
activities, such as bathing and dressing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Seniors Housing Association, a trade
group for developers, assisted-living facilities now account for
about three-quarters of the new senior housing being built.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the stand-alone assisted-living facilities that have
sprouted over the last decade are transforming themselves into
so-called continuing-care communities that often combine, on a
lush, campuslike setting, apartments for independent living, an
assisted-living facility, skilled-nursing beds and special-care
facilities for residents who have medical conditions like
Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Some continuing-care facilities bill themselves as ``life-care''
communities; in exchange for an often hefty entrance fee, as well
as monthly service charges, they provide unlimited medical care to
residents as they need it at no additional cost.
</P>
<P>
   Most such communities, however, charge residents for the care as
it is required. Some help in paying certain bills may come from
Medicare, which will pick up short-term medical costs, like
hospitalization. However, when it comes to the long-term care
provided by the senior living industry, consumers generally foot
the bill themselves, sometimes with the assistance of private
long-term care insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists in what is called senior living credit a host of
factors for the diversity. First, the elderly population, many of
whom can be expected to need long-term care at some point, is
growing quickly. Meanwhile, both because of efforts to contain
costs and because of concerns in many states about quality of care,
the construction of new nursing homes ground to a virtual halt long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the senior-living industry is also reinventing itself to
meet what are, in many cases, increasingly sophisticated consumer
preferences, not just for larger living quarters, but also for
smaller, more homelike buildings in which to house them.
</P>
<P>
   One trend has been the effort to take advantage of new findings
in gerontology to make notable changes in the physical plans of
many facilities. One such change has been the incorporation of
circular building designs that let residents who have conditions
like Alzheimer's wander freely without leaving a facility's
premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that badly stubbed its toes in the 1980s
when everyone rushed out and built one Taj Mahal after the next,
very little of which had any service or care component to it,''
said David Schless, executive director of the American Seniors
Housing Association, the developers' trade group. ``People were
building very upscale properties, but they discovered that very few
seniors were interested. So now they're building units that offer
more value and more service.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for many consumers, the options have only intensified the
head-scratching.
</P>
<P>
   Take the range of financing options available. Assisted-living
facilities typically offer services for about half the price of
skilled-nursing care; in exchange, residents generally agree to
share responsibility for certain basic personal chores, as well as
to forfeit the continual clinical supervision of a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, assisted-living facilities vary enormously in their
monthly fees, depending on where they're located, as well as the
type of accommodation or degree of medical services that a resident
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly fees can be less than $1,000, or more than $4,000. But
as an assisted-living resident becomes less independent and
requires more help with tasks like bathing and using the toilet,
costs can climb quickly, cautions Gregory Seal, a certified
financial planner in Denver, whose firm handles many long-term care
matters.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, he said, nursing homes may offer care that is not
only cheaper, but also more qualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the marketing that an assisted-living facility may do
to indicate that you can stay there forever, as you become more
dependent you will require a type of care that perhaps the facility
isn't prepared to give,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding what kind of continuing-care or life-care community
makes sense is often no less complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Entrance fees for life-care communities in the New York
metropolitan area, for example, can range from $170,000 to
$500,000, with monthly service fees that range from $1,900 to
$4,300.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly service fees at life-care centers usually stay the same,
their operators say as part of their sales pitch, even if a
resident requires more complex care later on. And in the long run,
a life-care community might cost a consumer less than a standard
continuing-care facility.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus is that life-care communities usually offer refunds
of at least 90 percent of residents' entrance fee when they leave
the community. In case of death, the resident's estate gets the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Most continuing-care facilities initially charge monthly service
fees only. In exchange, some provide an average of 120 days of
medical care a year (consumers pay for extra care), while others
require only that consumers pay daily rates for any long-term
nursing care that they may need.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a one-size-fits-all industry,'' said Michael
Ruffer, executive vice president and chief operating officer at
Marriott Senior Living Services, a division of Marriott
International. ``And because there are so many different products
on the market, it really makes sense for the prospective resident
and their families to learn what their options are.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ruffer conceded that consumer confusion over terminology within
the senior-living industry has been ``huge,'' with consumers, among
other things, often confusing assisted living with home health
care, an entirely different industry.
</P>
<P>
   To clear up some of the confusion, some newly developing
continuing-care facilities, like the Andrus Retirement Community in
Hastings-on-Hudson, N.Y., refer to themselves as ``full-service
retirement communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Terminology within the assisted-living industry certainly hasn't
been helped by the way the industry is regulated.
</P>
<P>
   According to Robert Mollica, deputy director of the National
Academy for State Health Policy, a nonprofit organization in
Portland, Maine, every state currently has some type of
assisted-living regulations on its books, but often the states use
a basket of names to refer to assisted-living centers; some of the
more common ones are residential care, personal care, basic care,
domiciliary care, housing with services, and board and care.
</P>
<P>
   Mollica added that only 25 states now had regulations that
specifically use the ``assisted living'' term, while three states
have regulations pending, and an additional half-dozen are either
studying the industry or drafting regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But states also differ widely in their assisted-living
standards. Staff training requirements vary widely, for example, as
do standards for living arrangements, with some states requiring
apartment settings, while others allow shared bedrooms. To further
complicate matters, a few states require that medical services be
provided by a licensed home health agency, while others allow
assisted-living facilities to either hire private nurses or use
their own personnel.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mollica, New Jersey requires assisted-living
industry staffers to have training in areas such as basic nursing,
hygiene, infection prevention, and working with the needs of the
elderly. New York does not have the same requirements, while
Connecticut simply requires that staffers be trained to meet the
needs of the residents they serve.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even those states that appear to regulate and license
assisted-living facilities may not regulate all of them, said
Cynthia Rudder, director of the Nursing Home Community Coalition of
New York State, a New York City group that says it represents 30
consumer, professional and civic groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, unlike most other states, regulations and
licensing for assisted living applies only to those programs that
receive public money, and which admit people who would otherwise go
to a nursing home,'' said Ms. Rudder. ``That means there is a whole
host of new, privately sponsored assisted-living residences that
are being built and that, with the exception of a some housing
regulations that apply to things like fire codes, are effectively
not regulated. We think consumers need to ask really good questions
when they visit these facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Ms. Rudder urges consumers to ask about
admission and discharge criteria, staff training credentials, and
financial issues, such as what might happen to the resident if he
or she were to run out of money to pay for their care.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts are under way to bring a common language of standards,
as well as quality, to the assisted-living industry.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a coalition of six organizations, including the
Alzheimer's Association and the American Association for Retired
Persons, announced a national quality initiative to help states set
minimum assisted-living standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``States argue that assisted-living residents can vote with
their pockets, but the reality is that once someone moves in it
often takes a lot for them to leave _ and often the move is
traumatic,'' said Rhonda Buckner, director of the Consumer
Consortium on Assisted Living in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite growing competition within the senior-living
industry, it's not clear whether many consumers really can vote
with their pockets, because of the rapidly ballooning elderly
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs of these facilities are not going down _ they're
going up,'' said William Steinberg, a long-term care benefits
consultant with Hirschfeld, Stern, Moyer &AMP; Ross, a New York-based
firm that specializes in employee benefit programs. ``In the Sun
Belt states, they can't build them fast enough. The industry isn't
oversubscribed, and it won't be for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Seniors Housing Association,
assisted-living facilities now account for about three-quarters of
the housing being built for the elderly, with development activity
currently strongest in Florida, Texas, California and the
Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast to the situation just a few years ago, most
assisted-living facilities are now being built as part of larger
senior-housing communities, to allow residents to ``age in place,''
an idea that has taken hold of the entire senior-living industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, the idea of aging in place was seen as a
problem because many facilities couldn't offer a lot of services,''
said Deborah Cloud, director of communications for the American
Association of Homes and Services for the Aging, which represents
the not-for-profit side of the senior-living industry. ``Now we
look at it not as a problem, but as a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Andrus Retirement Community, in Hastings-on-Hudson,
certainly sees it as a goal. Andrus opened its doors in 1953 and
now serves mostly women, who average 86 years in age, and who live
in a nine-story building with hotel-style rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But starting next summer, Andrus, a not-for-profit retirement
community, will be overhauled to cater to people who are roughly 10
years younger. As such, it will offer six new buildings, as well as
some 200 independent-living apartments, 24 assisted-living suites,
48 skilled-nursing beds, and facilities that will include a cafe, a
computer room, a wellness center, and a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andrus was appropriate for retirement living in the 1950s, but
it's not right for what we need now,'' said Skip Kedney, a partner
at Retirement Living Services in Hartford, Conn., which is
co-developing the new community with Beth Abraham Health Services,
a New York City-based, nonprofit provider of both long-term care
and rehabilitation services.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By many accounts, consumers are cottoning to the growing service
orientation within the senior-living industry. Take Mrs. Edwards,
who last winter picked an assisted-living facility that now houses
both her mother and her father, who suffers from less serious
memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   The facility, in Stamford, Conn., is run by Marriott Senior
Living Services, under the Brighton Gardens banner. According to
Mrs. Edwards, it won her family over with its flexibility, because
it was the only assisted-living center that was willing to
accommodate both her parents in a single room.
</P>
<P>
   Other facilities, she said, either wouldn't accept her mother,
because she requires more care then her father, or insisted that
the family hire a private nurse to offer additional care to her
mother, which would have roughly doubled the cost.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mrs. Edwards, her parents' assisted-living costs,
now roughly $5,500 a month including such extras as dry cleaning
and haircuts, add up to roughly half of what a skilled-nursing home
might cost for just one person.
</P>
<P>
   More senior-living facilities are trying to accommodate those
couples where one member may be healthy but the other is frail.
Meanwhile, others are trying to alter the image that the services
they offer are typically for the well-off. For some consumers, that
image has been cemented by developments that have marketed
amenities like bistros and grand staircases, often presented in the
form of well-appointed Victorian manors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is a good deal of product out there that is
oriented toward the middle-income senior,'' with monthly fees of
$1,700 to $2,000 a month,'' said Schless at the American Seniors
Housing Association. Even in large metropolitan areas like New
York, he added, ``there's a broad range of product.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York state the life-care concept is still a relatively
new one, because the state didn't authorize such communities until
1989, and since then it has used strict criteria to oversee their
development. Part of New York's strict approach can be traced back
to the state's nursing-home scandals of some years ago.
</P>
<P>
   New life-care communities, however, are breaking ground.
Kedney's company, for example, is developing, in collaboration with
Hebrew Hospital Senior Housing Inc., a life-care community on 30
acres in the Westchester community of Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   Called Westchester Meadows, the facility is scheduled to open in
2001. It will offer facilities such as a convenience store in
addition to 20 assisted-living beds, 10 skilled-nursing beds, and
120 one- and two-bedroom independent-living apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester Meadows won't be cheap. Entrance fees, depending on
the type of living arrangements, will range from $191,000 to
$427,000, 90 percent of which will be returned at the end of the
resident's stay, while monthly service fees will range from $1,950
to $3,600. Residents will also be expected to put down an
additional $18,000, to cover the costs of any future
skilled-nursing care.
</P>
<P>
   Kedney said that Westchester Meadows had already received
initial $1,000 deposits from some 140 individuals or couples.
Still, he conceded that selling consumers on the life-care concept,
especially within a consumer-savvy New York area market, has been
more of an educational process than his company had anticipated.
One problem, he said, is that developments such as his are
targeting healthy, independent seniors, while the ``life care''
term implies to some consumers that such seniors aren't well at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard response that we've heard is `Well, this sounds
wonderful, but I'm not ready for it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers, however, are embracing the idea eagerly. Take
Morton Bailey and his wife, Marian. In March 1997, the couple, who
are in their mid-70s and who live in Ridgefield, Conn., put 10
percent down toward a 1,380-square-foot two-bedroom condominium
(now worth $450,000) at Meadow Ridge, a life-care community that is
scheduled to open next year in neighboring Redding.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a former magazine publisher, has a few physical
ailments, as does Mrs. Bailey, a former schoolteacher. ``We did it
just for common sense,'' said Bailey, adding that the couple's
decision was also prompted by having to pay the bill for his
mother, who spent the last five years of her life needing long-term
health care, but who had no insurance to cover the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts on the aging urge consumers to also look at the
long-term social benefits of such postretirement communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social isolation is devastating,'' said Dr. Melvyn Hecht, the
chief medical officer at Youville Lifecare, a newly expanded
community for the elderly in Cambridge, Mass. ``It often leads to
functional decline, depression and weight loss. When we see these
signs, that's when we start recommending assisted living.''
</P>
<P>
   Hecht recommends that consumers begin to assess their possible
senior-living needs as early as possible, before a medical crisis
sets in. Too often, he said, that is when most people begin to
scramble for help.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Edwards agrees. Her parents, she said, are now comfortable
at their new, one-room home in Stamford, where among, other things,
they have access to their own doctors, as well as to free
transportation for activities like going to church. Still, she
said, reflecting on the considerable work her family had to do to
find care that would be both high in quality and comfortable for
her parents, ``as a family, we had a lot of catching up to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
