<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERBOATING: MANUFACTURERS COURT AMATEURS WITH NEW CLASS FOR
RACING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's usually the big, tricked-out Superboats with their
churning, 1,000-horsepower engines that draw crowds at offshore
powerboat races. Now, less-imposing production boats are beginning
to draw crowds of their own. Their footsteps lead directly to the
amateur boater's door.
</P>
<P>
   Jim York knows the path. Having recently bought a new 38-foot
Cigarette racer, York plans to compete May 16 in the U.S. Grand
Prix at Point Pleasant, N.J. His boat has two factory-sealed
engines, each 500-horsepower, which can produce speeds of 80 miles
an hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   Having his own race boat is a new experience for York, the owner
of a construction firm from Richmond, Va.. His previous powerboat
was a recreational craft, albeit a high-performance Cigarette model
called Top Gun. But he raced it only occasionally, mostly in
amateur meets around home.
</P>
<P>
   With his new boat, which York has named Cigarette Havoline, he
is competing at the highest level of powerboat racing. That
includes the seven-event Super Boat International circuit and other
competitions, such as those sponsored by U.S. Offshore and the
American Power Boat Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are boats you can actually race, and still use with your
family on weekends,'' York said. ``Before these factory boats were
built, you had to race in 30-foot custom boats with engines that
had to be pulled after every race. That got expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   New rules set up about two years ago by race planners and
Mercury executives make for a more level playing field. By agreeing
to develop two classes of production race boats _ Factory I and II
_ the industry hopes to sell more boats.
</P>
<P>
   The new factory boats all have the same Mercury engines, which
cannot be modified regardless of who makes the boat. And the hulls
must be vee-shaped rather than designed with a two-hulled catamaran
configuration.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the idea seems to be working. ``The intent is to bring
the average guy into racing, and not have to spend a lot more money
once he's in it,'' Donny Wadeck, project manager for high
performance boats at Wellcraft, said recently. ``He can use the F-I
or F-II for a recreation if he doesn't want to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the boats' price requires a commitment. A new F-II
racer from Cigarette costs about $250,000; a comparable Top Gun
recreational powerboat costs about $280,000, said Tom Kosto, vice
president of sales at Cigarette. The racing version weighs about
800 pounds less than the 9,000-pound pleasure-boating model.
</P>
<P>
   ``These boats are giving people something to do other than being
by themselves out on the water,'' Kosto added.
</P>
<P>
   John Carbonell, president of Super Boat International, agreed
that the factory models seem to be catching on. Race organizers are
preparing themselves by making rules for boaters who may not have
adequate experience in racing such fast boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new racer has to stay at the back of the pack,'' Carbonell
said. ``The boat has to be 100 to 200 feet behind the other boats.
And the team has to have the same physicals and safety checks
before the start of a race as the bigger boats. They can still get
into trouble, but it's not the same as doing 120 miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the purchase price, Cigarette includes race uniforms,
life jackets and helmets equipped with an onboard intercom system.
The company will also furnish a qualified racing partner if the new
owner requests it. Beyond that, Cigarette pays buyers $500 as a
starter bonus for racing, and $500 for winning.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette moved into the limelight early with its new race boats
by winning the Factory II world championship last autumn in Key
West, Fla. But other manufacturers, such as Wellcraft, Fountain,
Apache and Hustler, are also promoting factory boats. Factory I
boats are smaller than the F-II's and come with one engine instead
of two.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost a decade since Cigarette, once a leader in
powerboat racing, has fielded a factory team. At Point Pleasant,
two of the company's employees, Jack Cabasso as driver, and Phil
Lipschutz at the throttle, will compete aboard Cigarette Sony Music
in the Factory II Class. As many as 75 offshore powerboats, from 24
to 50 feet, are expected at the event, which is scheduled to begin
at 11:30 a.m. off Point Pleasant Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The factory boats, which will begin about midday, will run 16
laps on a four-mile course; the largest craft, the 40-to-50-foot
Superboats, are expected to race 13 laps on a seven-mile course
beginning at 1:30 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
