<HEADER>
A8614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-FISH-MUSEUM-     05-15 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FISH-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: FROM GAME FISH TO FISHING GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (bl)  
 By KEN SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you can't catch a real fish, you can always visit the
International Game Fish Association Hall of Fame and Fishing Museum
and line up at its virtual catch machines. In a state full of
tourist attractions, this multifaceted facility in Dania, Fla., is
unique.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, the most popular feature was the Catch
Gallery, where five people at a time were holding fishing rods
tethered to fish-fighting simulators. Marlin, bass, trout and other
species _ shown in action on video screens _ struck, pulled, ran
and leapt, to the joy and determination of the youths and adults
holding real fishing rods and struggling for control.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, displays in the Hall of Fame celebrated the
achievements of two dozen famous anglers, including Zane Grey and
Ernest Hemingway. The walls were lined with photos, literature and
memorabilia. Hanging from the high ceiling were hundreds of game
fish replicas representing real world records.
</P>
<P>
   The educational displays of the Tackle Gallery traced the
evolution of sportfishing equipment, complete with rods and reels
dating to the 19th century. And the Legacy Gallery, which tracked
the roots of fishing for sport, paid tribute to the art,
illustration, writing and visual communications that have depicted
and extolled sportfishing, as well as fisheries management and
conservation issues.
</P>
<P>
   This facility is an educational component of the International
Game Fish Association, which was founded June 7, 1939, largely by
Michael J. Lerner. A field associate of the Museum of Natural
History, Lerner and a group of big-game anglers from around the
world created an organization to record game fish catches and
establish ethical sportfishing standards. It originally had a small
office in New York City but moved to Miami and then Pompano Beach
before settling in Dania last December when construction on the $32
million World Fishing Hall of Fame and Museum was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to Fort Lauderdale, the site is virtually a
long-distance cast from Interstate 95. It started with a land
donation by an association trustee who purchased a block of real
estate in Dania that was a reclaimed Superfund site, once heavily
polluted by a lumber yard.
</P>
<P>
   The land today is host not only to the association's building
but also to an artificial lake with a mini-marina that has berths
for half a dozen assorted fishing boats. There is also a
work-in-progress wetlands exhibit, complete with nature trail and
real fish, which is meant as an environmental education tool.
Thanks to a community school program, by the end of the year every
sixth-grade student in Broward County will have visited.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was so engrossing that four hours slipped by, and
that was without visiting the 14,000 fishing-volume library. Not
only are the abundant interpretive and interactive displays
absorbing, but the minutiae of many of the exhibits are as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Tackle Gallery displayed a fascinating belt reel, made by
Wordens earlier this century and featuring a reel that is fixed to
a waist belt. There was also a unique corrosion-free, all-nylon
reel made in the 1950s by DuPont, and an 1870s-era baitcasting rod
sporting bell trumpet line guides and a triggerless handle.
</P>
<P>
   In the Legacy Galley, George Washington's fishing kit, complete
with hooks and supplies, shared top billing with a self-portrait
lithograph of Frederic Remington and his wife that is entitled,
``Her First Muskellunge,'' as well as fishing scenes from Currier
and Ives, and Norman Rockwell, plus a famous Winslow Homer work,
``Ouananiche Fishing, Lake St. John, Quebec.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fish Gallery contained a simple but clever simulation _ a
large current-charged bowl of water _ of how fish ``hear.''
Obviously, fish don't have ears like other animals, but they detect
noise through vibrations, which are sensed by inner organs and by
an external lateral line. Most anglers underestimate the ability of
fish to hear noises made by prey, lures, boats, and noisy or clumsy
anglers. The visitor can place both palms on the bowl to feel the
vibrations that are detected by fish.
</P>
<P>
   Information about fishing records is found at one of the
computer kiosks in the Records Gallery. While reviewing a few
species of personal interest, I stumbled across a cero mackerel
record established by the golfer Greg Norman. I also found the name
of the retired Gen. Norman H. Schwarzkopf, who caught a line-class
record Dolly Varden in Alaska in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   What impressed me as much as the displays was the number of
families. There's a special discovery room for young people, and
youth-friendly hands-on exhibits are located throughout the museum.
Volunteers take individuals and parties on personalized tours, so
anyone of any age or level of interest is accommodated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
