<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-ART-N     05-15 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH LEGISLATOR STRIPPED OF CITIZENSHIP OVER MUSLIM SYMBOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ A woman who was elected to Parliament in
April month but was denied permission to take her oath of office
because she refused to remove her Muslim head scarf will be
stripped of Turkish citizenship, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit said that the woman, Merve Kavakci, accepted U.S.
citizenship earlier this year without informing the Turkish
authorities. Under a rarely enforced clause in the legal code, the
government is therefore entitled to take action against her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dual citizenship is permissible under Turkish law, but Kavakci
should have obtained Turkish permission before acquiring a second
passport,'' Ecevit said.
</P>
<P>
   He said President Suleyman Demirel had signed a decree stripping
Ms. Kavakci of her citizenship. Such decrees take effect upon
publication in the official gazette.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning of Ms. Kavakci's U.S. citizenship last week,
Ecevit, who has led opposition to her efforts to join Parliament,
said she was in ``a totally illegal situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit and many other Turkish politicians, strongly supported by
powerful generals, insist that they can accept no compromise on the
issue of secularism. They say that sinister forces are seeking to
introduce religion into politics here, hoping ultimately to
undermine the secular republic and turn Turkey into a religious
state. Many see Ms. Kavakci as an agent of those forces.
</P>
<P>
   But some conservative Turks view her as a symbol of piety and
have rallied to her side. They have been supported by some human
rights advocates who believe that Members of Parliament, who unlike
civil servants are not pledged to neutrality, should be able to
dress as they please.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials said they had learned from immigration
authorities in the United States that Ms. Kavakci accepted U.S.
citizenship March 5, after she became a Parliamentary candidate but
before her election.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kavakci is a member of the religious-oriented Virtue Party,
which some military commanders and civilian politicians believe is
secretly opposed to Turkey's secular principles.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders say they seek only the freedom to express
themselves and have portrayed Ms. Kavakci's attempt to enter
Parliament with a head scarf as an exercise in democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Virtue leaders supported Ms. Kavakci. Three of its
representatives in Parliament have quit the party to protest her
stand. The most recent, Evliya Parlak, said Friday that Ms. Kavakci
``cannot be an emblem of Turkish women.''
</P>
<P>
   Revelations about Ms. Kavakci's citizenship led to speculation
that she might not be the only Member of Parliament who holds a
foreign passport in addition to one from Turkey. The leader of the
Virtue Party, Recai Kutan, estimated that there were 20 such cases
and demanded to know why the others had not been investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kavakci, 30, quit medical school in Turkey after she was
denied permission to take an examination while wearing her head
scarf. Later she joined her family in Texas, where her father
headed an Islamic association, and decided to stay there. In 1994
she earned a degree in computer science from the University of
Texas at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over Ms. Kavakci's scarf has not been limited to
Turkey. Several hundred women took to the streets of Tehran to
rally on her behalf, provoking a protest from the Turkish
government to Iran. Other demonstrations were held in West Bank
towns controlled by the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
