<HEADER>
A8617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS16-CO     05-15 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: This version is a rewrite of Cox-Israel-Election-Adv16 that
moved on Thursday
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ISRAELI ELECTIONS BOILING DOWN TO PERSONALITIES AND ETHINICITY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ World leaders hope Monday's Israeli election will
bring a new era of cooperation in the Middle East. But for
Israelis, an increasingly important question in this campaign has
become how they will live with one another.
</P>
<P>
   They will be voting on whether Israel should be a Western-styled
democracy or a Jewish fundamentalist state. They will be expressing
their frustration over a recession that stretches the gap between
rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   And, while they revel in the politics of the region's only
democracy _ voter turnout is expected to be over 80 percent _ the
divisions between what many call Israel's ``tribes'' are in plain
view.
</P>
<P>
   On major intersections across the country, religious Israeli
youth _ boys in yamulkas and girls in long skirts _ carry signs for
the several right-wing and religious parties. Opposing them are
left-wing secular youth, in halter tops and jeans _ touting their
favorite pols.
</P>
<P>
   They will elect their parliament from among 32 parties and, on a
separate ballot, they will choose a prime minister. The clear
front-runners are incumbent right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin
``Bibi'' Netanyahu and former general, left-winger Ehud Barak.
Barak, already leading in opinion polls, got a small boost Saturday
when the country's first Arab candidate, Azmi Bishara, withdrew
from the field. His supporters pulled down about 2 percent in the
polls and are likely to vote for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Should former defense minister Yitzhak Mordechai bow to heavy
pressure and withdraw his candidacy, Barak could win a majority in
Monday's election. If not, he will face Netanyahu in a runoff June
1.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, 57, and Netanyahu, 49, fought in the same elite commando
unit, but they battle each other now under the guidance of their
American political consultants. Netanyahu tells Israelis that even
the Arabs want Barak because he's weak. Barak, on the other hand,
seems to appeal on a wider range of issues. He tells Israelis that
Netanyahu has left the country ``stuck'' on all fronts, from
economic development to religious tolerance to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   While world leaders have blamed Netanyahu for raising Middle
East tensions, in Israel the election could hinge just as much on
his contentious personality, which seems to inflame the country's
internal divisions. His supporters are the ultra-religious and
ethnic groups that proudly call themselves ``the rabble.'' They
feel Netanyahu fights for them against Israel's elites just as he
does against the Arabs. Netanyahu's opponents are fed up with that
confrontational nature. They call him a liar who is exploiting
Israel's divisions and pushing it toward war its Arab neighbors.
Even many of Netanyahu's cabinet ministers have abandoned and
bad-mouthed him. The distrust seems to trickle down to his voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stay loyal to who is with the right wing,'' says reluctant
Netanyahu supporter Eliyahu Mordechai, 33. ``But, as far as the
personal aspect goes, there have been changes. He's not so
popular.'' Mordechai sells nuts in Jerusalem's Mehaneh Yehudah
produce market, long a Netanyahu stronghold. The market is filled
with blue-collar Sephardic Jews, descended from other Middle
Eastern countries. They feel alienated by Israel's Jews of European
descent. Mordechai removed the prime minister's picture from his
stall after Netanyahu fired Yitzhak Mordechai, the popular
Sephardic defense minister. Striding out of his shop toward the
crowded market, Mordechai sums up the changing mood: ``Barak is
going to win big.''
</P>
<P>
   Other former Netanyahu supporters have been repelled by the
power he has granted to the ultra-religious parties in his
government.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the 1 million immigrants from the former Soviet
Union voted heavily for Netanyahu in 1996, tipping the election his
way.
</P>
<P>
   They were hawks on security and felt ignored by the Labor Party
elites. But they are largely secular, and Netanyahu's religious
allies have challenged their Judaism, making it difficult for them
to get married or bring other relatives to the country. Polls show
many Russians are looking toward Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Last week(CQ), as he plunged in public opinion polls, the brash
Netanyahu turned to contrition. Telegenic as always, the
American-educated politician called his Likud Party loyalists home,
trying to remind them of the issue that has usually mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching a moment of truth in these elections,''
Netanyahu stated. ``I never said I was free of errors, but there is
one thing I can say, with my hand on my heart: That I have lead the
state of Israeli on the only road that can bring security and
peace. . . I implore you to put aside all other concerns. I implore
you to come home to the Likud.'' But, security is a tougher sell
this year than in the past. Barak's stance toward the Arabs differs
little from Netanyahu's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sting of the campaign, the Arabs, has been neutralized,''
said pollster Hanoch Smith. ``It's very hard to differentiate among
any one of the candidates as to what they're saying about the main
issue.'' After all, Netanyahu may be tough, but Barak was
Netanyahu's former army commander. He is also Israel's most
decorated soldier.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, he would implement more of the peace process, which
Netanyahu has halted amid claims the Palestinians have not kept
their promises. But, Barak pledges to stay as firm as Netanyahu on
the major principles. He refuses to share Jerusalem with the
Palestinians, insists on keeping most of the West Bank settlements
in place and says he'll be stingy with West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   There's a major difference in attitude. While Netanyahu reminds
Israelis of their fear of Arabs, Barak tells them they have nothing
to fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more powerful than any neighbor. We can afford to
pursue peace from a position of strength,'' says Barak, whose short
and stocky physique belies his commando past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to fight terrorism. I will not let anybody strain
our security,'' Barak says.
</P>
<P>
   The tough talk has helped Barak bring the Labor Party toward the
political center, just as U.S. President Bill Clinton and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair did when their parties were viewed as too
far left of the mainstream. As Barak has taken cues from the
outside world, world leaders seem to be pulling for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Clinton administration appeared to back Netanyahu's
losing opponent, Shimon Peres. Now, it has been careful to remain
neutral. But it's clear that Netanyahu has frequently upset Clinton
by stalling the peace process and encouraging settlements on
disputed West Bank land. Several Arab leaders, through appeals to
his opponents, indicate they also want Netanyahu out.
</P>
<P>
   That's a fact Netanyahu is quick to publicize. But, it doesn't
matter to people like Galit Natan, a 30-year-old architect who
brought her daughter to a ``Just not Netanyahu'' rally recently.
She said Barak and Netanyahu will make similar concessions in the
peace process but, ``the process to get there with Netanyahu will
be horrible. It's the person. We are voting for a person, not a
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
