<HEADER>
A8618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON16-COX     05-15 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jefferson descendants weigh claims of black `kin'
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ Lanita Boettcher hopes someday to
sprinkle the ashes of her deceased black grandmother on the shaded
hillside where Thomas Jefferson and his white descendents are
buried.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the 38-year-old from Marietta, Ga., must get beyond
the locked gate at the Monticello Graveyard, owned by Jefferson's
descendents, who hold the key to Boettcher's wish.
</P>
<P>
   In its 86th annual meeting today, the all-white Monticello
Association will consider recent DNA evidence and centuries-old
oral history in deciding whether to admit Boettcher and other
blacks who claim to have descended from Jefferson and his slave and
alleged mistress, Sally Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective black members have refrained from charging racism,
despite being snubbed for years. But Lucian Truscott IV, a white
association member, has accused the group of discrimination,
heightening tension and publicity for today's family gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Taboo still casts shadow
</P>
<P>
   ``It is racism; they do not want black people buried in that
graveyard,'' said Truscott, 52, a Los Angeles screenwriter and
novelist. ``Either you believe what Mr. Jefferson wrote, or you
don't, that all men are created equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's debate seems as complex as Jefferson's own hypocrisy
about owning slaves despite penning the famous words in the
Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this great interest in the evidence of a mixed
family,'' said Annette Gordon-Reed, author of the 1997 book
``Thomas Jefferson and Sally Hemings _ An American Controversy.''
``This topic has not been talked about much in America. It has been
taboo.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's wife, Martha, died in 1782 from childbirth
complications. Her husband lived another 44 years, and history
records Hemings as Jefferson's fair-skinned companion at
Monticello, his plantation outside Charlottesville, until his death
in 1826.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time at this weekend's reunion, the association
has invited three dozen black people who trace their lineage to the
American statesman.
</P>
<P>
   The private gathering in a downtown Charlottesville hotel is the
first since DNA test results last fall found that Jefferson may
have fathered one of Hemings' sons, Eston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a love story there,'' said Boettcher, who
feels certain she is a great-great-great-great-great-granddaughter
of America's third president, whose square-jawed profile is
engraved on the nickel.
</P>
<P>
   `Accuracy,' not racism
</P>
<P>
   She is so proud of her family's history that she and her
husband, Rusty, named their 3-month-old son, Samuel Madison, after
another of Hemings' sons, Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Boettcher learned her family's history from her grandmother,
Ellen Lucille Roberts, who gathered it from descendents of Madison
Hemings, freed in Jefferson's will.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts died at 83 last August, just weeks before the DNA test
results were released. Her granddaughter thinks she would have been
heartened by the findings, which bolstered her belief she was
entitled to burial in the same graveyard as Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to rest my grandmother there, part of her
ashes,'' Boettcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Before that could happen, the association first must accept
black members. That's unlikely, at least this weekend, said the
association's outgoing President Robert Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it is racist,'' the 53-year-old Richmond lawyer
said. ``If you take a careful look at it, we are not concerned
about race. We are concerned about accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The association's 700 members, linked by genealogical records to
Jefferson's family, have the right to be buried in the fenced
graveyard behind Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 150 association members attending today's meeting
are expected to hear from retired Virginia pathologist Eugene
Foster, who conducted the DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   Foster said his study did not ``conclusively say anything,''
creating uncertainty that Gillespie said needed to be resolved by
genealogical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, for instance, that one of Jefferson's male
relatives _ such as a brother or cousins _ fathered Eston. The
testing found no DNA match in the male line of another of Hemings'
sons, James Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Madison Hemings, no DNA test was possible because
Foster could not locate a male descendant to give blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever time it takes, we want to be accurate,'' said
Gillespie, who today turns over the presidency to James Truscott.
``I basically see it as a family matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Some blacks who claim kinship to Jefferson said they hope the
dispute at Monticello can be resolved amicably, as an example of
racial harmony drawn from better understanding of America's complex
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this coming out, it should open a lot of people's eyes to
what was happening at that time,'' said Marietta businessman Lantz
Balthazar, whose daughter, Lanita Boettcher, is attending today's
meeting in his place. ``Maybe by talking about it, the races can
come together; at least, that is my hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
