<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8625 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMPEACH-2NDLD-     05-15 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMPEACH-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVE TO IMPEACH RUSSIAN PRESIDENT DIES IN PARLIAMENT 

</HEADLINE>
 
(Eds: inserts new graf after 1st graf; subs original 2nd _ now 3rd
_ graf to note Duma is dominated by Communists; subs original 7th _
now 8th _ graf to note PM nominee may be confirmed)  (rk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With a flood of venomous oratory, the Communist-led
drive to impeach President Boris Yeltsin failed in Russia's
parliament Saturday as nearly 100 members of the legislature
unexpectedly stayed away from the session, and some ballots were
thrown out because they carried no names or were defaced.
</P>
<P>
   The result left Communist leaders who had confidently predicted
victory arguing that the nation had been betrayed, and their
opponents claiming vindication against an impeachment they always
said was more a lynching than a legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone had any kind words for Mr. Yeltsin, who emerged
from the proceedings an isolated figure, under attack from friends
and enemies alike.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's opponents in the lower house of parliament, the Duma,
which is dominated by Communists, ineeded 300 votes out of the 442
active members to win impeachment on any of the five charges
against him. The count deemed most likely to succeed was the charge
that Yeltsin waged an illegal war against the rebellious Russian
republic of Chechnya in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But late Saturday afternoon parliament officials reported that
only 283 valid votes were cast in support of the Chechnya charge,
17 short of what was needed. Forty-three legislators voted against
it.
</P>
<P>
   None of the other charges approached that total. Besides the
accusation involving the war in Chechnya, Yeltsin had been charged
with illegally dissolving the Soviet Union in 1991, staging a
violent 1993 coup against rebellious Communists in parliament,
destroying the Russian military and committing genocide by allowing
the nation's living standards to plummet, leading millions of
Russians to an early death.
</P>
<P>
   The genocide charge gathered 238 votes in support and 88
against. The charge of destroying the army collected 240 votes in
support and 77 against; the charge of dismantling the Soviet Union,
239 votes in support and 78 against, and the charge of staging a
coup against Parliament, 263 votes for and 60 against.
</P>
<P>
   Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov denounced the votes as a
betrayal of Russia and pledged that legislators who opposed
impeachment ``will pay with their political careers'' at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conscience is clear,'' he told the news radio station Echo
Moskvy. Yeltsin's nominee as prime minister, Sergei Stepashin, said
the Duma had averted ``an extremely serious political crisis'' by
rejecting impeachment, and given Yeltsin time to address the
nation's problems. Some predict that Stepashin, nominated by
Yeltsin after he fired Yevgeny Primakov as prime minister
Wednesday, will now be approved by Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leaders forecast Friday that the Duma would approve at
least the Chechnya charge, and possibly others. But their cause was
set back seriously when only 348 ballots were accepted at
Saturday's climactic vote, 94 short of the number of active
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 14 ballots were thrown out on some votes, either
because they were unsigned or were defaced with a large X.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a boycott of Saturday's balloting, the Communists sought
unsuccessfully Friday to hold the impeachment votes then, rather
than wait until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Kommersant quoted officials Saturday as saying
that an ``epidemic'' had struck parliament members and that many
had checked into Moscow's prestigious Central Clinical Hospital for
treatment. The hospital was unable to confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   Most legislators have been under intense pressure to vote for
impeachment because of Yeltsin's unpopularity among voters. But
many also feared retaliation from the Kremlin should they support a
failed impeachment attempt, and it was widely believed that others
were offered jobs or other inducements to support the president.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Volkov, a spokesman for one of the leading Communists,
the chairman of the Duma's security committee, Viktor Ilyukhin,
seemed resigned to defeat after the vote, saying that it was the
symbolism of the impeachment effort that mattered, not the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether impeachment happens or not, we have to look at things
realistically,'' the spokesman, Volkov, said. ``This is a big
political action, important for the entire country. The vote itself
doesn't show what it actually means, because there is a big
political game'' affecting the balloting. Volkov said that ``all
the numbers don't show reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With any result,'' he said ``this is a big achievement of the
parliament _ that it can speak out against the government and its
actions. It shows to those who come next that the people are not
without a voice. It shows to the next Duma that they have a right
to speak out.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The firebrand nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky told Interfax
news agency that the Communist loss was a signal for Yeltsin to
``crush the leftists.'' Zhirinovsky, the head of the Liberal
National Democratic Party and an opponent of impeachment, predicted
that Yeltsin would now move to ban the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Before the votes, Zyuganov said the impeachment process ``has
already had a refreshing effect in this hall and on the general
situation in the country'' by underscoring that even the highest
officials are accountable for their deeds.
</P>
<P>
   But if anything was underscored by the three days of debate this
week, it was that the division between the Yeltsin government and
the Communists who control the parliament has evolved from fierce
political rivalry to blood feud.
</P>
<P>
   Zyuganov branded Yeltsin ``absolute evil'' in his closing
speech, a savaging of the president and a mournful eulogy for an
empire lost, ``a thousand-year-old power; the power that Hitler
failed to conquer but which, through the efforts of Yeltsin and his
team, was torn to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country took almost five centuries to gain access to the
seas, the Baltic Sea and the Black Sea,'' he said, ``and today we
have been thrown back from these seas and we have sustained
colossal economic and moral losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all humiliated because the old people and the children,
the women and workers have been robbed. The reserves of the
strategic resources of this country amounted to more than $200
billion. Everything has been wasted _ sold and drunk away. We have
lost almost all property which was accumulated not during the 70
years of Soviet power, but during all the history of Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader of Yeltsin's most powerful bloc of supporters in the
party, Our Russian Home, Vladimir Ryzhkov, retorted that the
charges against Yeltsin ``rest on sand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obvious to any law student in his second year,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he defended Yeltsin against the impeachment
accusations _ noting, for example, that the Duma had voted to
support the same Chechen war that was the basis of a charge against
Yeltsin _ he conceded that the president has failed the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1991, when he had the support of 97 percent of the
population, he did not use the historic opportunity to create a
truly democratic and stable state with a genuinely responsible
parliament,'' Ryzhkov said. ``In December 1993, when he had a clean
sheet of paper in front of him on which he could write any
constitution he wanted, he wrote the ugliest constitution in the
world which gave rise to a politically irresponsible parliament, a
politically helpless government and a president who was a colossus
on feet of clay.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, he said, ``he brought us, after 10 years of
privation and setbacks, to a state where we have to begin
everything from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   And Zhirinovsky condemned all sides, saying that Yeltsin was
being upbraided for a dissolution that has been under way for
hundreds of years, at the direction of the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be said that the country was ruined in 1991. That
decision was made in 1717 in Paris; 280 years ago the West made a
decision to destroy the Russian empire,'' he said. ``Do you think
Napoleon invaded Russia just for kicks? That Hitler attacked Russia
just like that? That Yugoslavia is being bombed just like that? The
target is one _ the Russian empire, the Soviet Union; never mind
that we are now a democratic country. They are moving closer and
closer to the Russian borders.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Duma building in downtown Moscow, a vast crowd of
demonstrated cheered, waving Communist flags and signs reading
``Yeltsin resign!'' and ``We defeated Hitler, we will defeat
Yeltsin.'' One notable placard read, ``Yeltsin-out of the Kremlin!
Guilty!,'' twisting Yeltsin's name to give it a Jewish ending. As a
practical matter, Saturday's votes were mostly symbolic. Few
expected that a decision to impeach Yeltsin would actually result
in his removal, because the charges would have to survive review by
Yeltsin's appointees to constitutional and supreme courts, and then
pass the upper house of parliament, which has often backed Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   But impeachment had a gravity beyond mere condemnation of the
president. Many experts believe _ and some Kremlin aides have
hinted _ that Yeltsin would strike back at the Communists should
impeachment have passed, perhaps by finding a legal excuse to
dissolve the Duma and force new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Constitution prohibits dissolving the Duma while an
impeachment is in progress. An attempt by Yeltsin to sidestep that
requirement would have provoked a showdown that could well have
endangered the nation's young democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Communists now must decide whether they wish to rebuff Yeltsin
by rejecting his choice of Stepashin.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin is required to dissolve the Duma if it refuses three
times to ratify the nomination of a new prime minister. Although
the Duma seemed certain to reject Stepashin earlier last week,
Communist advisers said on Friday and Saturday that they hoped the
Duma would approve the nomination, if only to provide some
continuity in the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
