or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BUCHANAN, N.Y. -- May 15, 1999 -- NY-NUKE-WASTE, 5-15 --
Plant engineers checking a 40-foot-deep pool containing twenty-six
years' worth of spent fuel from the Indian Point 2 nuclear reactor
in Buchanan, N.Y. According to plant engineers, the pool is very
safe and clean, but it is also very nearly full. (Joyce Dopkeen/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 15, 1999 -- BARMITZVAH-QUADRIPLEGIC-2,
5-15 -- Joey Stulberg, 13, who has severe cerebral palsy,
rehearsing for his bar mitzvah. Joey uses a pointer attached to his
cap to activate a computerized voice which reads Hebrew text.
``What's unusual about this is that it's so usual. He's doing what
boys and girls have done for thousands of years, and has learned
enough to participate in his tradition,'' says Robert Stulberg,
Joey's father. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 15, 1999 --
SUB-BARMITZVAH-QUADRIPLEGIC-1, 5-15 -- Joey Stulberg, 13, who has
severe cerebral palsy, arriving Saturday at the Kane Street
Synagogue in Brooklyn for his bar mitzvah. Joey communicates by
tapping a talking portable computer with a pointer attached to his
baseball cap. The computer which reads Hebrew text was designed by
John Eulenberg, director of the Artificial Language Laboratory at
Michigan State University. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) JERUSALEM -- May 15, 1999 -- ISRAEL-ELECTION, 5-15 --
Torn election posters of Benjamin Natanyahu, left, and Ehud Barak
on a Tel Aviv wall hint at the bitterness of the Israeli campaign.
This race, like many Israeli elections, has brought out the blood
passions in a country that sometimes operates like a large extended
family, complicated by intense sibling rivalries, intermarriage and
generational disputes. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- May 15, 1999 -- TURKEY-POLITICS, 5-15
-- Merve Kavakci, a member of the religious-oriented Virtue Party
in Turkey, which some military commanders and civilian politicians
believe is secretly opposed to Turkey's secular principles. Kavakci
was elected to Parliament last month but was denied permission to
take her oath of office because she refused to remove her Muslim
head scarf. Kavakci will now be stripped of her Turkish
citizenship. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) DIYARBAKIR, TURKEY -- May 15, 1999 -- TURKEY-KURDS-2,
5-15 -- Kurdish men on the streets of Diyarbakir, the city's oldest
section. Kurdish nationalists enjoy wide support in Diyarbakir,
where their candidate for mayor won 62 percent of the vote, despite
police harassment that included banning and attacking his rallies
and arresting many who campaigned for him. (Staton R. Winter/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DIYARBAKIR, TURKEY -- May 15, 1999 -- TURKEY-KURDS-1,
5-15 -- A Kurdish man in front of a house bearing a poster for the
pro-Kurdish People's Democratic Party. Kurdish nationalists enjoy
wide support in Diyarbakir, where their candidate for mayor won 62
percent of the vote. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TUCSON, Ariz. -- May 15, 1999 -- DRUG-TRIALS-3, 5-15 --
Dr. Jay Grossman, a private-practice doctor who is an allergy and
respiratory specialist with Vivra Asthma and Allergy Inc. in
Tucson, says he was often a lead author on publications because he
had been a top patient recruiter in the clinical trials, even
though he rarely did much -- if any -- of the actual writing.
``That's common,'' he says. ``It's orchestrated by the drug
company's medical writer.'' (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DURHAM, N.C. -- May 15, 1999 -- DRUG-TRIALS-2, 5-15 --
Dr. Robert Califf, the director of the Duke Clinical Research
Institute, an academic drug-testing center in Durham, N.C. After
discovering how effective paying doctors to recruit patients can
be, the drug industry has opened the financial floodgates. There
are payments to everyone in the system who can come up with a
patient. ``The patient is an object to make money. Having patients
is just the dirty price for doing business,'' says Califf.
(Jennifer Warburg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DENVER -- May 15, 1999 -- DRUG-TRIALS-1, 5-15 -- Dr.
David Shimm, an oncologist and a member of the ethics committee at
Porter Adventist Hospital in Denver, who has written about research
conflicts. ``What the patients are not seeing is that the clinical
investigator is really a dual agent with divided loyalties between
the patient and the pharmaceutical company,'' says Shimm. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DENVER -- May 15, 1999 -- DENVER-GOATS, 5-15 -- Goats
from Wyoming working the land in Denver. It's the oldest
weed-control technique known to mankind,'' says Lani Lamming of
Alpine, Wyo., an owner of Land Whisperer, the company that is
leasing the goats to the city. The goats, which work in two
four-hour shifts daily in a temporarily fenced-in area, can mow
down about one acre per day and can reach areas that machines
cannot. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
