<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-WHITESOX-     05-15 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX BEAT YANKS, 12-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees have apparently become so futile that
their fans grasp at any positive development to root for. They
found one in the seventh inning of a lopsided game Saturday when
Derek Jeter beat the ball into the ground along the third-base line
and raced to first base for a single.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 45,824 at Yankee Stadium, which had watched another
inept effort by the home team, cheered lustily. Jeter, who had made
outs his first three times at bat, was on base for the 35th
consecutive game, all of the games the Yankees have played this
season. No other major league player has reached base in every one
of his team's games.
</P>
<P>
   But neither sidelights nor consolation prizes win games, and the
Yankees tumbled to the Chicago White Sox, 12-4, for their fifth
consecutive loss. Jeter's 60-foot single actually ignited the most
promising inning the Yankees have had in the past four games, but
later in the inning Tino Martinez, who had just cracked a two-run
double, ended it prematurely by being thrown out at the plate on
Chili Davis' single to center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' four runs were double the number they had scored in
their previous three games combined, but they mattered little
because the White Sox battered Ramiro Mendoza for seven runs in the
first two innings, six of them in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is a sinkerball pitcher and the ball wasn't sinking,''
said Don Zimmer, the beleaguered interim manager.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norton slugged a two-run home run and Magglio Ordonez
lashed a two-run triple in the six-run inning, which matched the
Yankees' worst of the perplexing season.
</P>
<P>
   The losing streak, the Yankees' longest since September 1997 and
their longest at Yankee Stadium since June 1994, can reflect a
series of possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   --The Yankees are only human after all and have found the forces
of nature and the American League working against them in their
effort to duplicate last season's incredible success.
</P>
<P>
   --Their hitters and pitchers have encountered an early-season
slump from which they will recover and proceed to play up to their
division-winning capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   --The players miss the guidance of Joe Torre, who is recovering
from surgery for prostate cancer, and have not responded to the
leadership of Zimmer, no matter how lovable they might find him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to shrug it off,'' Zimmer said before the game,
discussing the team's recent problems. ``What am I going to do? Cut
my throat? Jump out of a building?''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, he said he still was not ready to do either.
There is no need yet for such severe reaction to the Yankees'
plight, unless George Steinbrenner erupts in one of his memorable
tirades that 114 regular-season victories kept contained last
season. But the Yankees are in danger of going to Boston on Tuesday
behind the surprising Red Sox, who pulled even with the Yankees
Saturday with a 6-5 victory over Toronto. Now that wouldn't sit
well with the owner.
</P>
<P>
   The latest loss was the worst of the losing streak because it
was a band of inexperienced youngsters who trampled all over the
Yankees. The nine White Sox players who were on the field for the
first six innings had a combined 11 years of major league service.
The pitcher was John Snyder, who gained his sixth successive
victory by limiting the Yankees to two runs in six innings, one of
them Davis' eighth home run. The other eight collected 15 of
Chicago's 17 hits.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the inning after Snyder departed that the Yankees
threatened to get back into the game. Down by 9-2, they scored two
runs on Martinez's double, and Davis followed with a single to
center. With two out, Willie Randolph, the third base-coach, waved
Martinez around third, but Chris Singleton nailed him with a
no-bounce throw to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking a question of the wrong man,'' Zimmer said when
asked about the play, betraying an underlying feeling between
coaches that exists quietly in the Yankees' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph said he went with his instincts and followed his
aggressive nature. ``It wasn't a line drive, one hop to the guy,''
he said of the hit. ``It was a ground-ball single. In the seventh
inning I'm not thinking of playing safe. In the ninth inning I
might hold him because that run doesn't mean anything. In that
situation, we had a little rhythm going, a little momentum going. I
wanted to keep that going.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez was out, and the Yankees did not seriously threaten
again. The White Sox, on the other hand, scored three more runs
against Jay Tessmer in the ninth as Ray Durham doubled home two
after one had scored on a single by Singleton, who had hit a
two-run home run against Mendoza in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old story,'' Zimmer said. ``When the players
play good, the manager's good, and when the players play bad, the
manager don't know what he's doing. It's been that way as long as
I've been in the game. Ten days ago, 15 days ago, what a great job
Zimmer's doing. Well, I'm doing the same job now except the results
are different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
