<HEADLINE>
IN A LAND OF WIMPS, PALMEIRO REIGNS SUPREME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ His face clouded into a large frown. And his
voice became a snarl. ``That's a bunch of \Rbaloney\S,'' growled
Rafael Palmeiro. ``Ballplayers aren't wimps.''
</P>
<P>
   First, let it be noted Mr. Palmeiro is highly qualified to
defend The Brotherhood against this nasty charge. But in a court of
public opinion, I don't think Rafael wins the case.
</P>
<P>
   Any jock-kingdom random survey of ``gamers'' who ``come to
play'' already has a well-established pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   Ballplayers aren't wimps? Compared to what?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not NHL players _ the manly of the manly. Nor, of
course, the NFL types, a distant second to hockey. Even the NBA
membership seems to rank ahead of ballplayers on a toughness scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare baseball to those other sports,'' barked
Palmeiro. ``We play every day. We play 162 games. More injuries are
going to happen. More players are going to have to be on the
disabled list, or be out of the lineup, because of the daily grind.
People have to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK ... maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Except it doesn't sound too good when stories are retold about
Greg Harris, the old Rangers pitcher. He once went on the DL after
injuring his elbow flipping sunflower seeds in the bullpen. Or
another former Ranger, catcher Ned Yost, who was DLed for
``excessive eyelid strain.''
</P>
<P>
   Then you combine the massive amount of guaranteed salaries with
the long-term contracts, and the incentive to be a ``gamer'' in
baseball is no longer available.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, it's Cal Ripken Jr., the iron man of all
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Or unless it's, yes, Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a trivia question guaranteed to win a bar bet. What
baseball player has appeared in the most games in the '90s? And the
correct name can be seen in action today at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Hint _ Ripken has missed only 22 games in the decade, and those
came in the last month. He was back Thursday night from his
first-ever stay on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   But that Ripken absence pushed him back to second on the
decade's iron-man list. Second to Palmeiro, who leads baseball with
1,403 games played in the '90s, to 1,400 for Ripken.
</P>
<P>
   Let this one accomplishment, more than offensive numbers or Gold
Gloves at first base, define Palmeiro as a ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of it,'' he said, ``but I didn't know it until the
other night. I've never dwelled on it because I don't think it
should be any big deal to try and be in the lineup every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 34, Palmeiro went far beyond ``trying'' for this season,
which was his return to Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Two knee surgeries in spring training left him medically
doubtful for Opening Day in April. But Palmeiro vowed he'd be in
the lineup. And he was. He has only missed one game thus far, when
a hamstring flared on the turf in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Despite just two games of facing major-league pitching in spring
training, Palmeiro had a better-than-average April for him, and, as
usual, his bat is booming in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a state of mind _ my attitude is always to look for an
excuse to play, as opposed to not play,'' he said. ``All of us feel
tired at times, we've got nagging injuries at times, or we've got
the flu or something. But we're paid a lot of money to do this. I
feel an obligation to the people who pay me to be in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Spending the past five seasons with Ripken in Baltimore only
reinforced the already-established Palmeiro attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can't help but rub off,'' he said. ``I don't know how
many times I figured there was no way Cal could play that night. I
knew how much his back was hurting. But he was in there, and he was
contributing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people criticized Cal for playing when they thought
he shouldn't have played. But I never saw him hurt the team because
he was limited by an injury. He always helped the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro has been confined to DH duties this season, which is
not his preferred role. ``It's hard to adjust to not being at first
base, but it's also been a blessing for us. Lee \RStevens\S has
played so well. I'm about 80 percent with the knee, and I can take
my time with it. Because of Lee, there's no reason to rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of Florida, there were those of us who thought
Palmeiro was rushing an injury, based on his adamant stance of
playing the first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think management gets nervous at times,'' he said. ``They
have such a large investment in you, they don't want chances taken
with injuries. But it has to come down to the player knowing how he
feels.''
</P>
<P>
   By reputation, baseball players are going to take off if they
don't feel ``right.'' And their agents also stress a conservative
approach to playing.
</P>
<P>
   But then there are a few others _ the iron men. A Ripken. A
Palmeiro. They give ballplayers a strong defense against that wimp
label.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
