<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux loses 3rd in a row
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Greg Maddux was not the one to stop the Braves road
hurtin'. He's the one who's been in the most agony recently, and he
was feeling it again Saturday in a 5-1 loss to the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   In Wrigley Field, where he was 3-0 with a 1.14 ERA against his
former team, a struggling Maddux (4-3) looked even stranger. He
lost for the third consecutive time after allowing a career-high 14
hits and another five runs, and he didn't really understand why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thrown like this before and won a lot of games, a lot,''
said Maddux, whose ERA rose to 4.83. He has allowed 17 earned runs
in his past three starts and opponents are hitting .356 against him
this season. ``I was happy with my location, happy with my
movement, I got beat today. I know it looks bad and I know it may
sound stupid, but I like the way I threw the ball today.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox, catcher Eddie Perez and even Cubs
hitters agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he pitched good today,'' Perez said. ``His changeup
was perfect. He made some great pitches. They threw the bat on the
ball. He's throwing the same way he's been throwing the past three
years. It's hard for him. I think he's frustrated. But I don't
think he has to change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Henry Rodriguez agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's getting the same strike zone he had last
year,'' he said. ``But I see no difference in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had given up five runs in his 39 1/3 innings pitched in
his career against the Cubs in Wrigley. He gave up five runs in
only five innings Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case for most of this road trip, the first
inning was the killer as the Cubs took a 3-0 lead on back-to-back,
two-out pitches to Sammy Sosa (run-scoring double) and Rodriguez
(two-run homer).
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are 2-6 on this road trip and have lost a third
consecutive series. They are 21-14 and just ahead of the Mets in
the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have scored only two runs in their past three games
after Steve Trachsel pitched a complete game Saturday, allowing
only a bases-empty home run by Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
