<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine lacked his 'good stuff'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago _ The five runs Tom Glavine gave up Friday were more
annoying than worrisome, which makes them different from the five
runs he surrendered in each of his first two outings of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine's ERA climbed back up to 4.53 through eight starts and
his record dropped to 2-4. He had won two of three starts before
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was aggravating because I was starting to get on a roll,''
Glavine said. ``I can handle a game like that more than some of the
ones early in the year. You're going to have days where you don't
have good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine said he hung all the sliders he threw. He wasn't putting
his changeup where he wanted to against right-handers, so he wasn't
throwing it in the spots he normally would.
</P>
<P>
   A two-run home run to Sammy Sosa came on a fastball where
Glavine might normally have stayed with his changeup. A two-run
single to Henry Rodriguez came on a hanging slider.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in the season, the problems were more about not
getting his fastball where he wanted it, as Glavine said he
concentrated so hard on location and struggled to find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early-on I wasn't comfortable, and I didn't have a clue where
the ball was going,'' Glavine said. ``(On Friday) I was
comfortable, felt good, I just didn't have the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliable Remlinger
</P>
<P>
   Among the most-reliable and most-used relievers in the bullpen
this year has been Mike Remlinger, who's job is everything from
retiring a left-hander or two or pitching two or three innings to
finish a game.
</P>
<P>
   With his 14th appearance on Saturday in which he pitched a
scoreless inning, he's 1-0 with a 1.84 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's a bonus for me is I can do a lot of things,''
Remlinger said. ``I just want to be able to pitch in as many games
as possible.'' Offensive questions
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have allowed runs in the first inning of each of the
last five games _ 17 of them _ and hitting coach Don Baylor said
it's had an effect on the Braves' offense, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are trying to get it all back at one time and it works
just the opposite,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are hitless in their past 24 at-bats with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
