<HEADLINE>
LEITER'S PLIGHT A MET MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One month into the season, New York Mets left-hander Al Leiter
is hardly living up to the role of staff ace. He's won only once
and has allowed 29 earned runs in 47 innings, a 5.55 ERA. After
giving up two home runs to the Colorado Rockies on Tuesday night,
Leiter has allowed six this year _ only two shy of his total for
the entire '98 season.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong? Leiter, who signed a four-year, $32 million
contract last winter, confesses he doesn't really know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm throwing the same,'' he said. ``If there's one
thing that I'm not doing consistently enough, it's throwing my
fastball away for strikes, maybe establishing a couple more strikes
away. But my curve's as good as it's ever been, my velocity's as
high as it's ever been and I'm breaking bats with my sliders. It's
just a real unlucky time.'' &QL; 
TOM HARDLY TERRIFIC
</P>
<P>
   Leiter can look to Atlanta's Tom Glavine as a fellow left-hander
who has struggled. In his first five starts, Glavine's trademark
sinker and changeup were noticeably absent, allowing 20 earned runs
in his first 272/3 innings (6.51 ERA). Glavine looked like he was
snapping out of it when he allowed only two earned runs in 201/3
innings, lowering his ERA to 4.13 entering Friday's start against
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   But against Chicago, Glavine allowed five earned runs in 52/3
innings, including Sammy Sosa's ninth home run. &QL; 
THEY'RE EVERYWHERE
</P>
<P>
   Just because you can't crack the Braves starting rotation
doesn't mean you can't be successful. In his 15 starts since the
Phillies claimed him off waivers after he was released by the
Braves last August, right-hander Paul Byrd is 9-4 with a 2.89 ERA.
By beating St. Louis on Tuesday, Byrd improved to 4-2 and lowered
his ERA to 3.59 with the complete-game victory that included a pair
of strikeouts against Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Former Braves farmhand Chris Brock of the Giants beat Atlanta
5-1 on Wednesday, marking the first time San Francisco won a series
from the Braves since July 1996. Brock used the windy weather to
his advantage, allowing four hits and no runs in 51/3 innings. He
walked the first two batters he faced, then struck out Chipper
Jones, Brian Jordan and Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Brock, now 4-2 with a 3.74 ERA, downplayed the significance of
facing his former team, which called him up briefly late in the '97
season after he spent almost six full seasons in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone made a big deal about it, but I'm excited about being
in the rotation and pitching every fifth day,'' Brock said. ``I'm
not worried about who I face. I don't have a problem with that
team. They just didn't have a spot for me.'' &QL; 
BELL TOLLS
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Jay Bell homered in three straight games for the
second time this year, and Wednesday's home run off Montreal's
Ugueth Urbina was his fifth in seven games. Bell, who entered the
weekend tied with the Dodgers' Raul Mondesi for the league lead
with 13 homers, had homered in three straight games only once
before this year, Sept. 20-22, 1996. ``He's on poor man's
creatine,'' joked teammate Matt Williams, who hit his 12th
Wednesday night. ``Ranch dressing.''...
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati was viewed as a possible surprise team before the
season. Now, people are surprised how bad they are. Three starters
from the season opener are gone. Right-hander Brett Tomko was
optioned to Triple-A; right fielder Dmitri Young is hitting .203
and must share time with Jeffrey Hammonds; and third baseman Aaron
Boone was optioned to Triple-A on Wednesday after hitting .218....
</P>
<P>
   Some players do come back. Rockies second baseman Mike Lansing
was terrible last year after signing a four-year, $23.75 million
contract. He had no range, couldn't turn the double play and his
offensive numbers dropped off from 1997 despite the move from
Montreal's Olympic Stadium to Coors Field. Now, he's healthy and
hitting second in front of Larry Walker. Since the move, Lansing
has raised his average from .273 to .336....
</P>
<P>
   Florida right-hander Alex Fernandez, who went on the disabled
list May 2 with a pulled groin after a year-long recovery from
shoulder surgery, is eligible to come off the disabled list
Tuesday. When he originally pulled the groin, the Marlins said
Fernandez would miss at least three weeks. But now he only feels it
when he runs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
