</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MANY MOODS OF JERRY WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a flourish of Jerry West mania last week in the media,
with everyone giving weighty analysis to the status of the
long-time executive of the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   He's set to quit, one TV guy stated. He's had it up to here with
Jerry Buss, a reporter asserted. He still can't get Dennis Rodman
out of his system, declared another journalist. He is mad,
frustrated, upset, etc., and wants a one-year respite, still others
asserted.
</P>
<P>
   I heard and read the accounts, and smiled inwardly.
</P>
<P>
   To me, Jerry West never changes.
</P>
<P>
   I've known him closely since October of 1968, and he's still now
what he was then an enigma imprisoned inside a riddle.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Jerry West isn't what he seems to be, and what he seems
to be on the surface of public visibility is a calm, easy-going
gentleman with a coolly dispassionate personality that doubtless
was responsible for his once upon a time earning the sobriquet Mr.
Clutch for his facility at making final-second jump shots that won
games for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerry West I knew as a player was the most human of all
athletic superstars, a man constantly roiled up in pent-up
emotions, tormented terribly by failure, unmoved by success, lashed
by demons that conspired forever against his reaching a state of
tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   He has been for the past two decades perhaps the top executive
in professional sports, and yet this season has been in such
private turmoil that he has missed attending most of the Laker home
games.
</P>
<P>
   He is given to dramatic mood shifts, and one day will insist
he's destined for retirement at the end of the season, the next day
will contradict his own words and insist he didn't quite mean what
he was saying.
</P>
<P>
   He has had so many changes of the heart over the years that
you've learned to accept his revelations with a knowing nod and
surreptitious wink.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure there have been moments this season when West has
seriously considered giving up his position with the Lakers,
especially after Jerry Buss' acquisition of Dennis Rodman turned
out to be the disaster that West knew it would be.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time not so long ago that Buss allowed West to pull
all the levers with the Lakers, but that hasn't been the case in
recent times when Buss turned down West's request to acquire Mitch
Richmond and brought in Rodman over West's objections.
</P>
<P>
   These decisions by Buss have left West bitter and frustrated to
the point he'd like to leave the Laker organization, and even on
occasion in a fit of candor has said that's exactly what he planned
to do.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry West also has a keen understanding of economics.
</P>
<P>
   He might not sleep that well any longer and he doesn't and he
might not be happy with himself he isn't and he might want to get
away from the whirlwind that is his existence he does but he also
last summer signed a four-year contract extension worth
approximately $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   That calculates to $3{ million a year, and that's the kind of
income that will assure West and his family he lives with his wife
Karen and their two sons in Bel Air a lifetime of financial
security.
</P>
<P>
   Does he walk away from such dizzying stakes?
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry West is given to volcanic mood swings, but he's also an
exceptionally bright person who's a realist.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never forget the first year I worked with West I was the
Laker beat writer for the old Los Angeles Herald Examiner and he
confided to me off-the-record during an off-day after an agonizing
Laker loss that he would probably hang up his sneakers at the end
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   I would hear the same words at intermittent periods during the
next few years, but it wasn't until 1974 that West finally decided
to bid a farewell to a sport in which he had become a legendary
figure.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling here is that Jerry West wouldn't mind fading into
the sunset for good, would like to get away from all those
irritating press interviews, from this weird meddling from Jerry
Buss, from the frustration he's been absorbing from this erratic
Shaquille O'Neal-Kobe Bryant team he has put together.
</P>
<P>
   But he can't.
</P>
<P>
   By the normal standards of society, Jerry West is a wealthy man.
</P>
<P>
   But by the standards at which he's accustomed to living
membership at the Bel Air Country Club, the big mansion in Bel Air
he still has a ways to go before he reaches the level that would
allow him to enjoy a retirement free of economic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   And so, barring some unforeseen dark circumstance, Jerry West
figures to stay for the remainder of his Laker contract, unless he
receives an incredible offer from some team like the New York
Knicks that he couldn't resist.
</P>
<P>
   It's a certainty that rumors will periodically erupt to the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   But one always must be cautioned that what Jerry West said
yesterday won't necessarily jibe with what he says today, tomorrow,
or the following days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-LEADERSHIP16-COX     05-15 2389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LEADERSHIP16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One-on-one, charming leadership style Bush's strength
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He is an Ivy League good ol' boy, a Yale and
Harvard man whose leadership style belies the stuffy stereotype
conjured up by his patrician background.
</P>
<P>
   People like Gov. George W. Bush _ even those not politically
predisposed to being on his side. And Capitol players say that has
gone a long way in moving Bush to any success he has had in a job
that's not inherently blessed with power. What has made Bush a
successful hand-to-hand campaigner _ a social chameleon's ability
to talk to a variety of people about a variety of topics _ forms
the basis of his leadership style.
</P>
<P>
   American voters starting to take the measure of what kind of
president Bush might be will find a politician with a style that is
more personal than bully pulpit, according to lawmakers, lobbyists
and Bush watchers.
</P>
<P>
   He claims he knows how to lead and is not afraid to delegate
responsibility to staffers who earn his trust. He wades into
details only on issues that draw his intense interest, a technique
that can heighten the importance of the people who sign on to his
inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   For Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas government professor,
Bush brings back memories of another Ivy Leaguer with solid family
ties who set his eyes on the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts me in mind of somebody like John Kennedy. He was
someone who did not press the legislature much and was not
particularly aggressive in his lobbying. But he was someone who was
personable, who got along well with individuals. Kennedy had the
ability to strike the spark of affection and respect in mass
audiences that Bush seems to have,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's leadership style has a ``passivity dimension to it,''
Buchanan said. ``He is not a very hands-on leader in terms of the
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who jokes about how his life would be easier if Texas were
a dictatorship, has a shorthand explanation for his leadership
style in the legislative arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just what we call persuasion,'' he said. ``All types of
ways. I meet with people all the time. My staff members meet with
people all the time. ... People know exactly what my position is.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually. Anyone paying any attention knows Bush is for tax cuts,
teacher pay hikes and school vouchers, among other things. On those
topics, Bush leads.
</P>
<P>
   On others, he slaloms. The best recent case in point is the
effort to pass a revised anti-hate-crime law. Bush has declined to
say what he thinks of the proposal, which would enhance penalties
for crimes motivated by hatred for a person's sexual orientation,
gender, race or ethnicity. He has said he's uncomfortable creating
special protections for classes of victims, but he is not using the
bully pulpit to say he'll veto such legislation.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed for his stand, Bush has said repeatedly, ``I will
look at the bill when and if it makes if off the floor of the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, that kind of stonewalling has been the exception. By
policy, he almost always declines to give a thumbs up or thumbs
down on specific bills in the legislative pipeline. But on major
issues, he is generally clear on what he wants. Overall, it's a
leadership style that has helped him win friends and influence
people. Legislative criticism of Bush's leadership has been rare.
But it flowed freely last week as crunch time set it on the
legislative session and Bush's attention was divided between making
law and getting ready to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd say he's been missing in action, but it's
been pretty close to that,'' Houston Rep. Kevin Bailey said at a
news conference called by Democratic lawmakers unhappy with
progress on tax cuts, teacher pay raises and other money matters.
``He's a lot less involved than in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting styles
</P>
<P>
   By style, Bush differs markedly from other Texas leaders who
have trolled the Capitol halls in recent years. Democrat Ann
Richards, who served from 1991 to 1995, was about the best ever at
the public side of being governor. But she garnered a reputation as
a somewhat cloistered governor, a degree or two removed from the
lawmaking machine.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clements, Richards' Republican predecessor, suffered from
the run-government-like-a-business mentality, an approach that
ignores the fact that at times government is so upside-down that if
it were a business, you'd have a fire and collect the insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who retired in January, built a
reputation as a leader with unmatchable knowledge, relentless drive
_ and an intimidating presence.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush style is more personal and subtle, an approach honed
during hours of schmoozing at baseball games, where he spent a lot
of time as managing partner of the Texas Rangers in the early
1990s. A top state senator who is almost always ideologically
aligned with Bush says the governor's style works better than
Bullock's.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, who, like many lawmakers, would speak candidly
about Bush only if he remained anonymous, said Bush is a good judge
of audience and situation. The senator has seen Bush joke, cajole
or pound a fist on the desk when needed.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the lawmaker blames Bush for sticking too close to
``message'' _ sometimes to the point of counterproductive
inflexibility. This year's tax-cut proposal is an example. When
revenue projections showed Bush could not get the $2 billion he
wanted for tax cuts, Bush continued to insist on $2 billion, making
compromise more difficult to achieve, according to the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is disagreement on some core questions about the
Bush leadership style _ he is a detail guy, he's not a detail guy _
there is consensus that he is a successful delegator and a leader
who excels one on one.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush style has caused Sen. Rodney Ellis (D-Houston) to lose
sleep over liking a governor his political gut says he shouldn't
like.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Bush's first legislative session, he and Ellis
disagreed on welfare reform. Ellis, who had been tight with
Richards, expected an ugly battle. It never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I talked several times. He was always approachable and
available, even though we didn't agree. And I remember he told me
at one meeting he would veto the bill if it contained certain
provisions,'' Ellis said. ``When it was over, I voted for some
things in the bill that kept me up at night, but I knew that was
the best thing to do, everything considered _ because he knew right
where I stood, and I knew right where he stood. That's the way he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a style of charming that can be disarming. Bush has worked
on it this year _ perhaps as part of an effort to make sure his
presidential campaign does not make him look out of touch at home _
by making unannounced visits in lawmakers' offices. Austin Reps.
Sherri Greenberg and Elliott Naishtat, both Democrats, say it
scores big points with lawmakers and their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a one-on-one, or one-on-few, style in which Bush excels. He
used it to great advantage during his 1998 re-election campaign. If
his schedule had him in a hall for an hour, he'd speak for 15
minutes and mingle for 45, shaking hands and posing for photos.
</P>
<P>
   He is less comfortable when he has to stick to a text. His most
wooden performances have come in situations like his March 7
announcement that he was forming a presidential exploratory
committee. Bush usually does better when he can react to a crowd
rather than rely on a text. That talent is the basis for his
leadership style.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston, says that in his 22 years in the
House, he's never seen a governor as involved with legislators as
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is liable to stop by your office, which is very unusual,''
Wilson said. ``But that's his own personal style, and it bodes well
for him as he makes the move to the national scene. He's not faking
this stuff; he's not play-acting. That's his personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Democratic predecessor, Richards, herself long on
personality, never made the connection with lawmakers that Bush has
crafted, according to Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when Ann was here, it was like she was talking
down to us _ like a 'big me, little you' kind of thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ellis and Wilson, Sen. John Whitmire is a Houston Democrat
short on good political reasons to get along with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In January, when politics called for it, Whitmire was a leader
in the Democratic response to Bush's State of the State Address.
Whitmire ripped into Bush for talking a lot about tax relief and
not a word about improving transportation in Houston, one of the
few American cities with a need for 24-hour traffic reports.
</P>
<P>
   But while Whitmire does not shy from criticizing Bush's policy,
he has little criticism for Bush the man. Whitmire, a 26-year
lawmaker, tells the story of how Bush once helped him reclaim a
prized memento. When he graduated from high school, Whitmire got a
congratulatory letter from his congressman, George Herbert Walker
Bush. After Bush became president, Whitmire took the framed letter
to an aide for the president to autograph. He never got it back.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, when the younger Bush became governor, Whitmire
mentioned the missing letter and asked for help getting it back.
Within hours, it was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that goes to show you is George Bush is a people
person,'' Whitmire said. ``I've served under five governors and
he's probably the best people person in that respect of any. He
understands that governing is about people, that politics is about
relationships. And he pays a lot of attention to those
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential pull
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere is clearly different this year, thanks to Bush's
upcoming presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators perceive that Bush has not given his aides
clear direction on some issues, and that, at times, aides disagree
with each other.
</P>
<P>
   They also say Bush seems somewhat in the dark on details of key
issues.
</P>
<P>
   A lobbyist with a long-standing knowledge of how Bush operates
says the governor seems far less likely this year to put his neck
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on third base, but he's not taking a lead and trying to
steal home'' is how the lobbyist characterized Bush's
not-quite-committed posture this year. The lobbyist would not
comment on the record because his clients have bills en route to
Bush's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Several border-area leaders, who have been pushing for more
state spending on border highways and job training to compensate
for the effects of free trade with Mexico, say Bush's successful
courting of border voters last year hasn't translated into hands-on
support for their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Eliot Shapleigh (D-El Paso) said that when he and Sen.
Eddie Lucio (D-Brownsville) met with Bush recently to ask the
governor to get involved in their uphill battle to get more highway
money for the border, they went away disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``His heart has been there. His hands have not,'' Shapleigh
said. ``To say he's been a hands-on border governor this session
just isn't the case. His mind has been elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bush and his staff are getting credit for staying
involved in every detail of welfare reform. Senate Human Services
Committee Chairwoman Judith Zaffirini (D-Laredo) said Bush has
invited her to his office to make suggestions about bills before
her committee and to pick her brain in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's staff, she said, has watched over certain bills at every
turn of the process, even offering their own amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're involved in everything,'' Zaffirini said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments about Bush's style _ ranging from fully involved to
barely participating _ confirm his overall image as a leader who
picks his fights, dives into them head first and delegates the rest
to staffers.
</P>
<P>
   CEO of Texas
</P>
<P>
   Bush is quick to note that his title is governor, not head
lawmaker. ``I'm not the leader of the Legislature. I'm in the
executive branch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That makes him CEO for a multifaceted enterprise in which, at
any time, there is trouble in one or more of the agencies. How a
governor handles those messes can be a measure of how he or she
reacts to crisis.
</P>
<P>
   When one of Bush's big corporate donors, funeral home giant
Service Corporation International of Houston, became entangled in a
regulatory tiff with the Texas Funeral Service Commission last
year, questions were raised about whether the company's $35,000 in
Bush campaign contributions bought intervention from the governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office denies that anything improper occurred,
but the appearance of influence-buying helped fuel a growing
controversy about funeral home regulation in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has managed to stay out of the controversy. His top aides
have handled the political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Dick McNeil, chairman of the nine-member funeral service
commission, said Bush has never tried to interfere in the agency's
investigation of SCI's embalming practices. McNeil, a Fort Worth
funeral home executive, said neither the governor nor his aides
ever asked him to back off the SCI investigation.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil said his only conversation about the controversy came at
a Bush campaign stop in Fort Worth last fall. McNeil said he shook
the governor's hand and said, ``I sure hope we haven't embarrassed
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush told him, ``I will be embarrassed if you have not
done your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush realizes that how he does his job could go a long way in
determining if he gets The Big Job. Though criticism has flowed
from some Democrats, it is nothing like what he will face on the
campaign trail _ both from his GOP primary foes and, if he gets the
nomination, from the Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the legislative session churns toward its May 31
conclusion, Bush insists he has demarcated a clear line between
making law and running for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will worry about all the (presidential) exploratory
business and all that later on,'' he said. ``Right now, it's what's
best for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   This article was researched and reported by staff writers Mike
Ward, Dave Harmon, Denise Gamino, Osler McCarthy and Scott
Greenberger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
