<HEADLINE>
AN EARLY LOTTERY PREVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While savoring the ``incredibly Mike-like'' NBA playoffs, let's
pause to thank the little people who have made this post-season
unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   But leave Bob Costas out of it. The little rascals we're here to
toast are the down and out, those 13 teams that rolled over like
the family dog after he went frat boy on the living room carpet.
Teams whose final regular-season games had layoff implications.
</P>
<P>
   To help steer the same jokers away from doom next year, we have
decided to offer some helpful suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take it from the bottom:
</P>
<P>
   29. Vancouver Grizzlies. Motto: ``Please don't feed the Bryant
Reeves.'' Good news: The autograph Shareef Abdur-Rahim thought he
was signing for a three-year-old boy turned out to be a six-year
contract extension. Draft lottery Ping-Pong balls: 250 (out of
1,000). Needs: Forrest Gump and a sucker who will give them a
decent player for trading down to draft Duke power forward Elton
Brand.
</P>
<P>
   28. L.A. Clippers. Motto: ``Larry Brown slept here.'' Good news:
They know a great CBA player when they see one. Ping-Pong balls:
200. Needs: The green light to use what could be as much as $17
million in cap room.
</P>
<P>
   27. Chicago Bulls. Motto: ``Hang up after six rings.'' Good
news: Enough cap-room loot to hide GM Jerry Krause in the witless
protection program. Ping-Pong balls: 157. Needs: More American
players and another excuse to fire up a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   26. Denver Nuggets. Motto: ``Favored by 2 over the Clippers.''
Good news: Antonio McDyess still likes Nick Van Exel. Ping-Pong
balls: 0. Needs: A rap on the knuckles for sending their
first-round pick to Toronto for Chauncey Billups, who's a
right-handed version of Van Exel.
</P>
<P>
   25. New Jersey Nets. Motto: ``Nice shot, Stephon.'' Good news:
Instead of having four clients of super-agent David Falk in the
starting lineup, they only have three. Ping-Pong balls: 0. Needs:
The first-round pick they sent to Minnesota in the Stephon Marbury
deal, and a coach named Jackson ... Phil's a longshot, but Jesse
wouldn't allow Marbury to hold his teammates hostage.
</P>
<P>
   24. Washington Wizards. Motto: ``We didn't have sex with Miss
Lewinsky, either.'' Good news: Coach Bernie Bickerstaff was hired
by the Globetrotters before he could turn the Wizards into the
Generals. Ping-Pong balls: 64. Needs: Center + coach Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   23. Boston Celtics. Motto: ``Just add bourbon and we become
Kentucky!'' Good news: The conditional first-round draft pick they
traded to Cleveland may be worth less than Coach Rick Pitino's Y2K
playoff promise. Ping-Pong balls: 37 (may go to Cleveland). Needs:
A moving van for decimal-point guard Kenny Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   22. Dallas Mavericks. Motto: ``Don't mess with Don Nelson.''
Good news: Nelson can't botch this year's lottery pick, because he
already shipped it to Phoenix for Steve Nash. Ping-Pong balls: 0.
Needs: Re-sign Gary Trent, hope the next Nelson to run the team is
Craig T.
</P>
<P>
   21. Golden State Warriors. Motto: ``Not affiliated with Al
Davis.'' Good news: Saved a fortune on rookie-of-the-year mailing
campaign by trading Vince Carter. Ping-Pong balls: 18. Needs:
Extradition papers for ex-coach/GM Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   20. Cleveland Cavaliers. Motto: ``We have Browns tickets.'' Good
news: Shawn Kemp wasn't hired as stunt double for Oliver Miller.
Ping-Pong balls: 11. Needs: With injured center Zydrunas Ilgauskas
due to return, they need a fresh alibi for Coach Mike Fratello.
</P>
<P>
   19. Toronto Raptors. Motto: ``Just throw it high.'' Good news:
Last two lottery picks were Tracy McGrady and his cousin, Vince
Carter; two more lottery picks this year; spacious cap room.
Ping-Pong balls: 157 (from Denver), 7. Needs: New barber and
contract for Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   18. Seattle SuperSonics. Motto: ``Gary Payton sold here.'' Good
news: Vin Baker's opt-out clause includes a bonus for opting away
from the dinner table. Ping-Pong balls: 6. Needs: Jenny Craig.
</P>
<P>
   17. Charlotte Hornets. Motto: ``Elden Campbell woke up here.''
Good news: The current owner can't beat any of the players
one-on-one. Ping-Pong balls: 5. Needs: One more Laker ought to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   subu UF7 Weakly draft update
</P>
<P>
   By submitting his soul to the NBA Draft, UCLA point guard Baron
Davis has inspired local pundits to grant the Clippers a month of
vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   They figure the Clips are starving at point guard, so drafting
Baron will be automatic. No need for research or homework.
</P>
<P>
   Time out, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Clippers like Davis, but they have eyes for a few
other young turks available in the lottery pool. The waters remain
a bit brackish, because underclass hotshots like Rhode Island's
Lamar Odom, Duke's Corey Maggette and Jonathan Bender of Picayune
(Miss.) High have until today to declare their draft status. And
the Clips' draft position won't be determined until next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   So while the same media prophets who didn't bother advising them
to draft Vince Carter last year are offering wisdom this year, the
Clippers will be busy studying the strengths and weaknesses of
several players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a test scheduled for Friday,'' Jeff Weltman, the
team's director of player personnel said, ``why would you take it
on Monday?''
</P>
<P>
   subu UF7 Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   The league's all-defensive squad - as selected by its coaches -
seems invalidated by the omission of Portland's Greg Anthony and
Minnesota's Kevin Garnett. The 7-foot Garnett simply is the most
eager and versatile defender since Larry H. Parker. The on-the-ball
defense of Anthony, who spells Damon Stoudamire at the point, is
stickier than the fingers of a two-year-old. ... Dion Glover, the
Georgia Tech shooting guard who missed his sophomore season with a
bum knee and entered the draft this week, is listed as a top 20
selection by three NBA talent evaluators who begged to remain
anonymous. ... In his sneaker commercial, Latrell Sprewell refers
to himself as ``... the American Dream.'' Sleep tight.
</P>
</TEXT>
