<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC WINS THE PREAKNESS AT 8-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Charismatic, the onetime claiming horse who stunned
the racing world two weeks ago when he won the Kentucky Derby at
odds of 31-1, pulled an even more unlikely trick Saturday when he
won the Preakness at 8-1 and advanced to the brink of the Triple
Crown.
</P>
<P>
   He was chased home again by Menifee, who lost the Derby by the
length of his neck and lost the Preakness by a length and a half.
And so, for the third straight year, a colt won both the Derby and
the Preakness and needed only to win the Belmont Stakes to achieve
a feat that only 11 horses have accomplished, none since Affirmed
21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go to the Belmont full of optimism,'' said D. Wayne
Lukas, who trains Charismatic for Bob and Beverly Lewis of Los
Angeles. ``I told Bob and Beverly before the Kentucky Derby: `I
don't know about the first two. But we'll look good in the
Belmont.' I just like his style.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hollywood drama and soap-opera twists, few horses can
surpass Charismatic, a 3-year-old chestnut son of Summer Squall,
who twice was offered in claiming races for $62,500. But nobody
claimed him. Then, he went on a racing rampage, running in major
stakes every two weeks with these runaway results: fourth in the
Santa Anita Derby on April 3, first in the Lexington Stakes on
April 18, first in the Derby on May1 and first in the 124th
Preakness on this sunny and cool Saturday afternoon at Pimlico Race
Course.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the final mountain to climb: the Belmont Stakes in New York
on June 5, a mile and a half grind that proved the end of the
Triple Crown dream for Silver Charm in 1997 and Real Quiet in 1998.
Both were trained by Bob Baffert, and both missed their shot at the
Triple Crown in the final strides. Silver Charm was nailed by Touch
Gold, and Real Quiet was caught by Victory Gallop. And fate once
more casts Elliott Walden in a supporting role: he was the trainer
of Victory Gallop, who ran second in the Derby and Preakness, and
his colt Menifee so far has followed in those footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic also carried an entire team with him, starting with
Lukas, who won six straight Triple Crown races until Baffert
overshadowed him two years ago. And add his jockey, Chris Antley,
who missed 16 months of work recently after entering in an alcohol
and drug rehabilitation clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes beyond my greatest expectations,'' Antley said in
some disbelief after the Preakness. ``This is special. The road
back for me was long and hard. Maybe that's what I needed in my
life _ to have something taken away. Now, I have the chance to win
the Triple Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas and Antley worked their second dose of magic against nine
of the horses they outran in the Kentucky Derby, when Charismatic
won by rushing from seventh place to first in the homestretch, plus
three newcomers. People were flabbergasted that a colt with his
history could gain the splendor of winning the Kentucky Derby only
three months after running in a claiming race.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently were still flabbergasted Saturday: Charismatic
went to the post as the fifth betting choice and the highest-priced
Derby winner in the Preakness since Dark Star ran fifth in 1953 at
9-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the long shot raced one more time into sports history and
left some intriguing stars in his dust.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief, who ran third in the Derby, faded to seventh this
time after 10 straight finishes in the money. Kimberlite Pipe,
winner of the Louisiana Derby and a favorite with the betting
public, ran eighth. Valhol, who after winning the Arkansas Derby
was involved in a dispute over whether his jockey had buzzed him
with an electrical device, ran ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Vicar, who ran despite words from his trainer, Carl Nafzger,
that he would scratch the horse rather than run him from the No. 13
post position, finished 10th. Worldly Manner, the mystery horse
from Dubai who ran a reasonable seventh in the Derby after not
racing for eight months, finished 12th. And the only filly in the
race, Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Derby, developed some
breathing problems during the race and was pulled up by her rider,
Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic lingered in 10th for half a mile while speedballs
like Vicar, Cat Thief and Kimberlite Pipe swapped the lead. It was
a fast pace: they went half a mile in 45 1/5 seconds,
three-quarters in 1:10 1/5. By then, Charismatic was making his
move from eighth place with Menifee on his heels. But Antley,
ignoring the common wisdom that the rail was the speed lane at
Pimlico this past week, took his colt to the outside and asked for
action.
</P>
<P>
   He got it. Charismatic shot past seven horses in the stretch and
withstood the furious close of Menifee. At the wire, he had a
length and a half on Menifee, who held second place by a head over
Badge, with Stephen Got Even fourth and Patience Game fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The winner ran the mile and three-sixteenths in 1:55 1/5, paid
$18.80 for a $2 bet to win and added $650,000 to a bankroll that
has leapt in two weeks to $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, jubilant as he neared the Triple Crown, said, ``I told
Chris this morning, you get him to the far turn in position, and
I'll get him home.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lukas, this was his fifth victory in the Preakness. He won
three Triple Crown races in 1995 with two different horses: Thunder
Gulch won the Kentucky Derby, Timber Country won the Preakness and
Thunder Gulch returned to win the Belmont. But Charismatic gave him
a shot at sweeping the Triple Crown with one superior animal, a
onetime claimer who finally convinced his doubters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
