<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US DEFENDS AIRSTRIKE ON KOSOVO VILLAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States Saturday defended an attack that
killed scores of ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo, strongly
suggesting the victims died as ``human shields'' when US bombs
obliterated a Serbian military camp and command post.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the site as ``a valid military target,'' US and NATO
officials said they had no prior knowledge that the ethnic
Albanians, who reportedly had been traveling through southern
Kosovo on tractors, were situated near the Serb outpost Thursday
night when US bombs and missiles ripped through the village of
Korisa.
</P>
<P>
   The raid apparently caused the most civilian deaths, as many as
87, of any attack in NATO's 54-day air campaign against Yugolsav
President Slobodan Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   In expressing regret for the civilian casualties, Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon suggested the victims had been
positioned at the site by the Serb military.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out of the hills and they happened to be put next to
a building that the Serbs had to know was a target because it's
exactly the type of building, the type of installation, we have
been hitting with regularity throughout Kosovo,'' Bacon said at a
Pentagon news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, whose assertion was denied by Belgrade, cited numerous
reports by ethnic Albanian refugees that Serb forces have used
civilians as ``human shields'' at other military sites and
strategic locations, such as bridges. Bacon called the practice
part of Milosevic's effort to turn world opinion against the NATO
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think all of this is done to complicate the targeting and
to create exactly this type of public relations event that he
thinks he can use to his advantage,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the civilian deaths, NATO Saturday unleashed one of its
heaviest aerial assaults yet on Serbian targets in Kosovo. Serbian
media reported that NATO fired more than 90 missiles during the
daylight attacks, and attacks mounted after nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This accident did not shake NATO's resolve in any way,'' Bacon
said. ``The air campaign will continue, with increasing force,
particularly against Serb ground forces and police units in Kosovo.
. . . In fact, the destruction will accelerate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson stepped up his opposition to the US
policy in Kosovo, warning that ``the conduct of this war'' may soon
present a ``special moral challenge for this generation'' as
powerful as the challenge of the Vietnam era.
</P>
<P>
   In a commencement address at Mitchell College in New London,
Conn., Jackson renewed his call for NATO to suspend the bombing and
seek a negotiated peace. He also chastised allied leaders for not
seizing the apparent diplomatic opportunity that arose when
Milosevic, at Jackson's request, recently freed three American
soldiers. ``We must not succumb to the arrogance of power, the
idolatry of might,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO airstrikes are aimed at forcing Milosevic to accept a
peace settlement and permit the return to Kosovo of nearly 800,000
ethnic Albanians who have fled or have been forced from the Serbian
province.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little action Saturday on the diplomatic front,
other than plans for German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's meeting
Monday with Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who is expected to
mediate with Milosevic in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari is scheduled to resume talks with US and Russian
officials on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Saturday, as Serbian officials accused NATO of
targeting ethnic Albanians to thwart Milosevic's alleged desire for
the refugees to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their efforts to prove that they alone can bring the
refugees back home and that only by force, the NATO fascists are
murdering all those who wish to return on their own or with the
Yugoslav government's help,'' Milosevic's government said in a
written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia claims that more than 1,200 civilians have been
killed and 5,000 injured since the NATO bombing began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The US and NATO officials, thrust again into the uncomfortable
position of explaining civilian casualties, said they had no doubt
the Korisa bombing target had been used since at least late April
by the Serbs as a military camp and command post. An armored
personnel carrier and at least 10 pieces of artillery were spotted
at the site, the allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past weeks, looking at that target, we had no evidence
that there were civilians present,'' said NATO's military
spokesman, German General Walter Jertz.
</P>
<P>
   Three US F-16s bombed the site after the pilots visually
identified it through aircraft systems as the target, officials
said. One of the pilots ``did see silhouettes of vehicles on the
ground,'' Jertz said.
</P>
<P>
   But allied officials said the pilot had no way of knowing the
vehicles might have been tractors or that civilians might have been
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are civilians in a target that has been clearly
identified as a military target, it certainly wasn't NATO that
brought them there,'' said Peter Daniel, a NATO spokesman. ``We
know who brought them there.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute roiled as NATO intensified an effort to destabilize
Milosevic's troops, dropping leaflets on Serb forces in Kosovo that
said, ``Leave your unit and your equipment and get out of Kosovo
now. If you choose to stay, NATO will relentlessly attack you from
every direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the strife, about 300 ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo
crossed into Macedonia Saturday, the largest group to reach the
border in 10 days. Aid workers said the refugees reported that tens
of thousands of displaced Kosovars are surrounded by Serb forces
and unable to reach safety in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Montenegrin officials said that the Yugoslav army had
stopped Kosovars from fleeing to Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers accompanied 616 additional refugees Saturday to
Fort Dix, N.J., where the refugees will be temporarily housed
before living with relatives or host families throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In Westfield, hundreds of soldiers gathered at Barnes Air
National Guard Base Saturday for a sendoff for three units of
Balkan-bound troops.
</P>
<P>
   The 104th Fighter Wing out of Westfield was joined by members of
the 110th Fighter Wing from Battle Creek, Mich., and 124th Wing
from Boise, Idaho. The combined units, with nearly 500 troops, will
form the 131st Expeditionary Fighter Squadron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
