<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-DEADLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR SETS DEADLINE TO BREAK ULSTER DEADLOCK  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Prime Minister Tony Blair Saturday night set a deadline
of June 30 for the Northern Ireland parties to break the deadlock
blocking progress in the peace settlement and to establish the new
power-sharing government in Belfast called for in the accord.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from 10 Downing Street said Blair had told the party
leaders that the new final date was ``absolute.'' It argued that
proposals put on the table in extended discussions the past two
days offered a way forward that did not compromise the
``fundamental positions'' of the rival parties.
</P>
<P>
   The main obstacle is the refusal of the Ulster Unionists, the
Protestant party that has the most elected representatives in the
new Northern Ireland Assembly, to permit the political arm of the
Irish Republican Army, Sinn Fein, from taking up its two positions
in the 10-member Assembly executive unless the IRA begins to turn
over its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposals are understood to call for the immediate
appointment of the ministers and delineation of their
responsibilities. The final turnover of power would be dependent
upon a certification from John de Chastelain, the Canadian general
in charge of the disarmament commission, that the appointees can be
classified as nonviolent.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's announcement amounted to the third time that a firm
deadline has been set in the intensified two-year negotiations
aimed at ending the sectarian bloodshed in the conflicted British
province.
</P>
<P>
   Blair identified an ambitious May 1998 goal in a speech to the
House of Commons in September 1997 in which he first laid out his
objective of obtaining a settlement to the conflict that has cost
more than 3,600 lives over the past 30 years. When the talks
appeared to be faltering, George Mitchell, a former U.S. Senate
majority leader chairing them, boldly moved the date forward to the
second week in April. The accord was signed on Good Friday, April
10.
</P>
<P>
   The June 30 deadline coincides with the July 1 date on which
governing powers will be transferred from London to the two new
legislatures in Scotland and Wales. Creating regional assemblies to
deal with local problems in Belfast, Cardiff and Edinburgh, a
process called devolution, is a centerpiece of the Blair program of
reforming British politics.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the Northern Ireland Assembly were elected last
June and have already held meetings in their ornate refurbished
chambers in the imposing Stormont government palace in Belfast. But
the creation of the cabinet to run the new government, the step
that will lead to the formal transfer of power from London, has
been held up by the impasse on when guerrilla arms must begin to be
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   The Downing Street statement followed a series of telephone
contacts between Blair and the various party leaders Saturday and
10 hours of talks between those officials, the Irish prime
minister, Bertie Ahern, and Blair on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  bc-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      05-15 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS OF FEAR BECOMES POLITICS OF INEVITABILITY
</HEADLINE>
 bc-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Before Israel's last election, Bus No. 18 _ struck
twice within a week by militant Islamic suicide bombers _ became a
symbol of fear. Benjamin Netanyahu rode to victory in that vote
through nightly TV ads focusing on the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final days before Monday's vote, Israelis like Yoel
Markus clamber aboard Bus 18 without a second thought. Markus, who
voted for ``Bibi'' Netanyahu in 1996 because of security fears, is
switching sides this time, like many Israelis, to support
front-runner Ehud Barak, who polls say has a slight chance to avoid
a runoff with a big showing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace process is like this bus, it's going to go the same
way whether Bibi or Barak is driving,'' said Markus, 30.
</P>
<P>
   Markus and many Israelis seem to be turning their attention away
from securing Israel's borders to focus on problems within Israeli
society _ especially a deep religious-secular divide and a
faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters to me is Bibi's friends,'' said Markus. ``Over 2
1/2 years, we've watched Bibi get too close to the religious
parties. I don't have anything against the religious, but I don't
want to be controlled by them.''
</P>
<P>
   People who favor secular government _ some 75 percent of the
country's 6 million population _ fear that the ultra-Orthodox
religious parties have seized too much power in Netanyahu's
fractious coalition. Although many of these voters profess strong
links to Judaism and its traditions at home, they bristle at a
sense of religous intolerance and entitlement that they feel the
ultra-Orthodox have brought to government.
</P>
<P>
   So a growing number within the secular majority _ right and left
and especially the crucial Russian immigrant vote _ are galvanizing
forces against the religious parties that came to form the core of
Netanyahu's coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In the election to choose a new prime minister and parliament, a
new secular party emerged solely devoted to fighting against the
religious parties. Its slogan is ``We have to stop them.'' Natan
Sharansky's Russian-immigrant bloc _ which has surged in population
from 700,000 to 800,000 since the 1996 election _ has an ad
campaign with the slogan ``No to Shas Control,'' referring to the
powerful ultra-Orthodox Shas Party.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu keeps trying to make the issue security, even
resurrecting the 1996 bus bombing footage to make his point. But
Barak, a respected former general, has succeeded in blurring the
political lines by also stressing security in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup Poll Friday had Netanyahu trailing Barak by as much as
13 percent. For the first time, pollsters were projecting on Friday
that Barak could take the majority of the vote in the five-way race
for prime minister Monday and avoid an anticipated runoff election
slated for June 1. The key to Netanyahu's precipitous drop in the
polls appears to be the Russian vote. In 1996, Netanyahu carried 65
percent of that vote. In this election, his support has fallen to
about 50 percent of the Russian voters.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Sharansky, a Cabinet minister in Netanyahu's
government, said the religious parties' control of the influential
Interior Ministry has caused Russian immigrants to defect from
their traditional support for Netanyahu's conservative politics to
Barak's more secular line.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians seeking to emigrate to Israel have been challenged
on their status as Jews by the strict ultra-Orthodox who run the
ministry that oversees immigration and implements the Israeli Law
of Return. Thousands of Russians' conversions to Judaism are not
recognized by the ministry, nor are many marriages between Jews and
non-Jews. Dietary laws are being forced on Russian butchers who
sell pork sausage. And government investigators are cracking down
with fines on stores that open on the Jewish Sabbath. There is a
movement to change the laws that shut down public transportation on
the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of Russian voters don't like the ultra-Orthodox
having so much influence over their lives. They want to play down
the role of religion in this country. They want to feel part of
Israeli society,'' Sharansky said.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of religion in the race was clear aboard Bus 18
as it wound its way through the heart of Jerusalem last week. It
bumped past the neon-lit fast-food chains in the busy downtown,
through the largely secular and wealthy neighborhood of the German
Colony, and down into the modest housing blocks of Katamon, where
posters for the religious parties were plastered on nearly every
lamppost and bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   Markus, a grocery store manager, said that after serving three
years in the military, he resents the Yeshiva students' exemption
from compulsory military service, as well as their tax-exempt
status. The resentment is compounded by a constricting economy and
rising unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should have to do something for this country,'' he
said. ``No one gets a free ride.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Barak's most dramatic policy statements early in the
campaign was a vow to enforce a recent Israeli High Court ruling
against a blanket exemption from military service for Yeshiva
students. Focusing his campaign on Israel's failing economy, Barak
has made the economic link between public spending and the rising
influence of the religious parties. He has criticized Netanyahu for
funding their new religious institutions and settlements in the
West Bank while cutting funding for Israel's new lifeblood, its
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Peleg Bahat, 26, heading home from a computer programming class,
said: ``To me the main issue is the religious problem. The feeling
between the religious and the secular is something on the verge of
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am like most Israelis. I am not really religious. I
define myself as human, Jewish, then Israeli. I want to have
tolerance in our society. And I want that anchored in law.
Netanyahu has allowed the religious to diminish that. Barak will
protect that tolerance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Efraim Yosef, 34, a father of five children and a Yeshiva
student, was holding a plastic bag filled with leather-bound
interpretations of the Torah as he waited for the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secular people are afraid. They see religion getting
stronger. They want to stop it, but they can't,'' he said, running
his fingers through his long black beard as he spoke. ``They will
never succeed. The signs that the Messiah is coming are everywhere,
and should not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Barak is elected it is a big danger to the spiritual core
of Israel. Israel can only be a religious democracy. It can be
nothing else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiments like this reflect the battle for the soul of Israel _
whether it will define itself as a religious state or a secular
democracy. It has been an undercurrent of debate in Israel since
well before it emerged as a nation in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is as complex as it is polarized _ splintered among
ultra-Orthodox, modern Orthodox, religious nationalists,
conservative Jews, secular Zionists, and atheists.
</P>
<P>
   Yehoshua Porat, a history professor at Hebrew University, says
that what makes this election unique is that perhaps for the first
time a need to control the ultra-Orthodox and challenge their
attempts to fashion Israel as a religious state is being dragged
out into the open.
</P>
<P>
   Porat, a long-time activist in the Zionist-left Meretz Party,
surprised the country in 1996 when he openly supported Netanyahu
for his strong position on security. He believes Netanyahu has
succeeded in ensuring Israeli security within the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Now Porat insists that the power of the ``Haredim,'' or
``God-fearing,'' as the ultra-Orthodox are called, is the key issue
in the election, and justifies his switch to Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Haredim are becoming a parasitic sector. We should not
have to finance these parasites. We should have a better allocation
of our resources,'' he said. ``When Likud sees how much their
closeness to Shas undercuts their constituency, they will rethink
their attitude toward the Haredim. But for now, it is why Netanyahu
will lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
