<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PRESIDENT SURVIVES ATTEMPT TO OUST HIM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris N. Yeltsin survived an attempt to
impeach him Saturday, as opposition legislators, crumbling under
intense Kremlin pressure, failed to amass the necessary number of
votes on five counts against the Russian leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's political crisis showed no signs of easing. Yeltsin
faces a new showdown with parliament this week after outraging
lawmakers by dismissing the popular prime minister, Yevgeny
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   And in a potential sign of new health woes for the aging
president, whose penchant for erratic public behavior has grown in
recent weeks, Yeltsin made a surprise hospital visit Saturday that
the Kremlin described as a ``routine planned checkup'' that just
happened to be scheduled for the day of the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's vote laid bare the deep divisions in Russian society.
Although Yeltsin is universally disliked _ the approval rating of
Russia's first popularly elected leader has diminished to 2 percent
_ some Russians believe the democratic and market transformation he
began are moves in the right direction, no matter how flawed the
results so far.
</P>
<P>
   But a much larger number, represented by the Communists and
their allies in the Duma, believe that Yeltsin's policies have been
a cynical and corrupt exercise aimed at destroying the country. As
life for most Russians gets worse, this split could widen and
drastically affect the results of planned December parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lies, hypocrisy, and cynicism have become the foundations of
Yeltsin's policy,'' Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov told the
State Duma before the vote. ``Yeltsin is absolute evil for
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin Saturday was silent. A Kremlin spokesman said Yeltsin
had held meetings at one of his suburban residences. Yeltsin, who
has appeared unsteady and has had trouble speaking in recent weeks,
has a long history of serious illnesses played down by his
spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Yeltsin's health has become important again since
he fired Primakov and threatened to disband the Duma and set new
elections if the opposition-dominated lower house of parliament
voted for impeachment. The unpredictable Yeltsin, who thrives on
confrontation more than day-to-day governance, could still lash out
if the Duma refuses Wednesday to approve Sergei Stepashin, his
choice to replace Primakov as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Duma leaders said they would consider Stepashin's candidacy, but
most were noncommittal. Stepashin said: ``Thank God, disaster has
been averted.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the closest Yeltsin's opponents came to a ``yes'' vote
came on a motion accusing him of illegally waging war in the
separatist republic of Chechnya. The motion received 283 votes,
short of the 300 needed in the 450-seat legislature to begin
proceedings to remove Yeltsin from office, and far less than the
312 votes Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov, a Communist, had
predicted a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The other counts all failed by larger margins. Those charges
accused Yeltsin of betraying the Soviet Union, destroying the
Russian military, illegally using deadly force by sending tanks to
end a 1993 standoff with parliament, and conducting economic
policies that brought about ``genocide'' of the Russian people.
</P>
<P>
   As angry Communist supporters in the Duma shouted ``Shame!
Shame!'' at legislators who opposed impeachment, their disconsolate
leaders sought to put a brave face on the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a defeat because the majority of deputies
voted for impeachment,'' Zyuganov said. Before voting, Zyuganov had
accused Yeltsin of destroying thousands of years of Russian
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Yavlinsky, head of a pro-democracy bloc that supported
impeachment only on the Chechnya accusation, said it was the
Communists who had destroyed Russia during their 70-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communists killed tens of millions of people in this country,
brought the country to collapse,'' Yavlinsky said, adding that the
Communist Party ``has no right to power in the country, and no
impeachment can help it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You will share Yeltsin's responsibility,'' Zyuganov shot back.
The Communist leader later said he believed heavy lobbying by the
Kremlin had pressured some lawmakers to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   While other legislators charged that Yeltsin's administration
was offering money, perks, and plush government jobs in return for
``no'' votes, a more likely reason for the turnabout is that some
lawmakers did not want to risk losing the jobs and perks they
already have. Then there were those who could not be bothered, like
the lawmaker who sent in a telegram wishing the Duma well from his
vacation spot in the Canary Islands.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Mayor Yury Luzhkov, a likely contender in
next year's presidential elections whose new political party,
Otechestvo, is not eligible to take part in parliamentary elections
until December. Duma sources say Luzhkov ordered some 30-odd
supporters in the Russian Regions bloc, many of whom had supported
impeachment on the Chechnya motion, to vote against it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
