<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-STATISTICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GOLF, THE NUMBERS CAN LIE, EXCEPT FOR THE SCORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no secret who the longest hitters are on the PGA Tour.
Ask the most casual golf fan and they will likely tell you John
Daly and Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But who's the best iron player on the tour? How about the best
putter, the best bunker player or the most consistent player
driving the ball in the fairway? And, more important, does their
expertise translate into success _ in terms of tournaments and
money?
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're Woods, or David Duval _ the world's No. 1-ranked
player and top money-winner on the tour _ the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is proof that success in all areas means money in the
bank. He is ranked No. 1 on the tour in putting, No. 7 in driving
distance and No. 2 in greens in regulation, which has helped earn
him $2,728,750 this year alone. Like Duval, Woods also has used
statistical domination _ third in driving distance, fifth in greens
in regulation _ to vault his way to third on the money list.
</P>
<P>
   They are the exceptions, however.
</P>
<P>
   While statistics translate into winning in most sports, on the
PGA Tour it takes more than being the game's best putter, or sand
player, or iron player.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest money-winners are those who have all parts of their
game working well at the same time _ during the right week.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, whoever is winning each week seems to be the guy
who is hitting it the best and rolling it the best,'' Phil
Mickelson said. ``Just about anyone out here has the capability to
hit it close from 150 yards. But week in and week out, the guy who
is hitting it the best that week _ and putting the best _ seems to
be the guy who wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The names atop some of the tour's statistical categories are
probably unfamiliar to most. Fred Funk is No. 1 in driving
accuracy, hitting 80.5 percent of fairways, but he is 41st on the
money list. Chris Couch is second in driving distance behind Daly,
but ranks 131st on the money list. Rory Sabbatini is fifth in that
category and 102nd overall, and Robert Allenby leads the tour in
greens in regulation, but is 85th in money won.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pate, by comparison, is eighth on the money list without
being ranked in the top 25 in driving distance, accuracy, sand
saves, greens in regulation or putting.
</P>
<P>
   Just more proof that in golf, statistics don't tell the whole
story.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
