<HEADER>
A8660 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDY-RAY-TEX     05-15 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-RAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREG RAY HAS GONE FULL-CIRCLE AT INDY (FOR BULLDOG)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year after panhandling his way into the front row of the
Indianapolis 500, Texan Greg Ray has returned to the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway riding in style.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, a resident of Plano and No. 1 driver for Team Menard, is
the chalk favorite to win the pole position Saturday for the
world's greatest auto race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be on pole. I'll be very disappointed if we're not
on pole,'' said Ray, who wrote the feel-good story of the Speedway
last May when he qualified his underfunded and basic black
Dallara/Aurora in the middle of the three-car front row.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and powerhouse Team Menard made headlines during an IRL open
test at the 2.5-mile Speedway last month. Ray's lap at 227.072 mph
on April 12 was the fastest ever recorded by a ``new formula'' IRL
car. Ray also posted the fifth-fastest lap of the four-day session
at 223.753 mph, numbers that indicate Billy Boat's year-old
pole-winning average of 223.504 mph is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have way too much respect for all the other teams and
drivers to say we're the pole favorite,'' said Ray, anticipating
the scheduled opening of practice this weekend. ``But going off the
\Rtest\S speeds, I think they have to throw our name in the hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We qualified second last year and deep down in my heart _
without anybody taking it the wrong way _ I have worked so hard the
last three months. It's what I think about when I get up. It's what
I think about when I get on that treadmill, when I push those
weights, when I eat, when I go to sleep. I want to be on pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I do that? I don't know. But I know in my heart that
nobody is trying as hard to do all the right things on and off the
racetrack to prepare for qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray and team manager Thomas Knapp shocked the IRL community last
year when they overcame the last-minute loss of a major sponsor to
earn a then-career best No. 2 starting spot _ smack dab between
well-funded A.J. Foyt Racing teammates Boat and Kenny Brack.
Running with the backing of a patchwork quilt of sponsors that
included Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, Ray led 18 laps on
race day before retiring with a gearbox problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ray finished 18th in the 33-car field, but his determination on
the racetrack and his disarming demeanor off it marked him as a
marketable star.
</P>
<P>
   Team-owner John Menard took notes and hired Ray and Knapp at the
end of last season to replace NASCAR-bound star Tony Stewart and
veteran crew chief Larry Curry. Armed with Menard's considerable
financial and mechanical resources _ and their preferred
Dallara/Aurora/Firestone package _ Ray and Knapp immediately joined
the IRL's short list of elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Knapp's 1999 qualifying program earned the No. 1
starting spot at the one-mile Phoenix International Raceway in
March and for the tragedy-marred event at the 1.5-mile Lowe's Motor
Speedway in Concord, N.C., on May 1. Ray, who is winless in 16
career IRL starts, admitted that little of what was fast at those
tracks will transfer to the Speedway's long straightaways and flat
corners.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition has taken notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're somebody we're going to have to contend with for the
pole,'' Boat said of his Team Menard archrivals. ``They have an
in-house engine program, and they've shown they can be fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray was in the lead of the VisionAire 500 at LMS when the race
was stopped and subsequently canceled after three spectators were
killed and eight injured by a wheel and flying debris caused by a
three-car wreck. No points were awarded, and there are no plans to
reschedule the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have something tragic like what happened at
Charlotte, it's hard to even talk about the racing,'' Ray said
after an emotional sendoff luncheon/roast attended by 200 at The
Speedway Club at TMS on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That event featured a slide show and family stories about Greg
from his parents, Ginger and Benny; an IRL-commissioned feature
video on Ray's career; the proclaiming of ``Greg Ray Day'' by Plano
mayor John Longstreet and plenty of zings at Ray's lead-foot
driving style.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who finished a career-best second to Boat at TMS last June,
took everyone's best shots and fired a few back. But with his voice
cracking, Ray closed the program talking about being able to
realize his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get to live your dream is very, very special,'' said Ray,
32. ``Being a race-car driver is seen to be childish by some. But
this is all I've ever wanted to do. I really feel like I'm closing
in on that dream. It's nice. I'll leave it at that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
