<HEADLINE>
GIANTS LORD OVER DODGERS IN ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attitude is just one of the differences that give an epic
quality to the rivalry between the San Francisco Giants and the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, taking their cue from manager Dusty Baker, scratch
and claw for everything. They also refused to fold after losing
All-Star left fielder Barry Bonds for 10 weeks because of elbow
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were 13-11 without Bonds through Friday and still
hold a share of the lead in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have All-Stars at every position,'' pitcher Robb Nen
said. ``We just have a bunch of guys fighting for jobs who play
hard and do things right. We get runners home with less than two
outs, bunt runners over, things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' early success wouldn't be surprising with Bonds in
the lineup. This is still pretty much the same team that won a
division title in 1997 and lost to the Chicago Cubs in a playoff
for the wild-card berth last year. Without Bonds, they should have
almost no chance. They just refuse to believe that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blow, no doubt about it, but as a professional team you
have to deal with adversity,'' outfielder Ellis Burks said. ``You
have to find a way to win without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds is not the Giants' most indispensable employee. That honor
goes to Baker, a superb manager who commands unswerving respect and
loyalty from his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great guy to play for,'' Nen said. ``He's been through
it, anything you've done, he's done. Just look at him when the game
starts, he has a dip in, his wristbands on, he's ready to get out
there with you. He knows what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers haven't figured that out yet, but they certainly
have little trouble griping and complaining when things go bad.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Gary Sheffield, who threatened to retire in spring
training because of the team's facial hair policy, blasted the
Dodgers for their blase attitude after a 6-4 loss to the lowly
Florida Marlins last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we are not intimidating anyone,'' Sheffield said. ``We
haven't shown anyone any reason to be afraid of us. We did the
first six games \R5-1 to open the season\S and nothing since then.
We're too lackadaisical, just thinking it's going to make it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big inning, then take five innings off. The next
thing we know, we're down by two and we're trying to play with a
sense of urgency. In Florida \Rin 1997\S, we had a saying, `One
heartbeat.' We've got be relentless. When you do that you're going
to win the majority of your games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' payroll is just under $80 million, and they have
nine players who have appeared in an All-Star Game. The Giants have
a $45 million payroll and just four with all-star recognition. One
of them, Bonds, is out until July.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers could still be chasing them then.
Short hops
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, after Friday's win, have a five-game lead in the
National League Central. But manager Larry Dierker said, ``We got
it all in one week; another week it could be gone. I don't think
we'll stretch it out and run away with it, like we did last year.
To do it once like that is unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers player Lee Mazzilli is now managing the New York
Yankees' Double-A team in Norwich (Conn.) and there are those who
believe he will eventually be the permanent successor to Joe Torre
as Yankees skipper. That wouldn't sit well with Yankees coaches
Willie Randolph and Chris Chambliss. Both were disappointed when
Don Zimmer was named interim manager during Torre's current
absence.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Hernandez is 42-for-56 in save opportunities since being
traded by the White Sox on July 31, 1997. The White Sox's tag team
of closers _ Matt Karchner, Bill Simas, Bob Howry _ are 57-for-63
since then, going into the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After the Arizona Diamondbacks swept the Montreal Expos with
three game-winning home runs in the ninth inning or later, pitcher
Todd Stottlemyre said, ``The last time I saw a team win games like
this in the last at-bat was '92-93 when I played on those \RToronto
Blue Jays\S world championship teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals manager Tony La Russa, when asked how Mr. Versatility,
Super Joe McEwing, spends his spare time, said, ``In between
at-bats, he goes into the phone booth, puts that cape on and
rescues somebody out of a burning building or out of the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians made a shrewd move picking up Mark
Langston as a left-handed reliever. Now they're considering him for
the rotation if Dwight Gooden or Charles Nagy continue to struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies are interested in Twins reliever Rick
Aguilera. However, they refuse to give up pitcher Jamey Wright. The
Cubs and Braves continue to scout him as well.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Jones, 42, had thrown 10 2/3 scoreless innings before
Friday, getting a victory, two saves and a hold in four
appearances. His resurgence is one of many factors that allowed the
surprising Athletics to sneak over the .500 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Asked numerous serious questions about his left middle finger,
which developed a blister Tuesday and limited him to five innings,
Reds pitcher Steve Avery concluded the analysis by saying, ``I'm
just having a hard time picking my nose.''
SPOTLIGHT ON SCOTT ELARTON
</P>
<P>
   Elarton mightier in pen than as starter for Astros
</P>
<P>
   There are 29 teams that would kill to have Scott Elarton in
their rotation, including the Atlanta Braves. The Houston Astros
want him there, too, but right now he's too valuable as their
right-handed setup reliever. Elarton, whom the Astros refused to
include in a trade for Roger Clemens, entered the weekend with a
record of 2-0, a 1.37 earned-run average and 27 strikeouts in 19
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of this ballclub is offense,'' Astros general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``We don't need the Atlanta Braves'
pitching staff. What we need is starting pitchers who can hold the
opposition to three or four runs on the average and a bullpen that
can hold a lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put Elarton in the starting rotation, that leaves the
bullpen vulnerable and, because our starting pitching isn't the
Atlanta Braves, you're setting yourself up to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But to keep Elarton in the bullpen, the Astros need better from
Chris Holt, their fifth starter who is 0-5 with a 6.29 ERA. Almost
all of his troubles have come in the first inning, and the Astros,
taking advantage of some off-days, are skipping him in the rotation
right now until he can get straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't, the Astros will likely try to trade for a reliever
and move Elarton to the rotation. Either way, Hunsicker said this
will still be Elarton's last year as a reliever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
