<HEADLINE>
SIX TEAMS FACING A ONE-GAME SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because they weren't May sweeps, it should be riveting
television when three NBA playoff series climax with a fifth game
today:
</P>
<P>
   Knicks at Heat: The stakes are incredibly high as these rivals
play a decisive playoff game for the third consecutive year, but
they're at full strength for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   New York will consider firing coach Jeff Van Gundy and making
personnel moves like trading Latrell Sprewell with a loss, while
Heat players fear a breakup of the team if they lose to the Knicks
for the second consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is beyond everybody's control,'' said Heat coach
Pat Riley. ``This is preordained. This is something the gods
wanted. The consequence will be tremendous misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami wins with any kind of contribution from Jamal Mashburn,
shooting a wretched 31 percent in his brief playoff life. As it has
been all series, first one to 70 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Kings at Jazz: John Stockton ripped out the Kings' enlarged
hearts with his game-winning jumper in Friday's Game 4 thriller. As
most young teams do, Sacramento will wilt under Game 5 pressure and
the veteran execution of the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have already shocked most experts, by not only pushing
Utah, but by coaxing the normally cool Jazz into uncharacteristic
emotional outbursts, such as Stockton exchanging slaps with Corliss
Williamson. ``We ran into a team that is hungry,'' said Jazz guard
Shandon Anderson. ``And we're feeling the effects of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pistons at Hawks: The first round's wackiest series has seen the
Hawks win twice by 20 and the Pistons by 16 and 21. The Pistons
have momentum and three key strategic advantages.
</P>
<P>
   First, they have learned to double-team Dikembe Mutombo, who is
much better at cleaning up messes than making moves or dishing out
assists. In the first two games he amassed 45 points, then got off
only four shots in the Game 4 blowout. Also, the Hawks are without
small forwards Alan Henderson (eye) or Chris Crawford (shoulder)
and the game, because of a scheduling conflict, will be played at
Georgia Tech instead of the Georgia Dome.
Rocket flameout
</P>
<P>
   Was that the Rockets' last red glare yesterday? Not long ago
they were back-to-back champs. However, Houston played like
anything but a veteran, savvy group in being eliminated by the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley showed glimpses of his younger self, but at 36
will he be willing to stick around as a free agent next season for
another last chance to win a title? And is there any doubt that
Hakeem Olajuwon is headed downhill? He was overpowered by Shaquille
O'Neal, outscored by an average of 29-12. And there was Scottie
Trippin' Pippen: a key turnover in Game 1 and 0 points in Game 2
before a 37-point outburst in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying this season as much as any since going to the
Finals \Rwith the Suns in '93\S,'' Barkley said a while ago. ``But
if we lose early, it'll be hard to get excited about next season.''
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining players from Houston's two titles in '94 and
'95 are Olajuwon and Matt Bullard.
Best and worst
</P>
<P>
   Best clutch performance: Stockton's pick-and-roll jumper to win
Game 4 at Sacramento looked eerily similar to his miss in Game 6 of
last year's Finals loss to the Bulls _ except this one rattled in.
Talk about pressure; he misses that shot and the Jazz is
eliminated, along possibly with his and Karl Malone's last chance
for a title.
</P>
<P>
   Worst clutch performance: Terrell Brandon was on fire and Kevin
Garnett earns $126 million. Timberwolves fans had to be cringing
when veteran Sam Mitchell missed three consecutive jumpers and
threw a bad pass in the final 2:00 of yesterday's elimination loss
to the Spurs. Numbers game 8: Combined baskets by the Suns' Luc
Longley and Rex Chapman in their three-game loss to the Blazers.
24 seconds
</P>
<P>
   Most underrated player in the league is Portland forward Brian
Grant, who hit 23 of 32 shots against Phoenix. ... Worst free-agent
bust could be Orlando's ``Stone Cold'' Ike Austin, who made $5.2
million and produced one double-figure rebounding game in 54
appearances. ... If stubborn Dean Smith is the only man who could
hold Michael Jordan to 15 points, then boneheaded George Shinn is
the only man who could turn him down as a business partner. ...
Shame on the media for not voting the versatile Garnett first-team
or second-team All-Defense. ``I would not trade Kevin, defensively,
for any of the guys in front of him,'' said Minnesota coach Flip
Saunders. ... Clip and save for L.A.-S.A. from Spurs leader Mario
Elie: ``People have been hyping the Lakers all year. The way Shaq
talks, it's like he's got 10 banners, and he don't even have one.''
 &LR; tagtop:Richie Whitt (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:richie &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
