<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-STAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPLE CROWN RIVALRY, PART TWO?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The budding rivalry between Charismatic and Menifee
is eerily reminiscent of the Real Quiet vs. Victory Gallop battles
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Like Menifee, Victory Gallop finished second in the Derby and
was favored in the Preakness, but ran second again. Real Quiet won
both races. In the Belmont, however, Victory Gallop edged Real
Quiet to spoil his bid for the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Menifee and Victory Gallop are trained by Elliott Walden. ``It
would look kind of funny if I didn't run \RMenifee\S in the
Belmont,'' Walden said.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Chris Antley, who has had a great view of the rivalry
aboard Charismatic, can't fathom the sudden change in his fortunes.
Before this year, Antley had missed 18 months fighting weight
problems, and feared his career was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few months ago, I was staying with my mom and dad \Rin
South Carolina\S driving a '67 Mustang, playing the stock market to
keep me busy, and thinking about my future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, in the next minute, you're back in the game and maybe
ready to do something that hasn't been done in a long time. I have
a chance to win a Triple Crown.''
Spectator runs on track
</P>
<P>
   Pimlico avoided a power failure this year, but its Preakness
undercard was marred by a bizarre episode in which a spectator ran
onto the track during a race.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who was not identified, jumped the inside rail about a
sixteenth of a mile from the finish pole as horses in the Maryland
Breeders' Cup Handicap _ three races before the Preakness _ were
turning into the stretch. He swung his fist at some horses and
riders as they swerved to dodge him.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, the horses missed him and no one was injured.
Heavily favored Artax came closest to him, with jockey Jorge Chavez
having to move sharply inside to avoid a collision and pulling up
his horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking right at my horse,'' Chavez said. ``I was
afraid to move to one side or the other, so I waited till the last
second. He tried to punch my horse, but he missed and punched me in
the leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tense situation. I couldn't believe what was
happening. He could have killed my horse and maybe me, and himself.
Thank God everyone is all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The man was wrestled to the ground and taken away by security
officials, who said he was intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Pimlico officials refunded all money wagered on Artax, ruling as
if he had not run.
Vicar a surprise runner
</P>
<P>
   Vicar ran in the Preakness Stakes, although trainer Carl Nafzger
had repeatedly said he would be scratched because of his No. 13
post position.
</P>
<P>
   Nafzger changed his mind yesterday morning after Pimlico
officials convinced him that the post wasn't that bad. He probably
wishes he had stuck to his guns. Vicar finished 10th after running
18th in the Kentucky Derby.
Not excellent health
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, the only filly in the Preakness, did not
finish.
</P>
<P>
   She was pulled up nearing the stretch by jockey Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarian Larry Bramlage said on ABC that she suffered
respiratory bleeding, although she raced on anti-bleeding
medication Lasix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we'll just have to regroup,'' trainer Bob Baffert said.
A sincere thank you
</P>
<P>
   Entering the second turn of the Preakness, Chris Antley said
Charismatic was trapped briefly behind Stephen Got Even, ridden by
Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see he didn't have much horse,'' Antley said of
Stevens, ``and he actually gave me a little shot to get out. He
said, `Go on, little buddy.' I want to thank him for that.''
Wider is better
</P>
<P>
   Before the Preakness, trainer D. Wayne Lukas and Chris Antley
discussed the rail-favoring condition of Pimlico's strip.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas told Antley to ignore the bias and keep Charismatic on the
outside, as he did in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we could switch up our style to take advantage
of a rail bias,'' Lukas said. ``It's like any athletic contest. If
you get to the NCAA final with a press, you'd better press. I
actually think he made a bigger move this time than he did in the
Derby.''
Lone Star connection
</P>
<P>
   Allen's Oop, fourth in the Texas Mile at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie, finished second yesterday in the William Donald Schaefer
Handicap at Pimlico, the race before the Preakness. He was beaten
by a half-length.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's Oop is owned by James Jackson of Rockdale and trained by
Dallas Keen, the same connections of Valhol, who finished ninth in
the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Air, winner of the Premiere Stakes at Lone Star, faded to
fifth in the same race.
Preakness attendance solid
</P>
<P>
   The electrical blackout at Preakness last year didn't discourage
the Baltimore faithful this year.
</P>
<P>
   On-track attendance was 100,311, slightly less than the 103,269
last year and the 102,118 that turned out in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
