<HEADLINE>
TEXANS HAVE LINKS TO WOMAN WHO WILL BE AFRICAN QUEEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few people can boast that they have royalty in their family.
Edmond Sebugwawo of Keller, Texas, is one who can.
</P>
<P>
   His niece, Sylvia Nagginda Luswata, will become queen of the
African kingdom of Buganda this summer when she weds King Ronald
Muwenda Kimera Mutevi II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is looking to her as a Princess Diana,'' Sebugwawo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buganda, which has almost 7 million residents and 52 clans, is
in southeast Uganda. Decades of political strife caused many of its
people to scatter to places such as England, Sweden and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 friends and family members from Texas, California and
Oklahoma will say goodbye to the queen-to-be during a ceremony
Sunday at the Intercontinental Hotel in Dallas. Area Ugandans
estimate that 300 to 1,000 of their countrymen live in the Fort
Worth-Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to welcome her,'' said the Rev. Joseph Kamugisha,
president of the Uganda North American Association of Dallas and
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Many Ugandans living in the United States are expected to travel
to Africa for the wedding. The ceremony is important to the Baganda
_ the collective term for the people of Buganda _ because Luswata
will be the first queen since royalty was banished in 1966 during
the rule of then-Prime Minister Milton Obote.
</P>
<P>
   Luswata, 35, was born in England and raised in Uganda. She
studied at New York University and often visited the Metroplex to
reunite with relatives during holidays. Luswata and the king became
engaged on Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Luswata is expected to bring modern ways to the role of queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be the ladies who stayed in the palace. They
didn't do much, but things have changed. She's very independent,''
Sebugwawo said. ``We are very excited, because she has been one of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Edward Muteesa II, the father of Luswata's fiance, was the
last Buganda king before his son. King Mutevi, who was crowned in
1993, had lived in England for many years. He has been in Uganda
since his coronation.
</P>
<P>
   Mutevi ``was king, but he was a king without a kingdom,'' said
Francis Mayanja, a member of the Baganda who lives in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   The re-emergence of royalty in Uganda is seen as a sign of
stability in a country torn by political strife, civil war and the
cruelty of former dictator Idi Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the wedding of the century in Uganda,'' said
Sebastiane Lwanga, a North Texas resident who has known Luswata
about seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandans said the wedding allows the Baganda to reaffirm
traditions dating to 1200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this kingdom, we are not complete. We always had
somebody that we would look at to follow,'' Sebugwawo said.
</P>
<P>
   Buganda's hierarchy is similar to that of the British monarchy,
Mayanja said. A Muganda _ a singular member of the kingdom _ can
recite his or her family lineage back to the first Buganda king.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the queen comes, they will be introducing themselves by
saying which clan they came from and their lineage,'' Mayanja said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional dress will characterize the farewell ceremony Sunday
and the wedding, Mayanja said. Portions of the wedding will be
private, with rituals dating back hundreds of years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Buganda kingdom will flourish. Hopefully, they will have a
son and they will be able to carry on,'' Mayanja said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
