AFRICAN-AMERICAN WOMAN IS FIRST BLACK PhD FOR FORT WORTH SEMINARY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES and KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When some African-Americans in the ministry
learned of Cassandra Jones' plans to attend Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary, their words were harsh:
</P>
<P>
   ``One church leader told me, `Cassandra, if you go there, you
will be brainwashed and be no good to our community or to our
church,' '' said Jones, 41.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, she became the first African-American woman to receive
a doctorate from the Fort Worth seminary's school of educational
ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not brainwashed,'' she said. ``The professors here have
been wonderful. I've learned a lot. They genuinely cared about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was one of 330 master's and doctoral graduates to receive
diplomas in a ceremony at Travis Avenue Baptist Church in Fort
Worth on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who taught for 13 years in the Dallas public schools, was
a doctoral teaching fellow at the seminary. She said her seminary
years were good, but not hassle-free.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled comments made by two white students.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man told me he had never had a black teacher and he wasn't
going to start then. He withdrew from the class,'' she said. When
another student mentioned that he had never had a black teacher,
she asked him if her race was a problem. He said, `` `Not yet,' ''
she said. He remained in the class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the positive and the negative side,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who serves as national music director of the National
Baptist Convention U.S.A., the largest black Baptist denomination,
said it was difficult to hear opposition from black leaders she
respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are from the South, and they experienced how
white churches ... practiced bigotry,'' she said. When they grew
up, many ``vowed not to have anything to do with those
seminaries,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that black students get little or no financial
assistance from black denominations if they attend a white
seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our own,'' she said. ``All of my money, every dime,
came from Southern Baptist organizations and agencies _ all
white.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she is glad that, a year ago, Southwestern hired
Raymond Spencer, the school's first full-time African-American
faculty member. But she'd like to see the seminary become more
inclusive, using research produced by black scholars in every
discipline, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to teach at the college level.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
