<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LAUDS LEGISLATORS' ATTEMPT TO COMPROMISE ON HATE CRIME BILL
</HEADLINE>
 CRIMES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY DOCLAR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A day after the Senate rejected a hate crimes bill,
Gov. George W. Bush commended legislators for striving to reach a
compromise and said that Texas must rely on current law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senators of both parties tried hard,'' Bush said Saturday. ``I
put out a couple of suggestions. Good people just couldn't agree.
So now it's up to the prosecutors to use the current hate crimes
law. I hope citizens all across our state work diligently to treat
people with respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who gave the commencement address Saturday at Southern
Methodist University and later held a brief news conference, has
been accused of opposing the bill because it included protections
for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The governor insisted that the issue did not rest on the sexual
orientation provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, my position was, first of all, this was a moral conscience
vote on the Senate,'' he said. ``I stood back and said I was going
to analyze the bill once it made it off the floor of the Senate. It
never did.''
</P>
<P>
   However, when Bush was asked during a news conference in Austin
on March 22 if he thought lawmakers should include protections for
homosexuals in hate crimes legislation, he responded: ``No, I do
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been criticized by Democrats and activist groups for
remaining on the sidelines during the weeklong debate of the hate
crimes bill. They blamed his silence on not wanting to take a
stance on a divisive issue so close to his expected campaign for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not he intended it, the presidential campaign is
taking place on this floor today,'' said Sen. John Whitmire,
D-Houston, during an emotion-charged speech in the Senate chamber
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the way of a compromise, backers said, was the fact
that the bill would have punished crimes motivated by bias against
someone's sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``His unconscionable, immoral lack of leadership on this issue
is both tragic and exasperating,'' said Dianne Hardy-Garcia,
executive director of the Lesbian and Gay Rights Lobby of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said his office tried to come up with a compromise and
was unsuccessful. The bill was inspired by the racially motivated
dragging death of James Byrd Jr. in Jasper, Texas, last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was pleased that a bill that would require the
parents of a minor to be notified at least two days before a girl
could have an abortion won approval Friday by a House committee.
The bill is headed for the full House.
</P>
<P>
   The governor planned to talk about the bill to Texas Right to
Life, an anti-abortion group that held a fund-raiser luncheon
Saturday with Bush as keynote speaker. The event was not public,
but Bush said he planned to tell the group that ``I hope to get a
bill out that will reduce the number of abortions in the state of
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Right to Life spokeswoman Monica Hatcher said that Bush
was expected to speak about 10 minutes on his support for the
anti-abortion movement. The money generated by the $5,000-a-plate
event will be used for an anti-abortion ad campaign, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2222EDT &QL; 
