<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-LEAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERTS PUTTS WAY INTO LEAD WITH 62 AS TIGER FOLDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ For a time yesterday, the GTE Byron Nelson
Classic looked to be a rerun of that popular, long-running series,
It's a Tiger's World, and You're All Just Guests in It.'
</P>
<P>
   About halfway through the third round, however, a strange thing
happened: Tiger Woods got the hook and a veteran character actor
named Loren Roberts took center stage. Now he'll play leading man
in the final round of the $3 million tournament this afternoon at
Four Seasons Resort and Club.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, 43, is best-known for his nickname, ``Boss of the
Moss,'' a tribute to his exquisite putting touch. Yesterday, his
skill on the greens of the TPC propelled him to an 8-under-par 62,
the best round of the day, as he one-putted nine greens. That gave
him a tournament-record 54-hole total of 16-under 194 and a
two-shot lead over second-round co-leader Steve Pate, who battled
to a 68.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the other co-leader starting the day, led or shared the
top spot with Pate throughout the front nine but collapsed on the
back. He made three bogeys from the 11th through the 15th holes,
then found water with an errant tee shot on the par-3 17th hole.
From there, he suffered a golfing meltdown, recording a quadruple
bogey that dropped him to 8 under for the tournament after a 74 and
all but killed his chance of repeating his 1996 victory.
</P>
<P>
   That left Roberts and Pate, a pair of native Californians, away
from the pack, with Roberts six shots ahead of their closest
competitors, two-time U.S. Open champion Lee Janzen and teen
sensation Sergio Garcia, who are at 10-under 200. That gap, and the
likelihood of another day of howling wind, had Roberts confident:
The wind, he and Pate agreed, will make it difficult for any
challenger to shoot lights-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can shoot three or four under par \RSunday\S, they're
going to have to come catch me,'' Roberts said. ``It all depends on
what happens with the wind. Sunday's always a little bit tougher
unless you're coming from way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pate: ``It's possible to shoot low; it's not very likely.
It's more likely to shoot 75.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and Pate took different routes to the top. Roberts got
rolling with a four-foot birdie putt on the first hole, then set
the tone for his day on the fifth hole when he made a 40-footer
over a ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a little bonus,'' he said. ``The floodgates opened up
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   PGA Tour fans have come to expect the run of 12- to 15-foot
birdie putts Roberts embarked on after that. But Roberts also drove
well, hitting every fairway and every green but the 18th. A short
driver, Roberts ranks fifth on the tour in driving accuracy and
kept the ball in the fairway yesterday in spite of the vexing
crosswinds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the round of the year for me,'' said Roberts, who has
won five times on the PGA Tour, most recently in 1997 at the CVS
Charity Classic. He is 46th on the money list this year with
$364,869, largely on four top-10 finishes, including fifth at the
Shell Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   While Roberts cruised to his 62, Pate struggled to a 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit it nearly as well as I did the first two days,''
Pate said, noting that he spent much of his time off the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I was happy with my scoring. I made two bogeys.
I could've made a lot more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Roberts nor Pate was disappointed that most of the
attention went to Woods and Garcia yesterday, perhaps because that
allowed them to go about the business of climbing to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loren and I have been out here 15, 16 years,'' Pate said.
``There's no novelty in that.'' Referring to Woods and Garcia, he
added, ``They're the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they were yesterday. Today, though, the story is Roberts
and Pate. \Ntagtop:David A. Markiewicz, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:dmark\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
