r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TIGER-MELTDOWN-TE     05-15 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-MELTDOWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER TUMBLES TO EARTH WITH 74
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ His facial expressions yesterday bore the
intense look of an angry drill sergeant and the disappointment of a
crushed child.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, perhaps more than any member of the PGA Tour, wears
his emotions like a Nike emblem. Under constant scrutiny, Woods'
game is held to standards others can't meet.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, Woods can get a little wound up.
</P>
<P>
   During the third round of the GTE Byron Nelson Classic, Woods
and his day both unraveled on the same 17th hole that saw Fred
Couples' meltdown in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Couples triple-bogeyed the par-3 No. 17 last year and finished
with a final-round 72 to tie for second.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' problems began long before, with bogeys at Nos. 11, 14
and 15. Including a quadruple-bogey 7 at 17, Woods fell _ for the
tournament _ from 14 under (tied for first) to 8 under (tied for
11th) in seven holes.
</P>
<P>
   Woods granted no interviews after finishing a third-round 74
(4-over).
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia, the 19-year-old Spaniard making his professional
debut on the PGA Tour, took two deep, stunned breaths when told of
Woods' 7 on No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things happen,'' Garcia said. ``I was a little surprised.
When I saw the leader board on the 18th and saw him minus-8, I was
thinking `Is that wrong or what happened?' He hit a bad shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' attacking nature on the course had consequences
yesterday. In the end, the TPC Las Colinas course winds couldn't be
tamed with raw power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a needed rest,'' said Woods' playing partner, Steve
Pate, of waiting for Woods on No. 17. ``We've all been there, so it
doesn't tend to have any effect on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate said he thought Woods ``hit the wrong club'' off the No. 17
tee, a 6-iron. The drive landed in a greenside pond. Woods dropped
for a penalty on the pond's fairway side before hitting rocks on
the opposite end.
</P>
<P>
   Now on the fairway, Woods rolled a chip over the green and
needed three more strokes to find the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit a fairly solid shot,'' Pate said. ``He just didn't
gauge the wind right. Where his drop ended up is no picnic. That's
a severe penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   WOODS MELT DOWN Tiger Woods led at 14 under after 10 holes of
yesterday's GTE Byron Nelson Classic third round. But three bogeys
and a quadruple-bogey on the back nine unraveled his day. A
breakdown:
</P>
<P>
   No. 11, Par 4: Woods' second shot lands in a greenside bunker.
Sand wedge and two-putt for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   No. 14, par 4: Woods' iron off the tee lands behind a tree to
the right. Pitch shot lands short of water separating fairway and
green. Third shot to green and two-putt for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   No. 15, Par 4: Woods drives right and overshoots the green on
his second shot. Chip on is short and he two-putts for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   No. 17, par 3: Woods' 6-iron tee shot hits the water to the
right front of the green. He takes a penalty stroke, dropping in
rough on the back side of the pond. His wedge shot bangs off rocks
lining the green and back onto the fairway. Woods rolls a chip into
the backside rough, then chips onto the green. He two-putts for a
quadruple-bogey 7.
</P>
<P>
   Result: Woods falls from 14-under to 8-under in seven holes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
