<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8899 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VAN-GOGH-GOING-LADN     05-15 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAN-GOGH-GOING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS ATTEND NIGHTTIME VAN GOGH EXHIBIT IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE AND TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It was more like a nightclub than a gallery
Friday as hundreds of people dressed in everything from avant-garde
gear to $2,000 suits braved the twilight to see Vincent Van Gogh's
paintings in a Los Angeles exhibit's final hours.
</P>
<P>
   Some sipped martinis on a rooftop terrace. Children fell into
slumber while their parents marveled at the artwork. Others said
they enjoyed the absence, for the most part, of the elite culture
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an eeriness about this,'' said 52-year-old Lee Gurst
of suburban Sherman Oaks. ``Van Gogh only sold one painting in his
lifetime; now we can walk through here and see paintings that sell
for $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like going through the Egyptian pyramids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Museum of Art became the first in the
country to show a major exhibition on a 63-hour marathon basis,
which started Friday -- marking the final weekend for ``Van Gogh's
Van Goghs: Masterpieces From the Van Gogh Museum, Amsterdam.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the 70 paintings will return home. But not before
thousands of people will have viewed the display between 9 a.m.
Friday and midnight tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Another first for the museum was Club Van Gogh, an open-air
terrace featuring hors d'oeuvres, expensive drinks and music from a
jazz sextet. Booths sold replicas of the artist's famous ``The
Starry Night,'' alongside Van Gogh T-shirts and catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole event proves there's been a resurgence in the Los
Angeles art culture,'' said LACMA spokesman Adam Coyne, noting the
1997 opening of the Getty Center museum in Brentwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. has become a worldwide art destination -- an arts
leader,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers show as much.
</P>
<P>
   Since the exhibit opened Jan. 17, about 820,000 people have seen
the artwork -- the biggest LACMA hit since the ``Treasures of
Tutankhamen'' exhibit drew 1.2 million visitors in 1978, Coyne
said.
</P>
<P>
   It also came close to the nation's most well-attended art
exhibition, ``Treasure Houses of Britain,'' which attracted 990,474
visitors to the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C., in
1985, Coyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Gurst said he hopes the late-night museum scene stays alive,
thrilled by the fact he didn't have to push through a crowd to see
the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should open up museums late at night all the time,''
Gurst said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Garner of suburban Woodland Hills, whose brother got him
the tickets, said he also liked the unique night atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better to see on the last night when you can go out
with a bang instead of hanging with a bunch of stuck-up people,''
said 17-year-old Garner.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2243EDT &QL; 
