<HEADER>
A8901 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET--SPEED--2ndT     05-15 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET--SPEED--2nd </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INTERNET USERS, SPEED THRILLS -- AND COMPANIES MOVE TO MEET
DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ( Each has advantages and limitations. )
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to speed, nothing on the consumer market today can
beat a cable modem _ in theory.
</P>
<P>
   Under ideal conditions _ if you are the only one in the city
using the system _ cable modems offer lightning-fast download
speeds, up to 10 megabits per second, or 176 times faster than the
fastest dial-up modem, and more bandwidth than most customers could
conceivably put to use.
</P>
<P>
   The cable company, however, is not yet able to deliver that kind
of bandwidth to individual customers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, cable networks are shared systems. Like the water
pressure in an apartment building, the bandwidth is shared and
diminishes rapidly when everyone in the neighborhood goes online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, the cable guys keep on adding subscribers until the
customer complaints get too loud, then they add capacity,'' Dunsby
said.
</P>
<P>
   Road Runner and its cable brethren have heard complaints in
other cities, where prime-time access often slows to a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out on this,'' said Dempsey Yearry, another
tester of Time Warner's service. ``I'm curious to see what happens
when everyone gets on the pipe.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Goldberg, general manager of Road Runner in Kansas City,
says Time Warner has enough capacity in its upgraded network to
handle peak loads. And he says a slow cable modem will still beat
the top-speed service from the phone company.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company would argue that point.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell's answer to cable modems is called a Digital
Subscriber Line. Instead of requiring a new telephone line or an
ISDN connection, DSL can run on the same line as a voice call. The
phone company does it by extending the top frequency boundary on a
phone line and putting data on frequencies that aren't used by
voice.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference between cable modems and DSL is that DSL is a
dedicated service, meaning you don't share your bandwidth with your
neighbors. Consequently, the phone company can guarantee access
speeds, as Southwestern Bell plans to do.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell is touting the fact the DSL subscribers can
choose their own Internet service provider. And they point to their
stellar record of customer service, which happens to be the
Achilles heel of the cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone company is not your friend, but customer service is
in their lexicon,'' said Rosenberg of Insight Research.
</P>
<P>
   DSL has its shortcomings, too. To get the service, the end user
must live within three miles of the phone company's central office.
And the farther away you live, the lower the connection speed.
</P>
<P>
   Also, DSL works only over standard copper phone wires that run
all the way back to the central office. Because newer subdivisions
_ including many in Johnson County and North Kansas City _ are
served by a shared fiberoptic cable, they can't get the service.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner also will have trouble serving areas of Johnson
County until the end of the year, when it plans to complete the
upgrade of the cable networks formerly owned by TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell says it will be able to provide DSL service to
60 percent of the households in Kansas City when it rolls out the
product and invites customers to check availability in their area
on the company's Web site, {www.swbell.com}.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders feel those estimates are wildly optimistic.
Rosenberg's research puts the percentage of DSL-capable households
nationwide closer to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the difference between the two services may pale
beside the improvements that either provides over the current
generation of dial-up modems.
</P>
<P>
   Said Seley: ``Once you get used to this kind of surfing speed,
you can't go back.'' (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
