<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8902 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET--SPEED--2TAK     05-15 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET--SPEED--2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INTERNET USERS, SPEED THRILLS -- AND COMPANIES MOVE TO MEET
DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo _ Two weeks ago Shane Seley took a blind leap
into the uncharted future of cyberspace, a step that thousands of
Kansas Citians are eager to take.
</P>
<P>
   He bought a cable modem.
</P>
<P>
   Seley is one of 400 early-bird testers of Time Warner's Road
Runner, one of two services that will begin delivering high-speed
Internet access to Kansas City homes in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of cranking around the Internet at speeds up to
100 times faster than he could have achieved with his old dial-up
modem, Seley described the service with the enthusiasm of a true
believer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just smokin' fast,'' he said. ``This thing actually works
like the Internet should.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no more busy signals. No more screeching modems.
No more waiting for browsers to launch or Web sites to load.
</P>
<P>
   No more World Wide Wait.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever surfed the Internet from home can relate.
Instead of the easy access to text, audio and video that the
information highway was supposed to provide, most dial-up Internet
connections offer users a kind of perpetual electronic
rubbernecking: fast enough to grasp the potential, but too slow to
be truly useful.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   With high-speed access, Web pages _ even those with complex
graphics _ don't so much load onto your screen as pop up
instantaneously. Big graphics files _ such as the ``Star Wars''
trailer clogging corporate intranets across the country _ take
minutes, not hours, to download in their entirety.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, high-speed connections are ``always on.'' If
the computer is on, it is on-line, transforming the Internet into a
constant and far more useful presence in the home _ an information
appliance to check the weather, look up recipes, scan movie
listings, or do any of the day-to-day tasks that are too much
hassle with a dial-up connection.
</P>
<P>
   The pent-up demand for such a service is huge. And for many, the
need for speed is not just a convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a necessity,'' said Jon Kesovich, a systems administrator
for a software developer in California who plans to move to Kansas
City this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Kesovich will decide where to live based on the availability of
high-speed Internet service. ``I'm hoping to continue to work with
my office in Southern California....I can keep my job if I can get
high-speed access.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every neighborhood in Kansas City will have such access
immediately. And the two services coming to town initially are
being tight-lipped about their rollout plans.
</P>
<P>
   As in other parts of the country, cable will lead the charge.
Time Warner Cable says it already has 4,000 people on the waiting
list for its Road Runner service, which it will begin selling to
the general public at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   However, Southwestern Bell, in partnership with a variety of
local Internet service providers and Internet leviathan America
Online, is right on Road Runner's heels, promising to deliver a
similar service on standard phone lines by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, even Sprint plans to get in on the
action, introducing a bundled offering of phone service and
high-speed Internet access called ION.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're finally freeing the genie,'' said Robert Rosenberg,
president of Insight Research Corp. ``The cork is coming off the
bandwidth bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Long time coming The deployment of so-called broadband services
has been hyped for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching this thing closely since 1984,'' Rosenberg
said. ``Every year it's been three years away.''
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers have had a taste of things like Web browsing,
home shopping or stock trading over their dial-up connections. But
the staggering potential of the Internet remains largely untapped
because of inadequate connections to the home.
</P>
<P>
   The technology needed to fatten that pipe has existed for some
time. Most cable companies, however, weren't eager to spend
millions to upgrade their systems to carry two-way signals.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone companies also were reluctant to introduce a cheap
service that could undermine their lucrative business selling
high-speed ISDN and T1 connections to businesses for hundreds and
even thousands of dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
   With the explosion of the Internet, however, cable and phone
companies see a huge growth opportunity, both in the ability to
sell high-speed access, and the prospect of delivering new services
over the lines.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest drivers for broadband deployment _ as was the
case with VCRs and dial-up modems _ is adult entertainment,
observers say. But the widespread availability of high-speed
connections also will create an explosion of e-commerce, from
banking to gambling, music to travel. Most applications haven't
even been dreamed up yet.
</P>
<P>
   Most estimates put the number of households using broadband
connections at close to 20 million _ nearly one in five nationwide
_ by 2002. And according to Forrester Research, online shopping by
consumers will spiral from more than $7.8 billion in 1998 to $108
billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever gets the first pipe into the house is going to be able
to sell all kinds of add-on services,'' said Martin Dunsby, a
senior manager at Deloitte &AMP; Touche Management Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Dunsby said, whoever gets that customer first is likely to
keep him for some time because of the high cost of equipment and
installation.
</P>
<P>
   Just as wireless phone companies have buried consumers in hype,
industry observers are predicting a new marketing arms race between
the cable and telephone broadband services, each claiming higher
speeds, richer content, and better customer service.
</P>
<P>
   So who's telling the truth?
</P>
<P>
   The cable and telephone companies are using very different
technologies. Each has advantages and limitations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
