<SLUG> BC-BOAT-SAFETY--3rd </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI AMONG THE MOST DANGEROUS STATES FOR BOATERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA and DAWN FALLIK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   you're putting around the lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Frazier went out on Truman Lake on April 12, 1998, for
his first outing in his new 15-foot Streaker boat.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier and passenger David Braun anchored the boat from the
stern, something experts advise against.
</P>
<P>
   Winds of up to 25 mph created waves of at least 2 feet, filling
the boat with water. The men opened the back deck and saw water
about halfway up the gas tank. Their weight caused more water to
enter, swamping the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier and Braun started swimming to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Braun, a swimmer of moderate ability, did not make it.
Authorities say the shock of the 50-degree water and the weight of
his clothes prevented him from reaching the shore. Life jackets
were aboard but unused.
</P>
<P>
   The Water Patrol listed water conditions as the primary cause
but cited inexperience and inattention as contributing factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a difficult thing to deal with,'' said Frazier, of
Warrensburg.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say that boating is more dangerous than it appears
and that even experienced boaters can benefit from safety training.
</P>
<P>
   Many Missourians, however, choose not to take training classes.
The number of students in Water Patrol courses dropped 66 percent
from 1997 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   More boaters nationwide are taking courses over the Internet _
one safety group reports 35,000 Internet students since 1997. Even
Internet instructors, however, concede that their courses are no
match for live training.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen states _ but not Missouri or Kansas _ require mandatory
education.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Marvin, a longtime boater from Overland Park, said he would
support mandatory training even if he had to sit through a
repetitive class. He said he had noticed a lot of newcomers making
the waters dangerous. Many pull their motorized skis or boats too
close to others, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of them that need a little education,'' Marvin
said. ``They just get in the water and go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Water Patrol hopes to increase its enforcement ability. The
agency employs about 18 officers at Lake of the Ozarks, about 90
statewide. A federal grant, still under consideration, could add
officers next year.
</P>
<P>
   But enforcement isn't keeping up with the boats. And there is
always new traffic _ personal watercraft accidents have doubled
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Mosher said, boaters must watch out for their own
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have no respect for what boats can do,'' she said.
``They think the worst thing that can happen is they get wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think about running into the side of a boat on
their Jet Ski and getting their legs ripped off. A little common
sense is all you need. That would make things a lot safer.'' (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
