<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-SAFETY--2nd </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI AMONG THE MOST DANGEROUS STATES FOR BOATERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA and DAWN FALLIK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Water Patrol reports.
</P>
<P>
   With their 16-foot Bass Cat anchored on Table Rock Lake, Steve
Thurston and David Richardson did not wait long to break out the
whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   In the Water Patrol accident report, Richardson estimated that
they each drank about a pint of Canadian Mist.
</P>
<P>
   After several hours of fishing and drinking, Richardson said, he
was ``pretty drunk'' and fell asleep. Thurston began driving the
boat back to their hometown of Harrison, Ark., about midnight on
May 10, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Another boater, Harry Southwood, said he noticed a flash 90 feet
away and saw Richardson's boat speeding toward his Sea Nymph about
55 mph, well above the nighttime speed limit of 30 mph. The boat
had no lights on.
</P>
<P>
   The boats collided. Richardson awoke to a deafening crash.
</P>
<P>
   Southwood was not hurt, but the Water Patrol found Thurston
dead, submerged in about 2 feet of water. He had deep cuts on his
face and neck, and the boat's propeller had nearly amputated his
left arm.
</P>
<P>
   The odor of liquor wafted from the rear of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson did not want to talk about the accident last week,
but a close friend said the crash had a lasting effect: Richardson
no longer drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad that it takes something like this,'' said Sonia
Marler, a friend who had picked Richardson up at the crash scene.
</P>
<P>
   Others don't hear the warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri has more alcohol- and drug-related boating arrests than
any other state, according to Missouri Water Patrol figures. In
1998 the state made 535 arrests for boating under the influence and
1,322 for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 _ before the Water Patrol expanded checkpoints and
enforcement _ there were 331 BUI arrests and 1,008 drug arrests.
</P>
<P>
   New York, with almost 200,000 more registered boats than
Missouri, reported only about one-third as many arrests for
alcohol. Officials there say that only 10 percent of its accidents
involve alcohol, compared with 26 percent in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties for drunken boating in Missouri are much lighter
than for drunken driving. The first two violations are
misdemeanors. And violators don't have to worry about losing a
license _ boaters are not required to carry one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing as on the highways,'' said Connie Weyer, a
longtime boater from Sunrise Beach. ``You have 90 percent of the
people who are courteous and 10 percent who don't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same people who would have two or three drinks and not
drive a car will drink a six-pack or a 12-pack and drive a 4-ton
boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though safety experts say life jackets could prevent 80
percent of fatalities, only a tiny fraction of boaters will wear
them.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who can't swim well often forgo them.
</P>
<P>
   On July 23, Michael Stobaugh of Matthews took his 10-year-old
son for a fishing trip on Clearwater Lake in southeast Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Stobaugh couldn't swim and wasn't wearing a life jacket.
Missouri law requires them only for riders of personal watercraft
and boaters under 7. His son could swim but wore a life jacket
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The water was calm, the temperature 85 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Then their boat hit something, and both were thrown into the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Stobaugh's son took off his life jacket and tried to give it to
his father. The father refused. The boy screamed for help. As a
passer-by arrived, Stobaugh slipped underwater and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Stobaugh's wife, Marilyn, said she hoped such accidents would
spur people to wear life jackets, even if the water appeared safe.
Stobaugh said she would ``never, ever, ever'' ride a boat without a
life jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stress enough how important it is,'' she said. ``A
seemingly minor thing can change a person's whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three persons died in boating accidents last year, and 38
more drowned in Missouri waters. Most were not wearing life
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the evidence is there, trying to get adults to
wear life jackets is a real struggle,'' said Ruth Wood of the
BOAT//US Safety Foundation. ``Believe me, we've tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Indiana requires life jackets at all times. Hawaii, Idaho
and Wyoming have no requirements. Most states fall in the middle.
Kansas mandates life jackets for riders of personal watercraft and
boaters 12 and under.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities hope to encourage the use of life jackets through
public-awareness campaigns. Experts say inflatable life jackets
that are lighter and less cumbersome could increase their use. Such
jackets are being developed but are not yet in general use.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, life jackets are perceived as inconvenient. And many
boaters don't want to follow rules that can cramp their leisure
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on a boat, you want to be wearing nothing but
shorts,'' said Kenny Carroll, a Shawnee boater who never wears a
life jacket. ``You're kicking back and want to get a good tan. You
don't want to be wearing something that is going to annoy you as
you're putting around the lake.''
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
