<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOAT-SAFETY--3TAKES-K     05-15 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-SAFETY--3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI AMONG THE MOST DANGEROUS STATES FOR BOATERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA and DAWN FALLIK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE OZARK, Mo. _ Officer Stacey Mosher hears her dispatch radio
crackle a report of an injury accident. She guns her Missouri Water
Patrol speedboat and heads for the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Mosher discovers a woman who has slipped and hit her head; blood
streams from the cut. The injury appears minor.
</P>
<P>
   The real dangers, Mosher says, are still to come.
</P>
<P>
   On Memorial Day the Lake of the Ozarks will be overrun by
boaters _ as many as 40,000. The summer boating season will bring
the threat of more serious injuries and even deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is one of the most dangerous states for boaters,
according to an analysis of U.S. Coast Guard data. The agency
tracks serious accidents, those involving injury or death, or
damage exceeding $500.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Missouri ranked fourth, with 333 serious boating
accidents, and 11th in fatalities, with 25. According to an
analysis by state water officials, Missouri ranked first in arrests
related to drugs and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who come down here with more horsepower than
brains,'' Mosher said. ``That makes it dangerous for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The states with higher accident counts _ Florida, California and
Michigan _ have more miles of waterway and more registered boats.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, boaters were involved in 60 accidents and four
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities attribute Missouri's accident rates to too many
boats, too much alcohol and too few safeguards. In particular they
worry about the Lake of the Ozarks, where more than half the
state's accidents occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything goes at the lake,'' said Lou Mayer, a longtime
homeowner at the lake. ``It's like the Wild West all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri lacks the expansive waters of coastal states.
Competition for limited space makes it seem even tighter. Docks
extend from a growing number of residential projects. Boat
registrations are up 20 percent since 1990, and a new generation of
motorized-ski operators fights for a share of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Water Patrol officials say some boaters have surprisingly little
regard for the damage their vehicles can cause.
</P>
<P>
   As boats get bigger, many operators plow across the lake with
little fear, while others dart among the traffic on personal
watercraft, which now account for 30 percent of boating accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Most safeguards are voluntary, not mandated by Missouri law.
</P>
<P>
   Adults can legally operate a boat during the day at any speed
with no life jacket, no training and an open bottle of booze at
their side. With no lanes or stop signs, boaters often make
split-second decisions as they navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals for stricter boating laws have not been well-received
by those with financial interests in the lake, such as condo
builders and marina operators. Similarly, some vacationers grouse
at the prospect of more regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, laws setting nighttime speed limits and
establishing more drunken-boating checkpoints have been enacted,
but more- expansive proposals have failed in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Laws do make a difference. After Missouri enacted a law in 1997
that raised the minimum age for personal-watercraft operators from
12 to 14, accidents dropped 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Boating is increasing nationwide _ Missouri boat registration
tops 326,000 _ and some experts say lawmakers are taking action to
make waterways safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later you get to the point where the sheer numbers
create the conflicts,'' said Bill Engfer, president of the National
Association of State Boating Law Administrators. ``At this point
it's no longer a question of whether we should or shouldn't improve
boating laws. It's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Safe Boating Council says nearly all injuries and
fatalities could be prevented through three things: more
responsible use of alcohol; the use of life jackets; and education.
</P>
<P>
   And many of Missouri's 23 boating fatalities in 1998 listed one
of those factors as a primary or a contributing cause, according to
Water Patrol reports.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
