<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHER-FESTIVAL-KAN &LR;      05-15 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-FESTIVAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN FESTIVAL RAISES SCHOLARSHIP MONEY FOR EVERY STUDENT IN
SMALL KANSAS TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRONTENAC, Kan. _ Could teen-age cliques _ that high school
phenomena now so fearsome to parents across the nation _ be negated
with sumptuous helpings of risotto, chicken cacciatore, pasta
cordon, lasagna, crostini and ravoli?
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense to folks here.
</P>
<P>
   On April 10 residents of Frontenac, a southeast Kansas town,
turned out in droves for what's called Festa Italiana. They brought
home-cooked dishes like the above, had a wonderful time and raised
$35,500.
</P>
<P>
   That money _ and money realized from future festivals _ will
guarantee scholarships to graduates of Frontenac High who attend a
university, a junior college or a technical or trade school.
</P>
<P>
   That means everybody _ the jocks, the techies, the brains, the
nerds, the preppies, the weirdoes, the ins, the outs, the popular
and the not so popular, even the farm kid with cow manure on his
boots.
</P>
<P>
   This fall those here who choose to continue their education will
receive $100 a semester for four years.
</P>
<P>
   And Gary Cinotto, president-elect of the Frontenac Education
Foundation, which with the Pittsburg /{ Morning Sun/} sponsored the
festival, says people haven't seen anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may think $100 a semester isn't much,'' he said. ``But
it's just a start. We can increase it fairly rapidly. Look at the
response we got last month. This will grow. Four hundred dollars a
semester isn't out of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Why scholarships from a town as a whole?
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to show every student is that if he or she has
the gumption to go on from high school, we're behind them,'' said
Linda Grilz, president of the foundation. ``No ifs, ands or buts.
We value them. And they must value themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after Festa Italiana came the tragedy at Columbine High
school in Littleton, Colo. Nobody here said, ``I told you so.''
Nobody got puffed up with self-congratulation, because people here
know that what happened in Littleton can happen anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Frontenac, Cinotto said, has its little cliques like any school,
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser was just one step, in retrospect oddly
prescient. And, above all, unique.
</P>
<P>
   But then Frontenac and Unified School District 249 aren't
exactly a big-town suburban district. The school and the district
/{ are /} Frontenac, population roughly 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   District 249 is small _ 316 in high school, 361 in elementary.
Just about every student participates in something _ sports, band,
clubs, whatever. Kids ]Young people were all over the place at the
festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontenac is where if you mess up in school you'll not only
hear about it there but your parents' phone will be ringing long
before you get home,'' said Debbie Bridwell, a foundation board
member. ``This whole town raises these kids. That sounds
old-fashioned, but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, started in 1993, two years ago raised $250,000
to provide computers, technical equipment and furnishings for
Layden Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   That done, somebody asked if hardware was enough? Kids, the
reasoning went, were Frontenac's lifeblood. What more concrete
things could be done to send a message to the children that they
were more than just young bodies moving in and out of tax-supported
schools?
</P>
<P>
   Festa Italiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have almost 30 scholarships here in town available to
students,'' Grilz said. ``People, over the years, have made
bequests for a kid to have some extra money at the school he
chooses. Or somebody's donated so a student going to a certain
school can get some help. But this, I've been told, is one of the
few places where the a whole town has put it on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Fogliasso, another board member, said Frontenac wasn't
going to wait around for a ``sugar daddy,'' one of those admirable
yet rare individuals who endear themselves to a community and get a
ton of publicity when they commit to sending every child to
college.
</P>
<P>
   Frontenac, a largely Italian-American, Catholic, working-class
community, knew there probably wouldn't be any such outside
windfall, Fogliasso said. So, he said, it was up to the town.
</P>
<P>
   The people had responded before. A couple of years ago a bond
issue was proposed to finance a new, $2.5 million high school.
</P>
<P>
   Some fretted. The old high school _ which would have to be torn
down to make way for the new one _ oozed sentimentality, its
history going back to the 1920s. Some feared poignant memories and
a backlash against modernity might sway some patrons, 38 percent of
whom are retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Seventy-five percent of the voters turned out; the
bonds passed 70-30, a figure most other school districts would kill
for.
</P>
<P>
   Still, raising money for scholarships isn't exactly the same as
brick and mortar. Didn't matter, Grilz said.
</P>
<P>
   What the foundation relied on, she said, was the
Italian-Americans' love of good food, maybe a glass of wine, a
long-overdue celebration of their heritage, and concern for the
future of their children, grandchildren, great-grandchildren and so
on.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering at the nearby Frontenac Greyhound Racetrack
(formerly Camptown) featured a walk for cash, the Italian dishes,
wine tasting, 50 sponsors including Alitalia Airlines, an auction
and a raffle, and several hundred people visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought maybe we'd raise $15,000, tops,'' Grilz said. ``We
ended up with more than double that. We were absolutely stunned.
There were hundreds and hundreds who took part in the walk. And
we've hardly touched the people who've moved away from here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Contributions to the foundation can be sent to 208 S. Cayuga,
Frontenac, KS 66763).
</P>
<P>
   What amazed the board was the enthusiasm of Frontenac's older
generation. It wasn't uncommon, said Pat Terlip, board treasurer,
that people in their 70s and 80s _ especially women _ stayed up
well past their normal bedtimes on April 9 putting the finishing
touches on some favorite Italian dish they took to the racetrack
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like this around here,'' Cinotto said.
``People will drive a long way for the food we have. So we're using
the big Italian-American get-together on the Hill over in St. Louis
as our model,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, this could turn out to be really something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
