</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-COLUMN-HARTFORD-IMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT COLUMN: MUST HARTFORD KEEP GRASPING AT THE BIG TIME? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Homer Simpson entered the ``How Low Will You
Go'' gross-out competition in last week's episode of ``The
Simpsons'' because the prize promised a trip to Hawaii. But it
turned out the ticket was really to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   This prompted The Hartford Courant to ask the cartoon show's
producers if Hartford had been insulted. No, said the producers. A
trip to upstate New York would be an insult, they said, but a
sucker prize to Hartford, that was a compliment. This seemed to
satisfy The Courant.  &UR; D'oh. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To hear them tell it, people in Hartford have been spending a
lot of time worrying about their city's reputation these days, now
that Hartford has been worked over by another big-time
entertainment outfit, this time the New England Patriots. The
football team promised to move to Hartford if the state would pay
for a new, $375 million stadium. Unlike the newspaper, legislators
did not stop to ask if they were being insulted before they voted
to spend the money. But the Pats then said no thanks when they got
an improved offer from Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   So Hartford is deep into one of its periods of self-analysis, of
the sort it last went through two years ago when the state's only
major league team, the Hartford Whalers of the National Hockey
League, ran off to North Carolina. The dominant view is still that
Hartford must do what it takes to join the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the richest state in the union,'' said Francis
DelMastro, owner of the Civic Cafe, on Trumbull Street. ``We have
more money per capita than anywhere else, and we're still getting
dictated to by Boston and New York. And unless we keep making bold
moves, like we did for the Patriots, we're not going to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Parker, the manager at Coach's Sports Bar, lamented his
city's small-town reputation. ``You look at Hartford, stuck here
between New York and Boston, and you've got to admit, it's been
always a bridesmaid, never a bride for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford metropolitan area, 37th in size nationally, has
lost population since 1990, while Boston (7th) and New York (1st)
have grown. The once dominant insurance industry is now largely run
by out-of-town conglomerates, and despite the wealth of its
suburbs, the city has large pockets of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But the downtown business district and the state Capitol area
have a Midwestern openness and greenness in springtime. They are
spotlessly clean and, on an early morning, offer visitors an easy
and relaxed atmosphere by big-city standards. It may or may not
mean anything that Hartford has two memorials to the inventor of
anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   And some people like it this way. For all the official
scrambling for the trappings of the big time, there are dissenting
voices that want Hartford to stop trying to keep up with the
neighbors and focus on what it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hartford has to get over this thing it has about New York and
Boston and be glad the way it is,'' said Patrick Brossard, who was
at the Civic Center last week to watch the minor-league Hartford
Wolfpack hockey team. ``I drove in from Windsor Locks, I parked
right here, and after the game I'm home in 20 minutes. Can you do
that in New York?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some boosters of downtown Hartford wish people would
think of something other than ease of access to the outbound
Interstate. Molly Browning is the public relations director of the
Greater Hartford Arts Council, and she has all the subtlety of her
native Texas when arguing that Hartford already has what it takes,
if only people would pay a little attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hartford had a thriving, nationally important arts community
long before anyone started talking about bringing the Patriots
here,'' she said, ``and what absolutely galls me is that nobody is
saying, `Hey, guys, we already have it all right here.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford Stage Company is a strong regional theater, Ms.
Browning pointed out. The Connecticut Opera has just brought in a
seasoned new music director, Willie A. Waters. At the Wadsworth
Atheneum, crowds lined up last week to see the new Georgia O'Keeffe
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is this city going to decide to go with what it's got,''
Ms. Browning went on, ``and stop waiting for someone to come in
from the outside?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
