<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ, HIRSCHBECK CLEAR AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ Catcher Ivan Rodriguez made a special trip to
the umpire's dressing room after Friday's game to meet with umpire
John Hirschbeck and discuss their ninth-inning fracas. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Everything is cleared up,'' Rodriguez said. ``We both got a
little bit mad. It happens.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez thought Delino DeShields' ninth-inning dribbler was
foul when he picked it up. Hirschbeck ruled it was on the line and
called it fair. The two started screaming at each other while
manager Johnny Oates tried to separate them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were also words after the game, but Hirschbeck, who said
he appreciated the post-game gesture, said Rodriguez was not
ejected and there is no reason to file a report with the league. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good relationship with umpires,'' Rodriguez said. ``I
usually never get mad with umpires. But some times those things can
happen.'' &QL; 
Simms to resume rehab &QL; 
Reserve outfielder Mike Simms will resume his medical
rehabilitation assignment Wednesday barring any setbacks. With
Triple-A Oklahoma and Double-A Tulsa scheduled to play on the road,
The Rangers are undecided where Simms (torn tendon, left Achilles)
will be assigned, assistant general manager Dan O'Brien said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of looking forward to it because I'm finally
pain-free,'' Simms said. &QL; 
Clark takes BP &QL; 
Orioles first baseman Will Clark took batting practice on the field
yesterday for the first time since fracturing his left thumb April
18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clark could be reinstated from the 15-day disabled list before
the Rangers travel to Baltimore for a three-game series scheduled
to begin Friday. &QL; 
Athletics impress Oates &QL; 
The Oakland Athletics haven't had a winning season since 1992, but
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said he's not surprised they're three
games over .500 with their five-game winning streak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a good ballclub,'' Oates said. ``I've said that all
year. Putting Tony Phillips and Tim Raines in there with some good
young hitters was good, and they have some pretty good arms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing is I don't think overall they have as much
depth as the other teams in the division. They can't afford to lose
too many guys. If they lose two or three guys like \RMatt\S Stairs
or \RMiguel\S Tejada, it probably makes it a little more of a
difference with them.'' &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
Rangers left-hander Eric Gunderson, who went on the 15-day disabled
list May 8 with tightness in his left shoulder, is scheduled to be
examined today by Dr. John Conway, the Rangers' orthopedic
consultant. Gunderson underwent a magnetic-resonance-imaging test
Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez received credit for a seventh-inning
stolen base Friday after a scoring change announced yesterday. That
gave Rodriguez a career-high 10 stolen bases and established a
season record for a Rangers catcher. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle recalled right-hander Jordan Zimmerman from Double-A New
Haven of the Eastern League yesterday. Zimmerman is the younger
brother of Rangers right-hander Jeff Zimmerman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers promoted left-hander Robert Quarnstrom from Class-A
Charlotte to Double-A Tulsa. The Drillers needed a fresh reliever,
and Quarnstrom will return to Charlotte in the near future,
assistant general manager Dan O'Brien said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers purchased the contract of Ryan Karp from the
Atlantic League and assigned the left-hander to Tulsa. Karp, who
made 16 major-league appearances for the Philadelphia Phillies
during the 1995 and '97 seasons, will join the Drillers' bullpen. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
