<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONESTAR-ABAJO-TEX </SLUG>
 
Abajo sets Lone Star track record 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mary Rampellini 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Jockey Donnie Meche capped an outstanding
afternoon yesterday at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie with his
victory aboard Abajo in the $100,000 Alysheba Breeders' Cup. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A crowd of 11,739 spectators watched Meche win four races and
wagered $457,536 on the local simulcast of the Preakness Stakes
from Baltimore. From all sources, the track's handle had topped
$4.45 million by 8 p.m. yesterday, and was expected to be more than
the $4,446,191 wagered the day of the Preakness last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Alysheba Breeders' Cup, Abajo raced about a half-length
behind Fantastic Finish early in the seven-furlong sprint before
moving to a commanding lead entering the homestretch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He proceeded to dart clear of fast-closing Lexington Park by a
length, and covered the distance in a track-record time of 1
minute, 21.58 seconds, lowering the 1:21.70 standard set by The
Last Spell in 1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't feel like he's going that fast,'' Meche said. ``He
has a nice, long stride to him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abajo is trained by Steve Asmussen, who won three races
yesterday at Lone Star, and saddled Dreams Gallore to a
second-place finish Friday in the Black-Eyed Susan Stakes at
Pimlico Race Course. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's for real,'' Asmussen said of Abajo. ``He's a fast-running
son of a gun. And he looked so good doing it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abajo has won three of seven starts for owner Bill Heiligbrodt
of Houston. He earned $30,000 for the victory, improving his career
earnings to $82,081. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lexington Park earned $20,000 for finishing second in the
Alysheba. Unlike the winner, Lexington Park is Breeders' Cup
nominated, making him eligible for additional purse funds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abajo returned $9 as second choice in wagering. Trickey Crew,
the favorite, finished fifth after racing wide entering the
stretch. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
