<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-BLESSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLESSING WHEELS FOR PERILOUS TRAVELS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the holy water, hurled by a white-robed church
elder, fell upon their heads and on the handlebars of their 1962
Schwinn Twin tandem Saturday, Harris Silver and his wife, Roz
Makarechi, exhaled and exchanged a relieved glance.
</P>
<P>
   Not because of a belief in God as much as the hope that the
sprinkle would prove an effective taxi repellant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel with 20,000 taxis in New York and a mayor gone after
us, we definitely need all the help we can get,'' Silver, 33, an
avid cyclist from Greenwich Village, said in a low voice
immediately afterward. ``Even as atheists.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the tone of the Blessing of the Bicycles inside the
Cathedral Church of St. John the Divine on the Upper West Side of
Manhattan, where more than 100 cyclists gathered with their bikes
to indemnify themselves from harm on New York's inhospitable
streets.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-minute bike blessing was performed by the Very Rev. Harry
Pritchett, who read from the book of Ezekiel and from Psalms,
hurled holy water on cyclists _ of both the neon Lycra and
sweatpants-and-sneakers varieties _ and administered a moment of
silence to remember riders killed in accidents with motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the living creatures moved, the wheels moved beside them;
and when the living creatures rose from the earth, the wheels
rose,'' intoned Pritchett, reading Ezekiel to the cyclists under
the cavernous church apse. ``Wherever the spirit would go, they
went and the wheels rose along with them; for the spirit of the
living creatures was in the wheels.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 cyclists are killed in New York City each year, said
Charles Komanoff of Right of Way, a bicycle group that produces
street memorials for fallen cyclists. During Saturday's moment of
silence, Komanoff read off names of some of the deceased.
</P>
<P>
   Then Pritchett sprinkled holy water over the two rows of
cyclists as a small choir sang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that kosher hol water?'' asked one cyclist, Mike Kaback,
57, of Manhattan. ``It's Saturday, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   The bike blessing, said to be the first of its kind in New York,
was organized jointly by two rival bike clubs, the Five-Borough
Bike Club and the New York Cycle Club, as a kind of good will
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two clubs don't get along sometimes, so we thought this
would be a nice thing to do,'' Glen Goldstein, one of the
blessing's organizers, said before the service.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cyclists planned to complete Sunday's Montauk
Century, a 100-mile haul from Penn Station to the tip of Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``May the road rise to meet you, may the wind be ever at your
back,'' Pritchett said in a solemn closing benediction. ``And until
we meet again, may the Lord hold you and your bicycles in the palm
of His hand. Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most cyclists, Pamela Blumenthal, a lawyer from Washington,
emerged from the blessing feeling refreshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a lovely service,'' said Ms. Blumenthal, 31.
``I don't think it was a joke at all.'' Asked if the bicycle
blessing made her feel safer on the road now, Ms. Blumenthal
squinted her eyes and paused. ``No. But I feel cared for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
