u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT     05-15 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT PHILLIES, 9-6  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The cat that scampered all the way from right
field into the Mets' dugout during the third inning Saturday night
wasn't black. But it might as well have been.
</P>
<P>
   An awfully ugly spell has befallen the Mets' ace, Al Leiter,
this season, and Saturday night the Mets needed a heroic comeback
against even shabbier pitching from the Phillies to win their third
game in a row, 9-6. With the victory, the Mets (21-15) are a
half-game better than the Yankees, and a half-game behind Atlanta
in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   But the good news only temporarily pushes to the background what
surely must be an emerging concern among the Mets. Leiter was 17-6
with a 2.47 earned run average last season, but he has been
strangely ineffective much of this season. Saturday night he gave
up seven hits and six runs in three innings, his shortest
appearance in almost two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets got Leiter off the hook because the Phillies left their
starter, Carlton Loewer, in the game even after it was obvious that
he was incapable of holding a 6-0 lead. The Mets got five runs back
in the fourth inning, while reliever Pat Mahomes, called up from
Class AAA Norfolk only Friday, held the Phillies scoreless for two
and a third innings.
</P>
<P>
   They tied it in the fifth inning with a Brian McRae solo home
run. But the Mets could have taken the lead when Mahomes, in his
first major league at-bat, hit a double to right-center field. Rey
Ordonez, who had been on first base, ran hard all the way, but a
perfect relay from center fielder Doug Glanville to shortstop Alex
Arias to catcher Mike Lieberthal nailed him as he slid in
headfirst.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finally took the lead in the sixth, when reliever Ken
Ryan made the mistake of walking Roger Cedeno, the Mets' leadoff
hitter and superb stealer. Cedeno took an enormous lead off first _
both feet were on the turf _ and stole second on a pitchout. With
an equally huge lead off second, he came around to score when
Edgardo Alfonzo hit a single over the mound and into center field.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud walked on four pitches, and the stage was set for
Mike Piazza to break out of a minifunk. When the count was full,
everyone in the stadium waited for an enormous blast. Instead, with
Alfonzo and Olerud running on the pitch, Piazza hit a liner to
Arias for one out. Arias tossed the ball to second baseman Kevin
Jordan, who stepped on second to get the force on Alfonzo and then
reached over to tag Olerud just two feet away for the simplest
triple play imaginable and the first against the Mets since May 11,
1993, against St. Louis. Piazza ripped off his batting helmet in
disgust and repeatedly slammed it against his thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter contains his angst better. Each time the Phillies hit him
hard, he would turn around on the mound, his face tightened in the
grimace of a man unfortunate enough to watch his own execution.
Leiter has struggled with his consistency all season. But after his
last start, when he gave up a career-high eight runs in seven
innings against Colorado, Manager Bobby Valentine and the pitching
coach Bob Apodaca insisted that Leiter is throwing even better than
he did last year, that he has not been hit hard and that he is
merely the victim of bad luck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8942 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      05-15 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWICE BURNED AT THE STAKE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the time comes for her trial, the accused murderer Kelly
Blake won't be hauled into court in shackles. Authorities have
overwhelming evidence that Blake cruelly slaughtered two of her own
children and tried to kill a third, and for that, prosecutors would
love to lead her around in irons.
</P>
<P>
   But, they can't.
</P>
<P>
   The manacles would slip off the stumps.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Blake's hands are gone. As are her nose, her eyebrows, her
ears, her lips. Any chains attached to her ankles would have to be
wrapped around the braces she must wear in order to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she's much of a flight risk.
</P>
<P>
   Walking even a few steps requires assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can't do anything on her own,'' says Blake's attorney,
Arthur Gorman. ``The fire destroyed her. She can't eat or dress or
go to the bathroom. Is that not punishment enough?''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   At least, not for Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley, who
recently charged Blake with murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``She killed her two children. She attempted to kill her
third,'' Romley told a news conference. ``It is this office's
responsibility to say that children are important.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 20, 1998, Kelly Blake led her three children into a
shed attached to their home on Clarendon Avenue in Phoenix. She
told them it was a game. &QL; 
DESCRIBED AS `DANGER'
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that same month, Blake twice visited a county mental
health clinic, depressed. She was released with a prescription for
relaxants. One of the nurses who saw her wrote that Blake was ``a
danger to herself, children.''
</P>
<P>
   And she was.
</P>
<P>
   She blindfolded the kids, closed them inside the shed, doused it
with gasoline and lit it. Then she poured gas over herself and
stepped into the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Nine-year-old Venessa Fausto and 12-year-old Ramon Fausto died.
Blake's 14-year-old son John Fausto escaped with minor injuries.
Kelly was taken to the hospital with third-degree burns over 85
percent of her body.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't die.
</P>
<P>
   The death sentence she'd imposed upon herself was commuted to
life without parole. Kelly Blake lives in solitary confinement,
locked securely within the charred prison cell of her body, from
which there's no escape.
</P>
<P>
   She's already burned herself at the stake. There's no need to
relight the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vindictive prosecution,'' Gorman said. ``They didn't
do anything until after I sued them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gorman filed a lawsuit against the county and others
on behalf of Blake and her surviving son, claiming the county's
health care system failed them. &QL; 
SERVICES NOT PROVIDED
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't provide the services that would have prevented
this from happening, and now they're going to prosecute her,''
Gorman said. ``Prosecutors say they were waiting for Kelly to be
competent before they filed charges. Well, she had been competent
for months, and they didn't do anything until we sued them.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake is taking multiple medications. She's at risk for
infection. There may not be a facility in the state's prison system
that could adequately deal with someone in her condition. If
convicted, she could wind up in the same care facility where she
now lives.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, what's the rush?
</P>
<P>
   If, by some miracle, Blake improved and was able to lead a
``normal'' life, charges could be filed. There's no statute of
limitations on murder.
</P>
<P>
   Romley has said of Blake, ``As a parent, you have an obligation
to your children and you will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecuting this woman doesn't make her accountable, though.
</P>
<P>
   It only makes her a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   And wastes thousands of tax dollars that could be spent putting
other criminals behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about pity, or even mercy.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't about avoiding justice.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't about a killer going scot-free.
</P>
<P>
   Before anybody talks about Kelly Blake ``getting away with
murder,'' they should remember why it is the police can't take her
fingerprints. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
