<DOCNO> NYT19990515.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-15 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-REUNION-NYT     05-15 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-REUNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFERSON'S KIN NOT READY TO ACCEPT TIE TO SLAVE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ For the first time in nearly 90 years,
descendants of Thomas Jefferson on Saturday welcomed to their
annual family reunion descendants of children who claimed to have
Jefferson as their father and Sally Hemings, one of his slaves, as
their mother.
</P>
<P>
   And for long, sunlit moments late Saturday afternoon, the two
groups lingered together here on the verdant lawns of Monticello,
the plantation home built by slaves where Jefferson, the nation's
third president and author of the Declaration of Independence,
lived for more than 50 years until his death in 1826.
</P>
<P>
   But attitudes die hard among Jefferson descendants. For 200
years, oral histories of an illicit relationship have been passed
down by Hemings progeny, and recent genetic research suggests
Jefferson fathered at least one illegitimate child by her. But on
Saturday, the official organization of Jefferson's family said it
was not yet prepared to accept the Hemings line as Jefferson
descendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about accuracy,'' Robert Gillespie, a
Richmond lawyer who is president of the group, known as the
Monticello Association, told an audience that included Jefferson
and Hemings descendants, and many reporters. ``More evidence is
coming forward, and we invite it. But let's make sure we make the
correct decision, not a quick decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie said the association's six-member executive committee
had met privately Saturday morning to discuss the possibility of
allowing Hemings' relatives to join the group, which has among its
privileges the right to be buried with Jefferson in the family
cemetery at Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than respond to a groundswell of recent pressure and
publicity generated by Lucian K. Truscott IV, an author and direct
Jefferson descendant who has taken up the cause of the Hemingses,
Gillespie said the association would await further scientific
testing, more oral histories and whatever genealogical evidence
that Hemings' descendants could produce. He said a final decision
through a vote of the association's 700 members could take as long
as a year.
</P>
<P>
   Truscott, whose great grandmother, Mary Walker Randolph, was a
Jefferson granddaughter, called the delay racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this family, the word `genealogy' is a code word for
racism,'' Truscott said. `'But I'm going to make it much, much
harder for them to exclude the Hemings than to let them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie denied that racism had played a role in the executive
committee's decision. ``We have to live with this,' he said. ``Yes,
maybe some people will be disappointed. But many more will be
disappointed if we rush into it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jefferson descendants have been meeting here for the last
86 years, no previous reunion has matched this one for sheer drama.
In November, geneticists supported what Hemings descendants always
contended, that at least one of Hemings' sons, Eston, was probably
fathered by Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to convince Truscott that Eston's line, as well
as those of Hemings' two other sons, Thomas C. Woodson and Madison
Hemings, deserved affirmation of their heritage as a true
reflection of Jefferson and his times _ and, perhaps, as a symbolic
step toward healing racial wounds that still exist.
</P>
<P>
   The study actually said that Thomas Woodson was probably not
Jefferson's son. But Truscott said that did not matter to him,
adding that all of the descendants of Sally Hemings deserved to be
accepted as members of the larger Jefferson family.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Truscott invited about 35 Hemings descendants to
the reunion, a weekend that included a reception at Monticello
Saturday evening and the association's annual meeting on Sunday.
Rather than risk any public reproach for appearing indifferent to
Truscott's overture, the association then issued its own invitation
to the Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was clear Saturday that many of the 200 Jefferson
descendants here were unwilling to open their arms _ not to mention
the family cemetery _ to descendants of Jefferson's slave.
</P>
<P>
   After Gillespie greeted all the guests from a podium on the
steps of the main house, Truscott followed with brief remarks in
which he told association members it was time for them `'to do the
right thing, to welcome these good people into our hearts and our
family.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished to rousing cheers from Hemings' descendants but
tepid applause from association members. When a Hemings invited all
the guests to collect on the steps for a family picture, many
association members hung back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this needs to be studied, studied and studied, then it
will be resolved,'' said Frank Walker, an association member who
had declined to join the group at the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Many association members were skittish about discussing the
matter with reporters. Some simply walked away. Others, like
Walker, declined to say how they felt about the possibility they
might be related to descendants of a slave. ``Now is not the time
to be opinionated about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, many of the Hemings family members expressed
unbridled joy _ a happiness to be invited, to meet family members
they never knew and to help cast light on an American icon who
owned as many as 80 slaves yet espoused the bedrock democratic
belief that all men are created equal.
</P>
<P>
   Shay Banks-Young, 54, a domestic violence adviser from Columbus,
Ohio, who said her great-great-grandmother, Harriet Hemings, was a
daughter of Jefferson's and Hemings', contended that she did not
necessarily expect to be accepted into the Jefferson family this
weekend. Yet she looked upon the invitation as an important symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have experienced so many things based on the racial
attitudes of America all my life,'' she said. ``I sure didn't
expect this to be different. But I'm hopeful more might come of
this, and it will. A mile begins with a single step, and if this is
a part of a beginning, then that's good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-99 2355EDT &QL; 
